<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-NOTEBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS' WILLIAMS DENIES COACHING INTEREST AT UNC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   Fighting distractions: From the moment his team arrived in New
Orleans for the opening rounds of the Midwest Region, Kansas coach
Roy Williams has felt somewhat besieged.
</P>
<P>
   First there were the questions about Lester Earl, his junior
forward who was once the center of a scandal that landed LSU on
probation. Each time Earl stepped on the court in the Jayhawks'
first-round win over Evansville, fans at the Superdome booed him,
waving car keys and money.
</P>
<P>
   After the victory, Williams was then faced with the daunting
prospect of a second-round matchup today with Kentucky, a team that
defeated the Jayhawks in December, 63-45.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to preview that yesterday, Williams found himself
dealing with a rumor that he will soon replace Bill Guthridge as
coach at North Carolina, Williams' alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I love New Orleans,'' he said, ``but this has really
been tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``About all I can say about that is that Bill Guthridge is a
great friend and was once my coach, and I have no interest in his
job. I have an interest in North Carolina because my son just
graduated from there and my daughter is a student there, and I've
given them a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bill Guthridge even acts like he's gonna quit, I'm gonna
beat him up. Anyway, why would I want to work at a place where
someone in their own radio network can make something like that up
and turn it into a rumor?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like where I am. When I came to Kansas, I didn't even know
what a Jayhawk was, but now I love 'em.'' _Whit Canning
</P>
<P>
   Looking back: Regarding the December game with the Widcats,
Kansas forward T.J. Pugh said, ``It was just embarrassing _
especially the way we all felt in the locker room when we had been
outplayed so badly. But we were young then and had some injuries,
and I hope we're a different team now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said the Jayhawks (23-7) had struggled with their identity
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost some people like Raef LaFrentz and Paul Pierce, whose
mentality was simply that they were not going to be stopped,'' he
said. ``We have a lot of guys this year who were not really
comfortable with that role. We've become more of a team that
spreads the responsibility around and pays more attention to
detail.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the tradition of the two programs, Pugh said, ``They're
two of the best, but that's not going to make any difference in
this game. As far as Kentucky (26-8) is concerned, if this is a
`down' year, I'd say their program is in good shape.'' _Whit
Canning
</P>
<P>
   A marked man: In today's other matchup in New Orleans, Utah
coach Rick Majerus acknowledged that his team will throw everything
but the Mormon Tabernacle Choir at Miami of Ohio's Wally
Szczerbiak, who scored 43 points against Washington on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sure, we'll run four guys at him, we'll play him big,
we'll play him small, we'll box-and-one,'' Majerus said. ``But he's
a smart player and he feeds the others. He won't fall into the trap
of trying to beat us alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, you could win the Szczerbiak battle and lose the
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Majerus said the Utes will be at full strength, laying to rest
some fears that All-America point guard Andre Miller _ who suffered
a cut lip and a swollen hand Friday _ would not play. _Whit Canning
EAST
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for a cure: Brandon Wharton is trying but he can't figure
it out.
</P>
<P>
   When fourth-seeded Tennessee (21-8) plays 12th-seeded Southwest
Missouri State (21-10) today in a second-round East Region game in
Charlotte, N.C., the Volunteers hope that the Missed-Shot Flu that
swept through this region Friday has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's the 3-point line, teams relying on the three too
much,'' said Wharton, Tennessee's senior guard. ``Maybe it was the
tournament atmosphere and the first-game jitters. I really don't
know. I just don't think it can get any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight teams who played in Charlotte on Friday combined to
shoot 37.3 percent. Take away Duke's 61 percent shooting and the
percentage plummets to 33.6 percent. Southwest Missouri State held
Wisconsin to an opening-round record-low 32 points. _Wendell
Barnhouse
</P>
<P>
   Better not do it again: Tulsa committed 25 turnovers and nearly
blew a 26-point lead in its first-round victory over College of
Charleston. The Golden Hurricane (23-9) is averaging nearly 18
turnovers per game and have had 10 games with at least 20
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Against top-seeded Duke (33-1) today, ninth-seeded Tulsa knows
it can't afford to be as sloppy. The Blue Devils force an average
of 18 turnovers per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turnovers are a big key for Duke and some teams get scared of
Duke's pressure,'' said Tulsa sophomore guard Marcus Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski said that injured guard Trajan
Langdon is expected to start. He'll replace freshman Corey Maggette
in the lineup. _Wendell Barnhouse
</P>
<P>
   Barnes not upset: Texas coach Rick Barnes yesterday did not
appear overly concerned about the contention of Purdue's Brian
Cardinal that Gabe Muoneke punched the Boilermakers player twice in
a second-half spill _ a contention Muoneke denied and one on which
replays cast doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said one East Region staff official told him it didn't
happen. A member of the media sitting behind the Purdue bench also
said he heard one of the game officials tell a Boilermakers
assistant that Muoneke didn't punch Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he would look at a tape sometime after he returned
to Austin. The Longhorns flew out yesterday afternoon, and most of
the players went out to look around Boston during the morning. _
Mike Jones
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces: Teams from Temple and Cincinnati have played
seven times in the past six years. The Bearcats eliminated the
Owls, 77-71, in the NCAA first round in 1995 and 78-65 in the
second round in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that has any bearing at all,'' Huggins said. Mike
Jones
WEST
</P>
<P>
   Hood struggles: Derek Hood, Arkansas' leading rebounder, scored
nine points and grabbed nine rebounds in yesterday's 82-72 loss to
Iowa. But coach Nolan Richardson said the 6-foot-8 forward, who was
nursing a strained lower back, was little more than a shadow of the
player who averaged 12.5 points and 10.3 rebounds during the
Razorbacks' first 33 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hugged him after the game and we both cried,'' said
Richardson, who allowed Hood, a senior, to play 35 minutes in his
final college game. ``I don't think he should have played more than
20 minutes, the way he was grimacing out there. But every time I
brought him over to the bench, the first thing he said was, `I've
got to be in the game.' '' _Jimmy Burch
</P>
<P>
   Coaching carousel: New Mexico coach Dave Bliss confirmed he has
been contacted about the vacancy at Saint Louis, but declined
yesterday to discuss his interest, if any, in pursuing the
position. Published reports out of Iowa have identified Steve
Alford, the former Mavericks' guard who coaches Southwest Missouri
State, as the favorite to succeed Tom Davis, whose contract with
the Hawkeyes expires after the 1998-99 season. _Jimmy Burch
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' legacy: New Mexico center Kenny Thomas, a four-year
starter and All-America performer, cemented his legacy as an
underachiever in the NCAA tournament by scoring one point in his
final college game, a 78-56 loss to Connecticut. Thomas, who
averaged 15.7 points per game throughout his career, managed just
9.4 per outing in NCAA games, never leading the Lobos past the
second round of the tournament in any season.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss, however, defended his 6-foot-8 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a reputation for something, it's tough to
shake,'' Bliss said. ``Kenny didn't play well, but ... you don't
choose how you end your career. Many people don't like things that
happen to them. But Kenny will bounce back from this and play great
at the next level. The past four years, we went to four NCAA
tournaments and won four games in those tournaments. Without Kenny
Thomas, we would never have had the opportunity to do a lot of
those things.'' _Jimmy Burch
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
