<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-14 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCRAWNY KID PUTS UP BRAWNY NUMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ You saw Scott Pohlman on the floor of the RCA
Dome Saturday and your first thought was how precious, they're
plucking kids from the nosebleed seats to try a midcourt shot as
part of some pregame promotion.
</P>
<P>
   How could you have had a clue what Pohlman was about to do? The
slightly built, mop-topped Pohlman looked about as ready for his
Hollywood close-up as the scrawny neighborhood kid who rattles by
your house every afternoon on his skateboard.
</P>
<P>
   If you squinted real hard, you could have pictured Pohlman maybe
doing a guest stint on ``Dawson's Creek'' someday. But NCAA
Tournament stardom right away? As if!
</P>
<P>
   Only later would you find out Pohlman had been in the spotlight
plenty before he singlehandedly carried Auburn to the Sweet 16 on
his spindly shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Practically every night when he was growing up, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be dark by the time he got done with dinner so Pohlman, a
self-described ``driveway rat,'' would turn on the outside light in
front of his family's suburban Atlanta house, switch on the radio
and the headlights of the family sedan and shoot baskets until well
past midnight _ or until the neighbors across the street crossly
hollered at him to cease with all that thumping. No more bass or
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   A million jumpers later, Pohlman stood in wholly unfamiliar
territory, blinking in front of lights as bright as a comet, the
unlikeliest of shooting stars in the Tigers' 81-74 win over
Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the words to express how I feel right now,''
Pohlman said after pouring in a game-high 28 points in 32 minutes,
each basket seemingly bigger than his last.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the game's first shot, he made 11 of his next 16,
including 2 of 3 from beyond the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no hitch in my shot or nothing. Just one smooth
motion,'' Pohlman said, disbelief creeping into his voice. ``It's
just such a dream come true. All my life I've been watching players
(step up) in the NCAA Tournament. And today that was me in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   When the thermometer was turned up, he rose like heat. There was
the scintillating stretch late in the first half when Pohlman
outscored the Cowboys 11-0 all by his lonesome to turn a two-point
deficit into the biggest lead either team would enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Until a Pohlman jumper with six minutes left in the game put the
Tigers up by 10.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the jumper Pohlman knocked down with 52 seconds
left, after Oklahoma State had trimmed the lead to a
cuticle-bleeding two points, and the two free throws he netted for
the game's final points.
</P>
<P>
   At the final buzzer, an Auburn player picked Pohlman up and
carried him a few feet. It was the least any of his teammates could
do, after the lift Pohlman had given the No. 1-seeded Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways Scott put this team on his back and we rode
him,'' said Auburn coach Cliff Ellis, who didn't even try to hide
his delight as he watched the unassuming sophomore field the
Tiger's share of questions afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just like to see guys succeed who have all that heart and
character and are in the underdog role,'' Ellis said. ``He was not
one of the Parade All-Americans that you hear so much about. He was
not highly recruited.''
</P>
<P>
   That's putting it mildly. Pepperdine was the only Division I
school courting Pohlman for the first seven months of his senior
year at Roswell High. He flew west for a recruiting trip that was
memorable for two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beaches and girls,'' Pohlman said, blushing.
</P>
<P>
   While he was in L.A., Pohlman also attended a Clippers game,
which was more of a thrill than it sounds. He got to meet Dominique
Wilkins, then with the Clippers and the only player at the
University of Georgia to have his jersey retired.
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman was all pumped to move west. He had his mind ``pretty
much made up'' that he was going to Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Then he scored 29 points in a Class AAAA state semifinal playoff
game against a player Auburn was recruiting and roused the interest
of the Tigers. That was in late March. In early April, the
19-year-old accepted Auburn's last available athletic scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best situation I could have hoped for,'' said
Pohlman, who pined to play near enough to Atlanta to enable his
father, mother and sister to attend his games. ``Things work out
for strange reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman might as well have been an alien, so out of place did he
look when he arrived at Auburn. His new teammates didn't know what
to do, point him toward the nearest middle school or ask him to
fetch them a clean towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was the manager or something,'' said senior
Bryant Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Doc Robinson gave Pohlman a cursory glance and smirked.
``Ain't no way he can play at this level,'' Robinson recalled
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Tigers started practicing and Pohlman, who is very
generously listed at 6-foot-2, almost instantaneously earned his
stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week of practice he took over the intrasquad
games,'' Ellis said, ``and he never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman sheepishly admitted that he drew inspiration Saturday by
looking forward. He was determined to do whatever it took to get
out of next week's school exams. Even if that meant playing the
point for a bit _ in place of the foul-plagued Robinson _ and
banging the much bigger bodies inside for three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling myself I cannot take finals next week so we've
gotta win,'' Pohlman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I was thinking about out there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
