A9680 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-NORTHRIDGE-LADN     03-14 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE HASN'T LOST DANCE FEVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was the nightmare. Then the honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   What next for the Cal State Northridge women? What can the
program do to top a season in which the Matadors won the Big Sky
Conference title and appeared in the NCAA Tournament for the first
time?
</P>
<P>
   CSUN headed home Saturday night, one day after being eliminated
by Colorado State 71-59 in the first round. It wasn't a long
postseason trip, but, as somebody told Matadors head coach Frozena
Jerro late Friday night: ``You got to dance a little.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we knew all along we had the talent to be successful
in the Big Sky,'' Jerro said. ``Once we got through that first
round in the Big Sky and saw how we matched up against everybody,
we figured we had a good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who finished 21-8, won't be satisfied with another
first-round exit. Jamilah Jones and Tina Greer punctuated the
postgame press conference at Colorado State's Moby Arena with
several rapid-fire observations of their loss to the second-seeded
and seventh-ranked Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see a big difference between them and us,'' said
Greer, a sophomore transfer from Xavier who led CSUN in steals this
season. ``We just know that we have to battle next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a junior guard and team captain, said nobody in the media
expected the Matadors to compete with Colorado State, let alone
pull off an upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people that believed in us was us,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Jerro interjected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see we're hungry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A partial list of CSUN's milestones this past season:
</P>
<P>
   _The Matadors came one win short of tying the school record for
victories in a season, 22. They went 13-3 in conference, by far
their best record in the Big Sky and the first time a CSUN team won
10 games in conference.
</P>
<P>
   _It was the first time CSUN advanced to an NCAA tournament since
1989, when it went to the Division II playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _Jerro became the first CSUN women's basketball coach to win 20
or more games in her first season.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors are scheduled to return their entire roster. But
the challenge for Jerro in the coming weeks will be to cement the
status of CSUN's four foreign players who saw action this season:
starter Lynda Amari (France) and reserves Vivica Lof (Sweden), Neda
Milic (Serbia) and Daphne Verrept (Belgium).
</P>
<P>
   The foreign players all bonded with former coach Michael
Abraham, who resigned in November after being arrested for drug
trafficking. Any one of them could potentially transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Amari, a junior forward who was named All-Big Sky, said earlier
this season the presence of Abraham was the only reason she came to
Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prospect of an Amari transfer wouldn't leave the
cupboard bare. Far from it.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time all-conference guard Edniesha Curry comes back. So do
starters Greer, Jones and center Keisha Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Jerro, who was named the full-time coach the day after the
Matadors won the Big Sky Tournament, had a right to be upbeat after
the loss Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a disappointing loss,'' she said, ``but I told the
team `Let's put this disappointment past us . . . in some people's
eyes, we were the overachiever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
