<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MIDWEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH WOMEN SEND SFA HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY ROSETTA 
c.1999 Special to the Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ A year ago, the Texas Tech women walked off the
Lubbock Municipal Coliseum court wondering what might've been after
a second-round NCAA Tournament loss to Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   That wound has healed over time, but not completely. Last night,
the sixth-ranked Lady Raiders began to purge the rotten taste of
that loss with their first-round game in the Midwest Region.
</P>
<P>
   Tech scored the game's first 13 points last night and never let
overmatched Stephen F. Austin get closer than 11 points en route to
a convincing 80-54 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Lady Raiders (29-3) will face North Carolina
State (17-11) at 8:30 p.m. tomorrow in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stormed to the 13-0 lead in the game's initial five
minutes, with center Angie Braziel and guard Julie Lake each
scoring two early baskets. No. 15 seed SFA (17-12) didn't crack the
scoreboard until the 14:40 mark when Shawnta Johnson hit a hoop.
</P>
<P>
   By then the Lady Raiders were rolling,and even though the
Ladyjacks cut the deficit to 26-15 with 3:25 to go before halftime,
Tech was in control the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got off to a great start, and that was a big key to the
win,'' Lady Raiders coach Marsha Sharp said. ``For the first five
or six minutes we made them chase us, and we were able to set the
tone for what we wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What Tech wanted to do was make SFA run. The Lady Raiders did
that successfully and along the way hit 15 of 28 first-half shots
and forced 12 Ladyjacks turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   SFA made a bid late in the first half to make a move, but Lake
and Rene Hanebutt hit jump shots to fuel Tech's 10-3 run over the
final 3:14 before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   To remove any doubt, the Lady Raiders started the second half
with an 11-4 surge. Braziel and Lake picked up where they left off
in the first half with back-to-back baskets, and SFA never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to get a good shot because of the kind of defense
Texas Tech plays,'' Ladyjacks coach Royce Chadwick said. ``When we
finally did get a good look, it had taken so long that I think it
scared us. We started to press after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Braziel led the Lady Raiders with 21 points, while Lake scored
15, dished out a career-high 10 assists and grabbed 7 rebounds.
Anitra Davis led SFA with 14 points.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
