<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-GRIZZLIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS FIND SUCCESS VS. WOEFUL GRIZZLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Fisher 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Almost halfway through this abbreviated NBA season, a
modest Mavericks goal has crystalized:
</P>
<P>
   Become the best of the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got to take care of our own business, not take
possessions off, not have lapses,'' point guard Steve Nash said
after Dallas' 91-74 drubbing of Western Conference have-not
Vancouver last night at Reunion Arena. ``Take care of ourselves
first, then teams like this, then we can worry about the better
teams and the standings.''
</P>
<P>
   The dividing line in the West seems almost carved in stone.
Above the line are eight obvious playoff contenders. And below the
line?
</P>
<P>
   ``These kind of games,'' forward Samaki Walker said, ``give us
something to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a numbing 1-8 start, the Mavericks have won seven of
their past 13. That's not enough to fuel legitimate playoff talk _
Michael Finley's proclamations of contention seem more a function
of his team captaincy than his skills as a prognosticator _ but in
success-poor Dallas, it counts for something.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks (8-14) found the ideal victim in 4-17 Vancouver,
losers of 11 in a row. Fueled by the penetration of Nash (10
assists), Dallas stormed to an early lead of 21-6 before settling
for a 41-24 halftime edge. Those 24 points mark the third-lowest
first-half scoring total in NBA history and a Mavericks franchise
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense spoke up early, but it was there all game long,''
coach Don Nelson said. ``We were up to every challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The defensive effort was led by 36-year-old A.C. Green, playing
in his 1,000th consecutive game. Green was matched against the
Grizzlies' Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who scored 21 points, tying
teammate Felipe Lopez and Finley for game-high honors. But Green
dominated play when it counted, holding Abdur-Rahim, Vancouver's
leading scorer at 24.2 points per game, scoreless until midway
through the second period and limiting him to six first-half
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.C. gets the game ball, not just for his 1,000th, but for
sticking with \RAbdur-Rahim\S, who is a great player,'' Nelson
said. ``He was on him for 38 minutes and did a marvelous job.''
</P>
<P>
   With 2:31 remaining in the third period, Vancouver used a
three-point play by ex-Maverick Cherokee Parks to cut the lead to
three at 54-51, and what had been a 20-point lead at one point was
nearly gone. But the deficit initially created by Dallas' defense
and Vancouver's horrid shooting _ at one point, the Grizzlies
missed 11 consecutive shots while starting 5-of-29 (17 percent)
from the floor _ allowed the Mavericks enough cushion to hang on at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   When Vancouver sliced the lead to two with seven minutes left,
Hubert Davis (14 points) answered with a trio of 3-pointers for a
77-66 Dallas edge, sealing the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a game with everything the NBA has to offer,'' Nelson
said. ``We played great, played poorly, they made a run, we got the
win. What more can you ask for?''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
