<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES SITS AS THIGH TIGHTENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTER HAVEN, Fla. _ If it were up to the 25-year-old guy, he
would have stayed in and pitched. The manager, with 36 years of pro
baseball experience, said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes' third spring
outing ended in the third inning after his left thigh tightened on
him while covering first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt tightness in his left quadricep and we'll re-evaluate
(today),'' Dodgers trainer Charlie Strasser said. ``I have him
drinking water like crazy. That will tell us if it's a strain or a
cramp.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes experienced the tightness when he rushed to first after
Cleveland's Jim Thome hit a sharp grounder. First baseman Dave
Hansen fielded the ball and flipped to Valdes for the out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it a little bit on my left side when I went to sprint
over there,'' Valdes said. ``I agree with (manager) Davey Johnson.
You don't want to take chances. I could still pitch one or two
innings, but you don't know if it's going to get worse. If it's the
regular season or playoffs, that's different.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who allowed one run on three hits in 22/3 innings, said
he expects to make his next start, and also plans on completing his
between-starts work.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, Young pushed back: Todd Hundley's and Eric Young's
Grapefruit League debuts have been pushed back, with a new date not
yet known. Johnson said he made the decision on Hundley after
talking with the catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some tightness in his arm,'' Johnson said. ``I'm going
to wait until he's fully healthy for him to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was supposed to catch his first game of the spring today
against the St. Louis Cardinals. Young, who is yet to appear in a
spring game, was slated to play second base.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Hundley, recovering from reconstructive elbow
surgery, experienced the tightness because he's doing a lot of
wrist curls to strengthen his arm. When asked about being worried
about Hundley, he said: ``Not at this point. I'm not concerned,
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Johnson said he's also pushing back Young's spring
debut because the seven-year veteran is still experiencing
stiffness in his lower back. Young has been fielding grounders and
taking batting practice the past few days. But Johnson said he
wants Young, like Hundley, to be perfectly healthy before playing
in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Brown bashes toilet: Back at Dodgertown, right-handed pitcher
Kevin Brown took out some frustration by bashing a toilet with a
baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dodgers officials, Brown was showering when a
toilet was flushed. The plumbing setup at Dodgertown causes
extremely hot water to run through the shower when such an event
occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Upset about being scalded by the water, Brown left the shower,
grabbed a baseball bat, and slammed it a few times against the
toilet, Dodgers officials said. The toilet was broken, but no one
was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Cora fractures hand: Light-hitting Alex Cora wasn't given much
chance to earn a backup infielder's job out of spring training, but
now he has no chance. Strasser said Cora will be out four to six
weeks after X-rays revealed a fracture in the fifth metacarpal on
his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Cora, who played in 29 games for the Dodgers last season,
initially injured the hand when he was hit by a pitch March 7.
X-rays were negative, but Cora re-injured the hand on a swing
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Johnson is keeping a keen eye on the
bullpen, and he said he saw progress in right-hander Mel Rojas' two
innings against the Indians, though he did yield a run. ``I want
him to load it up, get more tilt in there and use his fastball,''
Johnson said. . . . Oft-injured minor-league outfielder Kevin Gibbs
was taken out of the game after the first inning with what Strasser
called a ``twinge behind his right elbow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
