<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS RESPOND TO CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Rob Blake spoke, and his teammates listened.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one game, but it was a small step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings are to make a move for a playoff berth in the final
five weeks of the NHL season, they will have to take many more
steps similar to the one they took Saturday night when they
defeated the Vancouver Canucks 3-1 before a Forum crowd of 14,348.
</P>
<P>
   A journey of what seems like a thousand points begins with a
single win, or something like that. Or maybe it began for the Kings
with Tuesday night's 4-2 victory over Detroit, followed by the
30-minute players-only meeting Blake called two days later.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Jozef Stumpel gave the Kings a lead 1:42 into the
game, Donald Audette made it 2-0 with 1:42 remaining in the second
period, and Stumpel scored again with 4:02 to play after the
Canucks had drawn to within one.
</P>
<P>
   In goal, Stephane Fiset stopped all but one of the 20 shots he
faced.
</P>
<P>
   With their second consecutive victory, the Kings (25-36-5) made
some important headway in their bid to salvage their season by
grabbing a playoff berth, moving to within five points of Edmonton
and Calgary, which occupy the eighth and final postseason berth in
the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also just about killed any lingering hopes the Canucks
(20-36-11) might have had of making a late playoff rush of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson, on the request of Blake and alternate
captains Luc Robitaille and Doug Bodger, played the same lineup
he'd used against Detroit, and the Kings were effective from the
start against the Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver had most of its significant scoring chances in the
third period after mustering a mere 12 shots on goal in the first
two.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, on the other hand, kept Canucks rookie goalie Kevin
Weekes constantly busy for the first two periods, firing 34 shots
but only beating him twice.
</P>
<P>
   On the first goal, Yanic Perreault outworked defenseman Mattias
Ohlund for the puck behind the Vancouver net. Audette then picked
the puck up and gave it back to Perreault, who centered the puck to
Stumpel in the slot. Stumpel snapped the puck past Weekes, off the
right goal post and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second period on a power play, Audette gave the
Kings a crucial insurance goal when, from the high slot, he
deflected a shot from the left point by Philippe Boucher past
Weekes for his 14th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Markus Naslund's power-play goal created some nervous moments
for the Kings, but Stumpel's goal _ which came after Craig Johnson
checked Ohlund off the puck _ sealed the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Kings had numerous excellent scoring chances, they
still aren't capitalizing on many of them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 forwards who dressed for the Vancouver game, only
Audette comes close to being hot, with two goals in his last six
games. Stumpel's goals were his first in eight games, Olli Jokinen
has none in nine, Robitaille has none in seven, Craig Johnson has
one in nine, Nathan LaFayette has none in 13, Ray Ferraro and Glen
Murray have none in 11, Yanic Perreault has none in 16, Ian
Laperriere has one in 48, Russ Courtnall has one in 22 and Sean
Pronger has none in 11 games as a King.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, though, the Kings produced plenty of chances
against the Canucks, and they scored enough goals to advance their
playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   They probably will need to do a better job capitalizing on their
chances Monday night, however, when they play host to the Ottawa
Senators, who have the best record in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
