<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DUCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID COYOTES WIN SAVE SCHOEN FELD?  
 WIN SOLIDIFIES GRIP ON 4TH SEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Well, they couldn't afford to waste those two points.
</P>
<P>
   Playing their most important game of the season, a game that
might have held their head coach's future in the balance, the
Coyotes' rolled up their sleeves Saturday night and gritted out a
hard-fought, 1-0 victory over their arch rivals, the Mighty Ducks
of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Khabibulin came up with 27 saves to notch his seventh
shutout of the season, tying his own franchise record. Mike
Stapleton scored on an early second-period rush, firing a slapshot
from just inside the blue line to beat goalie Guy Hebert for the
only goal of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensemen were playing back, Teppo (Numminen) made a nice
move to get me the puck and I just wound up and shot it,''
Stapleton said of his sixth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Coyotes (32-24-10) to four points ahead of
the Mighty Ducks (30-27-10) in the battle for the fourth spot in
the playoffs and home-ice advantage in the first round of the
playoffs. Anaheim, which had an eight-game unbeaten streak snapped
Friday night in Dallas, could have pulled into a tie with Phoenix
had it gone the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes might also have save Coach Jim Schoenfeld's job _ at
least for the time being. Speculation intensified throughout the
organization leading up to this game that Schoenfeld, in his second
year with the Coyotes, might be shown the door, possibly as early
as today, if Phoenix had another putrid performance like the one
here Thursday during a 3-0 loss to visiting Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld still might not be out of jeopardy, which may explain
why he bolted from America West Arena before the nightly three
stars of the game were even introduced.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his Phoenix tenure, he left without saying
anything to his team or to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't account for what Shoney does after games,'' Stapleton
said. ``I'm sure he's happy with the way we played. I don't know,
maybe he just doesn't want to talk to you guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much talking you can do anyway. Sometimes,
it's like beating a dead horse. Maybe he just had a different
approach. Maybe he felt we needed to just be left alone, left to
breath a little bit and it worked, so . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach John Tortorella said Schoenfeld went into his
office, grabbed his briefcase and asked him if he would mind
speaking to reporters instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a big deal,'' Tortorella said. ``I've seen
a lot of coaches do that.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bobby Smith is not ready to discuss his coach's
fate publicly, however, meaning anything could happen. A vote of
confidence now could have easily killed many of the rumors. But
Smith apparently is keeping his options wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not saying anything right now. He wasn't available to
discuss the reported trade he apparently is trying to pull off with
Montreal for veteran center Vincent Damphousse, either.
</P>
<P>
   NHL sources, however, said the deal is getting closer after
Smith reconsidered what to offer the Canadiens in return for the
31-year-old Damphousse, whom the Coyotes are eyeing for one of
their top two lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who had dropped 11 of their past 13 prior to
Saturday, could have used him against Anaheim in what shaped up to
be a close, tight-checking, playoff-type game. But to their credit,
they stood their ground, stuck to their game plan, and kept up
their intensity from start to finish in handing Anaheim its second
straight shutout loss.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin, meanwhile, rebounded in a huge way. After playing
one of his worst games of the season, which included giving up a
horrible flip-shot goal from the red line against the Canucks, the
Bulin Wall rediscovered his All-Star touch, turning away everything
sent his way during a brilliant, but heart-pounding performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a good game so I can feel better about
myself again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had to face the NHL's most-fearsome power play unit four
times, including a five-on-three advantage early in the game that
last 50 seconds. The Coyotes killed them all, though, and
Khabibulin didn't crak despite facing two of the league's most
leathal snipers in Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have had three goals tonight easy,'' said Selanne,
who took a game-high eight shots on goal. ``I hope I'm saving them
for when we meet them in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton got a break when Anaheim's Ruslan Salei, who
high-sticked Stapleton badly in the face the last time the teams
met, fumbled the puck away on a line change. With open ice in front
of him and only Hebert in his sights, Stapleton ripped a slapshot
that sailed under the goalie's pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a pass in the middle that cost us the game,'' Salei
said. ``I should have gone up the boards with it, but I tried to
make a play up the middle and they made me pay for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
