r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIDWEST-BICKLEY_A     03-14 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-BICKLEY_AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BICKLEY: ASU'S WHITE `ROBS' SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE - It's been a tough year for loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   And so the athletic director at Arizona State is here, in the
stands, wearing an Ole Miss sweater.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of Ole Miss is in Tempe, watching the games on
television. And the kid who had his coach stolen away by his father
_ the same kid who wears Sun Devils gear all over Mississippi _ is
dribbling out the clock, leading Ole Miss to its first tournament
win in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A weird, weird situation,'' said Mike White, a 22-year-old
senior point guard, son of Kevin White, centerpiece of a bizarre
triangle. ``It's probably something that has never happened before.
Just very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want a glimpse of the future, take note of today's
second-round battle between Ole Miss and top-seeded Michigan State.
Because, for the most part, these are still Rob Evans' kids playing
Rob Evans' brand of basketball. A team that broke through in its
third consecutive NCAA appearance. And if March Madness ever
permeates Tempe, if Evans overhauls Arizona State the way he did
Ole Miss, the assist will forever belong to Mike White.
</P>
<P>
   A kid who feared alienation, put aside his own feelings and let
his father take away the best coach he's ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my dad, I've been around coaches and athletics all
my life,'' White said. ``And Coach Evans is one of the best in the
country. Top five, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The saga began four years ago, shortly after White committed to
Ole Miss. Once, Georgia Tech Coach Bobby Cremins said he could back
up Stephon Marbury, but he'd probably never see the floor. Same
deal with Andre Miller at Utah. But more than anything, White
wanted playing time, and so he and his father swallowed hard when
they showed up for the first game at Ole Miss, hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people came to games at my Jesuit high school,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked around and saw 300 people in the arena,'' his father
said. ``I said to myself, `Oh, my God. Did we make the right
decision?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then, a couple of months later, a phone call that planted the
seed:
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Dad, this is a way that a program should be run.
He has everything under control. He has all these guys I didn't
think were anyone good playing at an unbelievable level,' '' White
said. ``I started the whole recruiting process.''
</P>
<P>
   The resurrection of Ole Miss is well-documented, a program that
became the hottest ticket in the Southeastern Conference, selling
out all of this year's games before the season started. But after
last year's tournament loss to Valparaiso, things got a little
sticky.
</P>
<P>
   The elder White had narrowed his list of candidates to two or
three guys. But he couldn't get away from Evans, or from the
implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad checked with me many times last year,'' White said.
``He asked how it would affect me if Rob Evans was their guy. He
asked if I'd resent him. He asked if he should drop Coach Evans and
pursue him at another time. I assured him I wanted the best for
Coach Evans. If he wanted to be at ASU, if that's how he wanted to
reward himself, that's what he deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there wasn't sacrifice involved. Evans spent many hours
on the phone with his former players this season, and given the
circumstances, that was just fine with his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was coaching two teams this year,'' Kevin White said. ``He
really was. It's funny, but Rob is still one of the most
intimidating men in my son's life, and he's thousands of miles
away.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the younger White, well, the alienation never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd take a lot of abuse,'' White said. ``People
saying, `What are you doing? You should've just gone with Coach
Evans.' I thought there would be a lot of anger. I'm real surprised
how well the student body has treated me this year. Then again,
maybe it would be different if we had a horrible team.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ole Miss has a chance to dethrone a No. 1 seed. A fan
base that wouldn't have known a basketball from a beach ball five
years ago is reveling in wild success. And as Kevin White watches
his son, there are twinges of jealousy and apprehension, a longing
for the day when he's sitting in the stands watching ASU winning a
tournament game in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming,'' White said. ``I smell it. I see it. You look at
Duke, Kentucky, Kansas, even Arizona. Maybe I'm crazy, maybe I'm
intoxicated by all of this, but we can become one of those
programs. We have all the elements, all the demographics. We just
need the product, and it's coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Ole Miss, they're sleeping out for tickets. They'll be
doing the same thing at ASU in a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets some top-notch players, it's over,'' Mike White
said. ``And when it does, I think Dad owes me a little
something.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
