</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-BALLPARKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CACTUS LEAGUE FANS HAVE PICK OF PARKS  
 8 SPRING TRAINING LOCATIONS RATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM WALSH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In Maryvale, Diamondbacks catcher Damian Miller signs
autographs for 10 minutes and savors Maryvale Baseball Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This field is beautiful, and I think this stadium in the best
in the Cactus League,'' Miller said. ``It would make me happy just
to stay out here all afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tempe, children run around the grass berm while adults soak
up the sun and chat at Diablo Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like you can come here, sit on the lawn and have a
picnic. It's kind of cool,'' Stephanie Dorsett said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesa, Sammy Sosa sprints into right field as adoring fans
snap photographs of his trademark salute. Sosamania reigns at
HoHoKam Park.
</P>
<P>
   These familiar images are repeated almost daily each March in
glimmering Cactus League parks, where the warm weather and casual
pace appeal to baseball fans and non-fans alike.
</P>
<P>
   There are six parks in the Valley and two in Tucson, giving
spectators a variety of options. But if forced to pick only one
site for watching a game, which would you choose?
</P>
<P>
   That isn't an easy question to answer. The league has so many
fine facilities, it's hard to go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to send a team of our own out to the ballparks to
survey the scene and talk with players and fans to determine the
best and the worst of the Cactus League.
</P>
<P>
   It was a close call, but Scottsdale Stadium was the favorite.
Its reconstruction in 1992 was the prototype for a wave of spring
parks financed by the Maricopa County Stadium District with rental
car taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale offers the best of everything: great sightlines, an
attractive setting next to Scottsdale Civic Plaza, a relaxed
ambiance, a great place to watch people.
</P>
<P>
   But Maryvale Baseball Park, Peoria Stadium, HoHoKam Park and
Tucson Electric Park are remarkably similar architecturally, with
only a few subtle wrinkles. None has bad seats. The biggest
differences come with ambiance and team loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson Electric Park was inspired by Peoria. Both are home to
two teams, have comfortable seats plus grass areas, and possess all
the amenities of modern parks.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to ambiance, HoHoKam and Diablo are in neighboring
cities but miles apart in identity.
</P>
<P>
   HoHoKam has the feel of a Midwestern reunion with the Cubs
faithful flocking from frigid Chicago to see their heroes. Retirees
predominate on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   Diablo has a more youthful orientation, with its proximity to
Arizona State University. Rock music blares between innings.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional critics prove you can't satisfy everyone. They label
these new stadiums as antiseptic and yearn for the smaller, less
sophisticated parks they replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they built this Taj Mahal, it was intimate,'' said Phil
Mangiaracina of Chicago, during his annual visit to HoHoKam.
``This, to me, is not spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   If intimacy is what you seek, Hi Corbett Field in Tucson is the
place to be. This older but renovated home of the Colorado Rockies
gives fans the feel of being on top of the action. And those
fortunate enough to sit near the bullpens can almost reach out and
touch the players.
</P>
<P>
   Maryvale Baseball Park is the league's overlooked gem. This
stadium, only 2 years old, offers excellent sightlines and the
Valley's best ticket availability.
</P>
<P>
   Maryvale finished last in Cactus League attendance in 1998, with
63,625 fans _ compared with HoHoKam's league-leading 134,329 _
largely because the Milwaukee Brewers have the league's weakest
following.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Miller of Phoenix is a big fan of Maryvale's new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't beat this park for beauty, the peaceful feeling you
get sitting here and being able to sit most anywhere you want,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Each Cactus League fan seems to have a preference, but the
comments used to describe most of the parks are nearly identical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd definitely rank this one high,'' said Scott Brown, an
Anaheim Angels fan from Rancho Cucamonga, Calif., making his first
visit to Scottsdale Stadium. ``It's a nice-looking park.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Marich of Seattle loves Scottsdale Stadium, but Maryvale
Baseball Park and Peoria Stadium rank high on her list as well. And
she compliments Diablo for high accessibility to players.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale Stadium ``is an excellent park,'' Marich said. ``This
park looks like an old-time ballpark, with the brick and iron.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Otto of Annapolis, Md., compares Scottsdale Stadium with
parks in the New York-Penn League, a Class A circuit in upstate New
York and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a lot of parks. This place gives me a lot of warm and
fuzzies like the minor-league parks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing minor-league about Scottsdale Stadium's
prices, some of the most expensive in the league with $16 and $14
box seats.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale's $16 boxes are only eclipsed by the $18 VIP club
tickets at Peoria Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Parking is free but not plentiful in the Scottsdale Civic Center
garage, and chances are you'll end up on one of the side streets
south of the park.
</P>
<P>
   A small fence atop the stadium's awning also captures foul
balls. The same fouls bounce off the press box and other offices at
Diablo and fall into the hands of happy fans.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the swanky club and box seats at Scottsdale and
Peoria, lawn seats cost only $3 at Diablo. During a recent
Diamondbacks-Angels game, lawn seats were popular, while closer
seats remained empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best $3 I spent today,'' said Jose Bennett of Mesa.
``I think this stadium has come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Mayland of Tempe said the lawn was best for families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have kids. They can't sit in the seats,'' she said. ``Here,
they can run around and see professional baseball. It's cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Cactus League parks have lawn seating. The only exceptions
are the two oldest parks, Hi Corbett Stadium in Tucson and Phoenix
Municipal Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Copeland of Seattle, also an annual visitor, said spring
games were more pricey and crowded than they were a few years ago,
but he and his wife, Linda, kept coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are more expensive, but heck, it's still great,'' Linda
Copeland said. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer, Mike Clancy and Jim Thomas contributed to this
story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
