<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-MEXICO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS TO MEX ICO SHOWS U.S. GROWING PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Bruce Arena emphasizes that this is a work in
progress. And if the new coach of the U.S. men's national team was
disappointed with his first loss, he was equally enthused by the
improvements made thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Arena led a group of relatively young and inexperienced players
into U.S. Cup '99. Growing pains were evident. After dispatching of
underdog Guatemala, 3-1, in the opening match, the Americans took
on fierce rival and battle-tested Mexico in Saturday's championship
game at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Needing only a tie to claim their first U.S. Cup title since
1995, the Americans had just that until the 57th minute. Mexico's
Jose Manuel Abundis, who was a thorn in the U.S. team's side all
afternoon, followed in a header by Joel Sanchez off a corner kick
for the winner in Mexico's 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys played pretty well today,'' Arena said.
``We have some young players, and some of our inexperience showed.
This is another step in our development. We still have a lot of
work to do. Every time we go out there, we learn something else
about ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making progress. I'd have to say that after five games
in '99, we've seen a lot of positives.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team is 3-1-1 this year, and 3-1-2 overall under Arena,
who took over for Steve Sampson not long after the Americans
struggled in the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Arena has brought in several new players and has experimented
with different lineups, in part because many veterans have
commitments overseas and in part to revitalize an aging corps.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defender Eddie Pope said he thought the team was on the
right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some fresh faces out there, and so far we've seen some
positive things,'' Pope said. ``All the new guys have done pretty
well, and that will help us in the long run. I think the more
players you have, the better off you'll be. You'll find that some
are suited for some situations, and some are suited for others.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the U.S. team was in a familiar situation, playing
in front of a decidedly pro-Mexico crowd of 50,324. The stands were
filled with red, white and green. Horns blared, firecrackers
blasted and all attempts to start chants of ``USA, USA'' were
quickly drowned out by ``Mexico, Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who had not beaten Mexico in the teams' previous
five meetings, fell behind early. Abundis took a pass off a quick
restart and tried to get a centering pass to Rafael Garcia. U.S.
defender Robin Fraser was a tad slow to get back, tripped in the
box and had the ball ricochet off his upper arm past a sprawled
goalkeeper Tony Meola in the 14th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Meola, who collided with Garcia, suffered a cut lip and damage
to one tooth. He had to leave the field and was replaced by Zach
Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first goal was just an accident all the way,'' Arena
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans got the equalizer in the 51st minute on a goal by
Frankie Hejduk. Fraser brought the ball out of the right corner and
fired a centering pass that bounced off Mexico's Salvador Carmona
and right to Hejduk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give our guys a lot of credit for coming back,'' Arena said.
``They really had to push hard to get that goal back, but it was
disappointing to see them give up that last goal so quickly after
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're still playing with some unknowns right now. We have
a bunch of players we still have to look at, and I think once we
get our full team together, we'll do well.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
