<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-ROCKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS FIGHTING FOR SURVIVAL  
 TIME RUNNING OUT IN SHORT SEASON  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - With the Suns just five games from the halfway point
of a shortened season, it's time to think about midterm reports. A
grade?
</P>
<P>
   How about an S?
</P>
<P>
   As in survival.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is Coach Danny Ainge's evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like survival right now,'' said Ainge, who has
heard ``S'' applied to some four-letter variations amid a growing
chorus of boos during his club's home-floor slide to a .500 record.
``A lot of teams are going through this. This is survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to the playoffs is no easy task. I think 10 teams are
capable of making it.''
</P>
<P>
   But only eight will. At this point, the Suns are the eighth and
final team. If this were the NCAA Tournament, the Suns would be a
bubble team.
</P>
<P>
   With a difficult schedule on the horizon, this bubble could
burst. There already are suggestions that things would be better
for the Suns if it did.
</P>
<P>
   With the their own first-round pick and a second first-rounder
acquired from Dallas in the Steve Nash deal, they could have two
picks (1 through 13) in the draft lottery. Isn't a roll of the dice
for a couple of young prospects better than being blown out in the
playoff's first round by, say, the Los Angeles Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to tell somebody as competitive as Jason Kidd or
Tom Gugliotta to lose?'' Ainge said. ``I can understand that from a
fan's perspective, but not from a player's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fan of a lot of teams, and I hope they lose to get a
higher draft pick. But I don't want to become part of something
like that. I don't want to develop that kind of an attitude. I'm
trying to eliminate the lackadaisical, lax approach.''
</P>
<P>
   The task doesn't promise to get any easier. After tonight's
visit with Charles Barkley and the Houston Rockets at America West
Arena, there's the road. The Suns play in four cities _ Milwaukee,
Charlotte, Atlanta and Houston _ in five nights. It looks perilous.
Then again, in this curious season, things aren't always as they
appear.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, in fact, might welcome a journey that in any other
year might be their undoing. On the road, they're 6-3. At home,
they're 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to be homeless?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But history is full of markers that indicate the road will take
an inevitable toll at some point. For now, the difference between
home and road mystifies Ainge.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, our play at home has not been as
passionate,'' he said. ``I don't have an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of anything reasonable, Ainge can only search for
what he believes will eventually correct the course. From him, that
means hard-edged, candid comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge's playing days with the Boston Celtics during their
championship run in the mid-1980s is his standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to Phoenix, everything was run very
professionally, but there wasn't the same approach and
discipline,'' said Ainge, who joined the Suns as a player in 1992
after stops in Sacramento and Portland.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, Boston's old level of discipline, commitment and
leadership is the mark he hopes his Suns will attain. Thus far,
they have fallen short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who plays us knows we're not a disciplined team,''
he said. ``On a scale of 10, we're about a three to a four.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the playoffs, hopefully we could be a five or a six. After
the next training camp, maybe a seven. This won't happen
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadership, he said, is the key. In Boston, the mantle fell to
Larry Bird. With the Suns, the job has been given to Kidd, who has
taken on the responsibility in games and, perhaps more important,
in practice.
</P>
<P>
   During the Celtics era, Bird was known for being the last to
leave practice. He was forever working on some element of his game.
On Saturday, Kidd was still on the practice floor 40 minutes after
the workout had ended. This was on the day after he had played 43
minutes in a two-point loss to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of leadership through example is contagious,'' Ainge
said. ``Larry Bird was the reason there were so many in Boston. He
was always on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jason's leadership skills have gone from a two to six
in the last year. As a coach, I'm at about the same stage that he
is as player. We're still learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
