<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS BACK BELEAGUERED SCHOENFELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago this week, the Coyotes' front office hastily summoned
reporters to discuss the fate of their second head coach in as many
years. After days of deliberations, the team announced that  &UR; Jim
 &UR; Schoenfeld's &UR; job was safe, despite a second-half collapse.
</P>
<P>
   How do they feel now?
</P>
<P>
   After streaking to the best start in franchise history,
Schoenfeld and the Coyotes have hit rock bottom. They entered
Saturday night's grudge match with Anaheim having lost 11 of their
past 13 games, choking away what once was a 17-point lead over the
Mighty Ducks for the No. 4 playoff spot in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim was in position to tie the Coyotes on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Is it Schoenfeld's fault? Some critics and some of the fans say
it is. They don't think he has his players motivated. They don't
like the way he repeatedly shuffles his lines. They think he's too
defense-oriented. They don't think he's getting enough out of his
players. They wonder why he still hasn't fixed the problem with the
power play.
</P>
<P>
   Valid points, all of them. But in Schoenfeld's defense, the
players are professionals and should be able to motivate
themselves. Coaches change lines all the time to find the right
match-up, change the flow, or simply because of ineffective play.
Too much emphasis on defense? Perhaps, but defense wins
championships and Schoenfeld' forechecking system creates offensive
chances in addition to excitement.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the power play stinks. That's a problem. But the biggest
problem of all would be if the players have quit on their coach,
which some people in the organization are starting to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld seems to have the players' support, however.
Publicly, at least, they're saying all the right things.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team is struggling, it's a lot easier to blame the
coach or fire the coach than it is to blame the players,'' veteran
center  &UR; Bob
 &UR; Corkum said. ``But the skid that we're in is not a result of
anything that Shoney or (assistants)  &UR; John (Tortorella) or  &UR; Gordie
(Roberts) have done. They've prepared us as well as I've ever been
prepared for games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it enough, that this slump is not their fault.
It's the players in the dressing room, and it has nothing to do
with the coaching staff. We've got to do it ourself and be proud
hockey players. I know there's a lot of talk about (a possible
coaching change), but I sure hope that doesn't happen because I
think Shoney's a stand-up guy and a good coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he treading on thin ice, anyway? Certainly. Yeah, there have
been injuries. Lots of them. But nothing like last year's rash,
which gutted the team. Still, Schoenfeld managed to get the Coyotes
to a respectable .500 record, an accomplishment he feels the group
never got enough credit for achieving.
</P>
<P>
   Can he get them out of the funk they're in now? Not if he gets
fired, which could be right around the corner if the Coyotes
continue to stumble. Don't forget, Schoenfeld was a leading
candidate for Coach of the Year just a few short months ago. He
coached in the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   But will he keep his job? Has he been given any advance warning
by General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith, who fired  &UR; Don Hay after just one
season specifically to bring in a coach like Schoenfeld?
</P>
<P>
   Smith hasn't exactly made himself available to discuss the
situation, which further clouds the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, though, shouldn't go down without a fight _ or
without his players fighting for him. He said it himself. The
players hold the key to whatever happens from here on out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to take some responsibility for their own actions,''
Schoenfeld said a few days ago. ``There's only so many  &UR; Knute
Rockne speeches you can make, only so many times you can jump up
and down and break things. After a while, it all falls on deaf
ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to recapture our commitment as a team, as a whole.
Tactically, technically and emotionally. Until we do, we won't win
on a consistent basis. We're going to have a hard time winning,
period. I still think we have the foundation to bring us back. They
have to remember who they are, who they were. It's a matter of
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want to be the team we were? Or is it too much bother?
It's a decision they have to make themselves.'' &QL; 
Who's the boss?
</P>
<P>
   The whispers have started up in Detroit again regarding the
future of future Hall of Fame Coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman, the winningest
bench boss in NHL history. The gut feeling here is, Bowman will
call it a career after this season, whether or not the Red Wings
threepeat, or record the natural hat trick, as Stanley Cup champs.
</P>
<P>
   Expect either one of the two assistants,  &UR; Barry Smith or  &UR; Dave
Lewis, to take over the reins. Smith is sounding a little impatient
over the whole thing, although he has a valid reason. His contract
is up and he needs to know if he needs to start looking elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to read Scotty's mind about what he's going to do,''
Smith said. ``For us to be waiting, that's not fair. When's he
going to make his decision, late August? What are you supposed to
do, wait all summer long? It just can't happen that way.'' &QL; 
More coach talk
</P>
<P>
   As long as we're on the subject, the word in Chicago appears to
be that the Blackhawks might just keep interim Coach  &UR; Lorne
Molleken around for the long haul. After replacing the fired  &UR; Dirk
Graham, Molleken was seen as a temporary stop gap until a new big
name could be found.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Molleken just might be the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk for all the guys, but I would be very glad to see
the whole staff come back,'' goalie  &UR; Jocelyn Thibault said. ``I
think most of the guys are really happy with the way things are
going right now. It was just a few weeks ago when everything was
kind of dark around here. We didn't see any light. But now, with
Lorne, we have some direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Zapped again
</P>
<P>
   We know times are tough in Tampa, where the bumbling Lightning
have just stunk up the NHL. But have you noticed what Team Tailspin
has been doing, lately? Take a look at their 10 most recent games:
</P>
<P>
   They beat the Coyotes, 4-2. Lost to Carolina, 3-1. Lost to New
Jersey, 3-2. Beat Philadelphia, 4-1. Lost to Washington, 10-2. Beat
Colorado, 2-1. Beat Montreal, 6-1. Lost to Ottawa, 9-3. Lost to
Toronto, 6-1. Beat Buffalo, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the weirdest team I've ever seen,'' Coach/General
Manager Jacques Demers said. ``I can't figure us out. We're like
yo-yos and it's just not acceptable.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
