<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-TUCSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STACY HOT ON TRAIL OF EGGELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Hollis Stacy took a look around tournament headquarters
and noticed an oddity on the leader board of the Welch's/Circle K
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Dale Eggeling was clearly out in front with a 12-under
total after three rounds. And, yes, Dottie Pepper was just 1 shot
back, tied with Michelle Redman.
</P>
<P>
   But where was Stacy's name? Had the three-time U.S. Open
champion been forgotten? Were observers discounting her chances
because she's 44 and has not won in eight years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you still want me?'' Stacy asked innocently.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for her score and where she stood, Stacy just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a 66,'' she said proudly. ``I'm 10 under.''
</P>
<P>
   So it goes on the LPGA Tour, where manual leader boards often
can't keep up with the red numbers. Unbelievably, Stacy was 2 shots
off the lead after going 6 under over the last six holes, including
an eagle at No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Such an oversight might miff some players. Not the easygoing
Californian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel blessed to be here. Thrilled!'' said Stacy, who closed
with four straight birdies. ``I got stuck in that wind tunnel on
Thursday and shot par, even though I double-bogeyed the 17th hole.
That (72), in my mind, was equal to my 66 (Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the way it goes. It's just such a luck thing with
tee times.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when Stacy's name finally was posted, it was
misspelled (Stacey).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Stacy might end up being overlooked after today. She
is an aging veteran who might have a tough time against the likes
of these strong contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Eggeling is in her prime and always plays well in Tucson. She
has a runner-up finish in 1992, two ties for third and five top-10
finishes. She is ready to win, she just doesn't want to think about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be really nice, but I have no vibrations, so to speak,''
said Eggeling, who carved out a 69 with five birdies and two
bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past (when leading), I've said to myself, `You've got
to do this, and you've got to do that.' So I'm not going to think
about a thing besides `swing slow and keep an even tempo.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Those words typified Redman's game on a warm and sunny day that
saw her make eight birdies to offset a lone bogey. Her sizzling 65
tied her for the low round of the day _ and week _ with Scotland's
Catriona Matthew, who was 3 shots off the pace at 9 under.
</P>
<P>
   Also tied with Stacy at 10 under was Nancy Scranton, the
third-round co-leader who hung on for a shaky 71.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a favorite going into the final round, it's got to
be Pepper, who made save after save on her way to a 69. When the
heat is on, she usually is as tough as a junkyard dog. Plus, she
has tasted victory in Tucson, during the 1995 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've had my best round yet,'' she warned in the
way only Pepper can.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is Se Ri Pak, the LPGA's 1998 Rookie of the
Year. The Korean, who seems to have broken out of an early-season
slump, got into the chase with a 69, leaving her 4 shots back.
</P>
<P>
   Four players were at 7 under, including defending champ Helen
Alfredsson (73) and Kelly Robbins (70), who has a victory this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Stacy has to be the sentimental choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made the eagle on 13, I knew I could use it to turn my
round around,'' Stacy said of the 3 she set up with a 7-wood from
210 yards that settled two feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't wait to get to the next hole and birdie it.
It's a lot of irony sometimes. When you're playing great, you can't
wait for the next hole. But when you're playing lousy, you can't
wait to get to 18 so the round will be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacy even has a secret weapon working for her as she goes after
her 19th career victory: a new ball called the Bald Eagle. The
Taiwanese import, which is legal, has six small spots symmetrically
positioned around the exterior that don't have any dimples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see a difference with it,'' Stacy said. ``The launch is
different, and I'm making a lot of putts because it rolls pure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf has grown so much the past few years, you've got to be an
engineer anymore to understand the equipment.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
