<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLETON GAINS A BIT OF REVENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The last time the Coyotes met the Mighty Ducks of
Anaheim, Phoenix center  &UR; Mike Stapleton nearly lost his left eye
when he was dangerously high-sticked in the face by  &UR; Ruslan Salei.
</P>
<P>
   Salei got away with it and wasn't suspended by the NHL, but
Stapleton got some justice of his own Saturday night, scoring early
in the second period to break a scoreless tie with his sixth goal
of the season. And Salei just happened to be one of the defensemen
who got burned on the play.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the few things he and his teammates have had to
smile about in a while, considering the Coyotes' recent slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been just one bad day,'' Stapleton said, ``it's been
a month of bad days. We're just trying to pull ourselves out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton missed four games because of the injury, which
required more than 20 stitches, and he's had to wear a shield ever
since. &QL; 
Selanne's streak
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Ducks' right wing  &UR; Teemu Selanne had a 17-game,
point-scoring streak snapped during Friday's 4-0 loss in Dallas. It
was the second-longest streak in the NHL this season, just one game
behind Philadelphia's  &UR; Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   The streak would have continued had a second-period rebound goal
by Selanne on the power play not been called back because
defenseman
 &UR; Fredrik Olausson had his skate in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a joke,'' Selanne said, noting Olausson's foot in no
way obstructed Stars goalie  &UR; Eddie Belfour. ``That rule is ruining
hockey. It's not because my streak was ended. It had nothing to do
with the play. I feel ashamed for hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's streak was the eighth-longest of the 1990s.  &UR; Mats
Sundin had a 30-game streak while playing for Quebec.  &UR; Adam Oates
had a 25-game streak with Boston,  &UR; Wayne Gretzy 21 with Los Angeles
and  &UR; Brett Hull 20 with St. Louis. &QL; 
Jim dandy
</P>
<P>
   Former Coyotes enforcer  &UR; Jim McKenzie, now of the Mighty Ducks,
explaining his scrum Friday night with the Stars' Belfour, in which
both players traded a few shoves and cross-checks:
</P>
<P>
   ``I forechecked him and maybe bumped him a little. I didn' hit
him,'' said McKenzie, who was handed two minutes for slashing, two
minutes for cross-checking and a 10-minute misconduct. ``Then he
hit me and I hit him. Then he said something about Duke winning the
national title and I said it would be UConn and it escalated from
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 0137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
