<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9700 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZ     03-14 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO MISSED HEINZ BONUS BY 1 GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's passing of  &UR; Joe DiMaggio brought out countless
stories about the Yankee Clipper's life and baseball career. The
words of praise poured in from nearly all corners of the continent
for the player who many believe was the most graceful to play the
game.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly every aspect of DiMaggio's life was covered in some
way, there were a few items that didn't surface last week.
</P>
<P>
   Below are some little-known tidbits about DiMaggio:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee Clipper had a $5,000 bonus check awaiting him if he
hit safely in one more game during his record 56-game hitting
streak. Heinz (as in Heinz 57 sauce) was prepared to sign DiMaggio
to an endorsement deal for $5,000, which was an amazing figure,
considering that DiMaggio's pay in 1941 was $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   While his prowess in Yankee Stadium's gaping center field was
legendary, remember that DiMaggio had little help from his corner
outfielders back then.  &UR; Tommy Henrich and  &UR; Charlie Keller were
little more than human statues defensively who were in the lineup
because they could hit.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio told Diamondbacks managing general partner
 &UR; Jerry Colangelo last September, when the two spent hours together
in Chicago, that he would gladly throw out the first pitch at
Arizona's home opener April 12 against Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, a three-time Most Valuable Player, hit .408 during his
record 56-game hitting streak. Ted Williams hit .406 for the entire
season.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was tagged with the nickname ``Yankee Clipper'' when
then-Washington Senators radio broadcaster  &UR; Arch
 &UR; MacDonald described the Yankee center fielder moving with the grace
of a clipper ship gliding across the waves during a broadcast
sometime around 1940.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting sidelight that stood out during all the hours of
DiMaggio footage shown the day he died: Take a look at his upper
body without a shirt on. There were no built-up pecs or washboard
stomach. Yet he still managed to hit 361 home runs in a 13-year
career. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that  &UR; Cal Ripken's major league record consecutive games
streak ended at 2,632 late last season, name the player with the
longest current streak heading into the 1999 season. &QL; 
She may have a point &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta owner  &UR; Ted Turner tripped all over himself last month
with controversial comments he made during a speech to the National
Family Planning and Reproductive Association. While his comments
fall short of those by Cincinnati owner  &UR; Marge Schott, who once
said  &UR; Adolf Hitler had good ideas but went too far, Turner didn't
seem to stray too far away from the Reds' embattled owner.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure, Turner is in some hot water with baseball, the type
that could easily result in a fine and a mandate to take
sensitivity courses.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were Turner's comments on Feb. 16 when he urged Pope
John Paul II to ``get with it _ welcome to the 20th century'' and
suggested that adultery should be stricken from the Ten
Commandments. He also referred to his upraised foot as a ``Polish
mine detector.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner  &UR; Bud Selig said he is taking the matter very
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how Ted Turner can get away with what he
said,'' Schott told Cincinnati area reporters last week. ``I didn't
say anything or do anything worse than what he said.'' &QL; 
Young and relentless &QL; 
Pittsburgh first baseman  &UR; Kevin Young couldn't help but reflect on
where his baseball career has gone in the last few years recently.
After signing a four-year $24 million deal to remain with the
Pirates, Young recalled exactly how far he's come.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Young was cut from Pittsburgh's camp during the final
week of spring training in 1996 so Pittsburgh could keep utility
man  &UR; John
 &UR; Wehner. Young was later let go by Kansas City, of all clubs, at the
end of the same season. Now he's considered one of the top players
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, but when I sat down in (general manager)  &UR; Cam
Bonifay's office to finish this contract, I was thinking it was the
same place where I had been released,'' the Ahwatukee resident
said. ``When I step back and think about it, it really is a nice
story. It's pretty amazing.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Baltimore teammate  &UR; Albert Belle has the longest current streak in
the majors at 366 consecutive games. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; The 1990s ballplayer: Toronto pitcher  &UR; David Wells recently
disclosed that he and former MVP  &UR; Kirk Gibson will co-own a jet
plane. Wells wants to take lessons and get his pilot's license so
he can fly when his playing days end.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The 1990s ballplayer II: While Cleveland outfielder
 &UR; Manny Ramirez decided to change his hair color back to black (it
was orange at the end of last season), Cincinnati pitcher  &UR; Denny
Neagle has gone from brown hair to platinum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Jim Walewander.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New meaning to the term  &UR; ``dead ball'': Maintenance crews
discovered more than 12,000 cubic yards (which we can only assume
is a very large load) of lead-contaminated soil where center field
will be at San Francisco's new Pac Bell Ballpark, which will open
in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Catcher  &UR; Todd Hundley, on whom Los Angeles is counting to be the
club's big run-producer, is scheduled to make his debut behind the
plate when the Dodgers meet St. Louis today. The big question, of
course, is how well Hundley's surgically-repaired elbow is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer  &UR; Yogi Berra disclosed last week how much he earned
in post-season money after winning six World Series championships
with the New York Yankees and losing two others. Berra said he
earned $43,000 for his eight World Series trips. The Yankees
individual full shares for winning last season's World Series were
$313,000.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming no one beats him to it,  &UR; Omar Daal's next shutout will
give him two and the all-time record in Diamondbacks' very short
history. Big deal? Well, the all-time record for shutouts by the
six-year-old Colorado Rockies is two, by  &UR; Roger Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Florida pitcher  &UR; Jesus Sanchez, a native of the Dominican
Republic, is planning to remain in the United States when this
season ends and he wants to run in the New York City Marathon.
Sanchez has won two marathons in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Whitey Herzog, who managed six first-place finishes, on new
Detroit Manager  &UR; Larry Parrish: ``I have no qualms that he'll do a
good job. He's been around enough that he can evaluate his players.
And he won't have any silly rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the  &UR; Jose Guillen visa problem has been cleared up, it
can be revealed that the Pittsburgh Pirates summoned the help of
Pennsylvania's U.S, Senators,  &UR; Arlen Specter and  &UR; Rick
 &UR; Santorum.
</P>
<P>
   THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Dodgers GM  &UR; Kevin Malone is throwing out signals that pitcher &UR; Dave
Mlicki may not necessarily be the pitcher the club plans to trade
this spring.  &UR; Ismael Valdez's name has not been eliminated from the
list of LA's available pitchers. Anaheim may be very interested in
Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota GM  &UR; Terry Ryan can deny it until he's blue in the
face, but other clubs are convinced Twins ace  &UR; Brad Radke, who will
be paid about one-sixth of the total payroll, can be had in a
trade, especially if the right prospects are dangled.
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Joe Oliver looking like he's ready to assume Tampa Bay's
every day catching duties, the Devil Rays may be willing to trade
one of the other catchers on their roster,  &UR; John Flaherty or
 &UR; Mike DeFelice.
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Bryce Florie looking very mediocre so far this spring,
Detroit is considering an almost  &UR; Dwight Gooden-like move,
promoting a pitcher from Class A to the majors.  &UR; Jeff Weaver, the
Tigers' No. 1 draft pick last summer, has impressed the Tigers to
the point that this idea is fairly serious.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Kevin Appier sweepstakes began in earnest last week when
the right-hander looked up to see 17 scouts in the stands for his
spring debut. If Appier remains healthy, look for him to be dealt
(with Cleveland a strong possibility) before the start of the
season. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
