<HEADLINE>
BENES NOT WORRIED ABOUT ERRATIC START TO SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ It's mid-March, so Diamondbacks pitcher Andy Benes
isn't too concerned he's yet to get his pitch limit beyond the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Benes, in his third start this spring, gave up three runs on
three hits _ including a home run by left fielder Angel Echevarria
and a two-run double by leadoff man Curtis Goodwin _ against the
Colorado Rockies on Saturday at Tucson Electric Park. He walked
pitcher Brian Bohannon in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good,'' said Benes, who walked two and struck out two.
``I'm in good shape. I was a little erratic today.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter said he still thought Benes was ahead of
where he had been this time last year. Benes started last season
slow but finished strong, winning seven of his last nine decisions
to end 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making progress,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Benes said he couldn't remember where he had been last year at
this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is to be in good shape and to build up,'' he
said. ``Obviously, the results aren't what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes said he felt he had decent command of his fastball,
curveball and change-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four of the five curveballs were strikes,'' he said. ``It
wasn't real pinpoint, but it's not like I was all over the place. I
was maybe overthrowing at times. The good thing is that when I
missed, I missed down. My delivery wasn't the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Kelly Stinnett said Benes had ``good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was spotting his fastball at both sides of the plate,''
Stinnett said. ``He was spotting his slider, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes will pitch again in four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a streak of two (innings an outing),'' he said. ``Maybe
next time, I'll get over that.'' &QL; 
On the side &QL; 
Closer Gregg Olson, bothered by tendinitis in his wrist, will join
the Diamondbacks in Scottsdale today and will throw on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he anticipated Olson being able to pitch in a
game Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually run into a bout of tendinitis right about now,''
Olson said. ``I'll be all right. I just have to take care of it.'' &QL; 
Shortstops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks on Saturday had their nine-game winning streak
snapped by the Rockies, the team that last beat them March 4 in
their Cactus League opener.
</P>
<P>
   With today's game against the San Francisco Giants being
televised regionally by Fox Sports Net Arizona, Showalter said he
would likely bring his A team to Scottsdale Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams, first baseman Travis Lee, second
baseman Jay Bell and shortstop Danny Klassen will make the trip
from Tucson. Omar Daal will start on the mound, with Brian Anderson
expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
   On utilityman Andy Fox, who played every position but catcher
and pitcher last season, Showalter said, ``I look at him as a
regular irregular.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he would likely go down to the wire before
picking his 25-man opening day roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if we're at 30 once we're done with
the exhibition games,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Kelly Stinnett earned the first Don &AMP; Charlie's Cactus
League Player of the Week award for March 4-11. Stinnett capped it
with a pair of three-run homers on Thursday. He gets a $100 gift
certificate from Don &AMP; Charlie's Restaurant in Scottsdale. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
