<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9702 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-DELLUCCI-A     03-14 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-DELLUCCI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELLUCCI PLANS TO PACE HIM SELF THIS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ David Dellucci is starting to realize that he doesn't
have to hit until his hands bleed, that he doesn't have to go to
bed wondering if he's going to be in the lineup the next day, that
he doesn't have to be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   No stress, no duress. That's his motto this spring. He's taking
it into the batting cage, to the game, taking it home.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci, trying to win an outfield position with the
Diamondbacks, where he made a sudden splash last season before
flaming out late during his rookie year, says , ``I've learned to
pace myself. It's going to make me stronger in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about just relaxing. If I'm going to take extra
cuts, maybe I'll just take 10 or 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dellucci would take his bat and hit endlessly in the
cage after an 0-for-4 game or after striking out in a pinch-hit
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a slump and realized how long a major-league season
was,'' he said. ``It got to where, if I had a bad game, I'd go in
the cage and take 400 swings after a game until midnight. I really
wore myself out before the season was even close to being over.''
</P>
<P>
   After a splendid start to his major-league career, after hitting
safely in 10 of his first 25 at bats, after chasing down flies and
making acrobatic catches in left field, expectations grew and the
25-year-old from Baton Rouge, La., began to press.
</P>
<P>
   Dellucci, who was recalled from Triple-A Tucson after 17 games
last year, lost his everyday job in left after Bernard Gilkey came
over from the New York Mets in an August trade. In part-time duty,
he had nine hits in his last 53 at bats. He end up hitting .260
with 51 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   There was confidence gained by his National League-leading 12
triples. He became only the second rookie since 1984 to lead the
league in that category and the first since Ray Lankford at St.
Louis in '91.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Dellucci isn't thinking of leading the league in
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal now is to make the Opening Day roster and work my way
in from there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be tough, even for a man of Dellucci's versatility (he
started all three outfield positions last year).
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks lost center fielder Devon White to free agency,
but added Steve Finley, Luis Gonzalez and Dante Powell. Tony Womack
is being turned into an outfielder and is penciled in as the
Diamondbacks' leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Gilkey, who is back, after having his vision
surgically corrected late last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think David took a big step last year,'' Manager Buck
Showalter said. ``He and Travis have that same mindset, that `I can
do this' mentality now.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed swinging Dellucci is showing that this spring,
while Womack and Gilkey have been out with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   He was hitting .500 (8 for 16) with three doubles and six RBIs
in seven Cactus League games. And he's struck out only three times.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in 416 plate appearances, Dellucci struck out 103
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appears more comfortable out there,'' Showalter said. ``He
hit stretches of challenges last year. You have to play at the top
of your game to compete at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   So, after the season ended, Dellucci worked on the mental game.
He stopped thinking about baseball around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   An avid pro wrestling fan, he hung out with World champion Kevin
Nash, a Valley resident, and went back home to Baton Rouge, where
he worked out and read his name in trade rumors on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ever rule that out,'' he said. ``Until it really
happens, I'm an Arizona Diamondback. I love this team. I love the
coaches. I don't want to be anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a late-inning pinch hitter, or as a defensive
replacement, Dellucci says he doesn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult going from playing every day to coming
off the bench or playing every third or fourth day,'' Dellucci
said. ``That's tough. I'm really concentrating now on excelling in
maybe that ninth-inning pinch hit or any little thing I can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
