<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-GOMES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILL WINDS BREW ING UP TROUBLE FOR YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA - Even when they should be sailing along with a gentle
breeze at their backs, the New York Yankees can't help but be at
the center of a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off their 125 wins last season, which culminated with the
club's record-24th World Series championship, it would seem the
Yankees would be a sea of tranquility, especially since all the
core players were re-signed during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, swirling storms have surrounded the Yankees' Tampa
complex, providing enough riveting story lines to cover a full
season.
</P>
<P>
   After all, these are the Yankees, easily the game's most-storied
franchise. Nothing is ever simple and easy with this club. There's
no real reason for it all, except that the baseball gods seem to
have mandated that the Yankees remain the most intriguing and
newsworthy club in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Consider everything that has already occurred with the Yankees
in the month since pitchers and catchers reported:
</P>
<P>
   They started with a bang, setting the baseball world on its side
with the blockbuster trade that resulted with five-time Cy Young
Award winner Roger Clemens coming and David Wells, who had a Babe
Ruth-type body and a way of living that seemed to make him a
perfect Yankee, going.
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Berra, one of the greatest Yankees ever, returned to the
Yankees family after reconciling a 14-year estrangement from owner
George Steinbrenner. To add perspective to the magnitude of the
event, remember that Bernie Williams, who has been in the
organization since 1986, met Berra for the first time last month.
</P>
<P>
   The club, and baseball, suffered a huge blow when Joe DiMaggio,
a member of Yankee royalty, died last week. The club will wear a
No. 5 patch on their left sleeve throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   Catfish Hunter, who has been diagnosed with Lou Gehrig's disease
(imagine the irony there), came to camp to throw out the first
pitch for the exhibition season. He has been a beacon of courage as
he battles one of the most debilitating afflictions known. Already,
Hunter can no longer even raise his arm for a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   On the very day Darryl Strawberry returned from extensive
chemotherapy treatments to battle colon cancer, Manager Joe Torre
checked out of camp after he had been told he has prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Torre's absence from the club he has guided to
two World Series titles in three years, the manager's office here
remains locked. Don Zimmer, the interim manager, refuses to even
walk into the office of one of his best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very bizarre,'' right fielder Paul O'Neill said. ``You
see the door closed and all. We know we've got a good team, but
there have been some very bad things happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre is apparently leaning toward surgery, a more aggressive
approach to combating his cancer. It also could mean Torre will be
away from the club for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Controversial and explosive-tempered pitcher Hideki Irabu, who
has had dark clouds surrounding him since he joined the Yankees,
has been basically the equivalent of a piece of furniture in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the sullen mood in and around the clubhouse, the
Yankees are preparing for a potential bombshell in the coming
weeks. Strawberry, who played for the first time this spring on
Wednesday, insists he's ready to go for opening day.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Yankees suffered the only two arbitration losses by
the owners (in Derek Jeter and Mariano Rivera), giving the Yankees
a combined loss of $3 million. So, Steinbrenner is searching for
ways to pare the $88 million payroll and the looming $5 million
luxury tax payment.
</P>
<P>
   One way would be to keep Strawberry off the active roster as
long as possible. Even one month could wind up saving the Yankees
close to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, these are emotional times around the Yankee compound.
But when it's all said and done, it's just a part of being
associated with the Yankees. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
