<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-IOWA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA KEEPS DAVIS WORKING OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ What's the difference between a pit bull and Iowa Coach
Tom Davis?
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the pit bull lets go.
</P>
<P>
   Not Davis nor his Iowa Hawkeyes, though. Not yet, anyway. Davis,
whose contract was not renewed by Athletic Director Bob Bowlsby at
the start of his 13th season, is supposed to be through as the Iowa
head coach as of their final game. The thing is, the Hawkeyes keep
putting it off.
</P>
<P>
   The end appeared imminent Saturday at McNichols Arena when Iowa
trailed the Arkansas Razorbacks by 13 points early in the second
half of their NCAA West Region second-round game. But in a
frantically played, fun-to-watch game of big runs by both teams,
Iowa ran last and ran best. The fifth-seeded Hawkeyes defeated the
fourth-seeded Razorbacks, 82-72, to advance to the regional
semifinals and a date with Connecticut on Thursday at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight, we dig down and find a way,'' said senior guard Kent
McCausland, who made 5 of 7 three-pointers in the second half to
lead the comeback after going 0 for 2 in the first. ``We have some
fight left in us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes outscored the Hogs, 23-6, over the last 7:20.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, whose job has practically been handed to Southwest
Missouri State Coach Steve Alford, was moved nearly to tears after
the game, engaging in group hugs with his staff and players. Asked
to put his feelings and thoughts into words, Davis said, ``I don't
think I can do it justice. My focus all year has been to try to
involve myself with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, we're doing the best we can. And I feel like we've
been doing it for 13 years at Iowa. I've just been giving it my
best shot. And if I fall short, I fall short. I'm just going to get
this team as well-prepared as I can and have as much fun as I can
and not worry about the bigger questions. The bigger questions I'll
try to answer when this is over.''
</P>
<P>
   That likely will be after the Connecticut game, but the way this
Iowa team is juiced, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our emotions have been carrying us all year, there's no
question, and we'll play hard,'' Davis said. ``If we lose the game,
it won't be because we weren't busting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Hawkeyes and Razorbacks were busting it, defying the
mile-high altitude and alternately seizing control at a frenetic
pace. Arkansas overcame a 19-10 deficit and led by seven at
halftime as its pressure forced Iowa into 16 turnovers in the first
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When Chris Walker, who had a game-high 22 points, hit one of his
six three-pointers (in 12 attempts), Arkansas led, 47-34, with
18:21 to go. Then it was Iowa's turn. With McCausland heating up,
the Hawkeyes ran off 16 points and 23 of the next 29 to go ahead,
57-53, with 11:24 remaining. Back came Arkansas, on a 13-2 run.
McCausland and Co. returned fire, scoring 12 straight to take a
71-66 lead with 4:35 left. Arkansas got within one on a Kareem Reid
three-pointer with 2:26 left, but Iowa closed the game with nine
straight points.
</P>
<P>
   McCausland and point guard Dean Oliver each had 17 points for
the Hawkeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was helter-skelter out there the entire second half,'' said
Iowa forward Jess Settles, a sixth-year senior. ``Half the time, I
don't think either team knew what defense they were playing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
