<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-UCONN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN'S FAST START DOOMS NEW MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER - Before their game Saturday against Connecticut, New
Mexico players spoke of the Huskies with reverence, saying that it
was a privilege just to share the same court with the No. 1 seed in
the West Region of the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But that privilege turned into a curse from the second the ball
was tossed in the air to start the game. Connecticut scored the
first 17 points and held New Mexico without a point for the first
7:12 and without a basket for the first 8:14. They followed that
with an 11-0 run to open the second half and coasted to a 78-56
victory in a second-round game at McNichols Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly feel better today than I did a couple of days ago
for two reasons,'' said Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun, who returned
to the sideline after missing Thursday's victory over Texas-San
Antonio because of a virus. ``Most of all because of how our team
played.''
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico (25-9) shot 26.3 percent from the field. Center Kenny
Thomas, the Lobos leading scorer this season, scored one point,
about 18 under his average, and managed just six shots. It was the
first time Thomas, a senior, had gone without a field goal in his
career, a span of 123 games. Lamont Long, the team's second leading
scorer, had 15 points, but missed 14 of 18 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played great defense, right down to a man,'' said
Calhoun, who earned his 300th victory at Connecticut. ``Even if we
don't shoot well today, we would have been awfully tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (30-2) will play fifth-seeded Iowa on Thursday in
the region semifinals at America West Arena. The players are on
spring break, so the Huskies were scheduled to fly to Phoenix
today.
</P>
<P>
   Two victories in Phoenix will put the Huskies in the Final Four
for the first time, even though this is the sixth time in the 1990s
that they've been seeded first or second.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut won its two games here by an average of about 24
points, prompting some to ask if the Huskies are trying to send a
message to Duke, the favorite to win the tournament. Calhoun
scoffed at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think where Duke is operating right now, they can't hear the
rest of us,'' Calhoun said. ``They're too far away, not getting any
messages. Home alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Richard ``Rip'' Hamilton and point guard Khalid El-Amin
led Connecticut Saturday with 21 points apiece, but the Huskies
struggled offensively at times, shooting just 37.5 percent in the
first half. They made up for it with their suffocating defense.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has a history of poor performances in the NCAA tournament
and after a few misses Saturday, his interest seemed to wane,
leaving New Mexico without a low post game. Thomas downplayed his
performance, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had great games,'' he said. ``I had a great game before
this (20 points against Missouri on Thursday). Just because it's
UConn doesn't mean anything. I just couldn't make a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lobos opened in a 2-3 zone to try and slow UConn, but the
17-0 run forced them into man-to-man defense. It worked for a while
as they drew within 9 , but success was fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you draw up in the dirt doesn't always work when the
other team has better players,'' said New Mexico Coach Dave Bliss. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
