<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-FLORIDA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATORS WIN, BUT WEBER STEALS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Florida Coach Billy Donovan finally found a
show-stopper.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a 2-3 zone defense midway through the second half to
try to frustrate Weber State forward Harold ``The Show'' Arceneaux,
who had 21 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   Arceneaux went 3 of 11 from the field in regulation and 1 of 4
in overtime as the sixth-seeded Gators wore down the Big Sky
champions and won, 82-74, Saturday in an NCAA West Regional
second-round game at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Florida (22-8) advances to a regional semifinal match-up against
10th-seeded Gonzaga on Thursday at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Switching to the zone got them to stand around a little bit,''
Donovan said of the 14th-seeded Wildcats. ``We knew their quickness
would cause us problems while they were fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had to play man-to-man the first 30 minutes to
set the pace and wear them down. You allow Arceneaux and (guard
Eddie) Gill to be fresh at the end, they are good enough to beat
you by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Arceneaux almost single-handedly beat third-seeded North
Carolina in the first round, getting 36 points, tying the most ever
scored against the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever nicknamed him `The Show' did him a disservice,''
Gators freshman guard Teddy Dupay said. ``He's the best player I've
ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators used their full-court press to try to tire Arceneaux
and then rotated two or three defenders against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to limit his number of touches,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work in the first half. Arceneaux hit 8 of 12 field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to make some big money some day,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Gators went to the zone in the second half, Weber
State started standing around on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Florida rallied for a 58-53 lead and seemed to have the game in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not moving the ball,'' said Weber State Coach Ron
Abegglen, who apparently has coached his last game for the
Wildcats. ``We were not cutting players to the holes. We were not
aware of the shot clock.''
</P>
<P>
   During several of the Wildcats' possessions late in the game,
they had to throw up desperation shots because the shot clock was
about to run out.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with eight seconds left in regulation and
Florida leading, 68-66. But Gators forward Kenyan Weaks fouled
Wildcats guard Noel Jackson on a wild three-point attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made 2 of 3 free throws to send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give Jackson a lot of credit,'' Donovan said.
``He's a veteran guy, and, obviously, it was not an intelligent
play by Kenyan Weaks.''
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, the Gators took control from the outset. Center
Greg Stolt scored back-to-back baskets inside for a four-point
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Weber State, 25-8, made only two field goals in overtime and was
forced to foul late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fatigued at the end,'' Abegglen said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
