<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-GONZAGA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA MAKES A NAME FOR IT SELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Jesuit priest sitting on the end of Gonzaga's
bench compared the enormity of the event to the first time he
witnessed a cow-milking contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been so giddy since I was 6 years old and went to
the Illinois State Fair in Du Quoin, and that was 60 years ago,''
Father Tony Lehmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with the agricultural theme, Don Monson, father of the
Gonzaga coach, congratulated center Jeremy Eaton, the team's
resident cowboy, by saying, ``I bet this is even better than roping
steers.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10th-seeded Bulldogs' 82-74 victory over second-seeded and
Pac-10 champion Stanford in the second round of the NCAA West
regional on Saturday at KeyArena sent them to Thursday's semifinal
round at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It also put Gonzaga (27-6) on the basketball map.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a long road for them to get recognition, for
people to learn how to pronounce `Gon-zah-guh,' '' Coach Dan Monson
said. ``People now know we're not just a freak show . . . This is
not a Cinderella story. It's about us being a good basketball
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Matt Santangelo, who scored a team-high 22 points, said
more than just the school gets mispronounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows where Spokane is, or how to pronounce it,'' he
said. ``They said we were from `Spo-kanny' one time in Alaska.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, Final Four participants a year ago, led only once _ at
1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal, the fourth and final Pac-10 team to be eliminated
from the NCAA tournament, caught the Bulldogs once in the second
half, but never slowed down their three guards _ Santangelo, Richie
Frahm and Quentin Hall, who combined for 51 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt coming to the tournament they were the team in the
bracket that was scary because a lot of people didn't know about
them, but I knew they were legit,'' said Stanford Coach Mike
Montgomery, whose team ended its season at 26-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping Minnesota would beat them (in the first round).
We get caught up in the name game, but they have very skilled
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their guards are very confident . . . The thing (the Bulldogs)
have to do is realize they're good. They play the way they did
today, they're capable of beating a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The much-taller Cardinal, one of the most physical teams in the
nation, was supposed to have the big edge inside. But Stanford was
outrebounded, 47-33.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most we've been outrebounded all year,'' Montgomery
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, Gonzaga's 5-foot-8 point guard, had a team-high eight
rebounds. Only Stanford's Mark Madsen, a 6-9 forward, had more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm known to rebound,'' Hall said, smiling. ``I'm about 6-8
when it comes to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, West Coast Conference champions, killed Stanford
with three-point shots, hitting 11 of 20. Santangelo, the best
Gonzaga player since Utah Jazz guard John Stockton, hit all three
of his attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford senior guard Arthur Lee, meanwhile, was only 6 of 18
from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not kid ourselves,'' Santangelo said. ``We're still
`John Stockton U.' We definitely have created our own identity, but
he's the best there is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal was forced to foul in the final two minutes to try
to cut into Gonzaga's 10-point lead. But the Bulldogs hit 13 of 16
free throws down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga's players said they expected a big crowd to be waiting
for them when the arrived back in Spokane today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little different,'' Frahm said. ``We'll probably go
celebrate with a tall glass of milk.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
