<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-SEASON-EN     03-14 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-SEASON-END-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDCATS: THE BEST AND WORST OF TIMES  
 HOPE, SENIORS' LEGACY SURVIVE UPSETTING FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ In final analysis, Arizona's basketball season was
better than expected at the beginning, but worst than expected at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the Wildcats overachieved with a senior point guard
who never had started but became a first-team All-American, and
with five freshmen, three of whom started.
</P>
<P>
   It was anticipated that UA would take a step backward on the
national scene, perhaps being a top-20 team rather than the top-10
team it had been while winning the national title in 1997 and while
reaching the Elite Eight in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a rebuilding year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats reached the NCAA Tournament, keeping alive a
15-year streak _ the second-longest of all time _ with a 22-6
regular-season mark. They were the No. 4 seed in the Midwest
Region. Advancing to the Sweet 16 had become a reachable goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then the people most responsible for the overachievement, point
guard Jason Terry and senior center A.J. Bramlett, came up empty
Friday in a 61-60 first-round upset loss to 13th-seeded Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona wasn't alone. Twelve times in the opening 32 games, the
lower seeded team won, a tournament record for opening-round
upsets.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.T. and I worked hard for this program,'' Bramlett said. ``I
don't think it's going to sink in for a few days that this was our
last game together. With all the inexperience, we really had a good
season for the team we had. We should have done more here in the
tournament, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry and Bramlett played on teams that went 11-3 in four years
at the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have relied on the two seniors to carry a tremendous
load,'' said UA Coach Lute Olson. ``It's a shame it had to end in
the first game in their last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the great things they did in their time here, the most
important is the legacy they leave with these freshmen _ and not
just in the won-loss records, but in leading with their work ethic
every day in practice. That is going to pay off for us in the years
to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The five freshmen will be the heart of the team next year. A
sixth member of the freshman class, Luke Walton, was red-shirted
after suffering a fractured foot in preseason. He will move into
the class with incoming freshman guards Jason Gardner of
Indianapolis North Central High and Gilbert Arenas of Van Nuys,
Calif., Grant High.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner (5-foot-11, 170 pounds) is regarded as the No. 1 point
guard prospect in the country by ``Prep Star'' magazine. He is
expected to step into Terry's position and start as a freshman, as
Mike Bibby did the year he took UA to the NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Arenas (6-3, 193 pounds) is listed as the No. 4 shooting guard
prospect by ``Prep Star.'' He will challenge Ruben Douglas at
shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   Walton (6-8, 229 pounds), son of basketball Hall of Famer Bill
Walton, returned to practice last month. Olson said Walton could
have played comparably with the other freshmen then, but he didn't
want to waste a season for Walton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luke is as dependable a guy as we've had here doing rehab,''
Olson said. ``He worked very hard. He doesn't look like he lost a
whole lot other than conditioning. He can still do the things he
had done so well up to the time he got hurt _ his passing, his
understanding of the game, setting backscreens, downscreens. It's
just amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on that, I might prescribe a couple of months off for a
couple of our other guys. It's obvious when he was on the sidelines
he wasn't counting light bulbs in McKale. He was paying attention
to what's going on. We were not going to use him, but he could have
played pretty quickly at the four and made up some ground on people
in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton said he had no pain in his foot for the first time in
about a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a frustrating year for me, but I'm sure it's going to
help me long-term to red-shirt,'' Walton said. ``I need to be
stronger and quicker. This year made me realize what I need to do
for next year. I was looking forward to playing with this freshman
class. It was a great class this year. It's going to be a great one
next year, too.''
</P>
<P>
   This might have been Olson's best freshman class. Power forward
Michael Wright, the Pac-10 freshman of the year, will be among the
top players in the conference next season and possibly an
All-American candidate. He has proven that he can get the tough
rebound and can score from the low post with proficiency. He will
be a go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is going to have a great career here,'' Olson said.
``He did not play like a freshman.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Jefferson, who started at small forward, might be the
most athletic in the class. He will have to be a more consistent
scorer and defender as a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a taste of what it's all about this year,'' Wright
said. ``I just feel bad for our seniors because J.T. and A.J. have
meant so much to our program. I wish we could have sent them out
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned a lot from them, and we'll learn a lot from this
experience. I know we'll come back hungry next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The X-factor is center Loren Woods, a 7-foot-2 transfer from
Wake Forest who sat out this season. He will be a junior. Woods was
a freshman All-American and a member of the Atlantic Coast
Conference all-rookie team in 1997 when he was billed as the next
Tim Duncan. Whether he has the strength and work ethic to pick up
where Bramlett left off remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   This was a young UA team, but the next one will be even younger.
Joining the eight freshmen and sophomores along with Woods will be
forward Justin Wessel, a junior, and forward Eugene Edgerson, who
will be the only senior.
</P>
<P>
   If Gardner is anything close to being the next Bibby, as many
are touting him to be, the Wildcats will have a reasonable chance
of posting their 13th 20-win season and their 16th successive NCAA
Tournament appearance.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll still be regarded as being a year away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
