<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS USUAL, PARCELLS TO SKIP NFL EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -  &UR; Bill Parcells won't need a note from his doctor to
miss this week's NFL meetings at the Arizona Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   His pulse is OK. He doesn't have a desert hangover. The stress
from sipping cocktails around the pool won't be too much for him.
</P>
<P>
   It's on Parcells' schedule every spring to skip the league's
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine coaches and Coach  &UR; Al Davis of the Raiders show up
regularly, while Parcells, bigger than the league, almost always is
a no-show. He heads for his winter home in Jupiter, Fla., to get
some `R and R.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells always finds an excuse not to come and gets away with
it, just as he got his doctor to excuse him from last month's Pro
Bowl. He wasn't on his death bed. He just didn't want to take the
long flight to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The Ahi gets away with it because the league refuses to force
him to attend.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad Parcells doesn't find time to fit the league
meetings into his busy schedule. He misses some great
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Last time the owners met in Phoenix, four years ago,  &UR; Jimmy
Johnson and  &UR; Barry Switzer carried on a civil conversation. A year
earlier, Johnson, then coach of the Cowboys, stormed out of the
meetings in Orlando, Fla., after Dallas owner  &UR; Jerry Jones had his
own version of midnight madness, announcing to those in the bar
that 500 coaches could have won the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Johnson bolted from the meetings and headed to his boat
in Florida, coaching his last game with the Cowboys. This year's
session could be just as lively.
</P>
<P>
   Will  &UR; Tom Cruise and  &UR; Nicole Kidman, both clothed rather than
how they dressed in their new film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' show up in
support of proposed Los Angeles owner  &UR; Michael Ovitz's &UR; bid for an
expansion team?
</P>
<P>
   Will agent  &UR; Johnnie Cochran roam the Biltmore's lobby to try to
drum up business for clients? Will Scottsdale resident  &UR; Fred
Goldman let him know that the Valley is too big for both of them? &QL; 
Teeing off &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expect a lot of opposition at the meetings to the NFL
competition committee's recommendation to change kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, trying to boost kickoff returns, is proposing
teams take over on the 25-yard line instead of the 20 after
touchbacks.
</P>
<P>
   `You are rewarding teams that have poor returners,'' one NFC
executive said. `You will just let kickoffs bounce into the end
zone and take over on the 25. It also punishes teams who have
kickers with strong legs. I can't see this passing.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition committee also considered eliminating the
kicking tee, but that failed.
</P>
<P>
   Teams will experiment without a tee during the preseason. &QL; 
Sweet deal &QL; 
Former Cardinals offensive tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown, who signed a
three-year $10.75 million deal with the Browns, said Cleveland
officials never promised him he would be the first player
introduced at the Browns' preseason opener.
</P>
<P>
   Browns general manager  &UR; Dwight Clark concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lomas Brown turns out to be the first guy introduced, it
will be because it'll be the day the left tackle is introduced
first,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he never told Brown he would try to steer stadium
business to Brown's parking management company, an enticement that
could be a salary-cap violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lomas joked that, sure, he'd like to drum up business for his
company,'' Clark said. ``Lomas asked if he could bid on the parking
contract for the new stadium. I said, `Sure.' No promises were
made. You can't do that with a player. But bidding on it? I said,
`As far as I knew, yeah, he could bid on it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clark also said Brown wasn't offered a job in the organization
when his career was over as has been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about it &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Please put the rumors to rest that the Cardinals are trying to
trade up with Cleveland for the first pick overall in the draft to
get Texas running back  &UR; Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The latest one has the Cardinals trading four picks and running
back
 &UR; Adrian Murrell to the Browns. Then, there's the one in which the
Cardinals trade the eighth and 21st picks overall and Murrell to
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns aren't trading the first pick. They plan to use it on
a quarterback and have attended the workouts of  &UR; Tim Couch of
Kentucky,
 &UR; Akili Smith of Oregon and  &UR; Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the Browns want to drop down to the Cardinals' pick at
No. 8? They could lose a shot at all three quarterbacks and
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals love Williams, but they have no interest in paying
for the first pick in the draft. They remember what it cost them
two of the past three years to sign defensive ends  &UR; Simeon Rice and
 &UR; Andre
 &UR; Wadsworth, both of whom were picked third overall. &QL; 
Briefly &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just wait until actress  &UR; Ali Landry, girlfriend of former
Cardinals quarterback  &UR; Stoney Case and selected as one of ``People
Magazine's'' 50 most beautiful people in the world in 1998, samples
the nightlife in Indianapolis. Cracker Barrel is big. Bob Evans is
bigger. They're not Spagos.
</P>
<P>
   The best wedding present former Cardinals linebacker
 &UR; Eric Hill, who got married this weekend in Houston, received was
his release from the St. Louis Rams. He never felt comfortable
there and was glad to be a salary-cap casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why the movement to have Turkey Day games in places other
than Detroit and Dallas won't fly: Do you wake up Thanksgiving
morning in eager anticipation of the Ravens-Saints match-up?
</P>
<P>
   There is no truth to the rumor the expansion Browns have offered
their next prospective free agent a discount on car washes near
their new stadium. But he'll get, along with his signing bonus, a
set of windshield wiper blades, two No. 2 pencils and a chance to
be the last player introduced at the preseason opener in Canton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona welcome home to Rams owner  &UR; Georgia
 &UR; Frontiere, the Sedona resident who hopes her new magic crystals and
pet red rocks can help the Rams rally from being the NFL's
losingest franchise in the 1990s. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
