r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MEETINGS-REPLAY-A     03-14 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEETINGS-REPLAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL LIKELY TO OK REPLAY  
 OLD CONCERNS ARE ADDRESSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Arizona Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill's eight-year
winning streak appears to be over.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill, who, along with the New York Giants, always has opposed
the use of instant replay, knows fewer and fewer owners are on his
side.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when instant replay is proposed at this week's NFL
meetings, which begin today at the Arizona Biltmore, the measure is
expected to pass for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we came so close,'' said Seattle Seahawks Coach
Mike Holmgren, co-chairman of the NFL competition committee that
has come up with the latest replay proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, it has been close and it will be close again.
But this year I think we have a real chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the measure could be the biggest reason it passes.
Last season was marred by many controversial calls, including a
phantom, game-winning touchdown scored by New York Jets quarterback
Vinny Testaverde in a 32-31 victory over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood of last season changed the minds of some teams who
traditionally vote against replay,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, 21 owners voted for replay, two shy of passing. With
expansion Cleveland being added this year, 24 votes are needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills, Tampa Bay Buccaneers and San Diego Chargers,
all of whom voted against replay a year ago, are expected to change
their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Even Giants owner Wellington Mara is considering voting for a
plan this year that includes a challenge system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear all about this new technology and everything,'' Mara
said. ``If I'm convinced they've done something to correct the
faults we had before (with instant replay), then there's a chance
I'll vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill, Mara's close friend, doesn't enter the meetings as
open-minded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave the game on the field,'' Bidwill said. ``Don't interrupt
the flow of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren, an ardent replay supporter, thinks the flow of the
game will not be adversely affected in the proposed system.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is a blend of two systems that have been used in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   For 56 minutes of the game _ all but the last two minutes of
each half _ coaches will be able to challenge calls. Each team will
be allowed two challenges a game.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two minutes of each half, an official in the press
box will control the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The referee on the field will remain in control at all times. He
will view the replay and determine whether the challenge should be
upheld.
</P>
<P>
   If the challenge is not upheld, the team loses a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some coaches who felt funny about the timeouts,''
Holmgren said. ``Part of the problem about the timeouts was what if
you used all of your timeouts and then you don't have timeout for a
big play at the end of the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never going to get all of (the coaches) to vote on
something dealing with timeouts. But there are six timeouts in a
game, and you only have two challenges. You get the timeout back if
you win the challenge, so you can make a pretty good case the
challenges won't affect the timeout situation. Plus, by eliminating
the coaches' decision-making the last two minutes, I think we've
dealt with that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren thinks another selling point is that there will
90-second limit on challenges. When replay was used from 1986
through '91, teams complained about long delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that bothered people originally, like the pace of
the game, we've answered that,'' Holmgren said. ``No one wants to
disrupt the game the way it was disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren said he always has been a replay supporter because ``I
think if you have a chance to correct play that's wrong, then why
not? No one wants a wrong play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People uncomfortable with someone up in press box making type
of decisions, we've answered that. The referee is going to make the
decision. We answered the idea we didn't want a challenge system to
be arbitrarily used for strategy at the end of the game. That can't
happen because the replay official in the booth initiates the
challenges in the final two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the technology that would be used hasn't been
determined. A handheld digit recorder is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches could make their challenges by hitting a buzzer or
throwing a flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get this thing through, we can wave flags,''
Holmgren said. ``I don't care what we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
