<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR DROUGHT'S EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - OK, let's look at one of the worst drought years in
Arizona history.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance of huge closures of Arizona's forests to
prevent wildfires. In 1996, the year before a dry spell ended,
large portions of the forests were closed to the public before
Memorial Day to prevent forest fires.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Wildfires were lower than the year before, mainly
because they were confined to lightning strikes, not human
campfires and cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   This year the situation may be worse. This could be the worst
year ever. The forests this year could be closed to the public well
before Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening with wildlife issues?
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Game and Fish Department doesn't want to close
fishing at a bunch of mountain lakes. The decreased sale of fishing
licenses costs the agency a lot of money. Since it's not financed
by general fund taxes, those license fees are important to the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through the process of seeing which lakes are most
desirable to the public,'' said Larry Riley, chief of fisheries for
Game and Fish. ``We have to see which waters won't be available to
the public.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants the public to look for waters they don't usually use
during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   If a number of mountain lakes close, he'd like the public to
look at Colorado River lakes, which got huge inputs of water from
heavy snowfall in the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Lakes Powell and Mead have great potentials for fishing this
summer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The department is in the process of predicting which mountain
lakes will go dry, which will be marginal and which can sustain
populations of trout.
</P>
<P>
   The department is prepared to stock trout at heavy levels _ and
early _ to avoid losing hatchery fish and to make fishing on other
lakes as successful as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The news isn't good for wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The production of acorns was excellent last year because of the
rains. Everything from deer to bears profited from these
high-calorie, high-fat nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The female bears went into hibernation in great shape,'' said
John Phelps, furbearer biologist. ``Their cubs (about 4 pounds now)
are in great shape. But I expect by the end of summer that few cubs
will survive. It doesn't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that because the lack of food from the dry year, bears
will cover much larger territories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be active much longer in the day because food is
scarce,'' Phelps said. ``Because they'll run a larger range,
they'll have to work much harder. They're eating machines when they
come out of hibernation. By ranging wider, they're much more likely
to encounter humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps said that unlike bears, which are omnivorous, the
mountain lions are likely to suffer more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The are predominantly meat eaters,'' he said. ``They'll
sometimes scavage if necessary, but primarily they kill what they
eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that nothing starves to death with an
empty stomach. It'll eat a hubcap if it has to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lions will turn to dogs, cats, anything they can kill. The dry
weather reduces the prey base. The predator works harder. It'll
settle for less. Lions will settle for jackrabbits and skunks
(instead of deer). They'll take what they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, he said, lions aren't particularly aggressive toward
humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on the other hand,'' he said. ``bears are attracted to
people's food.''
</P>
<P>
   That means they'll invade camps and trash cans in the mountains.
It also means as they become accustomed to humans and lose their
fear of them, there could be some major confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a definite chance of confrontations this year,''
Phelps said. ``Until the monsoons come (in late summer), we'll have
definite problems.'' That also means that small mammals, a
dry-weather source of food for lions, foxes and coyotes, will be
scarce. Even the plants that black bears usually eat will be hard
to find. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
