<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARTH WHO? HE'S JUST A `K' TO GIANTS' TAVAREZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If only  &UR; Puff Daddy had been batting . . .
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco pitcher  &UR; Julian Tavarez thought he was doing the
right thing when he struck out country singer  &UR; Garth Brooks
Thursday, and he found it odd that some of the 5,293 fans at Peoria
Stadium booed him.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out Tavarez may be the one soul in the Valley who has
never heard of Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the guy,'' he said. ``The way he was swinging, I
thought he was a pitcher. I listen to rap.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rough outing overall for Tavarez, who gave up five runs
and four hits in a 14-8 loss to the Padres. And it only got worse.
</P>
<P>
   He later discovered that a teammate had put shaving cream in his
new shoes.
</P>
<P>
   If Tavarez thought he had it bad, how about Chicago Cubs batting
practice pitcher  &UR; Jeff Davenport, who felt bad enough about hitting
pitcher  &UR; Kevin Tapani in the wrist with a pitch during workouts
recently.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Cubs official, Davenport found a note in his
locker requesting a 9 a.m. meeting with General Manager  &UR; Ed Lynch,
``to discuss Kevin Tapani's X-ray.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport panicked. It turned out Tapani was behind the stunt
and had Lynch's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Brewers pitcher  &UR; Jim Abbott may lead the Cactus League
in interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, who is attempting a comeback after taking off 1997 and
spending much of 1998 in the minors, has been interviewed by CBS,
NBC, ESPN (twice), ``USA Today,'' ``Baseball America'' and the
``Sporting News.''
</P>
<P>
   His solid start only makes his story more intriguing. He has
allowed one earned run and six hits in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Overheard at Peoria Stadium recently:
</P>
<P>
   Fan to Mariners  &UR; Jay Buhner, who is coming back from  &UR; Tommy John
elbow surgery: ``Jay, how do you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner: ``Aw, I feel terrible. My elbow's fine, but I feel
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Buhner, his rehabilitation is going so well he could
start in right field on opening day. At least ``he'' thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had him penciled in to start the season as a first
baseman/designated hitter, but he progressed so well they OK'd him
to play left, believing it might put less stress on his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctors think playing right might be pushing it, but Buhner
appears ready to make his best sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The first time San Francisco Manager  &UR; Dusty Baker met
then-Giants newcomer  &UR; Marvin Benard, the player was taking cuts at
a minor-league complex batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your name?'' Baker asked
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvin L. Benard, sir,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Benard pointed out his initials to Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``M.L.B. That means I was born to play major-league baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the meeting was memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle infielder  &UR; David Bell is the son of former major-league
third baseman  &UR; Buddy Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the day: Colorado's  &UR; Larry Walker, on whether his $75
million contract will change him: ``I'll still be the same idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clairol might consider sponsoring the Cactus League. A rash of
players have dyed their hair. The latest is Colorado's  &UR; Dante
 &UR; Bichette, who ignored the popular trend of blond to go red.
</P>
<P>
   Position battle of the week: The Nos. 4 and 5 spots in Seattle's
rotation. Mariners coaches said they hoped to make a decision by
March 22 or 23.
</P>
<P>
   After  &UR; Jeff Fassero,  &UR; Jamie Moyer and  &UR; Ken Cloude, it gets
interesting.
 &UR; Bill Swift and  &UR; Butch Henry are among those in camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners also are looking at  &UR; John Halama and  &UR; Freddy
Garcia, who both came from Houston in the  &UR; Randy Johnson trade and
have performed well. But are they good enough to start? Both also
are bullpen candidates.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Seattle Post-Intelligencer,'' Henry has a
clause in his contract that he can terminate it if he is not named
a starter out of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth spot in the Angels' rotation appears to be a battle
among  &UR; Omar Olivares,  &UR; Jason Dickson and  &UR; Jarrod Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   It's official: On the heels of an injury-plagued season,
Milwaukee outfielder  &UR; Marquis Grissom is back, in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a vote for  &UR; Darrin Jackson, one of baseball's nice guys,
to make the Chicago White Sox roster. At 35, the non-roster invitee
is hardly a shoo-in. &QL; 
Staff writer Paola Boivin can be reached at 602-444-8956 or at
Paola.Boivin(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
