<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS RESPOND TO CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Rob Blake spoke and his teammates listened.
</P>
<P>
   It was only one game, but it was a small step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings are to make a move for a playoff berth in the final
five weeks of the NHL season, they will have to take many more
steps similar to the one they took Saturday night, when they
defeated the Vancouver Canucks 3-1 before a Forum crowd of 14,348.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we have to play to win,'' said Blake, the Kings
captain, who had called a players-only meeting two days earlier to
try to spark his teammates for a last-ditch playoff run. ``We're
not talented enough not to work hard to win.''
</P>
<P>
   How the Kings (25-36-5) scored their goals was almost as
significant as the fact they won their second straight game and
moved to within five points of Edmonton and Calgary, which share
the final Western Conference playoff berth. On the first goal, 1:42
into the game, Jozef Stumpel scored after Yanic Perreault
outmuscled defenseman Mattias Ohlund for the puck behind the
Canucks' goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first goal was all Yanic,'' Blake said. ``The important
thing was Yanic was sticking up for himself. We want to see guys
with the care, the want-to-win. That's big for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perreault said, ``The guys understand we still have a chance to
make the playoffs and we believe we have a good hockey team in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second goal, Donald Audette camped out in front of the
Canucks' net _ a place the Kings have often feared to tread _ and
deflected a point shot by Philippe Boucher past goalie Kevin Weekes
on a power play with 1:42 left in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   On the third goal _ with 4:02 to play and with the Canucks
(20-36-11) within one after a power-play goal by Markus Naslund
five minutes earlier _ Craig Johnson knocked Ohlund off the puck,
leading to another Stumpel goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in desperate times,'' Johnson said, ``and we're playing
desperate hockey. Everybody is starting to believe in each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings outshot Vancouver 34-12 in the first two periods. They
became too passive in the third period for coach Larry Robinson's
taste but held on nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The players appeared to respond to Robinson's decision to heed
the request of Blake and alternate captains Luc Robitaille and Doug
Bodger, who had asked the coach this week to stick with the lineup
that had played in Tuesday's 4-2 victory over Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to at least listen to the people working for you,''
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said: ``We had to get across the lines of communication.
I'll run the dressing room, I'll take that responsibility, but
Larry has got to respect what I have to say. That's the good thing
about Larry _ he's willing to listen. He doesn't see everything
that's happening in the dressing room. If I can relate that to him,
then everybody is on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if communication had broken down, Blake said: ``I don't
know if it was broken, but if you start losing, it's difficult.
With the team we have, we've got to play one way and that's the way
we've played the last two games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will have to play that way for the majority of the
remaining 16 games if they are to have a chance to make the
playoffs. But for the moment, a seldom-seen emotion _ optimism _
seems to have found its way into the Kings dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing,'' Blake said, ``is we've got to win some games
to give us a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
