<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD, LEWIS DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bible says, ``Pride cometh before the fall.'' As
Evander Holyfield learned Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, it doesn't say anything
about ``Holyfield in three.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, however, it must say something about giving a
long-time friend a break when he needs it most, because that's what
the born-again heavyweight champion got Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield spent 12 rounds trying unsuccessfully to find a way to
get inside the long defense of World Boxing Council champion Lennox
Lewis and ended up with a most unpopular draw for his efforts, a
decision lustily booed by the crowd of 21,284.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stanley Christoudoulou scored the fight 116-113 for Lewis,
Jean Williams had it 115-113 for Holyfield and the English judge,
Larry O'Connell, scored the bout a 115-115 draw. The Globe card had
Lewis taking a razor-thin 115-114 decision after giving away Rounds
8 through 11 by simply choosing not to punch and then coming on to
win the final round and the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Lewis won the last round on all three judges' cards as
well, but had he not he would have lost his third of the title
despite the crowd's opinion to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely close,'' admitted Holyfield's trainer, Don
Turner. ``I thought we won the last four rounds to win the fight
but I'm not complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he wasn't for good reason, but his counterpart in
Lewis's corner certainly was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox controlled the fight,'' Emanuel Steward brayed. ``It
wasn't even close. This is what is killing boxing. It was a total
mismatch. Holyfield couldn't even be his sparring partner.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be a bit much, but certainly he couldn't knock Lewis
out despite having brazenly predicted he would in Round 3, claiming
he had been told by God it would end that way. Something must have
gotten lost in translation, however, because Holyfield won the
round but came nowhere near hurting Lewis either then or at any
other time.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis didn't really hurt Holyfield either, but he did rock him
several times, cut him on the bridge of the nose and under his
cheek, and successfully kept him at long range through most of the
evening, using his half-foot reach advantage to make it nearly
impossible for Holyfield to get inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got robbed,'' Lewis (34-1-1) said angrily. ``I controlled
the entire fight. I'm so disappointed. I wasn't going to leave here
with just one belt. I'm the undisputed heavyweight champion of the
world. What happened in there is what you call politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my time to shine and they ripped me off. He should give
me those two belts because he knows they're mine. Automatic rematch
next month, but I doubt he'll box me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Little happened in the first round beyond Lewis occasionally
landing his jab and a short uppercut while Holyfield (36-3-1)
picked Lewis up off the ground and put him on his shoulder when
Lewis tried to lean too heavily on him during a clinch.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis continued to throw his jab stiffy and hurt Holyfield
early in the second round and Holyfield looked a bit bothered by
the difficulty he was having finding any openings to get inside as
Lewis kept him at bay as the third round dawned.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no evidence in the first two rounds of an
impending knockout, but Holyfield suddenly began to press Lewis
early in that round and twice seemed to hurt him with left hooks
that forced Lewis to slide backwards, his chest heaving. In the
end, Holyfield was unable to come through on his bold promise but
for the first time he had made Lewis taste leather and the WBC
champion did not react well to it, slowing down and spending most
of the round trying to clinch and grab.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's reach continued to be a problem for Holyfield, however,
who kept looking for ways to get inside but couldn't find many. It
was at this juncture that a small cut opened along the bridge of
Holyfield's nose and although it caused him no problems it was the
first sign of the distress he found himself in.
</P>
<P>
   Clearer signs appeared in the fifth round when Lewis countered a
wild Holyfield left with a short right that hurt Holyfield and sent
him sagging into the ropes. Lewis tried to cautiously press that
advantage and seemed to have Holyfield in some trouble but was
unable to hurt him further and by the end of the round Holyfield
had scored with two flurries himself.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield then rapped Lewis with a left hook when Lewis dropped
his gloves early in the sixth round in disdain and Lewis's eyes
rocked along with his head, but he wisely grabbed Holyfield and
tied him up and went back to keeping his guard up and Holyfield at
long range as the first half of the fight ended with Lewis holding
a clear advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The two got into another wrestling match as the seventh round
opened and both fell to the floor. When Holyfield got up his left
cheek was cut and he was clearly angry and Lewis used this
emotional response to pick him apart throughout the round with
several more big right hands and a right uppercut that shook
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old International Boxing Federation-World Boxing
Association champion seemed to be getting older by the minute (or
by the Lewis right hand), but when Lewis took most of the eighth
round off Holyfield managed to get close enough to finally land
enough punches to win the round, although he did little damage.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old Briton continued in neutral in the ninth, 10th,
and 11th, and Holyfield didn't do much more to pick up the pace but
just enough to squeak out those rounds. But the conclusion was so
unsatisfactory that light heavyweight champion Roy Jones was left
shaking his head, saying, ``I'm ashamed of boxing tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
