<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ-CAWLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUIZ DOES HIS PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Ruiz didn't get much of a workout
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, but he did get some extra television time.
</P>
<P>
   The Chelsea, Mass., heavyweight needed less than four rounds to
rid himself of Mario Cawley in the opening televised fight on
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight
unification match at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz knocked Cawley to the floor four times and sliced open his
foe's right cheek before their bout was stopped at 1:04 of the
fourth to firmly cement the World Boxing Council's No. 1 challenger
ranking he now holds. But Ruiz may have done more damage to himself
than he did to Cawley when he bruised his left hand in the second
round on Cawley's head.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the fight that hand was swollen and discolored and
Ruiz spent a half-hour soaking it in a bucket of ice in the locker
room as he discussed his short night's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised when he got up a couple of times,'' Ruiz
(34-3, 25 KOs) said. ``But I just kept trying to do my job. After
the second round I really couldn't jab any more because of my hand,
but at this point I have to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Do it he did, maintaining his position as the mandatory
challenger for the WBC title in the fall while gaining some
much-needed national exposure against the kind of opponent you
fight once you've reached that lofty station _ a guy with a good
record but no chance to beat you.
</P>
<P>
   Cawley's record fell to 21-2, but those losses both came by
early knockout and in consecutive fights. The first was when
Lawrence Clay-Bey stopped him a year ago, and he had not fought
again until Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. Some would argue that he still hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz dominated from the opening round with Cawley's most
successful strategy being looping one arm behind Ruiz and holding
him when he tried to punch. This limited Ruiz's ability to land
early, but by midway through the second round he had solved this
mystery, dropping him with a solid left and right.
</P>
<P>
   Twice more Ruiz drove Cawley to the floor in the third round and
then landed another perfectly timed combination to open the fourth
that sent Cawley sprawling with no apparent interest in getting up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the night, James Page (24-3) kept his World Boxing
Association welterweight title with a unanimous decision over Sam
Garr (25-3). The judges scored the bout 117-111, 116-113, and
119-108 . . . Fernando Vargas easily made the first defense of the
International Boxing Federation junior middleweight title when he
stopped England's Howard Clarke at 2:29 of the fourth round.
Vargas, who won the title last December from Yory Boy Campas,
dropped Clarke (26-11-2) four times in the fourth round before the
bout was mercifully stopped, bringing to Clarke's mind the old
adage, ``Better late than never.'' ``I couldn't get into it at
first because no one was here,'' Vargas (16-0, 16 KOs) said . . .
WBA flyweight champion Hugo Soto did not fare as well as Vargas in
his defense efforts however. After losing the second round, 10-7,
on all three judges' cards when he was dropped three times, Soto
walked out for the third round and was knocked cold in 33 seconds
when Leo Gamez (31-6-1, 23 KOs) unloaded on him with a string of
punches. ``He just caught me by surprise,'' Soto (50-6-2) said.
</P>
</TEXT>
