<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS DERAILED IN BUFFALO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ The ``I Love New York'' bumper stickers the Bruins
stuck on their traveling bags Friday night, when they tap danced
triumphantly down Broadway, turned yellow, cracked, and peeled away
in the wind of western New York Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in a 3-1 loss to
the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soft goals,'' said coach Pat Burns, mildly disgusted by the
performance of his Bruins. ``We've stunk the joint out against
Buffalo all year. And you can't win when you give up soft goals.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing outrageously bad about what the Bruins did
inside Marine Midland Arena, where a sellout crowd of 18,595 saw
their Sabres add a slightly tighter grip on their hold of seventh
place in the Eastern Conference standings. The goals were soft, in
the sense that they came with only mild resistance from the
defense. The Bruins made their moves, often were around the puck,
but too often didn't engage in enough of a fight to fend off
disaster. They were sparring. The Sabres were fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The win gave the Sabres 73 points _ 5 more than the
eighth-placed Bruins. Meanwhile, Florida edged Tampa Bay, 1-0, and
pulled within a point of the Bruins. It gets tighter by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it's going to be the rest of the way, a total
dogfight for the last playoff spot,'' said Steve Heinze, who scored
Boston's lone goal _ his third strike in two nights. ``And when
it's this tight, minor errors kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three goals the Sabres scored, only the first, a pinpoint
Michael Peca wrister, was a work of beauty. As referee Bill
McCreary whistled a delayed call on Ray Bourque, the ever-digging
Peca broke into the right circle with a Vaclav Varada dish and
whistled his shot high over Byron Dafoe. The Sabres led, 1-0, with
4:06 gone in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there was some fatigue in our game, but I never use
that as an excuse,'' said Dafoe, whose own winning streak, the same
as the club's, was snapped at two. ``(Friday night) was such an
emotional high, you try to come in the next night and match that _
but the intensity wasn't the same.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, the Bruins pulled off a stunning 5-4 victory over
the Rangers Friday with four goals in the third period. Here, where
life clicks along at 33 1/3 RPMs to Manhattan's 78 (kids, your
folks will explain), the Bruins never got their game uptempo.
Worse, they too often found themselves a beat behind the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make a mistake against them and it's costly,'' said Heinze.
``They don't make a lot of mistakes, so you can't. And when you do,
they capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the biggest of the mistakes arrived, however, Heinze
hammered home his 16th, set up nicely by Joe Thornton on the power
play. Jumbo Joe fed into the slot and Heinze, shooting from the
moment he left the hotel, drilled it past former UMass-Lowell
goalie Dwayne Roloson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept saying, `Get the puck on the net, get the rebounds,'
'' said Heinze. ``A lot of times (Roloson) didn't look pretty out
there, but he was making the saves.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1-1 tie carried into the third period, but disappeared only
68 ticks off the clock when Michal Grosek slipped his check and
knocked in a Miroslav Satan relay at the right post. Hal Gill went
on a chase to get Satan, Grosek moved into the open space in front,
and the 2-1 lead was behind Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:19, Brian Holzinger finished off the Black 'n' Gold,
trailing into the slot and knocking home a Geoff Sanderson feed.
The clever Sanderson made the play with a dazzling dash through the
middle, curling off the right post and feathering his velvet feed
to the onrushing Holzinger. Dave Ellett and Mattias Timander were
the victims on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never effort. It's never a lack of effort,'' said the
mildly peeved Burns, knowing that every point squandered could turn
into a festering mess here in the last month. ``It's concentration
things, and if you aren't prepared to battle, they'll take it away
from you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
