<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC APPROACHING DAY OF RECKONING 
</HEADLINE>
 MEETING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS AND MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have been warned by their septuagenarian leader to be ready
for pain _ and profound change. When the International Olympic
Committee meets this week in a special full session at Olympic
headquarters in Switzerland, the members are likely to make more
significant and difficult decisions in two days than they have in
105 years.
</P>
<P>
   Besides expelling half a dozen colleagues beyond the four who
have already resigned amid the Salt Lake City bidding scandal, the
100-plus members also must put embattled president Juan Antonio
Samaranch to a confidence vote, decide whether to deny themselves
the right to pick future host cities, create an independent ethics
panel, and begin talking about radical structural reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do our best to respond to all the issues that
have been raised,'' says vice president Richard Pound of Canada,
``and see if we have to reinvent ourselves for the new
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the rest of the world weren't watching, what the IOC
will undertake Wednesday and Thursday will be an extraordinary step
for a private organization that has always functioned as an
exclusive club answering to nobody but itself.
</P>
<P>
   But the IOC is under enormous pressure not only from the
``Olympic family'' of national committees, international sports
federations, and corporate sponsors but also from skeptics _ from
US senators to English newspapers _ who doubt that it is capable of
reforming itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC must evolve with the society in which it lives,'' says
board member Jacques Rogge of Belgium. ``There is a need for
evolution, that is for sure. Everyone agrees on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet what the IOC will do inside its headquarters at the lakeside
Chateau de Vidy in Lausanne may well fall short of what its
harshest critics are demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Only one additional member, Seiuli Paul Wallwork of Western
Samoa, will be recommended for expulsion. Nine others, including
board member Kim Un Yong of South Korea, will be censured or
warned. Three others will be exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, the 78-year-old Spanish marquis who has been IOC
president since 1980, has been under pressure to resign since the
scandal broke in December. But his colleagues, four-fifths of whom
were appointed by Samaranch, are expected to give him a resounding
reaffirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will vote that I have confidence in him,'' says Francisco
Elizalde of the Philippines, a committee member since 1985. ``He
has done more for the IOC than all previous presidents put
together. It will serve no purpose for him to resign now.''
</P>
<P>
   And the members are almost certain to insist that they continue
to be the ones to vote on host cities after a smaller selection
committee narrows the field to two or three finalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice for the Games should reflect universal values,''
says Rogge.
</P>
<P>
   Though the week's decisions may seem modest in the wake of the
worst scandal in modern Olympic history, they will have a seismic
effect on a body that has weathered two World Wars, three boycotted
Games, and the breakup of Europe's socialist bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC will have forced out less than half of the two
dozen members implicated in the Salt Lake scandal, it will be a
traumatic act for a self-selected group that has not expelled one
of its own in nearly four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC had hoped that the original nine disgraced members would
step down on their own and avoid a bitter and unseemly scene this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tender your resignations,'' Samaranch had urged in January,
when the executive board voted to suspended them pending expulsion.
``Do not wait to be expelled by the session. Put an end to this
ugly chapter in the history of the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet only four members have resigned. The rest _ Agustin Arroyo
(Ecuador), Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir (Sudan), Jean-Claude
Ganga (Congo), Lamine Keita (Mali), and Sergio Santander (Chile) _
have vowed to defend themselves in person this week. And the
rank-and-file members, who normally rubber-stamp whatever the
executive board recommends, say they'll hear out their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to see everything,'' says Roque Napoleon Munoz Pena of
the Dominican Republic. ``I have to hear everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrenching and embarrassing as they may be, the expulsions and
censures have to do with the past. The IOC's most urgent and
important task here will be to change the bidding process that
created a junketeering culture built on lavish trips, expensive
gifts, and finally the cash payoffs that spawned the Salt Lake
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the executive board suggested taking selection
rights away from the members and giving them to a 15-member panel,
only eight of them from the IOC. But since most members claimed
that the change amounted to an indictment of their integrity, the
board has backed off.
</P>
<P>
   The members, though, have been banned from visiting any of the
six European cities bidding for the 2006 Winter Games, which will
be awarded in June. That has produced howls of protest from Turin,
the Italian city which is co-favorite with the Swiss resort of
Sion, a 2002 runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy IOC members visited Sion four years ago,'' says Marco
San Pietro, director of international relations for the Turin bid
committee. ``They know nothing about Turin. We will send them
documents and videos. But one thing is to go and see. Another thing
is to see a video.''
</P>
<P>
   Turin is an incidental casualty, San Pietro acknowledges, of an
ethical earthquake that has shaken the august IOC to its
foundation. The Lords of the Rings are under fierce pressure to
change the way they operate _ pressure not only from without but
within, from scores of members who resent being broad-brushed as
corrupt. The Netherlands's Prince of Orange, elected only last
year, has already stepped aside in protest and others are expected
to follow if the proposed reforms aren't adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger danger in all this is not that a few bad guys get
thrown out, but that the good guys will leave,'' says Pound, who
chaired the panel that investigated the Salt Lake scandal. ``If we
don't get that right, they're going to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Still ahead are the stickier issues of independence. Critics
have called for the IOC to open its books and allow outsiders to
choose many of its members. Though the IOC probably will create a
special commission this week to deal with structural change , those
reforms won't happen until the next meeting in June _ if then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things cannot be done in this session,'' says Philipp
von Schoeller of Austria. ``We can deal with the expulsion of
members and how to choose the 2006 city and vote on the president.
But much more will not be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the IOC has a century's worth of decisions to make
and a tattered image to cleanse and repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to undo the damage,'' concedes Elizalde of the
Philippines. ``It will linger. Let's talk reality. Our image is
kaput right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
