<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WILL BE BOYS OF ZIMMER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Let's start by saying we hope Joe Torre makes a speedy
recovery from prostate cancer and gets back in the Yankees dugout
by next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a possibility that Torre may be out for a while. And
this means beleaguered citizens of Red Sox Nation may be in for
another one of those mind-blowing sights that have become a
chilling part of the New England sports experience.
</P>
<P>
   Try this on for size, Sox fans . . . Think about the prospect of
Don Zimmer taking out the lineup card to home plate when the world
champion Yankees first play at Fenway May 18.
</P>
<P>
   That's Yankee manager Don Zimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. Bad enough we have to see Bill Parcells, Curtis Martin, and
the rest of the New England Jets beat the stuff out of the Patriots
twice a year. We've also got Mo Vaughn in Angel whites and Roger
Clemens with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Now Don Zimmer is the interim manager of the mighty Pinstripe
Gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll get me a few boos,'' Zim said as he stood around the
batting cage before managing the Yankees against Kansas City Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 20 years since Zimmer was the most maligned man in New
England. Zim's Boston woes started when he skippered the 1978 Red
Sox, the team that blew the 14-game July lead, then lost a one-game
(Bucky Dent) playoff to the Yankees at Fenway. He's still skewered
for running his veterans into the ground, going too long with Butch
Hobson, refusing to pitch Bill Lee in the Yankee massacres, and
sending Bob Bailey up to pinch hit in the playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember going up to home plate on Opening Day the
next year,'' said the 68-year-old baseball lifer. ``We had won 99
games and we were playing Cleveland in our opener. When I walked
out of the dugout, I got booed by 30,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   It was bad from then right up until he got fired at the end of
the 1980 season. There was no peace. He was hooted on a nightly
basis and remembers his daughter (who was then a grown woman)
crying in the back seat as he drove home over the Tobin Bridge.
Bill Lee called him a ``gerbil'' and Zimmer was one of the first
Boston managers/ coaches hounded by the growing monster that is
sports talk radio. Showing he was ahead of his time, he developed a
hatred for Glenn Ordway as early as 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when Sully (former Sox co-owner Haywood Sullivan)
fired me,'' said Zimmer. ``He had never fired anyone before. He
came into my office about 10 days before the season ended. He was
pacing. I said, `Sully, for Christ's sake, we're friends. Lay it on
me.' He asked me if I was tired of the abuse. I told him, `You and
Buddy (LeRoux) took over from me. It's easy for me now.' He
couldn't do it. So a day later he called me and said there would be
a noon press conference. And that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer got another job immediately. He was manager of the Texas
Rangers in 1981, and the Rangers opened (where else?) at Fenway
Park. When he popped out of the dugout, the boos rained down on his
head again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took off my cap and tipped it in every direction,'' Zimmer
said, smiling. ``I think they cheered a little after that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Zimmer's 51st year in baseball and he is one of the most
likable people in the game. For the first 47 years he bragged that
he never received a check from anything other than baseball. But
after he retired from a coaching job with the Colorado Rockies in
1995, he told Social Security he was ready for the checks to start.
He got one check, cashed it, then took a phone call from the new
Yankee manager. Torre wanted Zimmer as his bench coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stunned me,'' he said. ``It was the furthest thing from
my mind when he called.''
</P>
<P>
   Zim accepted the job and told Social Security to cease. Three
years later, he's got two new championship rings and now finds
himself managing a squad that some consider the greatest baseball
team of all time.
</P>
<P>
   He's a reluctant skipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe called me and asked me to do this,'' he said. ``Then
George (Steinbrenner) called me. I don't want to manage under these
conditions, but somebody has to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will be run the way (Torre) wants. But I will not
use his office, and I will not sit in his seat on the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer had arthroscopic surgery on his right knee a week ago. He
discarded his crutches and uses a fungo bat for a cane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a good team,'' he said. ``You can have a good team and
not always win, but we got a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Torre will be involved in all decisions whenever
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so will George,'' Zimmer added with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre won't be able to manage during the games. ``If I'm
managing, I'm going to be the one changing pitchers,'' said Zimmer.
</P>
<P>
   He is managing. He might still be managing when the Yankees come
to Boston. And let's not forget the All-Star Game at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe and I had already been joking about that,'' said Zimmer.
``Imagine Roger Clemens starting the All-Star Game and Mo Vaughn at
first base. Joe said he'd make me take out the lineup card for that
one. I told him, `No way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It could happen. If Torre's recovery takes longer than expected,
Don Zimmer could be the All-Star manager. The possibilities are
endless.
</P>
<P>
   But right now he's just finding his way along, doing what comes
naturally, managing one of the greatest teams in the history of
baseball, and leaving the front seat empty out of respect for his
friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
