<HEADLINE>
REPLAY MAKING NOT-SO-INSTANT COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Instant replay apparently has completed its seven-year
sentence in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Flying in the face of popular opinion, the National Football
League owners have managed to keep an instant replay officiating
system out of their game since 1992, but a Globe survey of team
owners last week indicates that instant replay will be voted back
in this week.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's owners meeting, the vote was 21-9 in favor of
replay, two votes short of the support required. Last year's ``no''
votes came from Arizona, Buffalo, Chicago, Cincinnati, Kansas City,
New York (Giants), Oakland, San Diego, and Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego and Tampa Bay say they will definitely vote for it
this time, which should swing the tide. In addition, the Giants and
Bills, who have always voted against, say they are leaning in
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to vote `yes' this time,'' says Chargers general
manager Bobby Beathard. ``This proposal is different than a year
ago. It is a compromise. We are not going all the way back to what
we used to have, but we can still get some things corrected that
should be corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I have always been against it personally,'' says
Buccaneers GM Rick McKay, ``we are going to vote for it this time.
Instant replay's time has come. The coaches want it, the players
want it, the fans want it. Let's try it again and put the best
system we can in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be the panacea people make it out to be.
I think our game is well-officiated. We are not perfect, and replay
won't make it perfect. I think this system will help keep a good
pace to the game, and not get it too long. Some people will be able
to sleep easier at night.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cleveland coming into the league as the 31st team this
fall, 24 votes will be neeeded to restore instant replay. Cleveland
has said it will vote in favor, which very well may be the
clincher.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal put forth by the Competition Committee is somewhat
different from the system that was used eight years ago. At any
point before the last two minutes, coaches would be allowed to
challenge calls twice per half but would give up a timeout when
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two minutes of each half, a press box observer
chosen by the league would notify field officials if he spots
anything that might be deemed changeable. The referee would stop
the game, view the play on a TV monitor on the sideline, and decide
whether to change the call.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason why instant replay was defeated a year ago was that
two franchises were concerned that their coaches would be
intimidated into saving timeouts to challenge plays in the closing
moments of each half. The two-minute exception presumably provides
the remedy in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a good chance we will vote for it,'' said
Bills coach Wade Phillips. ``I've talked with (owner) Ralph
(Wilson) about it this week, and he wants to hear exactly what the
proposal is. We want to see what is going to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is reasonable,'' says Giants co-owner Wellington Mara,
``we could vote for it. I want to see what the system is and what
the new technology is. I hope we have something that can cure some
the defects we have. Right now the thing that bothers me most about
our officiating is the big gap in the way we call pass interference
(which doesn't come under replay). Some crews call it one way;
others crews call it differently. A couple of big calls on pass
interference can change the whole outcome of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Other comments on the matter, from teams that voted against
replay last year:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona owner Bill Bidwill: ``We would like to see the game stay
on the field. We have always felt that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City general manager Carl Peterson: ``We are going to be
interested to see what the league is going to say. Our premise has
always been to devise a system that would not delay the pace of the
game, slow the flow of the game, or bring about too many technical
interruptions. Until that happens, we will vote against.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland owner Al Davis: ``I have some questions about this
proposal. I want to hear all of the arguments before I decide. What
if something happens with four minutes left and you are out of
timeouts, even though it is a serious mistake? We can't change it
because we can't challenge it. That doesn't seem right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati owner Mike Brown: ``I'm still against it. No matter
how much you tinker with it, you come out with the same problems.
There will be delays. There will be errors. It will cause
distractions. The focus will be on things that are negative. I am
so surprised that people are enamored with it. Last year we had
over 37,000 plays and of that number, only 77 of them would have
been reversible. That is less than one half of 1 percent. This is
more emotional than anything. I'm against it, but I think it is
going to pass this time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, a committee of four (coach Dick Jauron and three
front office types) said they would study the new proposal and then
decide which way to vote. The Bears have always been against
replay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles will be named the 32d franchise city in the league
this week, but with some reservations. The city will be given a
limited amount of time to come up with a stadium plan that will
please the NFL owners. If it doesn't, the franchise could be taken
back and awarded to Houston at a later date. Meanwhile, Houston
would become the so-called ``relocation'' city, meaning the next
team that wants to move, or sell, would have the opening to move
into that city. The NFL will try to make some kind of Cleveland
arrangement in Los Angeles. After the Browns left for Baltimore,
there was no owner in place when the league made a deal with
Cleveland to join forces to build a new stadium. When that was
done, the NFL conducted an auction and Al Lerner purchased the new
Browns for a record $530 million . . . Speaking of new ownership,
the owners are expected to vote down the bid of the Milstein group
to purchase the Washington Redskins and their new stadium. The new
group got the nod from the trustees of the estate of the late Jack
Kent Cooke, but it will not be approved this week unless it changes
its financial plan. The plan does not satisfy league rules on
purchasing a team. The potential owners have yet to produce the
required amount of cash, and they are using the team as collateral
for their $500 million loan, which is also against the rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots offensive coordinator Larry Kennan says that Tim
Couch of Kentucky can throw the deep ball as well as Drew Bledsoe.
Kennan has been working out Couch and UCLA quarterback Cade McNown,
getting them ready for workouts in front of NFL scouts. Because he
was in a quick-throw, short-pass offense at Kentucky, scouts
wondered whether Couch could throw deep. Kennan claims he can, as
effectively as anyone in the league . . . Former Pro Bowl guard
Walt Sweeney, the Cohasset native who had a 14-year career with San
Diego and Washington, has written a book, ``Off Guard,'' which he
is shopping to publishers. ``It's not an all-football book,'' says
Sweeney with a laugh. ``It's more about how I screwed myself up
playing football. It's supposed to be funny.'' Sweeney became
addicted to drugs and alcohol during his NFL days. His football
story became well-documented when he sued the NFL and Players
Association and won in court, only to have the finding overturned
on appeal. ``I played 14 years and my pension is $1,600 a month,''
says Sweeney, who now lives in Lake Tahoe, Calif. ``I have to pay
my first wife $400 a month, and some money back because of the
court case. It's not easy.'' . . . The owners will hear an update
in the next few days on what is happening in the San Francisco
49ers organization. The team's former owner, Eddie DeBartolo, has
been pushed out of the picture by his sister, Denise. Apparently,
Denise, who runs the DeBartolo Corp. and has been placed in charge
of the team by the league, is angry with her brother for not paying
back a reported $60 million loan given to him by the parent
company, which could cause further problems for the DeBartolo Corp.
if Uncle Sam decides to place a tax on the loan as
sister-to-brother ``gift.'' Denise has placed her husband, John
York, in charge of the 49ers, with former head coach Bill Walsh
coming back to run day-to-day football operations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If John Elway decides to retire, as close friends think he will,
he could become the third man in the booth on ``Monday Night
Football'' with Al Michaels and Boomer Esiason. Elway has to decide
whether to go for three straight Super Bowl victories or go out a
certain winner after a great final game. Elway doesn't need the
money. He will make his decision before the draft so that the
Broncos can act accordingly . . . The Giants left no stone unturned
in checking out Kerry Collins before they signed him for big money
in free agency. The Giants researched the troubled quarterback from
his high school days, talking to his coaches and teachers, through
his Penn State coaches and former teammates (who gave him high
marks), and people he played for in the pros, Carolina and New
Orleans. Collins admits he has been troubled by alcohol, and he is
trying to get his act together. The Giants felt he was the best
young quarterback available to them, and that he would turn out to
be worth the investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 0240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
