<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKLIN, CRENSHAW STIR RYDER POT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For a week that offered true New England winter
weather, there was an awful lot of golf on the menu, thanks to
back-to-back events put on by the Massachusetts Golf Association
and the Francis Ouimet Scholarship Fund. The opportunity to play
wasn't there, but talking golf is a second favorite pastime for an
awful lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Ryder Cup at The Country Club in Brookline is at
the center of most golf talk in this area. So it was only natural
that both the MGA and Ouimet group built their events around it.
Former European captain Tony Jacklin was at the MGA Spring
Conference Tuesday, while current US coach Ben Crenshaw was the
guest of honor Thursday night at the Ouimet Fund's 50th anniversary
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Jacklin was splendid, talking honestly and refreshingly about
his role in helping turn this Ryder Cup into the spectacle that it
is. There was a time, he said, when he thought his association with
the event would be over, back in 1981 when he was not selected to
the team. A former British Open and US Open champion, Jacklin was
truly hurt by the snub, so imagine his surprise when he was asked
to be the 1983 captain. He thought it over, and when his list of
demands (better clothes, better travel accommodations, a more
serious commitment to winning) was met, Jacklin found himself
leading the Europeans at PGA National Golf Club in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Wadkins's superb wedge shot into the 18th hole (``I can
still see (captain) Jack Nicklaus kissing the divot,'' said
Jacklin) stole that competition for the US, but Jacklin's teams won
in 1985 and 1987, then maintained the Cup with a 14-14 tie in 1989.
Jacklin stepped down as coach, but he has never really left the
Ryder Cup spotlight. He will be in Brookline in September, working
the corporate tents, watching as a fan, and doing some commentary
for television.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, Crenshaw was presented the Francis Ouimet
Award for Lifelong Contributions to Golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud to be associated with something as substantial
as this organization,'' said Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   His appearance at the dinner had been publicized for months, but
what had not been made known was the designation of $50,000 to
establish a permanently endowed scholarship in the name of Charlie
Crenshaw, Ben's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kept it a secret from him,'' said the two-time Masters
champion. ``I can't wait to tell him when I get back home. No one
has had a better father than I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Crenshaw accompanied his son to The Country Club in 1968
for the US Junior Boys' championship, the first USGA event for the
Texas youngster. He didn't win, but the event helped cement Ben's
love of classic golf courses in general and The Country Club in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an historic place,'' he said. ``But The Country Club is
anything but straightforward. Which is why I'm intent on getting
the players in here to know what it is like.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Crenshaw and Jacklin faced questions about the chance of
Europe having so many rookies on its team, as the current Top 10
features seven. While both conceded that first-time players are a
possible liability (``There is no way to prepare for your first
Ryder Cup,'' said Crenshaw. ``It's daunting.''), people should take
into consideration a couple of points before jumping all over this
aspect:
</P>
<P>
   1. We are only halfway through March, and there are nearly five
months _ and some 20 tournaments _ to go before the teams are
formalized. Heck, the 1999 European Tour season is just a few
events old and some stalwarts are just now starting to play
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   2. In 1997, Europe fielded a team with five Ryder Cup rookies.
Feel free to ask members of the US team if that made their week in
Spain any more pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt US Ryder Cup loyalists took delight in the fact that
five members of Europe's 1997 championship team (Nick Faldo, Colin
Montgomerie, Jesper Parnevik, Ian Woosnam, and Lee Westwood) went
down to defeat in Round 1 of the recent World Match Play, but take
note that Duval, Davis Love III, Justin Leonard, and Jim Furyk _
players who figure to be on the US squad at The Country Club in
Brookline _ did not exactly stir memories of vintage Walter Hagen.
</P>
<P>
   Love (who lost in the first round to Steve Pate) and Leonard (a
second-round upset victim to Shigeki Murayama) were startling
disappointments in the 1997 Ryder Cup loss, as well as members of
the US Presidents Cup team that got slapped around in Australia in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Duval, a marvelous talent who talked for weeks
leading up to the event about his dislike of match play. It was
almost as if he was setting himself up to fail, which is what he
did in Round 2 against Bill Glasson. You can shoot 66 and lose in
match play, complained Duval, though he conveniently ignored
another match-play truism: You can shoot 74 and win.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be a bit disconcerting to Crenshaw to know one of his
top players has such an aversion to the form of play that will be
demanded of him come September.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Monterrey, Mexico, for this week's Nike Tour stop
will be a little more enjoyable for Pembroke's Kevin Johnson,
thanks to his strong finish a couple of weeks ago. The former State
Amateur and State Open champion had started the season without
status, which left him on that most difficult road _ Monday
qualifying. Johnson got into the Nike stop in someplace called Pass
Christian, Miss., then stormed to the 54-hole lead. Though he faded
to third, Johnson earned $20,625 to vault into 13th place on the
money list. ``I bet the folks up (in Massachusetts) thought I was
dead,'' said Johnson, 31, from his home in Florida. He was
laughing, still taking comfort in the knowledge that when the Tour
reshuffles its status list, he should be in good shape . . .
Johnson failed in his bid to get into last week's Doral Ryder-Open,
but he stayed to watch Geoff Sisk, his good friend from Marshfield
who is a rookie on the PGA Tour. Sisk made his second cut of the
year, finished in a tie for 19th, and earned $29,000. He continued
his fine play by making it into the weekend at the Honda Classic .
. . For those who are wondering about popular caddie Mike ``Fluff''
Cowan, now that he has been fired from Tiger Woods's bag, look for
the Maine native to return to Peter Jacobsen . . . Michelle McGann
is hoping a new approach to her diabetes will help her rebound
effort on the LPGA Tour. A seven-time winner who was no worse than
16th on the money list the previous eight seasons, McGann recorded
just one top-five finish a year ago as she had a freefall to 45th
on the money list. Her poor play continued into 1999, but she
seemed poised for a turnaround when she shared the lead going into
the final round of the recent Hawaiian Ladies Open. Not so fast.
The 29-year-old McGann put up four doubles on her incoming nine,
closed with an 81, and finished in a tie for 34th. In five events
she has earned just under $14,000. McGann revealed after the
tournament that she would take a break from the Tour while she
recovers from the installation of a pump that automatically adjusts
insulin levels . . . Not a bad stretch for Alison Nicholas at the
recent Australian Ladies Masters. She began the third round with a
pair of birdies, then holed out her second shot to the 470-yard
par-5 third. Certainly, Peter O'Malley would have loved such
results. He trailed by one as he played the 72d hole of the
Australasian Tour Championship _ and made a 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 0243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
