<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      03-14 1603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS STEAL SETS UP BIG LAKER SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don't you think it would be charitable for Lakers owner
Jerry Buss to order up a couple of extra championship rings this
year for Charlotte boss George Shinn and Hornets henchman Bob Bass?
As Alfred P. Doolittle would say, ``It's the right and proper thing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Utah, Indiana, Miami, and maybe even Portland might
feel differently, but it's awfully hard not to concede the 1999
flag to the Lakers after last week's over-the-top deal for Glen
Rice. They might have won the whole thing if they didn't do
anything. Now, they've added the game's most selfless player in
Dennis Rodman and its most dangerous shooter to an already potent
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did LA major domo Jerry West extricate Rice, he also
got J.R. Reid and B.J. Armstrong, two older players to blend into
the youthful LA pot. And while they were salary-cap throw-ins
(Armstrong was immediately waived), Reid was quietly putting
together a very nice season amid all the tumult in Mayberry.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn and Bass, you may recall, also bailed out the Lakers a
couple of years back on draft night. Not only did they take Vlade
Divac off West's hands so that West had more money to pursue
Shaquille O'Neal, they then turned around and sent him Kobe Bryant,
even-up, for Divac. (They chose Bryant for the Lakers to boot.) So,
directly or indirectly, skinflint Shinn and bottom-line Bass are
responsible for Bryant, Shaq, and now Rice hanging out in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure West will vote for Bass for Executive of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Rice, on paper, is frightening. He can get off a
shot with no room and he's terrifyingly accurate. You double-team
Shaq, you pay for it with a Rice bomb. You try to rotate to Rice,
you pay for it with a Kobe slash. You guard Shaq even-up, well,
forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Having said all that, it will be interesting to watch the Lakers
now that Shaq has been satisfied. There still is, at last count,
only one basketball, and opponents will hope the Lakers go the way
of the 1976-77 Philadelphia 76ers, who crashed and burned against
team-oriented Portland in the NBA Finals. Or, closer to home, the
way of the 1968-69 Lakers, who had West, Elgin Baylor, and Wilt
Chamberlain and still couldn't beat the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   So let's see if they can play together and check their egos at
the door. Let's see if Kurt Rambis is up to it and can match wits
with Jerry Sloan when it really matters. Let's see how the Lakers
react now that they are expected to go all the way. But you must
admit that you have to like their chances a lot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You also have to like what the Nets have done, unless you have
to sign their checks. The addition of Stephon Marbury is a
slam-dunk for Jersey, but also a depressing sign for the Minnesotas
and Milwaukees of the world. Are they forever going to be the Kents
and George Masons of the NBA? David Falk's fingerprints are, of
course, all over the Marbury deal, but so what? That's his job. Can
anyone say that Marbury isn't in at least as good a basketball
situation, if not better, than he was a week ago? He didn't want to
stay in Minnesota; that's his choice. He had a nice thing going
there, but he has a potentially great thing going in New Jersey
with Keith Van Horn, Kerry Kittles (both Falk clients, as well),
and the irrepressible Jayson Williams. And he's closer to home. The
downside, of course, is more of a leaguewide concern. It wasn't a
lack of resources or an unwillingness to pay by Minnesota. It just
wasn't sexy enough. But when the big-market teams like Jersey and
the Lakers can pay, pay, and pay some more, you have to wonder
about the mid-level guys. Los Angeles, for instance, could be
paying its Big Three an astonishing $40 million next season alone
(Shaq $17 million, Rice $14 million, Bryant $9 million) . . . In
all the major deals that transpired this past week, there was one
common factor: the ability to re-sign a player. Charlotte was
worried about keeping Rice, even though it could have not paid
top-dollar and still been able to offer him more than any other
team, by far. The Wolves wanted to re-sign Marbury, just as they
wanted to re-sign Tom Gugliotta. They couldn't do it. Milwaukee not
only might not have re-signed Terrell Brandon, it then got out from
under Tyrone Hill's big deal because he was threatening to opt out
if Brandon left. Cleveland didn't necessarily want to part with
Vitaly Potapenko, but it has shelled out $230 million to Shawn
Kemp, Zydrunas Ilgauskas, Wesley Person, and Bobby Sura, still has
Brevin Knight and Derek Anderson to deal with, and, at last check,
was 25th in the league in attendance. The Cavs weren't willing to
add another $40 million for someone who was, in their mind,
dispensable, even though their only other center, Ilgauskas, seems
to have Bill Walton's feet . . . Kevin McHale did a nice recovery
job in getting Brandon to replace Marbury. It's the second time in
two months he has had to go to Plan B to restock his roster. It
would have been interesting to watch what would have happened had
McHale and Timberwolves owner Glen Taylor called Falk's bluff and
not made the deal. Would Marbury really have opted for a hideous
Chicago team over what he had in Minnesota? But the risk was simply
too great. Brandon, too, is a free agent, but his agent, Bill
Duffy, and McHale have all but chosen the living room furniture.
They were roommates in college and are still chums, so, provided
the Wolves open the vault, re-signing Brandon should not be a
problem. Milwaukee, meanwhile, gets a free look at the
disappointing Tim Thomas for the next year-plus and has Sam Cassell
locked up until 2002 at what is a reasonable NBA price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the Celtics, there really is no downside to the Potapenko
deal, other than it gives Falk another client on the team (joining
Antoine Walker, Kenny Anderson, Walter McCarty, and, in
brotherhood, Rick Pitino). Unless you are worried about losing the
fourth, fifth, or sixth pick in what now looks to be an
irretrievably weak draft, then it's a no-brainer. (Right now, the
first three picks could be Lamar Odom, Elton Brand, and Steve
Francis.) Potapenko gives Pitino what he did not have, a sturdy
fellow in the post. The Celtics did not have to part with one of
their three young guns to do the deal. The cynic in all of us
wonders why Cleveland would do the deal with Ilgauskas's health
concerns, but the monetary issue was paramount. However, after
watching the Celtics stumble around the conference this past week,
it's obvious there are bigger concerns than just having a full slab
in the paint. Anderson has been awful; there's no polite way to
phrase it and he is the first one to admit it. He isn't getting the
ball up the floor quickly enough _ that was always a problem with
Chauncey Billups, too _ he's having trouble in the halfcourt, and
his shooting has been abysmal. He is the engineer on offense and he
simply hasn't been getting the train on the right track. We all
wondered whether Anderson could master the Pitino system, and
Pitino was confident Anderson could, saying the system would make
Anderson one of the top point guards in the league. Right now,
Anderson is the sixth-best point guard in the seven-team Atlantic
Division. One thing we thought we wouldn't have to worry about was
scoring. Add that concern to an already suspect defense, and you
can understand why Pitino has all but a stamp on this season . . .
The other problem is Walker. Is he any better now than he was last
year? Or even two years ago? In the last two games, he's played 71
minutes, taken 41 shots, turned it over nine times, and has one
assist. He is an undeniable talent, but he's also doing many of the
same, stupid things that drive us crazy. Chuck Person may not be
the most reliable witness on the subject of ``touches,'' but he was
adamant about Walker's too-dominating role in the offense, at the
expense of others. ``This is a difficult, young team to coach,''
Pitino said. By now, however, we should be seeing some progress,
and it's hard to find any other than the potential of Pierce and
Ron Mercer's occasional outbursts. Yes, the Celtics could be better
next year because they'll have a full training camp and be in
better shape. But so will everyone else. With the trading of Andrew
DeClercq, there is only one Pitino-signed free agent (Bruce Bowen)
still on the team. Gone are Chris Mills, Tyus Edney, Tony
Massenburg, Travis Knight, and now DeClercq, not to mention Eric
Williams, Billups, Roy Rogers, and John Thomas . . . We noted last
week that Mo Taylor was not rushing to sign an extension. Well,
there's a good reason: He can't. At least by the books he can't.
However, one of the wrinkles in the new collective bargaining
agreement allows teams out of the playoffs to negotiate with their
two-year rookies. That means the Clippers should get the go-ahead
any day now, although they did avoid total humiliation by beating
Sacramento . . . Dee Brown looks at Vince Carter and sees a young
Dominique Wilkins. ``He is so explosive,'' Brown says of the
skywalking Raptor rookie. ``Dominique used to be like that. He
could jump, take a hit, and still elevate. It makes me reminisce
about the days when I could play above the rim, although I could
never play like that.'' . . . The Knicks stooped to an unconscious
low against the Bulls Friday. They had 22 points at the half (5 in
the second quarter) and 33 after three. How could that happen?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
