<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS TAKE A TUMBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If the Clippers believed in moral victories, they
might have enough by now to qualify for the moral playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' said point guard Darrick Martin, who
doesn't think basketball has anything to do with pitching
horseshoes, ``all they want to know is did you win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, all the Clippers did was lose for the 18th time in
19 games.
</P>
<P>
   That anticipated Clipper roll turned out to be little more than
a noisy somersault.
</P>
<P>
   The big, bad Portland Trail Blazers terminated a pair of
one-game streaks by stomping into the Sports Arena and rallying to
defeat the home team, 106-96, in overtime in front of 9,484
witnesses. The Blazers, who had their eight-game winning streak
killed and league-best record twisted by the Utah Jazz in Portland
on Friday, trailed by as much as 17 points against the team with
the league's worst record.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a gift,'' Martin said after outplaying Portland's
Damon Stoudamire almost as convincingly as he smoked Sacramento
rookie Jason Williams in Thursday's landmark first victory. ``They
(Blazers) know they got away with one.''
</P>
<P>
   They almost got away with it in 48 minutes, but Clippers center
Lorenzen Wright nailed a pair of free throws with .4 seconds on the
clock to tie the score at 91 and send the game into a lopsided
overtime. Wright, who established a career and 1999 league high
with 25 rebounds vs. the Kings, pulled in another 18 against
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   By taking advantage of Portland's press and making several open
shots, the Clippers led by as many as 15 in the second quarter.
Their lead slipped to three - 51-48 - at intermission, but an
11-point third quarter by Lamond Murray pushed the advantage to 17
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' hack-a-Blazer defense led to an 11-of-15 Portland
effort at the line and 27-15 margin in the fourth quarter. The
Blazers (16-4) completed the evening with 50 free-throw attempts;
the Clippers fired up a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just fouled too much,'' said Clipper forward Maurice
Taylor, who contributed 15 points and eight rebounds after
predicting a ``monster'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the monster role was assumed by Blazer Brian
Grant, the guy Taylor was assigned to check. Grant finished with 25
points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very active,'' Taylor said of Grant. ``Usually the guys I
go up against can't move around that well. I like their whole team.
They're big and strong and they have a great bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Four of those Blazer subs scored in double figures Saturday, led
by Rasheed Wallace with 21.
</P>
<P>
   Martin finished with 14 points, six steals, six assists and just
one turnover before fouling out in OT. Murray (18) and Eric
Piatkowski (14) combined for 32 points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Said Martin: ``We're not nearly as bad as they project us to
be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
