<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMIEUX MAY BE BOXED IN 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What first sounded farcical now appears, at the very
least, possible. Claiming he is owed some $32.5 million in past and
future pay, and with little or no chance of collecting more than
pennies on the dollar, ex-superstar Mario Lemieux now has a plan to
purchase the Penguins and, eventually, collect his cash.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux and all concerned parties _ suitors, sellers, and
pretenders alike _ met in NHL commissioner Gary Bettman's office
last week and continued to hash through the details.
</P>
<P>
   The Team Lemieux financial plan, which could be placed before
the bankruptcy court Thursday, is this: Working with a figure of
some $27.5 million (present-day value of the $32.5 million, some of
it originally deferred as far out as 12 years), Lemieux would
collect a lump-sum $6 million up front from his own group of
buyers. He then would fold $10 million, slightly more than 36
percent of what he's owed, into equity _ his personal ownership
position in the new venture. The balance of $11.5 million then
would be paid to Mario Magnifique over the next eight years, at an
interest rate of 6.75 percent (a note that would bring him some
$65,000 per month in interest alone).
</P>
<P>
   The Team Lemieux plan also asks the NHL to grant the Penguins
the same economic relief currently extended to small-market
Canadian clubs. Each year, if Edmonton, Calgary, and Ottawa reach a
ticket-sales plateau and various advertising sales levels, the
league will kick back up to $2.5 million. Imgaine how the likes of
Buffalo and Nashville, two small-market American clubs, will view
that proposed handout?
</P>
<P>
   Headed into the weekend, Lemieux's financial backer still had
not been made public. One wild rumor around Toronto had it that
former Bulls icon Michael Jordan, who shares Lemieux's passion for
golf, might be the mysterious money guy. One source believes the
backer could be Hollywood-based.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, Boston attorney Harry Manion said his client,
Penguins co-owner Roger Marino, would surrender his share in the
team under two conditions: if he were repaid the $5 million loan he
made earlier this season to keep the club afloat, and if new
ownership pledged not to gut the roster (i.e. dump Jaromir Jagr in
a cash grab). If he walks away now, the Revere-born and -raised
Marino will have lost perhaps as much as $40 million in the
dreadful venture. Given what he could lose by staying on board,
that kind of loss looks like a steal.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Lemieux, who couldn't wait to get out of the game,
suddenly so eager to get involved? According to those familiar with
the negotiations, it's simply because his contract, negotiated by
agent Tom Reich, didn't protect him against what has turned into
financial doomsday. The deal looked too good to be true _ and it
was. When it comes to fine print, no man, be he 66 or 9-to-5er, is
immune to being hoodwinked.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux's only choice, in the end, is to jump into what is
becoming an increasingly risky _ some would say absolutely no-win _
financial venture. Lemieux's deal played a large part in ushering
the Penguins into bankruptcy and escalating salaries throughout the
league. Salaries have gone from the garish to the outlandish to the
vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic it might be for Lemieux, one of those who gained so
much from the system, now to sign on as owner and see his savings
sucked from his pocket overnight in an attempt to keep the biz
viable. A front-row ticket to the theater of the absurd. His only
way back then might be to sell the movie rights to Hollywood. He'd
have an in there with Penguins co-owner Harold Baldwin, who has
helped shepherd a few flicks to the silver screen. The circle of
debt, it goes 'round and 'round.
</P>
<P>
   What if the Lemieux plan doesn't fly? There is at least one
other key suitor, Harvey Gainey, a homegrown Pittsburgh guy who now
owns and operates Gainey Transportation, a Grand Rapids-based
trucking company. His point man in the operation, Chip Gesner (ex-
of Connecticut), said Saturday that race-car driver Chip Ganassi
also would be part of the Gainey bid, which will be placed with the
bankruptcy court in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for handouts,'' said Gesner, asked if his
group would seek the same ``small-market'' element eyed by Team
Lemieux. ``Let's get the team first and see where we stand then. We
think we can turn the team around with a lot of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Gesner helped put together the Pittsburgh Pirates ownership
group, and the Bucs, said Gesner, have gone from losing $18.5
million a year to turning a profit. If the Gainey group is
successful, chances of Lemieux seeing more than a token financial
handshake (amount determined by the court) would be virtually nil.
</P>
<P>
   What if, in the end, no one can get the deal done? There remains
the possibility, perhaps remote, that the franchise goes Chapter 7,
is forced to dissolve, and the players ultimately get placed in a
dispersal draft. Wouldn't you pay to see the Board of Governors sit
at a table and figure out who picks first in the Jagr draft?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado winger Valeri Kamensky is high on the
``most-likely-to-be-dealt-before-the-trade-deadline'' list. He'll
be an unrestricted free agent come July 1. The Sabres made a recent
inquiry, but word around Buffalo is that the Avalanche were looking
for 24-year-old defenseman Jay McKee (14th pick overall in '95) in
return. No deal. Not only can Kamensky go free this summer, he
turns 33 next month . . . Ex-Bruin Joe Juneau, recovering from a
concussion, is another likely trade prospect. He, too, will be
unrestricted this summer. When he doesn't have ex-Bruin Adam Oates
dishing him the puck, Juneau's effectiveness drops considerably.
But don't look for the Capitals to package the two in a deal. Oates
still has the skills that make those around him better and he's an
ideal tutor for Jan Bulis, the 20-year-old Czech who projects as
the franchise's pivot of the future . . . Rangers coach John
Muckler, on the rumor that his old pal, Glen Sather, was trying to
pry Matthew Barnaby, Martin Biron, and Jean-Luc Grand-Pierre from
the Sabres in a deal that would include Bo Mironov going to
Buffalo: ``If Slats can make that trade, he's the executive of the
year.'' Barnaby finally got dished to the Penguins for former
first-rounder Stu Barnes . . . Biron's work in relief of the
injured Dominik Hasek has been promising enough that it doesn't
make the idea of a Hasek trade totally absurd. Just a year ago,
following Hasek's Olympic heroics, such a thought would have been
ludicrous. But Hasek's trade value never will be higher, he is 34
years old, and the Sabres aren't a serious Cup threat. If someone
were willing to pay his $7 million-plus per year and send the
Sabres some real value in return, they would have to consider it .
. . Anyone else out there look at Hal Gill, all 6 feet 7 inches of
him, and wonder whether he might be able to play a forward's spot
on the power play? That size. That reach. Some things you just
don't know until you try them . . . John Ferguson, now a scout for
the Sharks, in his days as GM in Winnipeg and Ottawa drafted no
fewer than four players who became NHL rookies of the year: Dale
Hawerchuk (No. 1 in '81); Teemu Selanne (10 in '88), Daniel
Alfredsson (133 in '94), and Bryan Berard (1 in '95). ``It should
have been five,'' Fergie recently told the Ottawa Sun, ``because
Yashin should have won.'' Alexei Yashin, chosen No. 2 overall in
'92 with the Senators' first draft pick, was eligible for the
Calder in '94, won by New Jersey netminder Martin Brodeur.
Then-Oiler Jason Arnott, now a Brodeur teammate with the Devils,
was runner-up that season . . . Los Angeles team president Tim
Leiweke said last weekend that the Kings' coaching staff (Larry
Robinson, et al) will finish the season. The question remains,
though, whether Robinson will want to return. This is the end of
his fourth season there and, in all likelihood, the Kings are going
to miss the playoffs for a third time under his watch. The Kings
play to their talent level, not an inch beyond that, and the talent
pipeline holds little promise . . . Steve Yzerman's deal in Detroit
is due to run out next season, when he'll earn $5.18 million. Word
around the Winged Wheels is that he's ready to sign a three-year
extension, through 2003, that will bring him $21 million . . . Word
around Toronto is that the Vineyard's Mike Smith, the Leafs'
associate GM, could be scooped away for the GM job in Chicago (if
Bob Murray gets the hook, as expected) or for the same post in
Minnesota (the Wild begin play in October 2000). If Smith goes,
Anders Hedberg, now the assistant GM and director of player
personnel, would move a spot closer to team president Ken Dryden.
Smith was believed to be in the mix here in Boston prior to Mike
O'Connell being tabbed as Harry Sinden's eventual successor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Senators get around to talking contract with Yashin
(his deal goes through next season), don't be surprised if they
welcome free-agent bids from clubs south of the 49th parallel.
Reason: Ottawa can match any offer by a US club, and are only
obligated to pay in Canadian funds. The league would have to make
up the difference. By current exchange rates, a US offer worth,
say, $60 million would have the Senators paying the equivalent of
about $40 million US and the league handing over some $20 million.
We are reminded of the old Butch Cassidy line: ``That's bad
business. If he'd pay me what he's spending to make me stop robbin'
him, I'd stop robbin' him.'' . . . A source familiar with NHL
finances pegs the Stars' operating deficit at $100 million over the
last two years. A little perspective: That's double what it cost
for Tampa Bay and Ottawa to buy into the league at the start of the
'90s. Given the economic woes of the six Canada-based clubs and the
overspending tactics of some of their Yankee partners, the league
soon may be begging the Players' Association to reopen the
collective bargaining agreement, which isn't due to expire until
2004. There is only one way the union will go for that: Two or
three clubs will have to fail (remember, Pittsburgh already is in
bankruptcy) . . . Another sign of the times: There is a distinct
possibility that Canada's national team, based in Calgary, will
fold operations after this season. Team Maple Leaf used to shape
the country's Olympic and World Championship squads. But the Games
went pro in '98 (2002 remains a question) and the International Ice
Hockey Federation is tinkering with the World Championship format.
Meanwhile, lack of governmental funding has the national team
looking for private donations from team alumni. It takes slightly
more than $1 million a year to keep the operation going . . . Leafs
forward Alyn McCauley, crushed by a Sheldon Souray check 10 days
ago, began off-ice workouts last Sunday, after neurological tests
showed his reaction times were diminished by some 20 percent by the
blow _ his fourth career concussion. It could be another two weeks
or more before he is back in the lineup. ``It wasn't the glass that
gave,'' said McCauley, ``it was my head.'' McCauley needed more
than four hours to shake the initial grogginess.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Pistons owner William Davidson took over the Lightning
less than two weeks ago for $100 million _ double the Bolts'
expansion cost, but $17 million below what Art Williams paid for
them just a year earlier. The front office trio of Cliff Fletcher,
Jay Feaster, and Jacques Demers remains intact, for now, but
Davidson can be expected to roll in his own crew over the next 2-3
years. Rick Dudley, signed as the Senators' GM last summer, would
be a likely candidate. He was rumored to have the inside track a
year ago, until Williams moved in as the surprise suitor . . .
Islanders GM Mike Milbury began the expected purge in Uniondale
Tuesday when he unloaded Scott Lachance on the Canadiens for a
third-round pick. Lachance was the No. 4 pick overall in '91 _
Peter Forsberg went No. 6 in that draft _ and never lived up to his
all-world potential on the Island. The Islanders now have dealt
away five of their first-round picks since 1991: Darius Kasparaitis
(No. 5 overall in '92), Wade Redden (2 in '95), Todd Bertuzzi (23
in '93), J.P. Dumont (3 in '96), and Lachance. Brett Lindros, the
No. 9 pick in the '94 draft, had to retire because of concussions.
Many more bodies are expected to be dumped, perhaps including
ex-Bruins Bryan Smolinski, Marius Czerkawski, and Craig Janney . .
. Years ago, upon exiting a September media luncheon at the Bruins
camp in Wilmington, Jeremy Jacobs, in from Buffalo for the day,
dashed through a pack of sportswriters as he made his way out the
Ristuccia Center's doors. ``Mr. Jacobs, do you have a minute?''
asked Dick Trust, then the beat writer for the Patriot Ledger.
``Not a second,'' said Jacobs, disappearing without another word.
During a recent stretch of self-imposed silence with the media on
Long Island, Milbury replied, ``Not even a second,'' when asked if
he had a minute for reporters. Imitation, the highest form of
flattery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 0249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKW-WOMEN'SWORLDCHAMP     03-14 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKW-WOMEN'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITTEN BACKSTOPS US WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPOO, Finland _ What's the saying, out with the old and in with
the new? To get to Sunday's final of the Women's World
Championships, the US hockey squad decided to twist the adage a
bit: in with the old and, oh, what the heck, in with the new, too.
</P>
<P>
   Led by two goals from 15-year-old center Natalie Darwitz,
playing on her first national team, and a brilliant return by
27-year-old goaltender Erin Whitten, playing on her fifth, the US
beat Finland, 3-1, in Saturday's semifinal and will meet Canada
Sunday night for the fifth time in five World finals. Despite its
Olympic triumph, the US has yet to get past Canada for a world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Canada had a tougher-than-expected time in its semifinal but
outlasted Sweden, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Whitten, who gained fame by being the first woman to play an
entire men's professional hockey game, was busy from the first drop
of the puck, as Finland came out strong to outshoot the shaky
Americans, 10-7, in the first period. She almost made it to the
buzzer unscathed, but Kirsi Hanninen drilled one in from the top of
the slot with just two seconds left to put the US behind, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second period, with just 11 seconds left on a power
play, Darwitz took a feed from Cammi Granato and snapped in the
puck from just outside the crease to knot the game, 1-1, at 6:46.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting it in in a game this big was great,'' said Darwitz of
her first world championship goal. A 5-foot-2-inch freshman at
Eagan (Minn.) High School, where she has played on the varsity
hockey team since seventh grade, Darwitz was forced to sit out a
practice and miss some playing time after hurting her hip in
Monday's 10-2 rout of Russia in the first game of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I can skate and have power with it, I'm fine,''
said Darwitz.
</P>
<P>
   If the first goal helped ease her pain, the second must have
made the entire team feel a lot better. With 3 1/2 minutes left in
the second, Darwitz put the US ahead to stay when Shelley Looney
found her in her favorite spot, the top of the crease, to give the
US its first lead, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Krissy Wendell, a 17-year-old from Brooklyn Park, Minn., also
making her national team debut, beat her defender to sneak one into
the right corner with exactly five minutes left in the game to seal
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   As exciting as the victory was for the newcomers, it may have
meant far more to the veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, it was so important for me,'' said Whitten, who was
kept home from Nagano by youngsters Sarah Tueting and Sara DeCosta.
``After being cut from the Olympics, I really didn't know if I was
going to get another shot right away. I took a lot of time away,
and I think it did some good for me mentally. It took a lot of time
for me to build up the confidence again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy for her, to get a game like this in a setting
like this,'' said coach Ben Smith, who nonetheless declined to
announce his starting goaltender for Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Finland game, it would be a surprise if it weren't
Whitten, just as it would be a surprise if Darwitz doesn't someday
list five national teams on her own resume _ even if she is still
in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still hard to believe I'm sitting next to Cammi Granato
or shooting pucks at Erin Whitten,'' she said. ``I have to pinch
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said Whitten: ``She beats me every day in practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
