<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXINGNOTEBOOK-BO     03-14 2012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY FOCAL POINT OF FEDERAL PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A major shakeup in big-time boxing may have begun
quietly last week with the resignation of attorney Pat English from
Main Events, Dino Duva's New Jersey-based promotional company.
</P>
<P>
   It is the start of a move by Duva and his sister, Donna, to buy
out sister-in-law Kathy Duva, who along with her children controls
about 40 percent of the company trust started by her late husband,
Dan. As the family Duva began these negotiations, English opted to
resign from Main Events's board after a 17-year association because
he is also Kathy Duva's family attorney and would be involved in
the negotiations of a financial settlement, if one can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   But changes at Main Events, one of the sport's biggest
promotional companies, may not be the biggest boxing story to come
out of New Jersey this year. A federal grand jury investigation
into the sport's often questionable business practices has begun
and may delve into the inner workings of the New Jersey-based
International Boxing Federation and its president, Bob Lee, sources
say.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's organization is not the probe's only target, however. Word
is, the government is asking questions about promoters Butch Lewis
and Cedric Kushner, fight manager Marc Roberts _ who ran a stock
deal that sold $10 million worth of shares in a management company
whose biggest asset was heavyweight prospect Shannon Briggs _ head
of the New Jersey state athletic commission Larry Hazzard, and
other boxing figures.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Bob Arum has voluntarily testified in front of that
grand jury, although he denied Friday that he had cut an immunity
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to give me immunity,'' he said. ``I haven't
done anything. You make an immunity deal if you need immunity from
something. Other than that, I don't know anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum refused to discuss the investigation, but another boxing
insider said it was a far-ranging one and several others in a
position to know insisted that Lewis may make his own immunity deal
in exchange for testimony against Lee, with the hope that Lee
eventually will crack and give the government another shot at
indicting promoter Don King, who has defeated three efforts to
convict him on various charges.
</P>
<P>
   The issues under investigation reportedly involve extortion and
bribery surrounding the selling of rankings and the title shots
those rankings produce, a scenario not unlike the one in the famous
boxing film, ``The Harder They Fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury reportedly is also looking into questionable
judging in New Jersey that appeared to favor certain fighters and
whether the managers of those fighters had financial connections
with boxing officials.
</P>
<P>
   Said a source, ``A lot of time and effort is going into this and
I think it will lead somewhere, although I don't think even the
feds know where yet. Without any question (Arizona Sen. John)
McCain is involved in this. Just how, I can't say, but I think his
committee has turned over a lot of information to these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. McCain has been trying for years to clean up the sport's
business practices and protect fighters from unscrupulous
promoters. He filed the Muhammad Ali Boxing Bill, which forces
state commissions to honor suspensions and rulings of other states,
and has has held several rounds of hearings on the sport.
</P>
<P>
   The probe, which included interviews with FBI agents involved in
an investigation of an unnamed boxing promoter that began more than
10 years ago, is nothing new for boxing. Managers and promoters
have had repeated run-ins with the government dating back to the
days when the Mob ran the sport at the behest of Frankie Carbo and
Jim Norris through an organization known as the IBC. In those days,
ratings were manipulated, fights were fixed in exchange for future
title shots, and the rackets controlled most everything that
happened in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Things may be more sophisticated as the dawning of the new
millennium looms, but boxing's address on the shady side of the
street seldom seems to change for long. If that is where it is
again, it won't be long before you'll be hearing about it from a
New Jersey courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boxing attorney Milt Chwasky was irate to learn that $20 million
in letters of credit King had to produce to insure the purses of
Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis for Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's fight were
actually backed not by King's bank but by HBO. Chwasky, who
represents Lewis's promoters, felt King had not shouldered the
promoter's burden. ``If you're going to do it that way, why not
just let some homeless person promote the fight?'' Chwasky ranted.
``They could have put up as much money as Don did.'' At that King
laughed, claiming he was on the hook for more than $4 million of
his own money and contending that Chwasky was ``just one of those
guys in boxing trying to prove to somebody there's a reason to get
paid. I sold this fight in 156 different countries. This was the
fastet sellout in heavyweight history. It will gross more money
than any promotion in the history of the Garden. What else they
want from a promoter?'' . . . Arum and HBO executives will watch
closely the Lewis-Holyfield sales; the closer it comes to 1 million
buys, the more likely it is that Oscar De La Hoya will fight Felix
Trinidad this year. ``If it does 800,000-850,000 buys, it's likely
De La Hoya-Trinidad can be made,'' Arum said. ``If it doesn't, it's
much less likely. I know the fighters' demands, and nobody will put
up that kind of money if the pay-per-view business doesn't exist.''
No one believes a nonheavyweight fight will exceed the
Lewis-Holyfield sales, so it effectively becomes the ceiling for
the De La Hoya-Trinidad sales potential. If that ceiling is too
low, then the promoters would be unable to raise sufficient money
to pay them. Hence, no fight. ``De La Hoya-Trinidad can't be bigger
than Lewis-Holyfield,'' HBO Sports president Seth Abraham agreed .
. . A secondary, but no less intense, heavyweight battle went on
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night between the trainers of Lewis and Holyfield.
Emanuel Steward and Don Turner did little to mask their longtime
feud in the days leading up to the fight. A week ago, Turner
refused to go on a New York television show with Steward, saying,
``If I go on that show, I'm going to slap that (expletive) in the
face.'' Steward has repeatedly suggested that Turner is riding the
crest of Holyfield, while Turner countered by saying, ``I thought
Lewis was a good fighter after the (1988) Olympics. I still think
he's a good fighter. I just don't think he'll ever live up to what
I thought he might achieve. I just don't think he's improved much
since he turned pro.'' Turner also suggested that Steward tries to
steal not only the thunder from his fighters but fighters from
their managers and trainers, and he included himself as a past
target of such efforts. Other than that, it wasn't personal at all
. . . Industry sources said Time-Warner needed roughly 800,000
pay-per-view sales on TVKO to break even on Holyfield-Lewis . . .
HBO used the occasion of Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's fight to bring together
all of the promoters with whom it does business in New York and
make clear to them that the network is no longer willing to accept
unattractive challengers for its stable of world champions. ``We
told them all we are going to be far more stringent in the fights
we'll accept,'' Abraham said. ``We have momentum going in boxing
and we want to keep it going with good fights. I don't know if
they'll act on it, but these guys are smart, they have contracts,
and they understand HBO is their bank. Part of what's opened up
this dam has been our doing business again with Don King. The fact
is, if we make the best fights _ the ones people want to see, like
Lewis-Holyfield _ in the long run all these promoters will win.
Certainly they will lose an individual champion from time to time,
but in the big picture, they'll all win because the sport will
win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newly crowned World Boxing Association super welterweight
champion David Reid had his third operation on a droopy left eyelid
only days after defeating Laurent Boudouani last weekend to win a
world title in only his 12th professional fight. The sagging eyelid
limits his vision at times but it didn't prevent him from winning a
clear decision over the 32-year-old Boudouani and becoming the
third member of the 1996 US Olympic team to win a world
championship. Reid joined Floyd Mayweather Jr. and Fernando Vargas.
Just as important to him, he stretched to 13 his streak of HBO
boxing shows that produced a double-digit rating, the longest such
streak in network history . . . Mayweather, meanwhile, will get his
best exposure yet on May 22 when he defends the World Boxing
Council junior lightweight title for the third time against Goyo
Vargas underneath De La Hoya's welterweight title defense on HBO.
De La Hoya takes on Oba Carr while awaiting some sign that he will
land Trinidad, the International Boxing Federation champion, before
the end of the year. But as negotiations for that fight move along
at a snail's pace, word is that Arum, De La Hoya's promoter, has
begun talking about a rematch with either Pernell Whitaker or Ike
Quartey in the fall. The more likely is Whitaker because he looks
less dangerous at this stage of his career . . . Arum shook up his
operation last week by severing longtime East Coast matchmaker Ron
Katz, saying Katz no longer did enough shows to justify keeping
him. He will pay Katz until the end of the year . . . Roberto Duran
lost a 10-round fight in Argentina last week. He reportedly weighed
175 pounds. For the greatest lightweight I ever saw, that is a lot
of baggage to be dragging around a ring at age 47. Sadly, this will
go on as long as there are promoters willing to exploit old
champions and old champions who go broke at the end of the line.
There's always plenty of both . . . Trainer Teddy Atlas returns to
boxing's bigger stage Saturday when he takes heavyweight prospect
Kirk Johnson into the ring for the first time. Atlas, who last week
was called ``the Michelangelo of the gym'' by veteran New York Post
columnist Jack Newfield, took over Johnson's training after Johnson
suffered through an unexpectedly long night with former
cruiserweight champion Al ``Ice'' Cole in which he had 3 points
deducted for low blows and was in big trouble several times. That
led Kushner to seek out Atlas, who trained Michael Moorer and Mike
Tyson in his formative years. Atlas will get to measure his
progress immediately when Johnson meets Cole in a rematch next week
on ``HBO Boxing After Dark'' . . . Atlas has been busy. He not only
trains Johnson at Marciano's Gym in Jersey City six days a week but
also is preparing 19-year-old Elvir Muriqi, a 1998 New York Golden
Gloves champions whose father is a guerrilla in the Kosovo
Liberation Army. When not in the ring, Atlas has been an analyst
for ESPN2's ``Friday Night Fights,'' done radio interviews to
promote Lewis-Holyfield for TVKO, and awaits a call from movie
director Ron Shelton, who is writing a part for Atlas into his
latest film, about the fight game . . . Efforts toward a Roy
Jones-Reggie Johnson match were successful after an initial
breakdown made it seem likely Jones would make a mandatory defense
against Gianfranco Rocchigiani in June instead of trying to unify
the 175-pound title against the IBF champion. Jones's promoter,
Murad Muhammad, has agreed to a Jones-Johnson unification fight
June 5 in Las Vegas . . . Showtime has penciled in Sept. 19 as the
date for a likely return to the ring by Tyson. He should be out of
a Maryland prison by June and free to train in a work-release
program that will allow him to travel outide the state to fight.
Arguments continue over his next opponent, however. Showtime wants
someone ``live.'' Manager Shelley Finkel wants something along the
lines of a creampuff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
