<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE WORKING TO PUT INJURY BEHIND HIM 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ROSE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Want a clue about how Red Sox righthander
Brian Rose looked in his second outing of spring training? Well,
the first two batters he faced in Saturday morning's ``B'' game
against the Minnesota Twins were hit by pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't completely by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he was out there trying to hit anyone,'' said
manager Jimy Williams. ``But for a pitcher to be effective, he has
to establish inside. And sometimes it gets pretty close.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the start, he threw freely. The important thing is that
he feels good. If he's not healthy, he can't pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams squeezed in the 10 a.m. game _ before the regularly
scheduled 1 p.m. exhibition against the Twins _ for a chance to
keep tabs on Rose, who a year ago as a rookie was Boston's starter
in the Fenway opener but now is simply trying to make the roster
following offseason elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Rose gave up two runs and one hit in two innings of work. The
first run was scored without a hit, the second was unearned, coming
in thanks to an error with two out. In a game Boston rallied to
win, 5-4, Rose had no walks or strikeouts, which is not unexpected
at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw some good, quality pitches today,'' said Rose. ``And
that is what I needed to boost my confidence level. I just want to
progress every time out there, build up my arm strength, and try to
get guys out.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want is to get back to where I can help the ball club.
In Boston or Pawtucket, I have to help out the ball club. But to do
that I know that I have to stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might surmise, Rose has already seen the writing on the
wall. The Red Sox have penciled in five starters: Pedro Martinez,
Tim Wakefield, Bret Saberhagen, Mark Portugal, and Pat Rapp. All
are veterans who are throwing well this spring. Portugal, in fact,
was the winner in an 8-2 victory in the afternoon game.
</P>
<P>
   Rose understands that unless one of those pitchers fails to hold
a spot in the rotation, Rose will start his season in Pawtucket.
Perhaps even lower in the system.
</P>
<P>
   But Pawtucket would not be the end of the world for Rose. In
1997, he was 17-5 with a 3.02 earned run average there, and was
named International League Most Valuable Pitcher and Rookie of the
Year. Rose showed such promise _ good control and an ability to
change speeds _ that the Sox felt they could let go of Carl Pavano
in the Martinez trade with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rose is trying to hone those tools again. And the more he
pitches, the better he should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put it in any time frame,'' he said. ``But my
elbow feels free. If I can do that, then I'll have a pretty good
chance of getting guys out.''
</P>
<P>
   What made Rose happy Saturday was that he was able to make
adjustments from his first start. It took just one sideline session
with pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked on Wednesday and found a couple of mistakes,'' said
Rose. ``I was breaking my hands and rushing. I wasn't throwing
downhill; I was throwing flat. Today, I was able to carry it out
there. I want to build, day by day, and hopefully things will work
themselves out.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time, said Rose, maybe he can pitch a little later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the earliest game I can recall pitching,'' he said,
``if you don't count some of those 9:15 a.m. starts in early minor
league spring training camp. It's good to wake, get up, and go.''
</P>
<P>
   He certainly gave the first two Minnesota batters a wake-up
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time, I was just trying to get the ball to change plane
levels,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, they cut in and hit the batter.
Still, I threw it in an area where I wanted, and that's all that
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what matters most at this point is that Rose stays
healthy. Coming off a bone spur and fracture in his pitching elbow
that limited him to eight starts last season, Rose feels he's spent
enough time out of uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that it was my first injury to overcome, and
that was a lot,'' he said. ``I don't like to sit on the sidelines
and watch games. I'd rather be out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sit out and watch a whole season go by was very
frustrating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
