<SLUG> BC-HKC-HARVARD-RPI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RPI SQUARES SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ It's back to square one.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a third and final game in the ECAC quarterfinal
series between Harvard and Rensselaer after the Engineers got a
pair of power-play goals from freshman left wing Matt Murley as
well as strong netminding from junior Joel Laing (35 saves)
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night to earn a 4-0 decision over the Crimson,
necessitating Sunday night's tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   RPI, which finished off the win with a pair of empty-net goals,
finished 2 of 6 with the man advantage, Murley's first tally coming
7:19 into the second period with Harvard's Mark Moore in the
penalty box for holding. Murley scored off a feed from the left
point from Danny Riva. Murley buried his second _ and 16th of the
season _ with Steve Moore off for tripping at 15:58 of the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt played very well,'' said RPI coach Dan Fridgen. ``He's a
kid who could well be the ECAC Rookie of the Year. He's been very
valuable all season.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Laing, the senior who notched his fifth
shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was (Laing),'' said Harvard coach Ronn
Tomassoni, whose team has been blanked twice by Laing this season.
``He had an outstanding game. We put a lot of rubber on him but
probably he had too many clean looks, especially on the power play.
We have to do a better job of screening and a better job on the
second and third chances. He just played one of those games.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard sophomore goaltender Oliver Jonas, playing for the
injured J.R. Prestifilippo (separated shoulder) was strong again,
denying 26 shots, 11 in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it was a 1-0 game,'' said Tomassoni,
whose team finished 0 for 8 on the power play. ``When it got to
2-0, it didn't matter whether it was 3-0 or 4-0. All we had to do
was tie it and we had to try (pulling the goalie).''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was close at the end with RPI finally taking advantage of
its power play,'' said Harvard captain Craig Adams. ``In the third
period, we took it to them but the bounces just didn't go our way.
As far as the empty-net goals, I'm not worried about them. RPI's
goalie played well.''
</P>
<P>
   RPI carried over its strong third period Friday night into
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no time when we were flat,'' said Fridgen. ``We were
totally focused. It was great that our power play went for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Sunday night's rubber match?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one of those low-scoring games and that
favors us,'' said Adams. ``We're going to clog it up and we're
going to keep it close. I have a lot of faith in our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a heck of a series,'' Tomassoni said. ``This is what
you play for. It's the deciding game. We played well Friday as well
as (Saturday &UR;  &LR; night) and I expect that we'll play a heck of a game
(Sunday night) as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 0300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-BOSTONCOLLEGE-OHI     03-14 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES PUT BEST FOOT FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-OHIO STATE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Sometimes just being asked to the dance is
not enough. You have to get your best clothes out, put on your best
performance, and hope that you're still standing _ and your partner
isn't _ by the end of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Boston College women's basketball team is still
standing. The No. 8 seed Eagles defeated No. 9 Ohio State, 72-59,
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night before 11,190 at Tennessee's Thompson-Boling Arena
in the first round of the East Regional. BC is making its first
NCAA Tournament appearance in the 27-year history of the program.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles will meet top-seeded Tennessee, which routed
Appalachian State, 113-54, in Monday's second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message all week was, `Don't be happy just to be here, come
to win,' '' said BC coach Cathy Inglese.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Eagles did, led by 6-foot-1-inch freshman
forward Becky Gottstein, who came off the bench to contribute a
career-high 23 points and 12 rebounds. Gottstein, who suffered a
high ankle sprain in BC's loss to Seton Hall in the Big East
tournament two weeks ago, only returned to practice two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Also shining for BC (22-7) was Alissa Murphy (22 points, 11 for
12 from the line) and freshman guard Brianne Stepherson (11
points).
</P>
<P>
   But most of the heroics were absent in the first half, as the
Eagles hardly looked ready to play with the top 64 teams in the
country. After an initial layup by 6-4 center Whitney Steele and
two free throws by Murphy, BC would go on a six-minute scoring
drought as Ohio State took off on an 11-0 run. The Buckeyes took a
13-4 lead behind three baskets by senior Marrita Porter and a
3-pointer by 5-4 guard Jamie Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were plagued by sloppy ballhandling. The Eagles had
turned the ball over eight times in the first eight minutes,
forcing Inglese to call a timeout. But after some substitutions,
the Eagles changed direction.
</P>
<P>
   Boosted by Gottstein _ taped ankle and all _ the Eagles went on
a 9-point surge to tie the score at 15. When BC took a 19-15 lead,
the Buckeyes had gone 4 1/2 minutes without a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   But not even the hot-shooting of Gottstein, who finished the
half with 13 points and four rebounds, could keep the Eagles in
front. With 4:45 left in the half, Ohio State went on an 11-3 run
to take a 34-31 lead at intermission. Ohio State had turned the
ball over 15 times, BC 17.
</P>
<P>
   But Inglese saw signs that her team would come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very confident at halftime, because there were some
things in the half that we just weren't executing,'' she said. ``I
knew we'd be successful if we got the ball to Alissa and really cut
down their post play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles jumped on the Buckeyes in the second half _ behind a
3-pointer by Murphy and three consecutive layups by Gottstein _ to
take a 43-39 lead. Ohio State tried to come back behind
high-scoring junior forward Michaela Moua (16 points), Porter, and
Lewis (14 each), but it was too late. With five minutes left the
gap was 13, 63-50.
</P>
<P>
   Three more baskets by Ohio State, including two Lewis
3-pointers, didn't make a difference as BC made 12 trips to the
line and was successful on 11 of them.
</P>
<P>
   As Murphy dribbled downcourt, the clock ticked down and the BC
fans stood and cheered. The Eagles can savor their win, for a day,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, this is the biggest win,'' Inglese said. ``We've had a
lot of big ones this year, but this is the biggest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 0302EST &QL; 
