<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-14 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEADY, PURDUE FIRST CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Stop the next 1,000 self-proclaimed sports fans you see
on the street and ask them which Big Ten basketball team is the
only one to have won three consecutive league regular-season
championships in either the '80s or '90s, and I will bet you an
autographed picture of Cazzie Russell the preponderance of guesses
will either be a) Michigan or b) Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, three-second breath. The answer is Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Purdue has won or shared more Big Ten basketball
titles period (21) than anyone, and I'll wager my autographed
picture of Rick Mount you didn't know that.
</P>
<P>
   But unless you reside in West Lafayette, Ind., or your name is
Mrs. Gene Keady, Purdue is not in your thoughts when the subject of
great basketball powers comes up. And when they talk about the
A-list of coaches, not many casual fans would include the name of
Gene Keady. He is an industry phenomenon, more Gene Hackman (and
when I closed my eyes while he spoke Saturday, I heard the final
locker room scene in ``Hoosiers'') than Tom Hanks. But I've spent
enough time around college basketball people to know that when the
people who really know talk about year-in, year-out solid programs
and coaches who make a habit of putting out teams whose whole
exceeds the sum of their parts, the name Gene Keady tumbles readily
from their lips.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a great Purdue team. It is a 20-12 10th seed that
has already given itself a successful season by defeating
seventh-seeded Texas in a tense and intriguing contest Friday night
at the FleetCenter. I doubt if anyone other than the West
Lafayette/Mrs. Keady crowd thinks they'll advance themselves to the
East Regional by defeating second-seeded Miami Sunday afternoon at
the Fleet, but things far more improbable than a Gene Keady team
winning an important game have transpired in the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue is a notably fine university that has given us men who
have walked on the moon (Neil Armstrong), US senators (Birch Bayh),
snack food moguls (Orville Redenbacher), authors (Booth Tarkenton),
ultimate basketball legends (John Wooden, and is that exalted
enough for you?), not to mention countless engineers and assorted
technical whiz-bangs among its 300,000 alumni, but which somehow
has no national cachet when stacked up against the likes of Big Ten
compadres Michigan and Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the matter of that ``other'' Big Ten school
located precisely 108 miles to the south of West Lafayette. NCAA
championship tally: Indiana 5, Purdue 0. Larger-than-life coaching
personalities: Indiana 1, Purdue 0.
</P>
<P>
   It is constitutionally impossible for us to comprehend what a
thing like Indiana-Purdue is all about, but take BC-BU in hockey to
about the 20th power. That might be a start.
</P>
<P>
   The outside world doesn't realize that Keady has beaten Knight
more than Knight has beaten Keady. It's part of being Purdue. There
isn't much they can do about it, except, to borrow a hockey
analogy, go out and skate their wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know why the university can have such a great
program and Coach Keady can be such a great coach and people don't
think of us being in the upper echelon of the college basketball
world,'' said junior forward Brian Cardinal, a banger in the finest
Purdue frontcourt tradition. ``All we can do is go out and play as
hard as we can, and, hopefully, Purdue and the coach will get the
recognition they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Keady took the diplomatic high road when asked if he were in any
way upset that his team's accomplishments have been so amazingly
overlooked. ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I really don't worry about
it. I hear people say I do, but I've never said that. The answer is
to win bigger. Go to the Final Four. Win the national title.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that he has never had the resources to go all the
way. Final Four? Sure, that was reasonable. But the classic Keady
teams have been the ones picked third or fourth that scrap, hustle,
and defend past more highly-regarded Big Ten teams. That's not to
say he hasn't had anybody. He did, after all, beat the world to
Glenn Robinson's door. But a more typical Keady pro is Steve
Scheffler.
</P>
<P>
   So here he is in Round 2 of the NCAAs, with a team that has had
a great struggle to get where it is. Winning that game the night
before last on Cameron Stephens's improbable jumper was the
culmination of much blood, toil, tears, and sweat for the
Boilermakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That picture in the paper this morning of our kids jumping and
pounding each other was something the coaching staff waited all
year to see,'' Keady said, alluding to the wonderful Dominic Chavez
shot on Page G1 of the Globe's final Saturday edition. ``All year
long we've been asking these kids to have fun and enjoy themselves.
Finally, we saw it all with that picture. Hopefully, it won't be
short-lived.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes up Sunday against a man who respects him very much. He
and Miami mentor Leonard Hamilton go back two decades to the time
when Keady was an assistant at Arkansas and head coach at Western
Kentucky and Hamilton was a talent-hunting star at Kentucky.
Hamilton is a paid-up member of the Gene Keady Fan Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always admired the toughness Gene's teams play with,''
said Hamilton. ``His kids are kind of like him. They play like
little Gene Keadys. They are very competitive youngsters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years we haven't,'' sighed Keady. ``Maybe in the
early '80s and '90s. The last few years I've accused them of being
soft, although I realize that with this generation that's not a
particularly good reference to make.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a guy who thinks a coach has a broader responsibility to
his kids than devising a way to better defend the pick-and-roll.
The Purdue kids have been to the JFK Library and have seen Old
Ironsides. The world ought to know more about Gene Keady. There's
more to life than getting to the Final Four. I guess what I'm
saying is maybe we press folk could have been doing a better job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
