A9737 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN     03-14 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WOMEN ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LaCresha Flannigan isn't the most-known player on
the UCLA women's basketball team, just the second-leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   She played her role perfectly again Saturday night, scoring 16
points to Maylana Martin's 18 in the No. 3-seeded Bruins'
hard-fought 76-69 victory Saturday night over No. 14
Wisconsin-Green Bay in an NCAA Women's Tournament first-round game
in front of 2,390 at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (24-7) will host No. 6 Kentucky, a 98-92 victor
earlier Saturday against No. 11 Nebraska, Monday at 9 p.m. The
Wildcats and Bruins played earlier this season, with UCLA winning
64-54 in a Hawaii tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Anytime a UCLA opponent tries to create a game plan, it first
must figure out what to do with Martin, the Pacific-10 Conference's
player of the year and the Associated Press third-team
All-American.
</P>
<P>
   That was foremost on Green Bay coach Kevin Borseth's mind, too.
But then he worried about Janae Hubbard because of her size
advantage (6-foot-4) against the Phoenix (19-10).
</P>
<P>
   Flannigan, with a 14.3-point scoring average, sort of fell
through the cracks, under the general strategy ``contain the
guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Borseth should have thought more about Flannigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, she can get up,'' Borseth said. ``She's got hops. She
really likes the baseline crossover on the left.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Flannigan scoring five straight points to give the Bruins
a 10-7 lead early. She also got involved in a 12-4 first-half run
that put the Bruins ahead 22-13 with 8 minutes, 40 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Her most important contribution, however, came in the second
half, when she scored seven points in a 9-0 run that put UCLA ahead
60-46 with 8:52 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Her output Saturday was her 14th straight game in double figures
and 20th in her last 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows she's quick and can take anyone to the basket,''
UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said, ``and when her shot is falling, she
can get out. Erica (Gomez) loves looking for her on the break. She
gets us going defensively and is one of the reasons for our win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins needed all of Flannigan's points because the Phoenix
(19-10) refused to quit. Led by Cheri Nordgaard, UWGB's AP
honorable mention All-American, the team went on a 22-9 second-half
run and turned an 18-point halftime deficit into a five-point game,
51-46, with 10:24 remaining. Nordgaard scored 21 of her game-high
27 points in the second half, including 13 of the 22 in the run.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA earned its big halftime lead with a 13-0 run over the final
3:08. Hubbard scored four, Gomez completed a three-point play, and
Michelle Greco, Martin and Melanie Pearson chipped in with a basket
each.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez finished with 15 points and Hubbard had 12 points and 12
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin-Green Bay also got 12 points from Melanie Tilque.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky 98, Nebraska 92: Six players scored in double figures,
led by guard Erica Jackson's 18 points, to lead the Wildcats
(21-10) over Nebraska (21-12). Nicole Kubik led the Huskers with 32
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
