<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The Palm Beach Post has a three-day package for Saturday,
March 13, Sunday, March 14, and Monday, March 15, on the business
of smuggling aliens; why the U.S. Border Patrol, the INS and the
federal court system cope poorly with it in Florida; and why
Florida employers are able to hire hundreds of thousands of illegal
workers each year. Here are the budget lines for the third day in
the series. STORIES HAVE MOVED. FOUR PHOTOS AND FOUR GRAPHICS ARE
AVAILABLE.
</P>
<P>
   SMUGGLE-WORKSITE _ It's unlawful to hire non-citizens. But
Florida is still the land of opportunity. An estimated 350,000
illegal aliens reside here. Most work in the vegetable and citrus
farms. Many keep the tourism industry booming as waiters, hotel
maids, etc. Some work on landscaping and construction crews. But
the INS cannot go into the agricultural fields and doesn't have the
manpower to do much other worksite enforcement because it has to
focus attention on alien smuggling. Farmers hire scores of illegal
workers and escape liability by paying licensed farm labor
contractors provide crews. They also argue that workers today carry
counterfeit documents. The INS says they don't expect growers to be
document experts. Migrant worker advocates argue that farmers use
their political clout to handcuff the INS. For example: in 1990,
the INS sanctioned 38 employers in Florida for hiring illegals.
That dropped to 16 in 1991, 6 in 1992 and 2 in 1993. In 1994, 1995
and 1996, it was a dozen or fewer. Only in 1997 did it get back up
to about 20-25 employers. (Kane/Holland, Palm Beach Post). 60.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas This was the night Glenn drank paint.
No misprint there, though I had to ask him to repeat it. He and his
friends were getting good and soggy from fumes in
spray-paint-filled soda bottles. At some point, so lathered, he
tilted his bottle skyward. Gold lacquer flowed into him. (John
Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ From Tom Brokaw's book, ``The Greatest
Generation,'' to Newsweek's cover photo last week of an American
Marine in Vietnam, the end-of-the-century recounting of wars that
shaped America has begun. But one aspect of war that gets little
attention is what happens to the refugees. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
