<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9812 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN15-COX     03-14 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vietnamese refugees still helping themselves
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From Tom Brokaw's book, ``The Greatest Generation,''
to Newsweek's cover photo last week of an American Marine in
Vietnam, the end-of-the-century recounting of wars that shaped
America has begun. But one aspect of war that gets little attention
is what happens to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, refugees of the Vietnam War are adding cultural
dimension to a city historically identified as black and white. In
suburban Chamblee's Asian Square, I enjoyed a bowl of Vietnamese
noodle soup recently with Xuan Nguyen-Sutter, who helped found the
national Refugee Women's Network. It's based in Atlanta but has
offices in 18 states.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Sutter took time off from a lucrative job as a
financial analyst to help Vietnamese refugees. She never went back.
``I couldn't find happiness in that work,'' Sutter said. ``I love
my country, and I wanted to help my people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter grew up in a well-to-do family in Saigon, studied
economics at the University of Lausanne in Switzerland and received
her master's degree in business from New York University. She met
her husband, a Swiss doctor, now on the staff of the Atlanta-based
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, in an Indonesian
refugee camp, where both were working for international
organizations. Sutter felt particular compassion for female
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our culture,'' she said, ``woman is the pillar of the
family. When Asian women cannot be the pillar, they are
depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   When Asians come to America, often the men get jobs and the
children go to school _ but the women are left behind. They
struggle to translate their skills in a strange culture. ``Look,''
she said, pointing out the female manager of the restaurant as an
example, ``these are smart, talented women.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter, whose Vietnamese name means ``young spring,'' is so
passionate about her work that I can't imagine her crunching
numbers or plotting business strategy in a corporate office. But
her analytical acumen shines as she pieces together the patchwork
of resources that aid refugee women.
</P>
<P>
   The main thrust of the network, funded by government sources and
private foundations, is leadership training for refugee women. Many
of them later initiate projects for families in their communities.
Soon the network will start a newsletter to further link refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter introduced me to some of her Amerasian friends, Nga and
Minh Vo, who have the same mother. They and two other children of
American servicemen and the same Vietnamese woman have created a
home together in Chamblee for their combined families _ eight
adults and nine children. They rent a house with four bedrooms, one
for each family. They arrange their work shifts (Nga and Minh have
factory jobs) so they can rotate child care. They hope to pool
their money to buy a house soon.
</P>
<P>
   A full-time job and caring for three children hasn't allowed
31-year-old Nga time to attend evening English classes like her
older brother, who's been in America for two years. Nga came to
America eight years ago, but Minh stayed in Vietnam to care for his
grandmother until she died, a traditional responsibility of the
oldest child or grandchild. There were five Vo children, and Nga
recalls sadly the hard times when her mother, before her death,
sold small bottles of gasoline alongside a road to earn money for
food. Both remember the hurt of hearing others say their American
fathers were murderers. Amerasians whose fathers deserted them
haven't been accepted very well by Vietnamese or Americans, though
the U.S. government paid for them to come to this country after
passage of the Amerasian Homecoming Act of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter's assistant at the Refugee Network is Nguyet Lam, also
Amerasian. Like Minh, her father was African-American. She and Minh
and other black Amerasian children suffered particularly vicious
taunts.
</P>
<P>
   Lam says the Vos are success stories. Some Amerasians never
recover their self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Minh is glad to to be in the land of his father. ``If you
work hard in America,'' he says, ``you can get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter says she lost her country in the war, but she has found
peace of mind in her work. Not long ago, she visited with some
friends from college. ``My classmates are all vice presidents of
such and such businesses,'' she said with a laugh. ``I say to them,
'Look, I am just a poor social worker.' But they say to me, 'Xuan,
you are the happiest of all.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
