<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A golden boy's suicide in progress
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ What Glenn remembers is the ``purple boy'' _ whose
chin he'd yanked against the wall, holding him at eye-level, which
meant the boy's feet were dangling. Purple is no natural hue. It's
the color of one whose windpipe is being crushed.
</P>
<P>
   What does Glenn remember next? A chair slamming against the back
of his head. The purple boy, being questioned as a snitch,
scampered from death's clutches.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn came to sore and angry. Now he acknowledges whoever swung
that chair may have saved two lives. Amazing, the forms heroism can
take. Amazing, the forms madness can take.
</P>
<P>
   This was the night he drank paint. No misprint there, though I
had to ask him to repeat it. He and his friends were getting good
and soggy from fumes in spray-paint-filled soda bottles. At some
point, so lathered, he tilted his bottle skyward. Gold lacquer
flowed into him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick your poison'' goes the barroom line. Gold paint is his,
although he's tried all sorts of poisons.
</P>
<P>
   He huffed his first paint when he was 9. Mostly it's been
shoplifted from security-lax retailers. He tried gasoline fumes
once, but returned to paint, ``'cause it doesn't kill you that
fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gold paint kills you slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Why paint?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I can't do weed.''
</P>
<P>
   At 16, he has to undergo urinalysis under terms of a probation.
Pot shows up in a urine sample, but not paint. That's stone-free.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is not his name but we'll use it. He's been several months
without any killer poison in him. He's on a waiting list for drug
treatment at the Vernon State Home. Every time a vehicle cruises by
you wonder if he'll make it.
</P>
<P>
   When you have his attention, he'll zero in on you with
intensity. But it takes nothing to dislodge his attention. The honk
of a horn. The chime of a popsicle truck.
</P>
<P>
   His mother has seen his reactions slowed, and those of his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not dead, praise God, but they can't carry on an
intelligent conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son is lean and freckled. His close-cropped hair gleams like
a colt's mane. He speaks of devotion to his mom and a will to live,
for her if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being sober is so good, like a soda when you haven't had
none for five days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet you worry that the next sound of a motor idling on the
street will lure him away from the vow that would save what's left
of his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's mother says huffing is an epidemic where she lives in
Bellmead, and that parents of her son's peers seem either oblivious
or are acting as outright enablers.
</P>
<P>
   Bellmead Police Chief Robert Harold said police have received
several reports about huffing but never catch it in progress. In an
average year, McLennan County juvenile authorities are able to
prosecute no more than 15 or 20 inhalant cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of makes me angry,'' said Harold. While Glenn's mom is
trying to do something about the problem, he said, other parents
``are leaving it up to law enforcement to take care of something
that should be taught at home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been screaming the longest,'' he said. ``Nobody wants to
do anything about this.''
</P>
<P>
   How innocent it must seem, boys and girls and spray paint. Nine
years ago a 17-year-old Waco boy who was huffing paint in a creek
bed smashed a 15-year-old's skull on one of so many unsupervised
nights, killing him in a fit of brain-blown insanity.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Glenn was about to do the purple boy until a blessed
chair cracked him on the skull. Thanks. He needed that.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll be there to save kids with paint in their veins tonight?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco (Texas )
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
