r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH15-COX     03-14 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS FOR KIDS: ``Star Wars'' prequel to come early
 &HT;    By Theresas Walsh-Giarrusso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luke, mark your calendar for May 19 _ the Force will be arriving
sooner than expected. ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace''
will open in theaters two days early, according to George Lucas,
the film's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work on the film has been going extremely well. We're going to
be able to release it on Wednesday, May 19, in hopes that we can
give the fans a head start and families can see it on the
weekend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The film goes back in time to explain how Luke Skywalker's
father, Anakin Skywalker, became the evil Darth Vader. Lucas is
planning to release ``Episode II'' in 2002 and ``Episode III'' in
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Some movie industry experts believe the movie will break
box-office records set last year by ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman for president?
</P>
<P>
   Republican Elizabeth Dole has formed a group to explore her
chances of becoming president of the United States in the 2000
election.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being known as the wife of Bob Dole, a 1996 presidential
candidate, Elizabeth Dole has held many offices of her own.
</P>
<P>
   She is a former secretary of labor and transportation. Plus,
she's been the president of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Two other women have recently pursued presidential politics.
Democrat Pat Schroeder made a short-lived run for president in
1988, and Geraldine Ferraro was a vice presidential nominee on the
Democratic ticket in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Hubble's in trouble
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts will rush to the Hubble Space Telescope this fall to
fix part of its guidance system. The mission was scheduled for June
2000, but will be broken into two parts _ one this October and the
second by early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The extra mission will cost NASA $75 million more than was
budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had waited until June 2000, there is a very reasonable
chance that we could lose three, four or even more months of
science,'' said Ed Weiler, head of NASA's space science program.
``This is a rather good insurance policy we're buying here.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Hubble's six gyroscopes, which are needed for stability,
have failed since the astronauts' last service call in 1997. And a
third gyroscope suffered a partial breakdown recently. Gyroscopes
are wheels mounted in frames that spin. They are similar to toy
tops.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers need at least three perfect gyroscopes to conduct
observations throughout the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
