<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, March 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (888) 346-9867. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Ned Kilkelly.
</P>
<P>
   The late supervisor is Josephine Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-CHINA-MILITARY (Undated) _ The revelation that China
appears to have stolen the design of America's most advanced
miniaturized warhead has promted new debate in Washington over
whether China's small nuclear force could become a far more potent
arsenal that could rekindle the kind of fears that shaped the cold
war. Most experts say that Chinese authorities are clearly seeking
to modernize their nuclear forces, but despite continuing evidence
of Chinese espionage abroad, they doubt the country intends to
fundamentally change its nuclear strategy, which has been largely
defensive. By David E. Sanger and Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ENTREPRENEURS (Beijing) _ On Monday, China's Parliament
will tip its hat to the country's emerging entrepreneurs, amending
its Constitution to declare private business ``an important
component of the socialist market economy.'' By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOMBINGS (NOVO SELO, Yugoslavia) _ Both Albanian and
Serbs in a village not far from where attacks killed six on
Saturday say that they hope the latest round of talks in Paris will
bring peace and that they trust NATO troops to insure any accord.
By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Washington) _ American officials expect little
from the latest round of talks over Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-MASSACRES (Shanker Bigha, India) _ In one of India's
poorest and most populated states, a series of massacres have been
aimed at keeping low caste Indians in line. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-ABORTION (Dublin, Ireland) _ The dispute over Ireland's
virtual ban on abortion accelerates as four members of the European
Parliament _ all women _ accused the government of delaying a
statement of its policy on issue. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-UNCERTAINTY (Istanbul, Turkey) _ With a national election
approaching, Parliament in open rebellion against the political
establishment, murderous terror attacks being launched against
civilians and the trial of a hated Kurdish guerrilla leader
approaching, Turkey suddenly finds itself facing deep
uncertainties. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CONSERVATIVES (LONDON) _ The principal challenge these
days for William Hague, who heads Britain's depleted and dispirited
Conservative party, is simply trying to matter. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-REFORM (Fort Irwin, Calif.) _ Struggling to stay relevant,
the Army considers changes in the way it organizes divisions and
trains them to fight. Out here at the Army's premier training base,
the Army is still training to fight the Warsaw Pact, taking on an
enemy no one expects it to confront, in a way no one expects will
happen, with tactics no one expects to prevail. By Steven Lee
Myers. With art.
</P>
<P>
   With: ARMY-CASPIAN (Washington) _ The Army's wargamers devise a
scenario for the kind of messy intervention the United States is
more likely to see: protecting Caspian Sea oil. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-SAFETY-LOCK (Undated) _ There is little question that some
of the 1,500 accidental shooting deaths that occur annually could
have be prevented if gun are safely stored or put away unloaded.
But a look at how firearms companies have approached the use of one
device _ a safety lock that disables a semiautomatic handgun when
the magazine is removed _ provides a portrait of an unregulated
industry, one that apparently neither seeks independent answers
about important safety issues nor is capable of reaching consensus
from within. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN-FISH (Conneaut, Ohio) _ Call it nostalgia. Or
sentimentality. Or call it an uncanny prescience. Jim Anthony
himself is not exactly sure why he kept a a blue pike in his
freezer for 37 years, carefully rewrapping it every so often and
making sure his wife did not let the fish thaw out every time she
defrosted the freezer. Now, nearly four decades later, the pike has
become the central clue in a compelling scientific detective story,
sleuthing that some scientists are hoping will lead to an
extraordinary result: the return of an extinct species. By Pam
Belluck. With art.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ How does a politician with little
experience beyond his own state educate himself so he can run for
president _ or even be president? Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
established an unusually systematic approach, where hundreds of
experts are voyaging to Austin to educate him. We look inside those
meetings. How are they run? What do they talk about? And we look at
how some of the participants are already angling for big roles
should Bush get elected. By Richard Berke and Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY-INTERVENTION (Undated) _ Programs that seek to reduce
violence, drug abuse, pregnancy and other dangerous or unhealthy
activities among adolescents are notorious for doing too little too
late and at too great a cost. But a new study has shown that by
starting early _ in grades one through six _ to foster an interest
in school and learning among children and to enhance their
self-esteem, many of these risky behaviors can be averted and
school performance and attendance can be improved through high
school. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-COMPUTER-INJURY (Undated) _ In the rush to bring 21st
century technology to every child in the nation, experts say that
there has been virtually no discussion of health or safety to
insure that children have appropriate equipment and furniture and
proper training in posture and keyboard technique. While no one is
predicting a nation of crippled children, there is widespread
concern among physicians, physical therapists and ergonomists that
a tide of injury is inevitable as youngsters spend more time on
computers, both at school and at home. By Jane Gross. With art.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-OSHA-WHISTLEBLOWERS (Washington) _ After finding that
workers who complain of health and safety hazards are often
dismissed from their jobs, the Clinton administration will soon
propose sweeping new protections for such ``whistleblowers.''
Republicans are receptive to the idea. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-GAYS-HARASSMENT (Washington) _ Group representing gay
men and lesbians in the military says in a report that cases of
harassment have doubled in the last year, leaving service members
in a bind, since complaining often begins an investigation into
their sexuality. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by William Safire;
details later.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET -- A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports,
and special section stories; will move by 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER -- A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1; will move at 5:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT -- Stories scheduled for Page 1; will
move by 7 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT -- A description of the front page layout of
the first edition of The New York Times; will move at 7:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New York Times Partners: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Please note that your New York Times News Service report
includes news and features from The Arizona Republic, Bloomberg
News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Kansas
City Star, The Los Angeles Daily News, The San Francisco Chronicle,
The Seattle Post-Intelligencer, States News Service, and the New
York Times Regional Newspapers.
</P>
