<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, March
15:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE (Coded e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIENNA-PHILHARMONIC-WOMEN (New York) _ For 156 years, the Vienna
Philharmonic was a male-only preserve. But early in 1997, bowing to
pressure from women's groups abroad, the orchestra voted to open
its ranks to women. But a change in its membership policy will not
soon change the makeup of the Vienna Philharmonic, as the eerie
sight of one lone female, Anna Lelkes, a harpist, amid a stage full
of white males during the Shostakovich symphony made abundantly
clear. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-SHOWDOWN (Hollywood) _ Two of the heavyweight moguls in
the entertainment business, Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of
Miramax, and Jeffrey Katzenberg, co-owner of Dreamworks, have been
locked in a not-too-subtle clash over Miramax's aggressive efforts
to win the Academy Award for best picture for ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' or, possibly, ``Life Is Beautiful.'' By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA-ORCHESTRA (Undated) _ During its centennial, the
Philadelphia will offer its subscribers only those works composed
during the orchestra's lifetime, which exactly encompasses the 20th
century. This pertains only to the subscription series, but still,
its regular subscribers will face a season of music from this
century, a programming concept that no other American orchestra has
ever tried. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-BURIAL-MEMORIAL (New York) _ When the federal building
at 290 Broadway was completed in 1994, one thing was missing: the
memorial the government promised to build marking the 18th-century
African Burial Ground unearthed during the excavation for the
building. Monday, the federal General Services Administration plans
to announce the five teams of architects and historians who will
compete to design and build a 2,000-square-foot Interpretive
Center. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTOROW-COLUMN _ E.L. Doctorow writes about the effect of
filmmaking on the practice of literature in the ``Writers on
Writing'' column.
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-CONNECTIONS (Undated) _ As appreciations of the director
Stanley Kubrick continue after his death, with paeans to his icy
brilliance and his meticulous artistry, one of his major characters
is being neglected, and I don't mean Dr. Strangelove or HAL or
Lolita. I mean music. The Connections column, by Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   BETTY-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews ``Betty's
Summer Vacation,'' an ecstatically angry new comedy by Christopher
Durang.
</P>
<P>
   MOM-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Anita Gates reviews ``A Mom's
Life,'' Kathryn Grody's one-woman show.
</P>
<P>
   WHISPERING-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Caryn James reviews
``Whispering Pines,'' John Laroquette's new series.
</P>
<P>
   WALLS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``And the Walls Came Tumbling Down: Kentucky, Texas Western and the
Game that Changed American Sports,'' by Frank Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   CMGI-WETHERELL (Undated) _ David S. Wetherell, the 44-year-old
chairman and chief executive of the investment firm CMGI Inc. is
holding his cards close to his vest in a gamble that could become
the first hostile takeover battle in the short history of Internet
commerce. By Evan I. Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSQUATTERS (Washington) _ Though often labeled hijackers,
pirates or extortionists, ``cybersquatters'' is the most common
term for investors who seek popular names, book titles or
celebrity-related words to add to their stockpiles. For an
investment of just $70, they can secure two-year rights to a name.
In return, they can reap handsome rewards from companies eager to
protect products or trademarks. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SHYSTERS (Undated) _ While many consumers have worried that
Year 2000 computer problems will cripple the banking system,
bankers and law-enforcement officials have been warning that the
bigger financial risks may come from scam artists and thieves
playing on such fears. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFET-REPORT (Undated) _ Accounting gimmicks and
misrepresentations to investors have become so commonplace at
public companies that it has prompted Warren Buffett, in his annual
report to shareholders of Berkshire Hathaway Inc., to make an
extraordinary attack on many of his fellow chief executives, who he
says have worked purposefully ``at manipulating numbers and
deceiving investors.'' By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS-MEDIA (New York) _ Since 1995, the number of
mass-market paperbacks sold in the United States has declined by
almost 9 percent, falling to 484 million copies last year, about
three times the percentage loss in consumer books overall. And the
immediate future offers little comfort; the book industry's
research arm, the Book Industry Study Group, is projecting
continued slight annual declines for the paperback market over the
next several years. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   VANITYFAIR-MEDIA (Undated) _ At Vanity Fair's Oscar party last
year, Morton's restaurant became so choked with people that at
midnight the Los Angeles fire marshalls stormed in and took action.
That annual party has come to embody the magazine's happy symbiosis
with Hollywood. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKSELLERS-MEDIA (New York) _ Facing intensifying competition,
the nation's trade association for independent booksellers is
creating its own national online store, Book Sense, to stave off
fierce competition from Amazon.com and Barnesandnoble.com. By
Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER-CHANNEL-MEDIA (Undated) _ Reaching 70 million homes and
offering programming that may cost less to produce than almost
anything this side of C-SPAN, the Weather Channel is ``a cash
machine,'' in the estimation of Jessica Reif, a media analyst at
Merrill Lynch. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLYNDAVIS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Advertising column: As
imaginary advertising characters go, Carolyn Davis, who pitches
products in the pages of Reader's Digest magazine, is no Betty
Crocker. But Davis is now starting to get around. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   REGULAR FEATURES
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-COMMERCE (Undated) _ The digital commerce column. By
Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Sabra
Chartrand.
</P>
</TEXT>
