<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-SHOWDOWN-2TAKES     03-14 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-SHOWDOWN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATZENBERG AND WEINSTEIN: A COUPLE OF OLD PALS WRESTLING FOR AN
OSCAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It's Harvey versus Jeffrey!
</P>
<P>
   Two of the heavyweight moguls in the entertainment business,
Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax, and Jeffrey Katzenberg,
co-owner of Dreamworks, have been locked in a not too subtle clash
over Miramax's aggressive efforts to win the Academy Award for best
picture for ``Shakespeare in Love,'' or, possibly, ``Life Is
Beautiful.'' Miramax itself has turned Academy Awards campaigns
into an expensive art, heavily promoting films as varied as ``The
Piano,'' ``Pulp Fiction'' and ``The English Patient'' and winning
Oscars in some top categories.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dreamworks film ``Saving Private Ryan'' remains the
leading contender for the Oscar, the comedy ``Shakespeare in Love''
seems to be gaining. Katzenberg and his Dreamworks partners, Steven
Spielberg and David Geffen, are not only upset but also pointing to
magazine and newspaper articles containing allegations that
Miramax, which is owned by Walt Disney, has been bad-mouthing
``Saving Private Ryan,'' their World War II epic. Weinstein
vigorously denies this.
</P>
<P>
   With the Academy Award ceremonies next Sunday, Weinstein and
Katzenberg, who are old friends, got on the phone together the
other afternoon with a reporter to try to make it plain that
whatever the bad feelings about the Oscar race, they still liked
each other very much. Sort of. Complicating the relationship is the
fact that Katzenberg, while chairman of Walt Disney Studios, played
a role in Disney's purchase of Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Early on in the conversation, Katzenberg made it clear he was
displeased that Dreamworks was forced to spend millions more on its
Academy Award campaign for ``Saving Private Ryan'' because Miramax
had upped the ante with ``Shakespeare in Love'' and ``Life Is
Beautiful.'' Studios routinely promote their films in Variety and
The Hollywood Reporter to persuade the 5,000 members of the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences to select their movies. (The
others films nominated for best picture are ``Elizabeth'' and ``The
Thin Red Line.'')
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``The reason we're doing this is to show the town and
the world at large that there's a unity between the companies. I
have tremendous admiration for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``Even though Miramax has brought Dreamworks to its
knees, we're not taking it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``Actually there'll be a series of benefit concerts
with Gwyneth Paltrow, Matt Damon and Ben Affleck to raise money for
Dreamworks' additional expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``Which we graciously accept. Send the check. Harvey
had spent between seven and eight billion dollars. That's a B.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein (ignoring him): ``We spent $800,000 on the
post-nomination campaign for `Shakespeare in Love''' in the
Hollywood trade papers. ``We'll probably spend $10 million
post-nomination to market the film nationally. Of that we bought
consumer newspaper and spot television advertising in New York and
L.A. for $1 million. And that has blurred some of these figures
being tossed around about our academy campaign; $800,000 is not an
unseemly figure for an academy campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``They spent $3 million on the trades.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: `` `Life Is Beautiful,' we actually spent $550,000 _
tops $600,000. And that's because the majority of the seven
nominations are for Benigni so we can do ads for Benigni that
include all his nominations in the same ad. The overall campaign
from beginning to end for `Shakespeare' is $30 million. It's a bit
less than the overall campaign for `The English Patient.' I'm not
doing anything different to market these movies this year than any
other year. We began the movie with a small release. Went wide. Got
to the academy. And the blitzkrieg was really in support of the
commercial release of the film. `Shakespeare in Love' was $38
million at the box office before the nomination. It's $66 million
now. And it'll be $75 million by the time of the awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg was asked if he had increased his budget for the
Oscar campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``Yes, we've increased it. They have run a very
aggressive and competitive campaign. To run a competitive campaign
is certainly Harvey's right, although one of the things I know is
that you can't influence academy voters. I believe it. We have not
yet decided to forgive Harvey for it. But it's his right to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein started to speak, but Katzenberg interrupted: ``Before
his retort let us both agree that if Harvey turns himself into a
victim, you've got to give me a moment to get some Kleenex. It's
going to be a sad story.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``No victim! I agree. You can't influence academy
voters. The trade campaign in `Shakespeare' was, in some ways, for
people who made sacrifices. It was made for $38 million, and four
and a half of that was because of a false start in 1992. A lot of
people made sacrifices. The trades can help your technicians,
production designers, others, raise their salaries. It's sort of an
IOU for them. It can never influence best picture or any of the
other major categories. You know who outspent everybody? `City of
Angels.' They spent the most money pre-nominations. And it wasn't
nominated in any category.''
</P>
<P>
   The two were asked how they would characterize each other's
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``It's been brilliant on Jeffrey's part. All I do is
defend myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``Here we are. The victim speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``But really.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``It's a sad song, Harvey.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``I have said to every newspaper in the country, I
have said how much I respect `Private Ryan,' and I've said this
from the get-go.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``Tell the truth, Harvey. He told me he voted for
`Private Ryan.' Admit it, Harvey.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``No, no, no. I can't say that. But I voted for
`Schindler's List.'''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``Thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``I loved `Ryan.' My dad was a combat veteran. He
would never watch World War II movies because the violence was too
cartoonish. When I saw `Private Ryan,' it solved a mystery for me.
My dad passed away when I was 20. I called Steven to congratulate
him. I told Mrs. Clinton that the movie was a masterpiece and she
should see it, and Mrs. Clinton has an aversion to films with
violence. She and the president loved the movie. So this charge is
scurrilous and an effort by people to ruin long-standing
friendships. It's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``Who are the people, Harvey? Tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein (laughing): ``I don't know. Look, we want to take this
as constructive criticism and take it to heart. There will be less.
We've diminished our whole approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``We've redoubled ours.''
</P>
<P>
   They both laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``It's been an incredibly good year. The five movies
nominated are really pretty brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``I adored all five films. Anyone that wins, I'll be
happy about.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men were told that despite everything they still seemed
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``Seriously, these are my friends. Jeffrey, Steven
and David. I would never hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``What a beautiful story.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``He brought me into the company. Ever since he
brought me in to Disney, I've had to follow him around. I'm his
manservant. That's always my relationship with Jeffrey. I'm the
servant. He's my man. When I came on, and Jeffrey promised me
autonomy, I didn't know that would mean a phone call every 15
minutes from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``At the time, that was considered hands off for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``Everything's relative. I never had a better teacher
than Jeffrey Katzenberg, and there's no director I admire more than
Steven Spielberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg: ``There's nothing more disgusting than Harvey
sucking up.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein: ``That's not true. Even when he insults me, I still
love him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
