<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALK-RADIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK RADIO COPES WITH LIFE AFTER LEWINSKY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's romantic travails and legal entanglements
proved both a boon and bane to talk radio over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners who tuned in to hear titillating discussions about
Oval Office trysts lifted ratings of most radio talk shows last
spring and summer, radio executives say. However, by fall, as the
scandal shifted to constitutional questions, the sobriety of
impeachment hearings put off some listeners more entertained by
tales of sex, lies and telephone tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite renewed interest in Monica Lewinsky as she took her turn
in the spotlight during a promotional book tour during the last two
weeks, radio hosts and program directors say they are eager to move
beyond the left-right debates that characterized their shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so glad it's over,'' said Mary June Rose, program
director for Chicago's top-rated news-talk station, WGN. ``The
public said, `We're sick of hearing about it.' It will force talk
show hosts to work for their paychecks.''
</P>
<P>
   More people tuned in to the nation's 1,200 news-talk stations
last spring and summer when talk radio ratings on average increased
to 14.8 percent of the total listening audience for radio, up
eight-tenths of a percentage point over 1997 figures. Also there
was a smaller-than-normal drop-off from the winter, according to
the ratings service Arbitron. (Generally, listening declines after
winter when news about the weather is less crucial.) Later, in the
1998 final quarter, talk radio drew 15.3 percent of listeners,
compared with 15.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Call-in hosts like Rush Limbaugh and G. Gordon Liddy, who thrive
on political discussion, made the most of the scandal. But interest
gradually waned. Richard B. Wood, director of WOR Radio Network,
which syndicates 10 programs, including the Bob Grant talk show, to
400 stations, said: ``Talk radio ratings went down in the fall.
People were so tired of Bill Clinton and this one story.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether radio will suffer life-after-Lewinsky doldrums came up
at a recent talk radio conference, but was not a focal point, said
Al Peterson, an editor for Radio and Records, a weekly trade
publication. ``It was the same thing after the O.J. trial,'' he
said. ``The overall sense was, there's always a new topic.''
</P>
<P>
   Limbaugh, who declined through a spokesman to be interviewed,
regained his position as the nation's most-listened-to host in the
year's last half, according to a ranking to be released Tuesday by
Talkers magazine, a trade journal about talk stations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the magazine said Limbaugh had tumbled to No. 3
behind Dr. Laura Schlessinger and Howard Stern, a ranking Limbaugh
disputed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1653EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
