A9873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-CHANNEL-MEDIA     03-14 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-CHANNEL-MEDIA-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER CHANNEL'S LOW COSTS AND LOYAL VIEWERS CREATE A CABLE TV
SUCCESS STORY
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ohio, Miss., Fla., Va., Alaska, Ill., Tenn., Nev.)   (ms) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He may not know it, but Elmer Gruber is a ``weather weenie.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the affectionate nickname people at the Weather Channel
use for their most devoted viewers. And Gruber is a true devotee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of days the entertainment programs are so bad, I just
turn on the Weather Channel and watch,'' Gruber, 80, said in a
telephone interview from his home in suburban Cincinnati. ``We
watch the local weather on the 8's _ 8 after, 18 after, 28, 38 and
48 after,'' he said, the other half of ``we'' being his wife,
Eugina. ``Five- and seven-day forecasts are on at 20 after,'' said
Gruber, a retired surgical appliances executive, who estimates that
he watches the Weather Channel at least an hour every day. ``And
some days more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Weather Channel has not become one of the cable
industry's most widely distributed and profitable programmers on
the ratings of retirees alone. The ``weather involved'' _ another
of the company's labels _ includes people whose work requires them
to keep tabs on the elements.
</P>
<P>
   One is Joe Dier, head of media relations for the Mississippi
State University baseball team. (``If we know it will rain in the
third inning, the coach's strategy might change.'')
</P>
<P>
   Another is Steve Bruce, a floor broker for grains at the Chicago
Board of Trade, who watches the Weather Channel from the trading
pit. (``If there is a hurricane expected to hit New Orleans it
plugs up the river system; that's a problem.'')
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there are the voyeurs who are simply
fascinated by the weather, particularly when nature displays its
telegenic fury. These are the types that the Weather Channel
celebrates in its popular TV ads, which feature weather fanatics
who hang out at a fictional place called the Front and carry on as
if they were fans in a sports bar.
</P>
<P>
   Dier might fit right in at the Front. He grew up in
hurricane-prone Florida, moved to typhoon territory _ Okinawa,
Japan _ and then lived in Alaska, land of weather extremes. ``I
went into public relations, but I might have ventured toward
meteorology,'' said Dier, who once sent fan mail to his favorite
Weather Channel weathercaster, Vivian Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching 70 million homes and offering programming that may cost
less to produce than almost anything else this side of C-SPAN, the
Weather Channel is ``a cash machine,'' in the estimation of Jessica
Reif, a media analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The financial figures are not reported, because the channel is
privately held, owned by Landmark Communications, a
family-controlled company in Norfolk, Va., whose other media
holdings include The Virginian-Pilot, The Roanoke Times, KLAS-TV in
Las Vegas, and WTVF-TV in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   But a person familiar with its finances said that the Weather
Channel generated about $100 million in operating profits in 1998
on revenue of $200 million that came primarily from advertising, as
well as from fees paid by cable operators. With a remarkably high
profit margin of some 50 percent, the service could probably
attract a buyer willing to pay as much at 15 times cash flow, or
about $1.65 billion, according to Derek Baine, a cable analyst at
Paul Kagan Associations, the media consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Battan family, Landmark's owners, reportedly has no plans to
sell the Weather Channel, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have 50 percent margins, why sell it?'' Ms. Reif said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The operation is run out of a sleek eight &UR; - &LR; story office
building just outside Atlanta. There, 80 meteorologists analyze
weather data provided primarily by the National Weather Service,
supplemented by other sources that include military weather feeds.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of any 15-minute segment, a Weather Channel viewer
can get national, regional and local coverage that includes maps,
charts and other data. The national weather programming,
transmitted by satellite, appears on all local systems. For local
forecasts, cable operators have hardware and software systems that
can sift out the relevant information from the Weather Channel's
data feed, to present the local weather in text and graphics during
local breaks in the national program.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, many of the 30 on-camera meteorologists have become
celebrities in their own right. Cheryl Lempke, for example, is
about to be featured in a fashion shoot in Mirabella magazine.
</P>
<P>
   With so many meteorologists, the Weather Channel can have
specialists, like John Hope, the channel's 79-year-old hurricane
maven, who works only during tropical storm season, from June to
November. His is a popular beat with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to talk to me all the time,'' Hope said, ``but I
can't take all the calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1982 and profitable by 1985, according to the Weather
Channel's president, Michael Eckert, the meteorological service is
able to repackage its material for other media. The channel, for
example, provides weather reports to 250 radio stations across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Channel's weather maps are also sold to 52
newspapers _ including The New York Daily News, The Detroit Free
Press and The San Francisco Examiner _ through a distribution
arrangement with Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to go global, though, were a washout. After opening a
network operation center in London in late 1995, the Weather
Channel began offering service in Britain, the Netherlands, Germany
and Italy. But with many of the European cable systems already
filled, or nearly so, the Weather Channel had trouble making its
way into enough households to create an advertising base. The
European experiment ended early last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, with 95 percent of the Weather Channel's
revenue and profit coming from the cable channel, the company is
exploring other media outlets. Its Internet site, Weather.com,
ranked 21st among all Web sites in January, with 6.2 million
different visitors, according to the measurement company Media
Metrix Inc.
</P>
<P>
   On the ad-supported site, visitors can order books, make
suggestions for the service, monitor snow conditions in ski country
and check out weather reports by city.
</P>
<P>
   Other technologies are beckoning. ``We are looking at new
platforms, new ways to generate revenues _ Palm Pilots, pagers, all
of these new technologies that let consumers receive weather
information,'' Eckert said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also testing interactive weather data with Wink
Communications Inc., a company that works with cable operators to
offer services that let individual viewers select information from
a variety of options. The Weather Channel is now testing a Wink
service with viewers in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the Weather Channel is almost totally dependent
on its regular cable business. And with the channel already
available in 98 percent of the nation's cable households, there is
not much room for growth in that medium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the network has one key advantage over many cable
channels: it does not have to worry about its programming going out
of style. Many viewers seem unable to get enough weather news _
even if the Weather Channel's forecasters are not infallible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's raining outside,'' Dier, the baseball publicist,
complained during a telephone interview from his home in
Starkville, Miss., last week. ``The Weather Channel said it was not
going to rain. They were wrong this morning. This is the one time
they were wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-UNCERTAINTY-NY     03-14 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-UNCERTAINTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID MOUNTING TURMOIL, TURKEY FACING DEEP UNCERTAINTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ With a national election approaching,
Parliament in open rebellion against the political establishment,
murderous terror attacks being mounted against civilians and the
trial of a hated Kurdish guerrilla leader approaching, Turkey
suddenly finds itself facing deep uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   ``A chaos is now awaiting Turkey,'' Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
said Saturday. ``This is a totally new situation. We will have to
think about it and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit spoke after a group of disgruntled members of Parliament
broke the pre-election recess and managed to convene an
extraordinary session. They voted to meet again later this week,
possibly to consider postponing the April 18 election and debate
other measures abhorrent to the political and military elite.
</P>
<P>
   As the parliamentary session was underway Saturday in Ankara,
three men sped past a crowded Istanbul shopping center and hurled a
fire bomb through a window. Thirteen people perished in the
inferno. No one took responsibility, and there were no immediate
arrests. It was the third fatal act of terrorism in Turkey this
month.
</P>
<P>
   A Maoist faction seriously wounded a provincial governor,
killing a 14-year-old girl and two others in the attempt, in a car
bombing near Ankara on March 5. One of the alleged assailants was
arrested, and information he provided led the police to raid a
house that was found to contain an arsenal of guns and bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week two bombs exploded in Istanbul, one of them killing a
taxi driver. As in Saturday's shopping center attack, there was no
claim of responsibility, but speculation centered on groups angered
by the capture of the Kurdish leader Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan is being held at an island prison 35 miles southwest of
the capital. He is reportedly cooperating with his interrogators,
and according leaked accounts of his purported testimony, has
expressed repentance for his group's violent acts.
</P>
<P>
   As Ocalan's admirers seek to decide how to proceed without him,
however, at least some have apparently decided to commit acts of
urban terror. Such acts have been rare in Turkey's western cities,
which lie far from the southeastern provinces where the Kurdish war
is being fought.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish authorities have announced that they will try
Ocalan, probably within the next few months. He has been charged
with treason, which can carry the death penalty, and may also be
charged with responsibility for a series of fatal attacks launched
by his guerrilla fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a disturbing combination of things happening at the
same time,'' said a foreign diplomat posted in Istanbul. ``You've
got a potentially very important election coming up, Parliament is
in upheaval, and now this rash of bombings. If the attacks spread
to tourist areas, the problem is going to become economic as well
as political. All in all it's quite a messy moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislators' session on Saturday was organized by a group of
deputies angry that their party leaders had dropped them from lists
of candidates for re-election. They want the election postponed,
and are supported by one party afraid that if elections are held
next month, it will fail to win the 10 percent of votes necessary
to enter Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Some deputies from the Islamic-oriented Virtue party also voted
for the successful motion to convene another parliamentary session
later this week. They don't much care when the election is held,
but have an agenda of their own, one that deeply angers Ecevit and
other secular politicians and generals.
</P>
<P>
   These deputies want to repeal a law that allows parties to be
banned if they are deemed to be challenging the secular Republic.
They are also seeking to overturn a court under which their most
prominent leader, former Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan, was
found to be introducing religion into politics and forbidden to run
for Parliament or participate in politics for the next five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1655EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKSELLERS-MEDIA-725     03-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKSELLERS-MEDIA-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT BOOKSELLERS PLAN TO OPEN ONLINE STORE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facing intensifying competition, the nation's trade
association for independent booksellers is creating its own
national online store, Book Sense, to stave off fierce competition
from Amazon.com and Barnesandnoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   The online venture, which is scheduled to open for business this
summer, is the most ambitious element in a series of
countermeasures to promote independent bookstores by the American
Booksellers Association, the dominant trade group for a beleaguered
fraternity that has seen its share of the popular consumer book
market shrink to about 17 percent today from 32 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Those pressures have continued to intensify with competition
from superstore chains and online bookstores, prompting some store
owners to abandon the business with bitter complaints that they are
under siege. The electronic bookstore and a planned national
marketing campaign are the first collective efforts of an
ordinarily disparate group of independents. The goals is to compete
against some of the forces that have reduced ABA membership to
about 3,300 from 5,200 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to knock off the Goliaths _ I don't want to
look naive,'' said Hut Landon, a bookstore owner in Mill Valley,
Calif., and the executive director of the Northern California
Independent Booksellers Association, which developed the pilot
concept last year. ``All we're trying to do is retain our market
share. We recognize that we've got to do this in this day and age.
We can't just be quaint little booksellers in our community asking
how the kids are.''
</P>
<P>
   The association already has organized a series of 12 customer
focus groups along with the development of the electronic
bookstore. In its initial stages, the store will feature all the
standard functions of popular online sites, including a search
engine, a stock of 1.5 million titles, credit card fulfillment,
gift wrapping, distribution services and a best-seller list. But it
will also allow individual stores to tailor Web pages to reflect
their individuality with store reviews and features.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're really trying to do is find the different ways that
we can do what our competitors are doing,'' said Michael F. Hoynes,
the association's newly hired marketing officer. He said initial
interest in the program was enthusiastic because booksellers have
been asking for a collective approach.
</P>
<P>
   The booksellers' association, based in Tarrytown, N.Y., will
begin its first national marketing campaign in May for the Book
Sense brand, which in some ways is inspired by the example of the
independent hardware stores that promote themselves under the True
Value label.
</P>
<P>
   The association plans to spend about $2 million to develop the
electronic bookstore and about $2 million more on the marketing
campaign _ money that comes in part from its half-share of $25
million that the association won from Penguin Group USA in a
dispute over favorable discounts that were given to large retail
bookstore chains.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern California, where there is a strong and active group
of independent booksellers, the regional association has also spent
about $100,000 to promote a common identity under the name Book
Sense. The brand and a slogan, ``Independent Bookstores for
Independent Minds,'' are appearing in newspaper advertisements and
on decals, posters, and plastic shopping bags in the Bay Area,
where more than 200 bookstores have signed up to participate in the
pilot program.
</P>
<P>
   But the collective approach envisioned by the national
association is broader in scope, conceivably allowing customers to
order books online with the freedom to pick up or return a book at
any participating Book Sense store. The association is already in
discussions with a national wholesaler, Baker &AMP; Taylor, to provide
distribution services, a critical element for an online service
that caters to customers with swift delivery. It is also
considering expanding the electronic title base to include
out-of-print books.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the pricing system still is being determined,
although individual bookstore owners will have great flexibility to
offer discounts on their templates, said Len Vlahos, the
association's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next few months, the association will start signing
up members to participate in the electronic project, which would
cost bookstore owners monthly development fees expected to range
from $175 to $450.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several technology analysts said that the move was a vital step
to protect the booksellers eroding turf, and noted that the
independents may be able to capitalize on strengths in ways that
Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble cannot.
</P>
<P>
   David Brodwin, an associate partner with Andersen Consulting who
follows electronic commerce, said the Book Sense venture would draw
on the loyalty of customers who prefer local bookstores over
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independents will feature locally relevant information _
travel, restaurant guides, local history _ with a degree of
sophistication and connoisseurship that the nationwide players may
have trouble matching,'' Brodwin said. He cautioned, though, that
associations often move slowly. That could present problems for
success in electronic commerce, which requires decisiveness and
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Delhagen, the director of online retail strategies for
Forrester Research Inc., a technology research company, said that
independent booksellers had no choice but to act because customers'
shopping habits were changing.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester projects that almost $1.2 billion in book purchases
will be made online this year, she said. Spending will rise in 2003
to almost $3 billion, or about 18 percent of the book market, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book lover in me is thrilled to hear about this for the
independents,'' Ms. Delhagen said. ``Banding together and forming a
network is the only way. This is a huge opportunity for them to
survive, because long term, they're getting eviscerated. There is
an option now rather than shuttering their stores. This development
presents them with an opportunity to say, `I'm sticking around, and
we're not letting Amazon and Barnes &AMP; Noble run us out of town.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
