<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PORTALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPROAR OVER USA NETWORKS-LYCOS DEAL MAY LEAD TO RETHINKING OF
PORTAL CONCEPT
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether or not shareholders ultimately bless or curse the
proposed merger of Lycos with Barry Diller's television shopping
company, USA Networks, the deal may well have catalyzed a
long-overdue rethinking of the business of Internet portals, those
launching pads from which millions of Web surfers rocket onto the
Internet each day.
</P>
<P>
   Until the announcement of the USA Networks-Lycos deal sent the
stock of both companies plummeting, Internet portals _ most of
which used to be known by the more nerdy term ``search engines'' _
had been the darlings of Internet-happy Wall Streeters,
stratospheric in their valuations.
</P>
<P>
   But even with most portal stocks holding their value, the
leaders of some of these companies now say their business needs
redefinition.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea was that the sheer numbers of visitors to
portals would draw advertisers, who needed to drive traffic to
their sites so that they, in turn, could sell advertising based on
traffic. As demand for ad space outstripped the available number of
Web pages at their sites, portal companies started bulking up with
news and contests, stock quotes and product promotions, shopping,
custom home pages and free e-mail _ just about anything they could
think of that would both create advertising space and keep the
largest number of users coming back.
</P>
<P>
   But now many portal executives are afraid the portal may become
the ``network television'' of the Internet by appealing to the
lowest common denominator. As a result, they are beginning to
question the value and the proper roles of content and services as
audience magnets. Some are also beginning to agree with early
critics who predicted that advertising would not be a viable
long-term business strategy for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They are even stepping up early to narrow the grandiose
expectations that electronic commerce _ like portals, part of a
long lineage of solutions in search of a problem _ will finally
kick the Internet into the high-gear global money machine we keep
waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Search engines were of inestimable value in the early days of
the Web because they were the only way to find anything on the
Internet. Everybody used them; virtually all were free and heavily
trafficked.
</P>
<P>
   The portal concept was born, says Chan Suh, the chief executive
of Agency.com, when ``America Online did this brilliant thing _
they got Internet access and content, but all the links led to
things inside AOL.'' Opening a door into America Online, instead of
onto the global network, created a huge, measurable audience for
advertisers in search of eyeballs and made America Online the most
valuable commercial real estate in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   But Suh now asserts that portals have already seen their best
days.
</P>
<P>
   Like Suh, at least one portal executive believes that the
business is beginning to veer perilously close to the ways of a
dying medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest fear is becoming like TV networks, a commodity,''
George Bell, the chief executive of Excite Inc., said at a recent
industry conference. ``How do we avoid being seen as a commodity
distributor? How do we become more than a little bit of
everything?''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're taking generic content and reorganizing it''
under Excite's brand, but that idea is certainly not proprietary.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it proving particularly valuable to users, said Linda
McCutcheon, president of Time Inc. New Media. ``We're describing
assets, not consumer benefits,'' Ms. McCutcheon said of most
portals' attitudes about content. ``It's like getting in your car
and saying, `Honey, it's a beautiful day. Let's drive through the
Lincoln Tunnel.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If questioning the value of content were not heretical enough,
some portal purveyors are also sure that advertising itself, as it
is practiced today, is on its way out as a significant revenue
stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising won't carry the freight, because there's no reason
it should,'' Bell said. ``The Web does something different. It
interacts, and interactivity begets data. We should focus on direct
marketing, driven by personalization and away from the retail
chain.''
</P>
<P>
   This may prove trickier for portals like Excite, which does not
own anything it can sell, than it has been for sites like Time
Inc.'s Pathfinder and Viacom's MTV Online. Through the eyes of
these companies, which sell their own products through their
portals, it is even clearer that traditional Web advertising may
have seen its day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the audience is there, we will be able to monetize them,''
said Matt Farber, president of MTV Online, using one of today's
favored buzzwords for turning a customer relationship into cash.
``Advertising becomes E-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Suh said, is that ``portals are dead.'' Search
engines and generic advertising and content, he said, are nearly
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that a lot of people had in the beginning of the Web
revolution is finally starting to gel a little bit,'' he said.
``People are inventing their own content. On discussion boards,
stock chat areas, family picture and discussion sites _ they've
invented content in ways they couldn't have before, and that is
going to be the most important thing for portals.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means the Web is in fact not a mass medium, but a medium
for the masses, who are already well along in the process of making
it their own.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bell, Diller and many others are already devising new
marketing stratagems to take advantage of this shift, it will be
fascinating to see who is willing to participate. Will people
inventing their own content welcome personalized marketing? Or will
most folks simply say, ``Monetize this''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
