<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOROW-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK CUTS: THE NOVEL FOLLOWS FILM INTO A WORLD OF FEWER WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This is an article in a series in which writers explore literary
themes. The series began on March 1 when John Updike, writing as
his character Henry Bech, considered the relationship between an
author and his alter ego.) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By E.L. DOCTOROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The effect of a hundred years of filmmaking on the practice of
literature has been considerable.
</P>
<P>
   As more than one critic has noted, today's novelists tend not to
write exposition as fully as novelists of the 19th century. Where
the first chapter of Stendahl's ``Red and the Black'' (1830) is
given over to the leisurely description of a provincial French
town, its topographic features, the basis of its economy, the
person of its mayor, the mayor's mansion, the mansion's terraced
gardens and so on, Faulkner's ``Sanctuary'' (1931) begins this way:
``From beyond the screen of bushes which surrounded the spring,
Popeye watched the man drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20th-century novel minimizes discourse that dwells on
settings, characters' CVs and the like. The writer finds it
preferable to incorporate all necessary information in the action,
to carry it along in the current of the narrative, as is done in
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are 19th-century works, Mark Twain's ``Tom
Sawyer,'' for example (`` `Tom?' No answer.''), that jump right
into things, and perhaps American writers always have been disposed
to move along at a snappier pace than their European counterparts.
But the minimal use of exposition does suppose a kind of filmic
compact between writer and reader, that everything will become
clear eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the rise of film art is coincident with the
tendency of novelists to conceive of compositions less symphonic
and more solo voiced, intimate personalist work expressive of the
operating consciousness. A case could be made that the novel's
steady retreat from realism is as much a result of film's expansive
record of the way the world looks as it is of the increasing
sophistications of literature itself.
</P>
<P>
   Another crossover effect has to do with film's major device, the
instantaneous reposition in space and time: the cut. Writers today
derive all sorts of effects from scanting the interstitial
explanations or transitions that get their story from one character
to another, or their characters from one place to another, or from
yesterday to next year. More daring uses of discontinuity have
occurred from violations of the grammatical protocols of person or
tense.
</P>
<P>
   But after a hundred years or so, it may be that movies can do
nothing more for, or to, literature than they already have done. By
now film has begun to affirm its essentially nonliterate nature and
to make of its conventions an art form detached and self-contained,
like painting.
</P>
<P>
   Movies began in silence. The early filmmakers learned to convey
meaning apart from the use of language. For the most part the title
cards of the silent films only nailed down the intelligence given
to the audience nonverbally. (Young couple on porch swing at night.
He removes a ring from his vest pocket. He gazes into her eyes.
Title card: ``Milly, will you be my wife?'')
</P>
<P>
   In the modern audible feature film, especially as made by
Hollywood, spoken dialogue tends more and more to function as the
old title cards of the silents. The genre of the film is indicated
with the portentous opening credits. The beginning shots site the
film and identify its time period. A given scene is lighted, and
the camera is positioned to create mood or inform the audience as
to how it is to regard what it is seeing, how serious or unserious
the story may be, how objectively we may regard the characters, how
intimately we are being asked to share their adventures.
</P>
<P>
   The film stock is color coordinated with its subject. The actors
are dressed, and their hair is cut or coiffed, to indicate age,
economic class, social status, education and even degree of virtue.
They're directed to demonstrate their characters' states of mind
with bodily attitudes, gestures, facial expressions and the
movements of their eyes. Given all this, the weight of the scene is
carried nonverbally. What is seen and felt is a signifying context
for any words actually spoken. In some of today's film dramas, 95
percent of a scene's meaning is conveyed before a word is uttered;
98 percent if you add music.
</P>
<P>
   Of course recent filmmakers _ Eric Rohmer, for example, or Louis
Malle _ have made highly verbal films. As a generalization, the
assemblage of visual effects that make of dialogue a capstone is
less true of comedy. The art of the television sitcom, for example,
is highly verbal. Its standing sets, and its inclination to
celebrate character, provide the impetus for wordplay, gags and
verbal economies that can verge on the aphoristic. On the other
hand the sitcom's mostly interior scenes and its limited scope for
camera setups suggest it is closer to a filmed stage play than it
is to movies.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s and 40s, when stage plays and books were a major
source of film scripts, the talkies were talkier (as adaptations of
Shakespeare are still). Films of that period were, by comparison
with today's products, logorrheic. Even action films, the Bogart
film noir, the Errol Flynn swashbuckler, abounded with dialogue.
Now, after a century of development, the medium of film generates
its own culture. Its audience is as schooled in its rhythms and
motifs and habits of being as Wagnerians are in der Nibelungen.
Films work off previous films. They are genre referential and can
be more of what they are by nature.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1708EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTOROW-COLUMN-ART-2     03-14 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOROW-COLUMN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: by nature.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Literary language extends experience in discourse. It flowers to
thought with nouns, verbs, objects. It thinks. That is why the term
``film language'' may be an oxymoron. Film de-literates thought; it
relies primarily on an association of visual impressions or
understandings. Moviegoing is an act of inference. You receive what
you see as a broad band of sensual effects that evoke your
intuitive nonverbal intelligence. You understand what you see
without having to think it through with words.
</P>
<P>
   What shall we make of this? Today, at the end of the century,
film is ubiquitous. There are more movies than ever. They are in
theaters, on television; they are cabled, videotaped, CD'd and
DVD'd. They are sent around the world by satellite transmission;
they are dubbed and translated and available from all their periods
for consumers to choose as books are chosen from the library. Their
enormous popularity reaches all classes and all levels of
education. Their primary producers are major entertainment
conglomerates that put lots of money into them and expect even more
money in return.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that great and important films will no longer be made.
But one can imagine a merger of film esthetics and profit-making
incentives that, apart from the efforts of this or that serious and
principled filmmaker, effects a culture of large, beautifully
dressed, tactically pigmented, stimulating and only incidentally
verbal movies that excite predetermined market tastes and offer
societal myths that slightly vary with each recycling: films
composed artfully from the palette of such basic elements as car
drive-ups, interiors, exteriors, faces, chases and explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Just as significant for the culture of the future may be the
declining production costs of computerized, digitally made movies.
It is not hard to understand the lure to the creative young when
making a film will be as feasible as writing a story.
</P>
<P>
   That pictograms, whether corporately or privately produced, may
eventually unseat linguistic composition as the major communicative
act of our culture is a prospect I find only slightly less dire
than global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most thoughtful if not ingenious criticism written
today is written by critics of film who, often as not, address
themselves to work that is hardly worth their attention. The most
meretricious or foolish movie will elicit a cogent analysis. Why?
It may be a film's auspices that obligate the critics. But it may
be that, however unconsciously, they mean to reaffirm or defend
print culture by subjecting the nonliterate filmgoing experience,
good or bad, to the extensions of syntactical thought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1708EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUBRICK-CONNECTIONS-A     03-14 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUBRICK-CONNECTIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK AND BEETHOVEN, A MARRIAGE MADE IN HELL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN 
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As appreciations of the director Stanley Kubrick continue after
his death, with paeans to his icy brilliance and his meticulous
artistry, one of his major characters is being neglected, and I
don't mean Dr. Strangelove or or Lolita. I mean music.
</P>
<P>
   For Kubrick music is not just background. It has all the
lineaments of a very complex and literal character, playing a
particular role, affecting the films' other characters, altering
our perceptions. The music's fate, particularly in ``A Clockwork
Orange,'' reveals much about the peculiar nature of Kubrick's moral
and political universe.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, what happens to Alex, the sadistic thug
in ``Clockwork,'' when he is being reconditioned by the government.
Alex is brought into a movie theater and is forced to watch films
of grotesque violence. He can't turn away from the gushing blood
and brutal beatings. He is physically prevented from blinking or
closing his eyes. Instead of experiencing the thrill of ecstasy
such images once brought him, they become associated with nausea
and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, we are meant to think. We know exactly how he feels
strapped in that chair, for we have just gone through the same
experiment. During the first half-hour of the film , as Alex and
his friends stomp and kick and rape for the sheer pleasure of it,
there are few viewers who do not want to turn away in disgust and
fury and either return the videotape or exit the theater.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other way in which we end up feeling some empathy
for this monstrous being strapped in a straitjacket. The films used
to brainwash Alex are accompanied by background music from
Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, Alex's favorite composition. By the
time the conditioning is over, not only does the thought of
violence churn his stomach, so does the sound of that music.
</P>
<P>
   But Kubrick has done audiences the same favor earlier in the
film. Some of the musical allusions are just jokes: the doorbell of
Alex's victims chimes out the theme from Beethoven's Fifth. The
association of Beethoven with violence is unrelenting. The Ninth
Symphony, traditionally considered an ecstatic celebration of
transcendent brotherhood, is inextricably knit by Kubrick into the
way we experience Alex's imaginings of sadistic rape and massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``O, bliss, bliss and heaven,'' he thinks as he listens, ``I
never knew such lovely pictures.'' Rossini's effervescent overture
to ``La Gazza Ladra'' (``The Thieving Magpie'') becomes the
balletic score for a vicious gang rape and rumble inside an
abandoned theater.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of Kubrick's legacies is the way he sullied certain
compositions by completely inverting their familiar associations.
So much so perhaps that there may be music lovers who never escape
the director's reconditioning, any more than listeners of a certain
age can avoid thinking of the monolith in ``2001'' when hearing
Richard Strauss' ``Also Sprach Zarathustra'' or of a gracefully
turning space station when hearing the ``Blue Danube'' waltz.
</P>
<P>
   The music in ``A Clockwork Orange,'' as in some of Kubrick's
other films, is not incidental to the work but is at its center. By
the middle of the film, as Alex's horrific acts fade into memory
and it becomes ever more clear how venal, shallow and creepy many
of his victims and persecutors are, we are meant to begin to feel
some sympathy for him.
</P>
<P>
   We object to the psychologists' forced associations of Beethoven
with violence and nausea. Our old love for the music as noble and
transcendent is meant to kick in. Alex becomes a state-programmed
victim, at sea in a world without music's comforts.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alex's earlier association of Beethoven with violence and
rape, Kubrick seems to suggest, is partly a product of a world
where beauty is violated: sexual graffiti mark up a classical
mural; an opera house stripped of seats is the scene for a gang
rape.
</P>
<P>
   So music is a wronged innocent. Surrounding Alex is a world of
vulgarity. His parents have velvet kitsch on the walls. One of his
victims has her walls covered with erotic kitsch; a writer and his
wife decorate their home as if it were a rejected stage set from
``2001.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alex loves higher things, even keeping a bust of Beethoven
in his prison cell. Alex is an enlightened victim in a heartless
world, and his sins reflect that world, although his tastes show a
greater authenticity and promise.
</P>
<P>
   This vision of Alex as ``authentic'' is ugly as well as
sentimental. But Kubrick wants to go even further. He seems to
suggest not just that Alex's dystopian society has corrupted
beauty, but that there is something latent in the classical
tradition that has caused the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Alex, as well as his tormentors, have it right in their
associations between the classical world and violence. Beauty has
nothing to do with morality. Opera houses may not stage such
gruesome rapes as Alex and his pals perform, but they are home to
dramas that reek with inhumanity. (Even Rossini, in ``La Gazza
Ladra,'' puts his characters through extensive traumas for the sake
of a joke about a bird that steals silverware.)
</P>
<P>
   Great art holds the seeds of great horror. Alex is finding in
Beethoven what other listeners have found, for example, in
associating Wagner with Nazism. Some of these ideas have even been
raised in recent years by musicologists who seek to determine the
political meanings of music. (One musicologist has even associated
a Beethoven symphony with images of rape.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the soldiers in ``Full Metal Jacket'' wears a peace
symbol along with a helmet proclaiming ``Born to Kill.'' When asked
why, he replies: ``I think I was trying to suggest something about
the duality of man, the Jungian thing, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick also wants it both ways in many of his films, admiring
the ideals of classical art (even in his filmmaking) while
condemning them, scorning unholy violence while suggesting that its
origins and ultimate responsibility lie elsewhere, demanding that
human beings be judged as moral animals but not finding them free
enough to ever make a choice.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that Alex's forced programming, which links music
with nausea, is undone in the movie, allowing him to enjoy freely
his earlier associations. But Kubrick never releases his audience.
One departs unsettled, hung over with hints of nihilism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1717EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
