<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CMGI-WETHERELL-ART-2T     03-14 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-WETHERELL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE LYCOS SHOWDOWN, A POKER-FACED SHAREHOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ohio., Conn., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EVAN I. SCHWARTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, almost without fail, David Wetherell played
poker with friends on the first Thursday night of each month. Two
years ago, as his Internet investments started taking more of his
time, he had to give up poker. But the 44-year-old chairman and
chief executive of the investment firm CMGI Inc. is holding his
cards close to his vest once again _ this time in a gamble that
could become the first hostile takeover battle in the short history
of Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of moves meant to disrupt the pending merger of the
Web ``portal'' Lycos Inc. with the Internet holdings of Barry
Diller's television company, USA Networks Inc., Wetherell resigned
from the Lycos board last week. He then promptly hired Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter to seek other buyers for Lycos, in which
Wetherell's firm holds 18.5 percent, the largest single stake.
Potential acquirers might include CMGI itself, which has invested
in scores of Web start-ups over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainties may have contributed to a selloff of both
companies' stocks on Friday _ along with investor disappointment
that CMGI did not announce a hoped-for stock split when it reported
second-quarter earnings late Thursday. In a stampede of apparent
profit taking, CMGI's shares fell $18.125, to close at $164 in
Nasdaq trading, while Lycos shares fell $10.375, to close at
$98.625.
</P>
<P>
   The battle is over a company that Wetherell himself founded. In
1994 Lycos was a noncommercial Web directory _ a site for
conducting searches _ based on software developed at
Carnegie-Mellon University. Through CMGI, Wetherell bought the
technology for $2 million and hired a former Wang Laboratories
salesman, Robert Davis, as the first employee of Lycos Inc., which
is now based in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who soon became the chief executive, took the company
public in April 1996. At that point, Wetherell got out of the way
and watched Lycos mushroom into a company with a share price of
$127.25 and a market value of nearly $6 billion, just before the
USA Networks deal was announced on Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
   By many measures, when Davis and Diller announced their plan to
merge Lycos with the Internet operations of USA Networks, it
completed an ideal cycle for a venture capitalist like Wetherell _
from start-up, to successful public stock offering, to a merger
with a potentially complementary media-company partner. The
agreement, a complex stock swap, valued Lycos at $6.6 billion. That
meant CMGI's initial modest investment was now worth about $1.2
billion. And at first, Wetherell said he supported the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But when investors turned cold on the complex terms, which
seemed to many to favor Diller, the Lycos stock price plunged more
than 31 percent in two days, to $87.25. That reduced the company's
market value to $4.42 billion. Wetherell began wavering, soon
called for a renegotiation of the merger pact, and, then, last
week, took more drastic steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its present construct, I am opposed to the deal,''
Wetherell said in an interview last Thursday. ``As far as I know,
in the history of acquisitions, no stock of an acquired company has
gone down by that much so soon. And the more I've analyzed the
deal, the more I've found difficulties with pieces of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that a number of options are open to him, including
CMGI's trying to trump the USA offer by coming up with a counterbid
to buy back the rest of Lycos, perhaps with the assistance of a
giant media or technology partner. ``We're taking a fresh
approach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Lycos is now in play. And if Wetherell resumes
control of it, he does not rule out significant changes in
management and strategy.
</P>
<P>
   With the stock market value of Lycos now down to $4.2 billion, a
CMGI takeover is certainly more affordable than it would have been
in early February. Yet, by the same measure, the value of the
original deal _ even after the initial two-day stock slump _ now
looks a lot better than it did at the time. But people who know
Wetherell say the motives here may not be purely financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is looking at the numbers, but it's also about the
people,'' said Margaret Heffernan, chief executive of Zinezone.com,
an online lifestyle magazine in which CMGI is the majority owner.
Ms. Heffernan and others who know Davis and Wetherell say they have
watched the relationship deteriorate over time.
</P>
<P>
   Davis declined to comment last week, but the company issued a
statement saying that ``Bob Davis and Lycos remain committed to the
transaction with USA Networks.'' As for the CMGI chairman's
resignation from the board, the statement said, Davis and Lycos
``appreciate David Wetherell's contribution to the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Davis struck an agreement with Diller, it was widely
discussed that some sort of major Lycos deal was imminent _ rumors
that were swapped on bulletin boards on most of the major online
investment sites. Driven by such speculation, the already
stratospheric stock of Lycos doubled again in a matter of weeks in
early 1999, soaring as high as $145. As a result, by the time Lycos
and USA Networks announced their deal, an already sizable takeover
premium was built into the price _ bolstering Diller's reluctance
to offer a big premium in the merger agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Wetherell insists that price is not the only issue. He said
it was a mistake for Davis to concede majority voting rights in the
combined company to Diller's company, and he no longer thinks that
USA Networks is the right partner strategically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand Disney's model with the Go network,'' Wetherell
said, referring to Walt Disney Co.'s new Web service, which Diller
and Davis have cited as a competitive factor in their wanting USA
Networks to team up with Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   ``ABC News can drive traffic to ABC.com, and ESPN can drive
traffic to ESPN.com,'' Wetherell continued. ``But USA doesn't have
the same reach. How much traffic can USA Networks drive to Lycos?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Diller, to the extent that he has been willing to address
Wetherell's moves in recent interviews and speeches, has tended to
dismiss them as maneuvers motivated more by stock valuations than
by long-term strategies.
</P>
<P>
   So who is David Wetherell, this executive whose name until
recently was little heard outside the Internet investment world but
who is now taking on one of the media industry's best-known
entrepreneurs?
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell grew up in Connecticut and Florida, before attending
Ohio Wesleyan University, where he majored in mathematics. By his
own account, he has a ``facility with numbers.'' And colleagues are
often awestruck by his ability to work complex financial models in
his head during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Wetherell was an obscure software industry executive
when he engineered a leveraged buyout of a 20-year-old company
called College Marketing Group, which rented out mailing lists of
college professors. He took the company public as CMG Information
Services Inc. in 1994, by which time it was throwing off enough
profit to finance other investments. These included Lycos, as well
as a little company called Booklink that Wetherell scooped up for
$900,000 and sold 10 months later to America Online for about $70
million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We then had more money than we knew what to do with,''
Wetherell recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He soon had inquiries from Microsoft Corp. and Intel Corp.,
which each bought 4.9 percent stakes in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, CMG Information Services (which changed its name to CMGI
last December) was an active investment company, setting up At
Ventures, the investment arm of CMGI that attracted hundreds of
millions of dollars in fresh venture capital and led to big hits _
like CMGI's approximately $6 million investment in Geocities, a
popular online community Web site that is in the process of being
sold to Yahoo, netting CMGI a profit of about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI is now in the process of selling one of its operating
companies, CMG Direct, for $24 million to a New York marketing firm
called SMGI. At that point, CMGI will more closely resemble a pure
investment company _ a characteristic that could prompt the
Securities and Exchange Commission to consider reclassifying CMGI
as a mutual fund concern. That change would have a significant
impact on its financial reporting requirements and potentially
negative tax consequences for its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to avoid that,'' Wetherell said. The company has
until October to tell the SEC how it plans to clear up the
ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's stock, which was trading around $8 a share in January
1998, has been on an Internet surge in the last 15 months. Last
Monday alone, it rose $47.50, to close at nearly $200 before giving
up most of those gains as the week's events unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell said he expected to invest in two new Internet
companies every month and bring perhaps two dozen or more of his
investments public within a couple of years. Among the attributes
he looks for when choosing among the thousands of Internet business
plans he reviews each year is whether a company would have
``synergy'' with the rest of the CMGI portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, this synergy is extremely hard to achieve.
Wetherell contends that he runs his portfolio of start-up firms
somewhat like a Japanese keiretsu, an amalgamation of firms with
interlocking investments and business relationships that help each
other in the marketplace. But there have been many instances of
friction and outright rebellion among CMGI's offspring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build companies this way, you have to hire
entrepreneurial people,'' Ms. Heffernan said. ``It's the nature of
the model that companies are going to want to break away.''
</P>
<P>
   This appears to be exactly what happened with Lycos. In an
attempt to control his own destiny, Davis of Lycos held
negotiations with many giant media companies in the months leading
up to the USA Networks deal. Davis was ``flying solo on this,''
Wetherell said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Lycos showdown may come down to the cards that
Wetherell is holding in his hand. Many Wall Street analysts predict
that if Diller responds by renegotiating the terms, then Wetherell
will turn back to supporting the merger. By that reckoning,
Wetherell's sharp criticism and his hiring of an investment banking
firm are part of a bluffing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Diller has said that he will not budge.
</P>
<P>
   But as any experienced poker player knows, the most difficult
bluff to call is one from a player with a winning streak and a
hoard of cash. And Wetherell has both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
