 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, March 15, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Josephine Schmidt; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-CHINA-MILITARY (Undated) _ The revelation that China
appears to have stolen the design of America's most advanced
miniaturized warhead has promted new debate in Washington over
whether China's small nuclear force could become a far more potent
arsenal that could rekindle the kind of fears that shaped the cold
war. By David E. Sanger and Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Washington) _ American officials expect little
from the latest round of talks over Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-UNCERTAINTY (Istanbul, Turkey) _ With a national election
approaching, Parliament in open rebellion against the political
establishment, murderous terror attacks being launched against
civilians and the trial of a hated Kurdish guerrilla leader
approaching, Turkey suddenly finds itself facing deep
uncertainties. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-OSHA-WHISTLEBLOWERS (Washington) _ After finding that
workers who complain of health and safety hazards are often
dismissed from their jobs, the Clinton administration will soon
propose sweeping new protections for such ``whistleblowers.''
Republicans are receptive to the idea. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN-FISH (Conneaut, Ohio) _ Jim Anthony himself is not
exactly sure why he kept a a blue pike in his freezer for 37 years,
but now, nearly four decades later, the fish has become the central
clue in a compelling scientific detective story, sleuthing that
some scientists are hoping will lead to an extraordinary result:
the return of an extinct species. By Pam Belluck. With art.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TWO-SLAYINGS (New York) _ They did not know each other, but
Amy Watkins and Marvin Watson were both young archetypes of the New
York newcomer. She was the Midwest idealist come to the big city,
he was the striver from Jamaica. Both were stabbed to death in
Brooklyn this year, and while Ms. Watkins's death has attracted
national attention, Watson died anonymously. Yet if both killings
were treated differently, they each touch on fears held deeply by
many New Yorkers, even as crime has fallen in the city. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-COMPUTER-INJURY (Undated) _ There is widespread concern
among physicians, physical therapists and ergonomists that a tide
of injury is inevitable as youngsters spend more time on computers,
both at school and at home. By Jane Gross. With art.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-FED-DEATH (New York) _ When Tabitha Walrond, a
19-year-old welfare recipient, gave birth to her first child, she
did what new mothers rich and poor are urged to do these days: She
breast-fed her baby. But her two-month-old son died in her arms of
malnutrition. And Ms. Walrond is now charged with recklessly
causing the death by failing to nourish her son adequately and by
failing to obtain prompt medical attention when his condition
became dire. The case is extremely unusual because while some
nursing mothers have problems producing enough breast-milk, it is
rare for a baby to die as a result, and rarer still for the mother
to then be prosecuted. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PARADE-GAYS (New York) _ The first St. Patrick's Day parade
in the Bronx in 70 years has, in the last few days, become
embroiled in the same political turmoil over gay marchers that has
troubled the St. Patrick's Day parade in Manhattan since 1991. By
Katherine E. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FLEET-BANKBOSTON (Undated) _ Fleet Financial Group plans to
acquire the BankBoston Corp. for $16 billion in a deal that will
create the eighth-largest bank in the country and the pre-eminent
bank in New England, executives involved in the talks said Sunday.
By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS-MEDIA (New York) _ Since 1995, the number of
mass-market paperbacks sold in the United States has declined by
almost 9 percent, falling to 484 million copies last year, about
three times the percentage loss in consumer books overall. And the
immediate future offers little comfort; the book industry's
research arm, the Book Industry Study Group, is projecting
continued slight annual declines for the paperback market over the
next several years. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
