</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOM-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A MOM'S LIFE': MOTHER'S WORK IS NEVER DONE, NEVER DONE ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She begins her day in a chenille bathrobe and envies
her husband the luxury of taking an uninterrupted shower. Her day
is an endless medley of dressing children, undressing them, taking
one to school, picking him up, mediating their arguments, sprinting
when they try to run into the street and generally responding to
the call ``Mommy!''
</P>
<P>
   Her sons, Isaac and Gideon, are 7 and 3, and Isaac already
enjoys telling her all the things she's doing wrong as a mother.
(``You are such a breaker of promises.'') Just when she thinks she
might escape for a grown-up lunch with a friend because her husband
has volunteered to take the boys to the park, Daddy has ``one of
those unexpected meeting days,'' as Mom explains, and all is lost.
</P>
<P>
   In Kathryn Grody's satisfying one-act, one-woman show, ``A Mom's
Life,'' it adds a little celebrity zip to know that the work is
autobiographical and Daddy is Mandy Patinkin. But having a famous
actor-singer husband apparently does not excuse her from the trials
of the average Upper West Side parent. Ms. Grody captures the
never-ending, energy-sapping, sleep-depriving, brain-snatching,
no-coffee-breaks-ever experience that modern motherhood seems to
be. She does great impersonations of her children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grody wrote and first performed ``A Mom's Life'' in 1990, so
her sons are now 16 and 12, but her memories of their early
childhoods are vivid. She is funniest and most endearing when she's
right on the edge, which is often.
</P>
<P>
   When she suggests that if a child says ``It was a accident'' one
more time, she may snap. When she asks her husband, on the phone,
between gritted teeth, ``Did you ever read that book `Wife Kills
Self and Kids'?'' When she reads the bedtime story in record time,
without taking a breath. There may not be any new insights into the
human condition here, but sympathetic audiences probably won't
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Mom's Life,'' expertly directed by Jack Hofsiss, is at the
Arclight Theater on Sundays and Mondays only. I wonder if Ms. Grody
thinks of those as her days off.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A MOM'S LIFE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and performed by Kathryn Grody; directed by Jack
Hofsiss; sets by David Jenkins; lighting by Eric Cornwell; sound by
Otts Munderloh; Julian Schlossberg, artistic director; William
Repicci, managing director. Presented by the Arclight Theater
Company, Schlossberg and Meyer Ackerman.
</P>
</TEXT>
