<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-REFORM-ART-925(2     03-14 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-REFORM-ART-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY STILL TRAINING IN A CONSERVATIVE WAY AS IT CONSIDERS CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(With ARMY-CASPIAN) 
(ms) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT IRWIN, Calif. _ Out in the rough ochre hills of
California's high desert, Staff Sgt. Joseph W. Burris of the 4th
Infantry Division clambered from his M1-A1 tank, dusty and tired,
and explained how the enemy had knocked him out of the day's
wargame.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of the enormous tank battle that helped rout the
Iraqis in 1991, Burris said the Army had nearly replicated the
experience of actual battle here at the National Training Center _
from the ``minefield'' he dodged earlier in the day to the two
``shells'' he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty close to the real thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But is it the right thing? Here at Fort Irwin, where the
nation's combat brigades prepare to fight the next war, the Army is
still, by and large, training them to fight the last one.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the end of the Cold War and eight years after the
heady triumph of Desert Storm, the units that come to this
sprawling desert base take on an opposing force designed to look
like some Warsaw Pact behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   It is an enemy no one expects them to face, in terrain no one
expects them to encounter, with tactics no one is certain will
prevail in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to fight us like that anymore,'' said Gen.
John N. Abrams, commander of the Army's Training and Doctrine
Command, referring to Iraq's attempt to confront the American-led
coalition with Soviet-era methods and weapons. ``They all watched
CNN. They know what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing that reality, the Army is now moving to change the way it
organizes its units and trains them to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Army announced plans to create a ``strike
force,'' able to move more quickly than the Army's heavy armored
divisions, but still carry significant punch. The Army is also
devising new technologies, relying on satellites and computers to
give soldiers an advantage in battle. That, the Army says, will
help it adapt to 21st-century warfare, which is far more likely to
involve missile threats and guerrilla tactics than set-piece tank
battles.
</P>
<P>
   But military experts and reform-minded critics, some within the
Army itself, say the service has moved far too slowly to transform
a force that, although smaller, looks much as it did when the
United States prepared to slug it out with the Soviet Union on the
plains of central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short answer is: No, the Army is not doing what it needs
to do,'' said Rep. William M. Thornberry, R-Texas, who sits on the
House Armed Services Committee. ``Nor are the other services.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he and others argue, is that bureaucracy, tradition
and history have bound the Army to the status quo. ``After all, we
won the Cold War,'' Thornberry said. ``There is not the incentive
to change as there would be if they had lost the last war.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seriously doubts the U.S. Army is still the
best-equipped, best-trained force in the world today. As it
approaches the turn of the century, however, it is seen as the
armed service having the most difficult time making the transition
from the Cold War to this new, ill-defined and unpredictable era.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the difficulties are inherent to the Army. It is the
largest of the four major services and, at a time when most
American military action occurs in faraway places, the least
mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s, the Army has shrunk by 40 percent _ from
780,000 soldiers to roughly 470,000 today. It once had 18
divisions; it now has 10, six ``heavy'' armored divisions and four
``light'' infantry or airborne divisions. At the same time, the
Army is as busy as it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States was able to pull back in Europe in the
1990s, the Army still needs 30,000 soldiers in South Korea to repel
any invasion from the north. The Army is also relied upon more and
more to carry out peacekeeping and other missions _ from Somalia to
Haiti, Bosnia to hurricane relief in Central America _ that the
other services are less equipped to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army is having a nervous breakdown,'' said Stephen Peter
Rosen, a professor of government at Harvard University and a former
official at the Pentagon's Office of Net Assessment. ``It's being
asked to fight a lot of little wars and to prepare itself to fight
the next big war.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of finding a balance falls to officers like
Abrams, whose headquarters at Fort Monroe, Va., oversees all of the
Army's training and warfighting experiments, including the effort
to create what the service calls the Army After Next.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, son of another four-star commander, Gen. Creighton W.
Abrams, the former Army Chief of Staff, said the Army recognized
the need to adapt. he said it had already begun to incorporate the
hard realities of the post-Cold War era, including lessons learned
in missions like the disastrous assault in Somalia in October 1993,
which left 18 Americans dead.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, more needed to be done in devising new tactics
and highly technical weapons, some of them still just figments in
industry's imagination, like a new generation of ``light tanks''
more powerful, but smaller than the current Abrams tanks (named, as
it happens, after his father).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just apply new world variables to a Warsaw-based
doctrine,'' Abrams said. ``In my mind, that is not enough for us to
keep our edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the heaviest brigades, he added, now had to prepare for
``asymmetric threats,'' like missile strikes, that are more likely
than ever before to succeed in combat. ``The Iranians, the Iraqis,
the North Koreans _ all of them are making adjustments,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Here at Fort Irwin's training grounds, spread over more than
600,000 acres not far from Barstow, the Army has begun to make its
own adjustments. Trainers devising war games now stage terrorist
bombings at base camps and place hostages in the middle of the
battlefield. Commanders encounter civilian protesters and even
hostile journalists in the heat of battle.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with senior officers during a visit here, Abrams said
the base needed to build an urban center to fight in _ not a
cut-out town in the open desert, but a ``city'' in one of the
craggy canyons that rend the terrain here. His idea of the most
likely enemy the Army will face is ``a hostile force using a human
shield in an urban area that is a sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you defeat our technologies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Col. John D. Rosenberger, commander of the 11th Armored Cavalry
Regiment, which serves as the opposing force at Fort Irwin, said
his ``op for'' was already shifting its tactics from the strict
``mass and momentum'' style of the Soviets. Now his forces wield an
array of ``capabilities'' soldiers can expect to encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more unpredictable than we've ever been,'' Rosenberger
said, standing atop a hill overlooking the day's battle, which his
side, with 11 tanks, easily won against a much larger force of 84
tanks from the 4th Infantry Division.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many analysts believe the Army is moving too slowly,
clinging to old ways. They point to last year's redesign of the
Army's heavy divisions, which trimmed the number of troops and
armored vehicles, but otherwise left the structure intact. To
critics, the new name said it all: the Conservative Heavy Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``For God's sake, Napoleon created divisions,'' said John
Hillen, a former Army captain and now a senior fellow at the Center
for Strategic and International Studies, who supports radically
restructuring divisions into smaller more mobile units.
</P>
<P>
   Like other critics, Hillen says the Army has also skewed its
budgetary priorities, planning billions for a new helicopter for
attacking tanks, the Comanche, and a mobile cannon, the Crusader,
rather than devoting more resources to lighter weapons better
suited for the new kind of warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality,'' he said, ``the Army is going to change very
little over the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams defended the Army's approach, saying there was ``a
reformation'' underway, but a deliberate one. ``The deliberate
approach is what keeps us on solid footing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are,'' he added, ``an institution that's conservative by
nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
