A9898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANITY-FAIR-MEDIA-ART     03-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANITY-FAIR-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANITY FAIR'S EDITOR CELEBRATES HOLLYWOOD, AND ADVERTISERS
APPLAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Vanity Fair's Oscar party in West Hollywood last
year, Morton's restaurant became so choked with people _ balding
billionaires, actresses with plunging necklines and
silicone-enhanced poitrines, studio heads and their entourages,
gawking advertisers trying to look nonchalant and the ephemeral
characters who circumnavigate Hollywood society _ that at midnight
the Los Angeles fire marshalls stormed in and took action.
</P>
<P>
   The marshalls commandeered the guest list and became the de
facto bouncers for the rest of the evening, pushing back the
hundreds of spectators packing the sidewalks of Melrose Boulevard,
moving the 200 members of the press clustered hungrily outside on
the driveway, and allowing guests like Matt Damon and Minnie Driver
into the party _ one by one, like regular folk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a crush at the door,'' Graydon Carter, the
magazine's editor, said a year later. ``It did get a bit `Day of
the Locusts' out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it simply a sweaty celebrity scrum, but Vanity Fair's Oscar
party _ held for the last six years on the night of the awards at
Morton's _ embodies the magazine's happy symbiosis with Hollywood.
It is a relationship so strong that not only does Carter celebrate
Hollywood, but the day before the Oscars, Barry Diller _ the
chairman of USA Networks and one of Hollywood's premier movers and
shakers _ celebrates Carter, by hosting a lunch for him on the
beach at his estate in Malibu. (If it rains, the invitation
specifies, the lunch will be held at Diller's Beverly Hills house.)
Regular guests include the billionaire media kingpins Ronald
Perelman and Edgar Bronfman Jr., chief executive of Seagram Co.,
which owns Universal Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The adoring back-scratching fest is a perfect metaphor for the
three-way love affair between Vanity Fair, the movie industry and
advertisers. Everyone benefits. Fledgling stars get free publicity
by appearing on the cover; readers, in turn, are drawn to the
magazine, thinking that they are witnessing the birth of the next
big Hollywood supernova. (And who could resist when the woman in
question is swathed in little more than gauze or a skimpy strip of
fur?) Advertisers share space with glossy movie stars; by
association, the stars receive the affirmation of some of the
country's wealthiest advertisers. To top it off, more than two
dozen Vanity Fair articles have been optioned by Hollywood in the
last few years, most of which have been or are being made into
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Carter took the reins at Vanity Fair from Tina Brown in 1992,
and the following year filled the social vacuum left on Oscar night
by the death of the legendary agent Irving ``Swifty'' Lazar in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had to take over, and I figured it might as well be
us,'' he said in an interview in his office, two weeks before
departing for Los Angeles with the 25 Vanity Fair factotums who put
the finishing details on the evening. (Lazar's decades-long
tradition of hosting Oscar-night parties at Spago died with him.
And Carter said that in at least one departure from Lazar's style,
he does not go around screaming at people to stay in their seats.)
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan International is taking advantage of Vanity Fair's
glamour-soaked image this month. The company has produced a
128-page stand-alone insert, shrink-wrapped with the magazine's
annual Hollywood issue. Originally timed to coincide with the
opening of the Donna Karan flagship store in Manhattan, the booklet
is one of the largest single advertisements ever to appear
associated with a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Fox, Vanity Fair's publisher, said that the profit
margin is slim on such a mammoth stand-alone insert but that the
magazine benefits ``when a prestigious company like Donna Karan
chooses us to convey its largest single communication ever,'' he
said. Donna Karan, chairman of Donna Karan International, said she
would not have produced the ad _ which cost her company more than
$1 million _ if Vanity Fair had not been interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there was no choice but Vanity Fair, which reaches a
huge audience of men and women,'' she said. ``And the Hollywood
issue is a particularly powerful issue. The magazine stands for
everything the clothes are about: personality, eclecticism,
glamour, timelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Timelessness? Glamour? Carter has come a long way since the
shirtsleeve days when the transplanted Canadian edited Spy
magazine, the satiric and sometimes cruel monthly he founded with
Kurt Andersen in 1986 and edited until 1991. When Spy was at its
peak in the late 1980s, it made fun of people who used words like
``glamour'' and ``timelessness'' with any gravity: Frequent targets
included Donald Trump, the gossip columnist Liz Smith, and S.I.
Newhouse Jr., the chairman of Advance Publications, which owns
Vanity Fair's publisher, Conde Nast Publications. Now Carter
lunches with Trump. He enjoys a close friendship with Ms. Smith.
And Newhouse _ who was once portrayed in a cartoon in Spy
blindfolded, holding a fistful of darts, standing before a
dartboard littered with the names of Conde Nast editors _ is now
Carter's boss.
</P>
<P>
   Carter thinks of Vanity Fair and Spy as kindred spirits, and now
says that ``Vanity Fair is Spy, with money.'' And the Spy days are
clearly water under the bridge for Newhouse, who is said to spare
no expense when it comes to the magazine, the success of which has
conferred a ducal status upon Carter in the ranks of Conde Nast
editors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Carter and the Vanity Fair staff photographer Annie
Leibovitz recently renegotiated her salary. When Carter reported to
Newhouse that he was hesitating over the small matter of an extra
$250,000 for a five-year contract, Newhouse reportedly told Carter
not to ``nickel and dime'' Ms. Leibovitz. Vanity Fair writers are
also well paid; Carter would not confirm the salaries of some of
his higher-paid writers, but he said they exceeded $400,000, and
wriggled his eyebrows dramatically to emphasize the fact that no
Vanity Fair writer was getting, well, nickel and dimed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's success is not based on its Hollywood coverage
alone; it does depart from the Hollywood air-kiss formula.
Sebastian Junger, author of ``The Perfect Storm,'' spent a month in
Kosovo and wrote an article about the conflict there in the July
1998 issue. A profile of Terry Lenzner, the Washington private
investigator who has worked for President Clinton, appeared in the
same issue as an essay on the origins of Billie Holiday's song
about lynching, ``Strange Fruit.'' James Wolcott delivers the kind
of soul-withering criticism that sends novelists screaming into
other careers.
</P>
<P>
   In a decade when hype and infamy seem to sell magazines better
than sweepstakes promotions or centerfold pinups, Vanity Fair has
managed to attract the kind of press attention that sells covers,
warms advertisers and cultivates what can best be described as a
kind of palatable notoriety. When the magazine showcased Monica
Lewinsky in a series of lush photographs by Herb Ritts in its July
1998 issue, for example, few people criticized Vanity Fair for its
lack of decorum.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the network news anchors who led their broadcasts with
the story, cable-television pundits and newspaper editorial
cartoonists blamed Ms. Lewinsky and her lawyer for their
questionable taste. (And Carter's discretion was praised for his
decision to put Ronald and Nancy Reagan on the cover instead of Ms.
Lewinsky.)
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers love that Teflon reputation, which adds sizzle
without harmful controversy. The magazine's relationship with
advertisers is close. Last year, Vanity Fair hosted promotional
parties for Nautica Enterprises and the Gap's Banana Republic
chain, then displayed pictures of grinning marketing executives at
the front of the magazine similar to the magazine's regular party
pages.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Vanity Fair ran an article by an anonymous author
praising the Gulfstream V jet; a few pages away, Gulfstream
Aerospace Corp. ran an ad showing Nathan Myhrvold, Microsoft
Corp.'s chief technology officer, posing with a Gulfstream. And
when it turned out, as reported in The Wall Street Journal, that
Myhrvold was the author of the article extolling the virtues of the
jet, a magazine spokeswoman defended what looked like shameless
back-scratching as coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream is a new advertiser with the magazine, as are
companies as varied as the crystal maker Baccarat and Kinko's, the
chain of copy shops. More than 100 new advertisers flocked to
Vanity Fair last year; the magazine packed in 1,882 ad pages in
1998. Ad pages and revenue have increased steadily since 1994 and
revenue topped $109 million in 1998, according to Publishers
Information Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Total paid circulation was down _ by less than 2 percent _ for
the second half of 1998, at 1.08 million. But the minor circulation
decline does not seem to have affected advertisers, who covet the
reader demographic: The median age of the Vanity Fair reader is 37,
the average household income is $58,000, and 70 percent are
college-educated, according to Mediamark Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the near-middle-age median, Carter is focusing more and
more on downy young movie stars. Vanity Fair's covers are now seen
as a first critical step toward stardom, rather than a juicy reward
at a career peak. Leslee Dart, a co-owner of PMK, a public
relations firm that represents dozens of movie stars, calls the
Vanity Fair cover ``the brass ring on the Hollywood
merry-go-round.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it can also backfire,'' she said. ``I think it is all
about timing. If you don't have the product that shows your
client's talent and prominence, then they shouldn't be on the
cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter is proud of the fact that few of the subjects on the
April Hollywood cover are recognizable to a non-Hollywood person.
</P>
<P>
   ``People start getting old when they stop going to movies,'' he
said. ``Movies synthesize the Zeitgeist in a way that newspapers
can't, and that magazines try to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at these young kids,'' he said, pointing to his April
cover. ``They change the culture. When you get over the age of 35,
you don't want the culture to change, you want it to stay exactly
the way it was when you were, say, 33. But if you do that, you get
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wiatt, the co-chairman of International Creative Management,
the talent agency in Los Angeles, said movie stars were pleased to
be blessed by the advertising community, which plays an
increasingly important role in the film industry. ``They are the
most sought-after covers for a young star,'' he said. ``And Vanity
Fair gives them validation from a couple of worlds. They have been
anointed by publishing, by the magazine and by definition by
advertisers, too. That can't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vanity Fair's lust for celebrity and scandal seems to have
exhausted another city where the magazine hosts an
attention-getting party: Washington. For the last five years, the
magazine has hosted a party after the White House Correspondent's
Dinner, a black-tie affair held in late spring by the White House
Correspondents Association, to which the president is invited.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Powell, the current president of the association, said
Vanity Fair was partly responsible for a ``celebrity-zation'' of
the dinner that he does not encourage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is concern in the ranks of the correspondents that the
Vanity Fair party gets a lot of coverage, and we don't know that
it's the kind of coverage that underscores the purpose of our
effort, or that Washington needs right now,'' he said. And what if
Ms. Lewinsky _ who has said she will attend this year's Vanity Fair
Oscar party _ is a dinner guest, courtesy of Vanity Fair, this
year?
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely on the good judgment of our colleagues to select
guests who would be comfortable at a dinner where the agenda is
really to honor the president,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hitchens, the magazine's flamboyant political
columnist, at whose apartment the party was held the first two
years, sniffed at the criticism: ``That dinner was in danger of
dying on its feet,'' he said. ``It was dismalness defined, mediocre
in every way possible. You'd find yourself at the end of the
evening standing in a light rain wondering why you had bothered to
rent a tuxedo. If anything, we saved it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
