<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, March 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Snow will fall across parts of New England and the northern
Middle Atlantic states Monday as vigorous low pressure moves toward
Cape Cod. Heavy accumulations, over ten inches, are likely in a
narrow swath from eastern Pennsylvania to interior Maine, including
the western side of New York City and Boston. Near the coastline,
brisk ocean winds will import slightly milder air, allowing a
mixture of rain, sleet and snow to fall. As a result, just a few
inches of accumulation are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, mixed precipitation will end as a period of snow
in interior Maryland and northern Virginia as chilly breezes
develop in the storm's wake. A few light showers will fall across
the Carolinas as the disturbance aloft supporting the ocean storm
moves by.
</P>
<P>
   Tranquil weather will occur from the Great Lakes states to the
lower Mississippi Valley due to high pressure crossing the region.
It will remain chilly in much of the South, however, where cool
breezes from the north will keep temperatures in the upper 40s and
50s despite the abundant sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, breezes from the southwest and sunny skies will
promote warm readings over the western Plains. High temperatures
will rise 15 to 20 degrees above average in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   Rain showers and very cool weather are expected in southern
California as a pocket of cold air aloft drifts over the region.
Snow levels will be quite low, with several inches expected in the
mountains above 3,500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Northwest will be generally dry before a weak storm
system arrives Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Perplexing Forecast
</P>
<P>
   From St. Louis to Columbus, Ohio, residents wondered why the
weekend snowstorm never materialized. However, just an hour drive
south of both cities, heavy snow fell. The computer simulations
predicted a 200-mile-wide swath from Missouri to Ohio, where the
equivalent of ten inches of snow would fall; instead, 15 inches
fell in a much narrower band, only 100 miles wide. On Monday, the
computer forecasts show a similar pattern for the Northeast coast,
leaving the densely populated region from New York to Boston with a
perplexing problem of exactly how wide an area will see a heavy
snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Thursday: The East will be noticeably warmer as high
pressure off the coast circulates mild, dry air into the region.
Clouds and scattered showers will accompany a cold front moving
from the Great Lakes into the northern Appalachians. A disturbance
developing in Texas will produce some snow in the southern Rockies
and an expansive area of clouds in the southern Plains. The
Northwest will become damp and rather cool.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Saturday: The Northeast will turn brisk and cooler as
high pressure builds into the region. Flurries will linger over
northern New England. A large but weak disturbance moving northeast
from Texas will cause plenty of clouds and patches of mainly light
rain. There could be a few thunderstorms in the Gulf states. Warmer
weather will return to the eastern Rockies, but a cold front will
bring rain and snow to the Far West.
</P>
</TEXT>
