<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-MERGER-525&AMP;ADD-N     03-14 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-MERGER-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET FINANCIAL SAID TO BE BUYING BANKBOSTON FOR $16 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., R.I.)   (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fleet Financial Group plans to acquire the BankBoston Corp. for
$16 billion in a deal that will create the eighth-largest bank in
the country and the pre-eminent bank in New England, executives
involved in the talks said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank, which is to be based in Boston and will be called
the FleetBoston Corp., will have such a stranglehold on consumer
accounts in states like Massachusetts, according to lawyers
specializing in banking law, that federal antitrust law will
require large sales of bank branches there and elsewhere in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction will most likely involve a significant number of
job cuts and layoffs throughout New England, anywhere from 2,500 to
5,000, according to people involved in the deal, though the exact
number of job cuts could not be determined. Fleet and BankBoston
employ about 50,000 people combined.
</P>
<P>
   If shareholders and regulators approve the deal, the merged bank
will still lack the heft necessary to join the ranks of the
nation's new banking titans that have been created by a wave of
mergers. With about $178 billion in assets, the new FleetBoston
will remain a quarter to half the size of Citigroup, BankAmerica
Corp., Chase Manhattan Corp. and Bank One Corp. That raises the
possibility that the new bank could be involved in another big
merger in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to be announced Monday. The boards
of both banks approved the deal after meeting Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The banks renewed discussions about a merger about six weeks
ago. Earlier talks fell apart last year.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet will exchange 1.1844 of its shares for each BankBoston
share, valuing BankBoston at about $53 a share, or about a 15
percent premium above BankBoston's closing price on Friday of
$46.9375 a share. Shares of Fleet rose 12.5 cents on Friday, to
$44.75.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston shares have been trading well below their 52-week
high of $59.0625 because of investor concern about the bank's heavy
exposure to volatile economies in Brazil and Argentina. BankBoston
executives have repeatedly noted that the bank turned in a record
performance in Latin America last year and that they expect to make
a substantial profit in the region this year, too.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a combination with Fleet will further insulate
BankBoston from financial problems related to any economic
downturns in Latin America. Last year, Fleet had operating earnings
of $1.6 billion on revenue of $7.14 billion. BankBoston posted
operating earnings of $792 million on revenue of $4.4 billion in
1998. The merged bank will have about 20 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Execution issues aside, this might be a terrific deal,'' said
Diane Glossman, an analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``They have
strengths in divergent areas, and if they combine correctly they
could have significant opportunities to boost revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Murray, the 59-year-old chairman and chief executive of
Fleet, is to be chief executive of the merged bank for the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Charles K. Gifford, the 56-year-old chairman and
chief executive of BankBoston, will succeed Murray as chairman of
the merged company.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fleet, which grew rapidly through a series of mergers from its
original base in Providence, R.I., has 1,200 consumer branches
reaching as far south as New York and is the country's
sixth-largest commercial lender. It is also one of the biggest
mortgage lenders in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet also owns Quick &AMP; Reilly, the nation's third-largest
discount brokerage firm, and provides investment management
services for both individuals and institutional clients, with more
than $74 billion in assets under management. It also own the AFSA
Data Corp., one of the largest processors of student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fleet bought a large credit card portfolio from the
Advanta Corp., but recently sued Advanta, contending that Advanta
overstated the value of that business. Fleet says that Advanta did
not disclose coding errors that resulted in excessive interest
charges of at least $3.9 million, which Fleet had to repay. Advanta
has said that the lawsuit has no merit.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's mix of businesses has been criticized by analysts and
advisers as something of a hodgepodge, but the bank has focused
more closely recently on performance and turned in strong results
last year, when many other banks had difficulty meeting earnings
goals. Its credit card and commercial lending businesses did
particularly well last year.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, which has a blue-chip, Brahmin lineage, has a
well-regarded management team and has been praised as a friendly,
supportive company for employees, with relatively little turnover
among its work force. It has also established a strong record on
community outreach programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, was a difficult one for BankBoston. It was
buffeted by trading losses, the untimely and expensive acquisition
of the Robertson Stephens investment banking firm and a financial
scandal involving millions of dollars stolen from its private
banking division. The downward pressure on its stock had made the
bank a more vulnerable takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston has a charter dating from 1784 and once numbered Paul
Revere among its clients. The bank is an unusual hybrid of
old-fashioned banking, corporate lending and stock underwriting,
married to extensive Latin American operations.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of BankBoston's profits come from its Latin
American operations; the bulk of the bank's profits, about 67
percent, come from its corporate banking and regional banking
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's consumer banking business has been hobbled by
problems related to the acquisition of Baybanks three years ago, a
situation that Fleet and BankBoston must avoid if they want to
integrate their operations successfully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
