<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETTY-THEATER-REVIEW-     03-14 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BETTY'S SUMMER VACATION': DURANG IN FIGHTING TRIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the name of sanity, can someone please stop that
noise? All those chuckles, titters, giggles, guffaws: They are so
much scarier than the usual shrieks, groans and clanking chains.
Such are the diabolical, synthetic sounds of amusement that plague
the sunny but definitely haunted beach house of ``Betty's Summer
Vacation,'' an angry new comedy by Christopher Durang that suggests
that Western civilization is ending not with a bang but with a
laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   Horrendous acts from rape to dismemberment occur in this
relentlessly fierce, relentlessly funny story of a summer rental
for which the word ``nightmare'' is gentle. But the truly
unpardonable crime in this world of the comedy, which opened Sunday
night at Playwrights Horizons in a heavenly hell of a production
directed by Nicholas Martin, is silence, which means boredom. The
unseen spirits of the laugh track, who can find plenty of amusement
in stories of incest and wife beating, don't like it when things
get quiet. Fortunately for them, that doesn't happen very often.
That's fortunate for us, too.
</P>
<P>
   Please welcome Durang back to the ranks of America's liveliest
living playwrights. This influential dramatist, who steered the
suburban domestic comedy into dark and uncharted waters in the
1970s and '80s, has himself been mostly silent in the past decade.
When last heard from several seasons ago, it was with the shrill
and petulant ``Sex and Longing,'' a screed of a play that died
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Vacation,'' however, Durang is in fighting trim, an
anarchic moralist with a mission to entertain us while pointing out
how pathetically addicted we are to being entertained. The way that
grating laugh track often blends with the laughter of audience
members can be a trifle disconcerting and even embarrassing as it
seems to include us in the play's general spirit of condemnation.
It should be noted that in previews some people were stalking out
at (and even before) intermission. Believe me, it was not because
they were bored.
</P>
<P>
   Stated baldly, the premise of ``Betty's Summer Vacation'' is
sitcom simple: Take a group of wildly incompatible people, mix them
together into one small house and watch the fur fly! For the first
minute or two, you may think you've wandered onto the set of a
pilot for the Fox network, although Thomas Lynch's inspired
shell-decorated interior is a bit too pastel for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The evening begins with the entrance of two housemates to be,
the ever-so-perky Trudy (Julie Lund) and the more sensible Betty
(Kellie Overbey), who just wants a little time to herself but seems
doomed not to find it. Trudy, you see, can't sit still (watch her
play with her legs as though they were newfound toys), can't keep
her mouth shut and can't begin to stay on one subject. She is a
classic television cutie pie cum kook who has been pushed just one
notch over the top into a vivacity that verges on the nuclear.
</P>
<P>
   That also describes the atmosphere in which the show takes
place: a heightened, jittery and all-embracing brightness through
which swim a quartet of obsessive-compulsive characters of
diversely caffeinated sensibilities. In addition to Trudy, there
are Trudy's mother, Mrs. Siezmagraff (Kristine Nielsen), whose
vitality makes her daughter seem zombielike, and Buck (Troy
Sostillio), a young macho strutter who requires sex at least 20
times a day. Keith (a delectably furtive Nat DeWolf), the quiet
one, arrives with a shovel and a hatbox and can occasionally be
spotted wearing bloodied rubber gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, there are also those darn displaced voices, which seem
to be coming from the house's ceiling and which can find something
to laugh about in practically everything. That's true even when the
talk slides, as it does quickly, into the kind of confessional
conversation found on ``Jerry Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, for example, is Mrs. Siezmagraff, still as chirpy as a
flight attendant, describing her relationship with Trudy: ``We
don't talk much because her father incested her when he was drunk,
and I never did anything about it because I was co-dependent.''
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing compared with what happens once Mrs. Siezmagraff
brings home an elderly drifter (Guy Boyd) whom she picks up on the
beach and who wears nothing but a raincoat. Things go from the
merely perverse to the apocalyptic in a route that (be warned)
includes scenes involving the whereabouts of a severed penis, a
homage to Durang's artistic ancestor Joe Orton.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the voices obligingly explain to anyone who
asks exactly what they find funny and why. When Trudy yells
bitterly, ``I'm glad you're dead, Daddy,'' the voices roar in
delight, offering the analytic footnote, ``It sounded corny.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly the idea that life imitates and blurs into television
in a country where attention deficit disorder is the No. 1 disease
is not exactly startling. It is the conceit behind movies like
``The Truman Show'' and the forthcoming ``EdTV,'' as well as more
earnest studies like Neal Gabler's recent book ``Life the Movie:
How Entertainment Conquered Reality.'' And perhaps in the reading,
Durang's text, whose topical references are well worn, would seem
like just one more preachy (although still funny) variation on a
very familiar theme.
</P>
<P>
   But theater, praise be, can still go where other forms of art
cannot. What Martin and his crack cast and production team provide
is a pure physical charge of pathological energy that comes from
highly animate human presences. Aside from something expressly
athletic like ``Stomp,'' it is hard to think of a theater piece in
which the performers sustain such a level of vigor and adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   The exhilarating abrasiveness of ``Vacation'' comes not so much
from its taboo-baiting sensationalism as from the hyped-up
intensity of the actors. All of them are terrific, but it is Ms.
Nielsen who provides the evening's touchstone performance. The body
of this Siezmagraff is in perpetual vibration, as though her
muscles were made of gelatin and infinitely sensitive to all
cultural tremors.
</P>
<P>
   Swigging vodka in her hideous hostess clothes (the dead-on work
of Michael Krass), propelling everyone else into the funniest game
of charades seen on a stage since ``Hay Fever,'' she is a one-woman
millennial New Year's Eve party. Even if you are among those who
take offense at Durang's portrait of societal offenses, you would
be a fool to leave before the second act because that is when Ms.
Nielsen enacts an entire ``Court TV'' trial by herself.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Overbey acquits herself appealingly as the sole straight
woman in a land of demonic cutups, while drolly humanizing a role
that is just a shade too righteous. (She is also a gifted
screamer.) It would be unfair not to mention the exquisitely
synchronized work of Jack Ferver, Geneva Carr and Godfrey L.
Simmons Jr., though it would also be unfair to explain what they
do.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that those involved in ``Vacation'' realize that
today's audiences need more than mere dialogue to remain engaged.
Accordingly, the production has come up with two genuinely
startling special-effects demonstrations, one of which gives new
piquancy to Neil Postman's notion of ``amusing ourselves to
death.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BETTY'S SUMMER VACATION'
</P>
<P>
   By Christopher Durang; directed by Nicholas Martin; sets by
Thomas Lynch; costumes by Michael Krass; lighting by Kevin Adams;
sound by Kurt B. Kellenberger; original music composed by Peter
Golub; production manager, Christopher Boll; production stage
manager, Kelley Kirkpatrick. Presented by Playwrights Horizons, Tim
Sanford, artistic director; Leslie Marcus, managing director; Lynn
Landis, general manager.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kellie Overbey (Betty), Julie Lund (Trudy), Nat DeWolf
(Keith), Kristine Nielsen (Mrs. Siezmagraff), Troy Sostillio
(Buck), Guy Boyd ( Vanislaw), Jack Ferver (Voice No. 1), Geneva
Carr (Voice No. 2) and Godfrey L. Simmons Jr. (Voice No. 3).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
