<HEADER>
A9918 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-OSHA-WHISTL     03-14 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-OSHA-WHISTLEBLOWERS-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PROTECTIONS PLANNED FOR WORKPLACE WHISTLE-BLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Minn., N.J., N.Y., Ohio)  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After finding that workers who complain of health
and safety hazards are often dismissed from their jobs, the Clinton
administration will soon propose sweeping new protections for such
whistle-blowers, federal officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The law that created the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration prohibits employers from retaliating against people
who report unsafe or unhealthy working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the inspector general of the Labor Department, Charles
Masten, said such reprisals often occur, and Charles Jeffress, the
assistant secretary of labor in charge of OSHA, said the Clinton
administration would soon recommend changes in the law to increase
the protection of workers who expose health and safety hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If employees hesitate to exercise their rights for fear of
losing their jobs, these rights are meaningless,'' Jeffress said.
``Too many employers feel they can retaliate against
whistle-blowers with impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers file more than 2,000 complaints a year contending that
they have been dismissed, demoted or penalized for reporting health
and safety violations to employers or to the government. But,
Jeffress said, the existing federal law is ``too weak and too
cumbersome to discourage employer retaliation or to provide an
effective remedy for the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans in Congress who have harshly criticized OSHA
say new protections are probably needed, because workers have been
punished for complaining about conditions that lead to illness and
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Such conditions include exposure to toxic chemicals; the use of
dangerous machines, which can crush fingers; the use of
contaminated needles, which expose workers to the AIDS virus, and
the strain of repetitive hand motion, whether at a computer
keyboard or in a meat-packing plant.
</P>
<P>
   Masten, the inspector general, scrutinized cases in which
employees said they had been punished for reporting health and
safety violations, and he concluded: ``Workers, particularly with
small companies, are vulnerable to reprisals by their employers for
complaining about unsafe, unhealthy work conditions. The severity
of the discrimination is highlighted by the fact that for 653 cases
included in our sample, nearly 67 percent of the workers who filed
complaints were terminated from their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, workers who believe they have been dismissed
or punished for reporting workplace hazards may file complaints
with the Labor Department within 30 days of the action taken
against them.
</P>
<P>
   The department will investigate, and it is supposed to file suit
against the employer in a U.S. District Court if it concludes that
the employer's action was illegal. Under the law, the court may
order ``all appropriate relief,'' including the rehiring or
reinstatement of an employee with back pay.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general said the Labor Department rarely filed
cases in court on behalf of whistle-blowers, even when OSHA found
strong evidence of retaliation. In 1998, the department says, it
received 2,474 complaints from workers who said they had suffered
discrimination for reporting health and safety violations, but it
filed only 14 cases in court. In 1997, it received 2,124 such
complaints and took 18 cases to court.
</P>
<P>
   A Labor Department task force that studied the issue said such
cases typically involved small amounts of money and were not a high
priority for government lawyers or for the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they would ask Congress to
give workers six months, rather than 30 days, to file complaints of
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   To provide more rapid assistance to workers, the White House
will propose that cases be tried before hearing officers known as
administrative-law judges. The administration will ask Congress to
authorize punitive damages in cases where an employer has falsified
records or disregarded the requirements of federal law in a
particularly brazen or egregious way.
</P>
<P>
   The White House will also propose legislation allowing workers
to take their claims to a federal appeals court if they are
dissatisfied with the decisions of an administrative-law judge.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current federal law, the secretary of labor decides
whether to seek help for an aggrieved employee, and workers have no
right to seek relief on their own if the secretary does not file
suit on their behalf. Federal courts have repeatedly held that
individual workers do not have a right to sue under the existing
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the administration wants Congress to require each
employer to post a notice in the workplace explaining any
settlement agreement or ruling in favor of a whistle-blower. In the
absence of such notices, other workers often conclude that they
will be punished for reporting health hazards, since the person who
filed the original complaint frequently goes to work for another
company.
</P>
<P>
   Bills to increase the protection of whistle-blowers are being
drafted by lawmakers as diverse as Rep. Cass Ballenger, R-N.C., and
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. Ballenger is chairman of a House
subcommittee responsible for occupational safety and health;
Wellstone is the ranking Democrat on a similar Senate subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions welcome the administration proposals. ``Many
employers feel free to fire or harass workers who report an injury,
especially if the workers are not in a union,'' said Eric Frumin,
the health and safety director at the Union of Needletrades,
Industrial and Textile Employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Eide, manager of labor law policy at the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce, said the proposals would ``open the floodgates to
meritless charges'' by workers and their lawyers. ``Plaintiffs'
lawyers are all too willing to sue an employer with no intention of
getting a verdict, simply to blackmail the employer, to force him
to pay off the plaintiff,'' Eide said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The regional office of the Labor Department covering New York
and New Jersey said it had secured a total of $211,000 in back pay
for 41 workers who were dismissed or otherwise penalized by
employers in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   One company, Dyno Nobel, which makes explosive devices, agreed
to pay $8,367 to a man dismissed as safety manager of its plant in
Port Ewen, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Gaffney, the supervisor of industrial relations at the
plant, denied that the company, a unit of Dyno Industrier, a
Norwegian corporation, had retaliated against the employee. But he
said, ``It was easier to settle the case than to get into a legal
battle with the government.'' Gaffney said the company had
increased safety precautions since two workers died in an explosion
at the plant in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, James E. Fisher, a 37-year-old mechanic, said he
was dismissed from his job in December after reporting safety
hazards at a factory that produces small motors for automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are laws to protect people like me who raise
safety issues,'' Fisher said in an interview. ``I'm supposed to be
protected under those laws, but it seems that I'm not being
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   OSHA found 24 violations, including exposure to excessive
amounts of copper dust at the plant, which is owned by DCM
Manufacturing, a unit of Dreison International. The company
negotiated a settlement calling for $15,210 in penalties, but did
not admit wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he was still out of work. Christopher Berger, a
senior executive of Dreison, denied that Fisher had been dismissed
for reporting health hazards. ``It would be absurd for any company
to retaliate against an employee for reporting OSHA violations,''
Berger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
