<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CONSERVATIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT MATTERS THE MOST TO WILLIAM HAGUE IS MATTERING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The big issue of the day was a Labor-Conservative
dispute over reform of the House of Lords, and Baroness Jay, leader
of the peers, was scheduled to appear on a Sunday morning talk
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that Hague was doing the David Frost show right before
me,'' she recounted that January night, ``so I rang No. 10 and said
they needed to watch it and let me know what he'd said so I'd be
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide from 10 Downing St. called her just before she entered
the television studio. ``You don't need to know,'' he told her.
``He said zero, nothing. He doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to matter is the principal challenge these days for
William Hague, 37, now nearly two years in the job of heading up
the depleted and dispirited Conservative party, once Europe's
mightiest election machine.
</P>
<P>
   He is less than consequential not just to people like Jay, a
member of the Labor government, but more crucially to his own
constituents, members of the party that has dominated British
politics for most of this century but now finds itself at a
continuing loss since suffering its worst defeat in 165 years in
May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated predictions of imminent stirrings of recovery,
poll numbers continue lower than the already dismal levels when,
with John Major leading the party, the Conservatives attracted only
31 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of Hague continually have counseled the growing number
of critics of his leadership to wait until the government
inevitably blunders. But Tony Blair has confounded those theorists
by standing tall in the public's estimation longer into his term of
office than any prime minister in British history.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Christmas, personal rivalries produced feuds in the
Cabinet, and four of Blair's principals, including Peter Mandelson,
his closest confidant, were forced to resign. It was the kind of
disarray that had brought the Major government into disrepute, and
it seemed that the much-awaited stumble had arrived on the
Conservative doorstep. But Hague didn't seize the moment, and Blair
emerged unbruised.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking on the imposing title of Leader of the Opposition
in June, 1997, Hague doggedly has tried to reshape his party's
fortunes and his image. He has put on jeans and a baseball cap and
gone to ethnic culture festivals, he has traveled the country on a
campaign he titled ``Listening to Britain,'' and he has countered
Blair's fashionable ``Third Way'' with his own upbeat ``British
Way.'' He has even freshened the wallpaper and removed the pictures
of Major and Margaret Thatcher from the entrance hall of party
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he ventured yet another approach, saying the party
should own up to past mistakes, acknowledge it was ``crushed'' in
the last election and get in touch with everyday people by
practicing something he called ``kitchen table Conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a party gathering, Hague pledged to do better by
teachers, doctors, nurses, public service workers, married couples
and others the party may have neglected in its pursuit of efficient
economic management. ``We must choose to be free,'' he told
delegates, ``we have to let go of arguments we have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   He faces a dilemma in attacking New Labor. Does he fault them
for being Old Labor in disguise or accuse them of being copy cat
Tories? There is little convincing evidence to support the former
and little gain for the Conservatives in arguing the latter.
</P>
<P>
   A canny debater since his days as president of the Oxford Union,
he has had noted success against Blair only in the weekly question
time encounters in the House of Commons. But even that has not
produced dividends for him or the party in a country where
presidential-style leadership is leaving Parliament itself less and
less relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, Labor presented the latest annual
budget. Although Hague was able to point up significant failings
and posturings in the government's presentation to Parliament,
complete with soundbite barbs about ``stealth taxes'' and
``pickpockets'' in the Treasury, headlines the next morning
celebrated the fact that for the first time in history a Labor
government had reduced the basic rate of income tax.
</P>
<P>
   There will be tests of Conservative voter appeal this May and
June with elections to local councils, the new Scottish and Welsh
legislatures and the European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is the one issue where Hague has succeeded in drawing a
line between his party and the government. He has insisted that
Britain will not adopt the euro for at least eight years. But this
position has disenchanted some key members of the party and served
to remind voters of the party's divisive past.
</P>
<P>
   Prematurely bald, crisp and concise in his comments and clearly
most comfortable in a business suit, Hague doesn't appear as
youthful as he is and settles easily into the rational and
considered modulations of the McKinsey &AMP; Co. management consultant
that he once was.
</P>
<P>
   He is the youngest party leader since 24-year-old William Pitt
led the Tories in 1783. But he is a more experienced observer of
British politics than his age and his stint of only three years in
Major's cabinet would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 15 in his South Yorkshire home he busied himself
reading parliamentary reports, learned speeches by Winston
Churchill by heart and memorized the names and districts of all
Tory members of Parliament. The pin-up on his wall was Mrs.
Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   He burst upon the scene a year later when, as a mop-haired
student, he took the podium at the annual Conservative party
conference and fired up the faithful with a call to arms in defense
of Tory principles.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, he became a member of Parliament from the toney South
London suburb of Richmond. He joined the cabinet as the secretary
for Wales, and last year he married Ffion Jenkins, who was his
Welsh language teacher.
</P>
<P>
   He won the leadership by appealing to the dominant Euroskeptic
wing of the Conservatives in Parliament who were determined to deny
the prize to the candidate who ran best among party members across
the country, former chancellor of the exchequer Kenneth Clarke.
Clarke remains the favorite of the rank and file, but his positive
view toward Britain eventually adopting the euro makes him
unacceptable to the Conservatives in Parliament, who control the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   The most formidable alternative in the party with the needed
antipathy towards the euro, former Defense Minister Michael
Portillo, cannot bid for the leadership because he lost his seat in
Parliament in the 1997 Labor rout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
