<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING-SIZED LEGEND CARRILL ENJOYS NBA LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The visitors' locker room looked like the wardrobe tent on the
set of ``Reefer Madness II.''
</P>
<P>
   To the left sat Chris ``Tangled'' Webber. Parked on the right
was ballyhooed rookie point guard Jason ``White Men Can Get On
SportsCenter'' Williams. The near corner had been annexed by Vernon
``Slap A Fan'' Maxwell. Barging into the far corner was Vlade ``The
Inhaler'' Divac, who - unlike the aforementioned trio - had built
his smoking reputation on nothing riskier than tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting among these reclamation Sacramento Kings was 68-year-old
Pete Carril, who seemed as incongruous to this scene as Gandhi at a
cockfight.
</P>
<P>
   But Carril appeared to be the most relaxed guy in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's off me,'' he said before Thursday's
Kings-Clippers game at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   When L.A. hoop fans last thought of him, Pete Carril had just
coached the Princeton Tigers to a stunning upset victory over
defending national champion UCLA in the first round of the 1996
NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   His Ivy League Tigers had no scholarships. No hamburger
All-Americans. To slip past the mighty Bruins, Carril had to lead
them through the back door.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, the ol' back door, just one option in Princeton's wicked,
man-to-man offensive scheme, made Carril something of a household
name for about two days.
</P>
<P>
   The win over UCLA was his last at Princeton. He retired from the
head-coaching grind to join former Princeton star Geoff Petrie in
Sacramento. Petrie, who is the Kings' vice president of basketball
operations, hired Carril to be an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the variables, this is not unlike hiring Martin
Scorsese as technical adviser on the next ``Rambo'' flick.
</P>
<P>
   Carril appears to be enjoying this role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice,'' he said of teaching young players without
obligations of a head coach. ``I don't have the headaches.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the game itself, Carril said recent grumbling about the
quality of NBA action is misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's missing is training camp,'' he said in
explaining why this season looks more like abstract art. ``But I
think the league and the sport is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't hurt the NBA to bring in more teachers such as
Carril, whose 525 college victories were rewarded two years ago
with a spot in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Carril, who still would appear to be more at home in a
collegiate atmosphere, hasn't lost his interest in March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think four Big Ten teams are gonna get beat in the first
round,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Big Ten-Plus One was 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   All this proves is that Pete Carril never coached at UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) Legends of the Falk
</P>
<P>
   Now that Stephon Marbury is the third client of superego agent
David Falk to join its starting lineup (Kerry Kittles and Keith Van
Horn are the others), the team just west of the Lincoln Tunnel
should be known as the New Jersey Gross.
</P>
<P>
   And the Meadowlands can be redefined as the Falklands.
</P>
<P>
   It should be interesting to see if Marbury - who forced
Minnesota to unload him because he was jealous of teammate Kevin
Garnett's lockout-inspiring contract - can help the Gross win
enough games to devalue that first-round draft pick New Jersey
surrendered in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's action, the Gross had the league's
second-worst record, a run of incompetence that's quickly gathering
lottery Ping-Pong momentum. The Timberwolves could chose to use
that pick in the 1999 draft, which may include intriguing prospects
such as point guards Baron Davis (UCLA) and Steve Francis
(Maryland), along with playmaking swingman Lamar Odom (Rhode
Island). However, the Timberwolves expect to sign point guard
Terrell Brandon, acquired in the three-team Marbury deal, to a
multi-year deal. In doing so, Brandon would be backpedaling from a
recent guarantee of testing the free-agent market this summer
before settling his future.
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) More bricks with Jay
</P>
<P>
   One day after claiming their first victory of the season, the
Clippers took on ``The Tonight Show'' and Jay Leno. A ticker-tape
parade led to seats in the studio audience, where three Clippers -
Lamond Murray, Darrick Martin and Lorenzen Wright were included in
the show's ``You Make The Call'' routine.
</P>
<P>
   All three lost.
</P>
<P>
   (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Laker Dennis Rodman
</P>
<P>
   can avoid further elbow discomfort by alternating hands when
gulping kamikaze shots. ... Three NBA scouts contacted this week
said Arizona's Jason Terry
</P>
<P>
   will be a better pro point guard than ex-teammate and current
Vancouver rookie Mike Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   Two different NBA scouts said the other three NBA scouts are
insane. ... With the NCAA Tournament in full swing Friday, six of
the nine scheduled NBA games were played to sellout crowds. ...
During a break in Tuesday's Lakers-Clippers' game at the Sports
Arena, the listed answer for a message-board trivia question was
``Elgin Taylor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
