A9924 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-NYTIME     03-14 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-NY </SLUG>
 TIMES  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PUTTING IT BEHIND US &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mother Love &LR;  is the host of ``Forgive and Forget,'' a daytime
talk show broadcast around the country that features guests
attempting to heal wounds, reunite with friends who had become
enemies and think good thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to teach people that if we love each other and
learn to forgive each other, we can make the world a better
place,'' Love told the Utne Reader. Sometimes it doesn't work. One
guest whose apology wasn't accepted ``collapsed and had to be held
off stage,'' says the Utne Reader.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Love's ideal guest would be  &UR; President Clinton &LR; . ``I even
sent a letter to the White House inviting him,'' she said, ``but
they wrote back saying he wouldn't be able to do it. ... Forgive
the man. Let's get on with it. ... Any man caught with his pants
down lies. It's human nature. He's gonna lie quicker than a cat
covering up crap.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE DIDN'T MEAN IT BUT WE'RE SORRY ANYWAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - raditional herbalists are worrying that commerce and profits
in trendy herb remedies are overshadowing their spiritual benefits.
``We need to respect (plants') needs, their space, their lives, so
they can in turn be that much more enthusiastic for us,'' says
herbalist  &UR; Rosita Arvigo &LR; , a Mayan healer speaking on behalf of one
of the old-fashioned companies, Rose Botanicals.``I actually feel
sorry for echinacea. It's like slavery. All people are seeing are
the dollar signs in their eyes. Echinacea ... should lead us to the
altar and not to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   _Crayola, which is holding a contest to find a new name for
Indian red, says the crayon was named for a paint pigment found
near India and has nothing to do with Native Americans. Still, the
crayon maker's announcement of the search for a new name quotes
 &UR; JoAnn Chase &LR;  of the National Congress of American Indians, as
saying the change ``underscores the American public's growing
sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Kathie Lee Gifford &LR;  told US magazine that her dentist, Dr.
 &UR; Larry Rosenthal &LR; , is ``brilliant. He's made all the difference in
my confidence. Now that I've reached the age where everything is
falling, fading or sagging, I know that my teeth are just
dazzling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Michelle Kwan &LR;  told TV Guide that she's applied to Stanford
and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   - The living person most admired by 85-year-old  &UR; Hedy Lamarr &LR; ,
she told Vanity Fair, is  &UR; Michael Tilson Thomas &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art's ``Mirror Images:
Women, Surrealism and Self-Representation'' got a boost from an
unlikely source last week: Two characters on TV show ``Party of
Five'' said they were planning to see the show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Al Guthertz &LR;  says he often saw  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR;  at the Hot
House near at  &LR; Ocean Beach, eating not spaghetti, not chow mein,
but tamales. And on KFOG the other morning,  &UR; Penny DeVries &LR;  heard
an announcer speculating on what a ``nosh'' is: ``I think it's some
kind of sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``How We Keep Passion Alive'' is the subject of an
investigative report in Redbook, which interviewed  &UR; Carmen &LR; 
 &UR; Electra &LR; , married to  &UR; Dennis Rodman &LR;  since November. ``Dennis is
very romantic and sweet,'' she says. ``He writes me letters all the
time. When my mother passed away, he filled my entire apartment
with flowers _ I could barely open my door to get in. It was
flowers everywhere. It was simple and real sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   - Maxim magazine asked  &UR; Lucy Lawless &LR; , who plays Xena, Warrior
Princess, whether Xena could kick Superman's butt. ``She'd distract
him with something like `Hey, look at that run in your tights,''
said Lawless, ``then stuff him back into his telephone booth.''
</P>
<P>
   - San Francisco consultant  &UR; Mark Borsuk &LR; , talking to the Wall
Street Journal about what to do with old malls _ their average life
span is 15 years _ suggests pet cemeteries and mausoleums.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have someone who's not going to threaten women who
when they wake up in the morning do not look their best. They
shouldn't be overly polished, threatening. When you had Joan as the
housewife in the early days, slightly overweight and having kids,
it sat well with American viewers. She wasn't the perfect specimen.
It was that change in her personal life _ her divorce and
re-emergence as a single woman _ that began to cause problems.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  - &LR;  Former ``Good Morning America'' producer  &UR; Jackie Leo &LR; 
putting the blame for the decline in show ratings _ eventually
 &UR; Diane Sawyer  &LR; was tapped for an emergency rescue _ on  &UR; Joan &LR; 
 &UR; Lunden &LR; , in Brill's Content.
</P>
