<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENUHIN-OBIT-MENUHIN-     03-14 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENUHIN-OBIT-MENUHIN-2NDTAKE </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: was deafness.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In later life, Menuhin used hearing aids on both ears but
continued to conduct. He had given up playing the violin in his 70s
when his technical ability no longer met his own high standards.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt no desire ``to spend hours working away again at
something which I myself in the past and other people can play far
better than I can now. I don't see the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Jewish, he followed no particular creed, calling himself
``an ardent neutral.'' He considered himself neither an optimist
nor a pessimist.
</P>
<P>
   He last visited San Francisco in May 1997, when he was awarded
an honorary degree by San Francisco State University. He used the
occasion to honor his parents. His mother, Marutha cq &LR;   &LR; Menuhin,
had died recently at her home in Los Gatos at the age of 101.
</P>
<P>
   There was some embarrassment in 1996 when no musical institution
in this city had done a single thing to honor Menuhin's 80th
birthday, and the San Francisco State event was seen as a way to
make up for it.
</P>
<P>
   His last performance in the Bay Area was in 1995, when he
conducted the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra at Davies Symphony Hall
during the commemoration of the United Nations' 50th anniversary.
He had played the Beethoven Violin Concerto here exactly half a
century earlier to celebrate the signing of the U.N. Charter in the
War Memorial Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is a wonderful city, and it's right that it
should have been the host to the first U.N. meeting,'' he said in
an interview with The Chronicle for the 50th anniversary. ``It's
still a city which is basically liberal, basically committed to so
much voluntary action that's good, the soup kitchens, music in the
schools ...'`
</P>
<P>
   The names he was closely associated with throughout his life
form a roster of legendary musicians.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, they included Louis Persinger and Alfred Hertz
of the San Francisco Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, they included Romanian violinist and composer
Georges Enescu and German conductor Fritz Busch and his brother,
violinist Adolf Busch, English composer Edward Elgar and Hungarian
composer Bela Bartok. Violinist Nigel Kennedy was one of his
pupils. He played with sitarist Ravi Shankar and with jazz
violinist Stephane Grappelli.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin left San Francisco at age 10 for Paris, hub of his
international career. He later made his permanent home in England,
where he became a British subject while retaining American
citizenship. He received an honorary knighthood in 1965 and became
a lord in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin married Nola Nicholas in 1938. They had a son, Krov, and
a daughter, Zamira. After a 1947 divorce, Menuhin married Diana
Gould, a British ballerina and actress with whom he had two sons,
Gerard and Jeremy.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin's pianist sisters, Hephzibah and Yaltah, were born in
San Francisco, as was son Jeremy, also a pianist, who played as
soloist under his father's baton. Hephzibah, his most frequent
recital partner, died in 1981. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
