<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-OBIT-MENUHIN-CAR     03-14 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-OBIT-MENUHIN-CAREER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEHUDI MENUHIN'S CAREER HIGHLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   March 12, 1924: The 7-year-old prodigy plays his first
professional performance, doing de Beriot's ``Scene de Ballet'' at
a San Francisco Symphony young people's concert.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; March, 12, 1926: Menuhin makes his official S.F. Symphony
debut, playing Lalo's ``Symphonie espagnole'' &LR; cq &LR;  under the baton
of his violin teacher, concertmaster Louis Persinger, at the Curran
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; November, 25, 1927: Menuhin makes his triumphant Carnegie
Hall debut, playing the Beethoven Violin Concerto with the New York
Symphony, led by maestro Fritz Busch.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; April 29, 1929: A few days before his 13th birthday, he plays
with the Berlin Philharmonic, under Bruno Walter's baton, as part
of an extensive European tour. Albert Enstein was so thrilled with
the performance he went backstage and told the young violinist,
``Now I know there is a God in heaven!''
</P>
<P>
   1932: Menuhin records his historic rendition of the Elgar Violin
Concerto, conducted by the 72-year-old composer. Elgar felt it was
the definitive version. It's still in the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; 1946: Records Bartok Violin Concerto No. 2, which remains a
classic.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; 1947: Menuhin stirred up controversy by performing with
Wilhelm Furtwangler and the Berlin Philharmonic, the first Jewish
musician to do so. He said he did it to further tolerance and ``the
brotherhood of man.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; 1963: Menuhin founded the Yehudi Menuhin School at Stoke
d'Abernon, in Surrey, England, combining musical and scholastic
training to gifted students.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  1965: Knighted by Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; 1970: Menuhin was awarded the Jawaharlal &LR; cq &LR;  Nehru Award for
International Understanding.
</P>
<P>
   1993: Was made a baron. His title: Lord Menuhin of Stoke
D'Abernon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
