<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-MASSACRES-ART-2     03-14 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-MASSACRES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWER CASTE VICTIMIZED BY MASSACRES IN INDIA'S BIHAR STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANKER BIGHA, India _ This hamlet on the edge of a lush,
palm-fringed field lay quiet on the moonlit night of Jan. 25. But
as the villagers slept, more than 50 upper-caste men, members of an
outlawed landowners' army, crept toward them through rustling
spears of wheat.
</P>
<P>
   The men fanned out in the dirt lanes, flinging open the doors of
mud huts and shouting: ``Kill them! kill them!'' Guns blazing, they
massacred 22 people in just a few minutes, among them a 3-year-old
boy and his baby sister who were crying as they huddled in their
grandmother's arms.
</P>
<P>
   This massacre of farm workers and their families _ untouchables
at the bottom of Hinduism's hierarchical social order _ was
numbingly similar to dozens of others committed over nearly three
decades in the eastern state of Bihar.
</P>
<P>
   The state is blessed by mineral wealth and fertile soil but
cursed by the nation's highest rates of illiteracy and poverty.
Almost nine out of 10 of the state's 100 million people live in the
countryside and more than half are very poor. The untouchables, who
make up 14 percent of the population, are the poorest of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Bihar is now in the midst of an upheaval that has seen the
middle castes depose the upper castes from the seats of political
power. The untouchables _ now called Dalits, which means ground
down in Hindi _ have not yet gained an independent political voice,
but they have begun grass-roots organizing.
</P>
<P>
   And as they have banded together under various leftist banners
to agitate, sometimes violently, for higher wages, a share of land
and an end to the sexual exploitation of Dalit women and other
humiliations, both middle- and upper-caste landowners have struck
back with terror tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the American South after the Civil War, the lynchings of
blacks were aimed at curbing their uppitiness,'' said Ashutosh
Varshney, a political scientist at Columbia University. ``India
never had slavery, but the Dalits are as close to slavery as you
can get. The massacres are aimed at checking their uppitiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Successive governments, dominated by the upper and middle
castes, have failed since the 1970s to stop the carnage or to
address the harsh social and economic inequalities between the
landed and the landless that persist in Bihar and in most of north
India. But this time, the massacres got caught up in a power
struggle between the upper and middle castes.
</P>
<P>
   The blood letting here in Shanker Bigha and another massacre of
12 untouchables on Feb. 11 in the village of Narayanpur set off a
crisis that rocked the state's political establishment, humbled the
national governing coalition and, for a time, riveted public
attention on the violence that has raged here like an intermittent
fever.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which draws most
of its support in Bihar from the upper castes and which leads the
national coalition government, maintained that the massacres
justified its dismissal of the middle-caste state government,
widely seen as corrupt and inefficient.
</P>
<P>
   But even after central rule was imposed last month, the violence
continued. Retaliating for the massacres of untouchables, a squad
of leftist militants gunned down seven people on Feb. 14,
apparently for no reason except their upper-caste status, human
rights workers said. Four more upper-caste men were slain on March
2.
</P>
<P>
   Police say they arrested 47 members of the landowners' militia,
the Ranvir Sena, for involvement in the two massacres, as well as
dozens of members of leftist groups. Human rights groups say the
police, dominated by upper castes, have in the past cracked down
much harder on the leftists than on the landowners' armies.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, the central government, unable to get its takeover
of Bihar ratified in Parliament, took the humiliating step of
reinstating the dismissed state officials.
</P>
<P>
   While political intrigues have swirled in New Delhi and the
state capital of Patna, the mourning has continued in Shanker
Bigha, an isolated hamlet of 300 to 400 Dalits.
</P>
<P>
   The village has no electricity, no phone, no school, no clock,
no car, no scooter and no health clinic. The villagers are
illiterate, and their children go to work in the fields at a young
age. When asked how old they are, the men and women, their faces
weathered and prematurely aged, look blank. They do not know.
</P>
<P>
   There is no road leading into Shanker Bigha, only a dirt pathway
through a glorious, rippling field of wheat, the same one used by
members of the Ranvir Sena. Itwaria Devi saw her son, who was about
20, gunned down as he reached the door of her hut to warn her of
the danger. The husband of Pyari Thakur was fatally shot in a lane
as he rushed to her from the men's sleeping quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Sona Dhari, a young mother whose eyes are pits of sorrow, had
left her mud hut to go to the bathroom just before the armed men
arrived. She told her husband, who was in the men's quarters, to
come keep an eye on their 3-year-old son and 9-month-old daughter.
By the time he got there, gunfire and screams echoed through the
lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children started weeping, so I gave them to my mother,''
said Raj Kumar Paswan, who hid himself while his mother and
children cowered on their straw pallet.
</P>
<P>
   When his wife made it back to the tiny, windowless hut, she
fainted at the sight that confronted her: the bodies of her
mother-in-law, toddler son and baby girl torn apart by bullets and
sprawled akimbo on the blood-soaked pallet.
</P>
<P>
   Once the killing was finished, the men shouted, ``Long live
Ranvir Sena!'' Then with three sharp whistles, they melted away
into the field.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no reason why Shanker Bigha was singled out
for attack, other than its identity as a Dalit settlement. Police
and the villagers say there was no dispute between the landowners
and the farm workers who labor in the fields for 50 cents a day,
less than the widely ignored state minimum wage of almost $1 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it difficult to fill our stomachs,'' said Paswan, a
slender young man in a loincloth and tank top. ``But we were always
afraid we'd lose our jobs, so we never raised our voices.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   None of the leftist groups organizing Dalit farm workers in
central Bihar had ever visited the hamlet before the massacre,
though they have come since. Most of the villagers said they have
never voted. The survivors of the massacre say they recognized some
of the killers as familiar residents of Dhobi Bigha, an upper-caste
village within plain sight of Shanker Bigha, just on the other side
of the wheat field.
</P>
<P>
   Dhobi Bigha is filled with sturdy brick houses inhabited by
landowners from the Bhumihar caste, which makes up 3 percent of the
state's population. Residents said the village solidly supports the
Bharatiya Janata Party.
</P>
<P>
   By Western standards, Dhobi Bigha's residents are far from
wealthy. Bhumihar landowners in central Bihar own from two to 50
acres of land. But by Bihar's standards, they are the rural elite.
</P>
<P>
   As dusk, Shrikant Singh and Kameshwar Singh, Bhumihar
landowners, stood talking next to a towering haystack. Both men
have sons charged with taking part in the massacre _ charges the
fathers deny.
</P>
<P>
   Dhobi Bigha itself was deserted. The men said the other
residents had fled, fearing more arrests.
</P>
<P>
   After India gained its independence from the British in 1947,
land reform was supposed to bring justice to farmers who had been
exploited for hundreds of years by the colonialists.
</P>
<P>
   Like states across India, Bihar in the 1950s abolished a system
that had operated through absentee landlords known as zamindars.
The British had given the zamindars land, and in return the
zamindars had leased the land to farmers and paid revenues to the
colonial power.
</P>
<P>
   After the reforms, land was distributed to people from upper and
middle castes who had been tenants of the zamindars. But the Dalits
got virtually nothing. They were pariahs so politically powerless
they were unable to assert their right to a share, said Anand
Chakravarti, a sociologist at Delhi University.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalits continued sowing and weeding and harvesting,
providing cheap, pliant labor for the landowning castes.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1970s, leftist radicals began organizing the Dalits
to strike against certain landowners and enforced blockades on
their land to prevent them from cultivating crops, often with
threats of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The landowners responded with violence. The massacres of Dalits
date back to 1971, researchers say. And by 1979, various landowning
castes were organizing private armies of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Ranvir Sena is only the most recent of the armies. It was
founded in 1994 in the Bhumihar village of Belaur in central Bihar
and has since committed numerous massacres. The worst was in
Laxmanpur-Bathe, where its members killed 61 Dalits on Dec. 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shivanand Tiwary, a maverick Brahmin in the state assembly who
represents a district that is a Ranvir Sena stronghold, said he
sympathizes with both the oppressed Dalits and the landowners. He
understands that the Dalits want to be treated like human beings,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't approve of the way the Ravir Sena takes revenge,''
he said. ``This is a sick mind approach. But what would anybody do?
Those with small holdings are forced to leave their fields without
crops for several years and that is their only source of income.
What will they do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
