<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE15-COX     03-14 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke by 41 _ again
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C._ After watching his team lose by 41 points and
being helpless to stop it, Tulsa coach Bill Self was asked if he
had seen anybody who could beat No. 1 Duke.
</P>
<P>
   He paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indiana Pacers,'' he said. Another pause. ``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke (34-1) used a 30-5 burst in the middle of the first half
and went on to thoroughly destroy the Golden Hurricane from the
Western Athletic Conference 97-56 in the second round of the NCAA
East Regional. But the Blue Devils' second consecutive 41-point
victory in the tournament still did not convey the degree of
dominance they displayed at the Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are better than advertised,'' Self said. ``And we thought
they were great coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke advances to the regional semifinals Friday in East
Rutherford, N.J., to play 12th seed Southwest Missouri State, which
beat Tennessee in Sunday's second game.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils, who beat Florida A&AMP;M 99-58 in Friday's first
round, became the first team in NCAA history to win consecutive
games in the tournament by 40 or more points. The victory continued
a string of dominating performances for Duke, which extended its
school-record winning streak to 29 games. Since an eight-point
triumph at Georgia Tech on Feb. 6, Duke has won its past 11 games
by an average of 31.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made up our minds that we were going to play every
possession today like it was 0-0,'' said Augusta's William Avery,
who scored a team-high 19 points for Duke. ``And that's exactly
what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke welcomed the return of guard Trajan Langdon, who had missed
the past three games with a foot injury. With Langdon back, coach
Mike Krzyzewski had enough players to really turn his defense
loose. As a result, the Blue Devils held Tulsa to 33.9 percent
shooting (20 of 59) and forced 20 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The hyped matchup between Duke center Elton Brand and Tulsa's
Michael Ruffin, the school's career leader in rebounding and
blocked shots, never materialized. Ruffin had eight rebounds but
was held scoreless. Brand had 17 points and six rebounds in only 23
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Elton's defense today was the best he's played all
year,'' said Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa (23-10), which ended a 25-game winning streak by the
College of Charleston in Friday's first round, trailed 9-8 at the
first TV timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a few well-chosen words by Krzyzewski, Duke kicked
its game into high gear. The Blue Devils blitzed the Golden
Hurricanes for 13 consecutive points and led by 30 at halftime. The
lead grew to as much as 42 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys were ready to play, and we were convinced we could
get to the second half and hang with them,'' Self said. ``But once
the dam burst, there was nothing we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
