<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS15     03-14 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield vows to return
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The face looked familiar. It was the look of a former
champion who had just had his face drilled repeatedly by the crisp
jab of a young contender named Riddick Bowe in 1992, a look that
told many this warring heavyweight had fought one too many wars and
should consider a new past-time _ like gardening.
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield knew the look. After taking one shot after
another to his face from Lennox Lewis, leaving massive welts on his
forehead and by his left eye, he knew he hadn't looked this bad
after a fight since losing the unified heavyweight championship to
Bowe. Only Saturday night against Lewis, he lost everywhere but on
the scorecards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I did after the Bowe fight _ I came back,''
Holyfield said after being the recipient of a fortunate draw with
Lewis before 21,000 booing fans at Madison Square Garden. ``I'm not
a quitter and I'm not ashamed of my face. I still believe I was
supposed to get him in three rounds. Unfortunately I didn't. But
that doesn't mean I don't get him in three next time.''
</P>
<P>
   So that should take care of the retirement question.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who looked every bit of 36, admitted going into the
fight that he ``had no Plan B,'' and it showed.
</P>
<P>
   He had vowed a third-round knockout over the larger, younger
Lewis, believinghe could get past the Brit's perceived mediocre
jab, then unleash an avalanche of body punches and uppercuts to
make it a short night and unify the three title belts.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis didn't cooperate. He had a career night as a boxer,
consistently punishing Holyfield with the jab. Holyfield said leg
cramps plagued him and prevented him from ducking inside the jab
quicker. When Holyfield leaned against the ropes and covered his
head, hoping to get Lewis to charge in so he could nail him with
counter shots, Lewis didn't bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to fall for any sucker,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer, said Lewis ``gave up his power
to use his savvy. He refused to gamble. He was always a step ahead
of Evander where he could move out of the way when Evander got
close to him. He fought a lot different than I thought he would.''
</P>
<P>
   After showing little respect for Lewis in the weeks leading up
to the fight, Holyfield said afterward, ``The man sure is smart. I
was thinking if I can't get him out of there, let him come in here
with those lumberjack uppercuts. But I didn't have no springs in my
legs. But I don't take nothing away from a man's victory.''
</P>
<P>
   That was as close as Holyfield came to conceding defeat. But he
somehow won on the card of one judge, 115-113, and was even on
another 115-115. Lewis won on the other 116-113. Lewis won the 12th
round on the cards of all three. If he hadn't, Holyfield would have
won an even more unpopular decision.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said, ``I was robbed.'' His trainer, Emanuel Steward,
said, ``This is what's killing boxing,'' and called Holyfield a $20
million ``sparring partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said only, ``I fight, I don't judge fights,'' adding,
``I don't feel beaten. I feel bruised up.'' Don Turner, his
trainer, knew Holyfield was in trouble late and told him before the
eighth round, ``You've got to win the rest of the rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The ego took the biggest shot, particularly with the ill-fated
third-round prediction. Holyfield would not second-guess himself on
that, except to say, ``I was wrong,'' in his forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Before the round, Holyfield told Turner, ``This is it. This is
the round I'm gonna get him.'' So did it deflate him when Lewis was
still standing three minutes later?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was spent a little bit,'' he said. ``But I've been wrong
about myself a lot of times. I just thought, `Maybe it ain't
coming. Maybe I'm supposed to get him on another day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis could not resist taking a shot in the post-fight news
conference, saying to Holyfield, ``Where was that third round?''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield responded, ``When we fight again, I've got another
chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With his face swollen and his stiff lower back being massaged by
a camp member, Holyfield already was looking ahead to the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great day. My day wasn't too great,'' he said. ``I'm
just waiting on my great day. It's coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
