<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HUMMER-COLUMN15-C     03-14 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HUMMER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hustled by unanimous decision
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What was advertised to be the ``undisputed,
unadulterated, unmitigated heavyweight championship of the world''
_ Don King's very own blather _ of course fell immediately into a
swamp of dispute, adulteration and mitigation. Just when it seemed
that boxing had run out of cons, it pulled one of its biggest
stings yet.
</P>
<P>
   You wanted a unified title. A little bait and switch and,
presto, you get the same old unfinished puzzle, with the piece that
always goes missing.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but wait until Holyfield-Lewis II. That will set everything
right. Start searching the couch cushions and cutting back on the
kids' lunch money now for that next $49.95 pay-per-view show.
Really. Honest. Trust them.
</P>
<P>
   I think King waited until after the three ringside judges handed
in their strange draw Saturday night to begin his braying for an
Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis rematch. Although I can't be sure of
the timing, one promotion running so directly into the next.
</P>
<P>
   Where there is the smell of something rotten, there is King. He
stood up straight and proud at the news conference following
Saturday night's charade, with a wide, satisfied smile.
Unapologetic. Unashamed. Here clearly was the man determined to
keep his grip on the heavyweight division and Holyfield a part of
it well past the point of a dignified retirement. ``No, we're not
going to let anybody get away with this. The question still hounds
us, who is the best? We've got to resolve this thing,'' King
spewed.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone did seem to know who was the best Saturday night,
except two of three judges. Lewis won the fight, completely keeping
Holyfield at jab's length. Punch stats are not always reliable, but
it must mean something when one man is purported to have landed 218
more punches than another. Only try to make sense of the judges'
cards if you are also capable of reading ``Alice in Wonderland''
backward.
</P>
<P>
   How bad was the decision? One member of O.J. Simpson's defense
team, Robert Shapiro, was overheard leaving Madison Square Garden
complaining about the verdict's blindness.
</P>
<P>
   It was up to Lewis's trainer, Emanuel Steward, to speak the
truest words of the night. ``I can't laugh about this,'' he said.
``People paid a lot of money for this fight. It was supposed to be
a heavyweight unification bout in Madison Square Garden. You can't
just say, `That's boxing.' That's disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   He also went on to call for federal regulation of the sport. But
this activity is beneath even government. As much as it pains me to
say, there is no cure for boxing short of ignoring it to death.
Sooner or later, won't it have to run out of sheep to shear?
</P>
<P>
   Lewis will be OK. He'll enjoy the role of wronged champion while
awaiting another big payday.
</P>
<P>
   As for Holyfield, his association with King has taken another
sorry turn. Wrongly, his boxing reputation will be smudged. He'll
be marked by the suspicious draw long after the swelling has
subsided. It is impossible to be near the electric-haired promoter
without getting some of him on you.
</P>
<P>
   And when you hear Holyfield answer a question about how many
fights he has left with a quick ``as many as it takes to unify the
title,'' you know King has set the hook.
</P>
<P>
   This fight wasn't even good enough to demand a rematch. What
really is called for after an event like Saturday's is a good, long
shower.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
