<HEADER>
A9947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OWNERS15-COX     03-14 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Owners leaning toward L.A. expansion
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Apparently more interested in the rash of upsets at
the NCAA Tournament than in league affairs, NFL owners spent more
time huddled in front of television sets here Sunday than in
committee sessions. The result, as the NFL commences its annual
meetings this morning, is an agenda that on some key issues is
mired by inertia.
</P>
<P>
   The Expansion Committee adjourned early Sunday without
recommending a site for the league's 32nd franchise, but the owners
are expected to announce before the end of the week they have
selected Los Angeles over Houston, to begin play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious we're leaning that way,'' Dallas owner Jerry
Jones said. Added New York Giants owner Wellington Mara: ``Nothing
against (Houston), but they have a lot more TVs in Los Angeles and
that's a big advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   But the return to a city abandoned by two NFL franchises this
decade, and where TV ratings have improved dramatically since the
Rams and Raiders exited the nation's second-largest market, will
come with stipulations. It is expected Los Angeles will face strict
deadlines on the sale of season tickets and luxury suites and must
come up with a viable plan to finance a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Those deadlines almost certainly will come before Jan. 31, 2000,
the date when the city of Houston likely will redirect public funds
set aside for a new stadium there. A few owners said Sunday they
remain skeptical Los Angeles will be able to meet the deadlines.
Jones agreed the optimum scenario would be for both cities to get
teams, but said that could be accomplished only be relocating an
existing team.
</P>
<P>
   League vice president Joe Browne acknowledged a city will be
selected but ``not necessarily a (stadium) site or owner'' by the
time the meetings adjourn Thursday. ``It's too big a battle right
now to get it all done. There are plenty of issues to address.''
</P>
<P>
   That probably means a bid process similar to one used with the
Cleveland Browns, who fetched a $530 million price tag. The size of
the Los Angeles market, several owners claim, could push the
franchise fee to $1 billion. Former Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz
and real estate mogul Ed Roski, the part owner of the NHL's Los
Angeles Kings, are bidding for the Los Angeles franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Bob McNair has guaranteed sellouts if the
league grants him the franchise and, along with public funding, has
some supporters among the owners. ``They are more ready right now
(in Houston),'' San Diego owner Alex Spanos said. ``Unlike the
people in Los Angeles, they didn't lose a team because of lack of
support. They had the team taken away from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Finance Committee met into the evening Sunday on the
status of potential Washington Redskins owner Howard Milstein.
While there were reports of progress, the sale remains in jeopardy
while Milstein continues to rework loans of $400 million. ... Kerry
CollinsFalcons general manager Harold Richardsonof unrestricted
free agent guard Greg Bishop
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-ADVANCE15-COX     03-14 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-ADVANCE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC meets this week with world watching
 &HT;    (Eds: Today means Monday.)
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The International Olympic Committee
begins meeting today to confront the Salt Lake City bid scandal,
what may be the most threatening crisis in the organization's
105-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's executive board today will set the stage for the
IOC's special emergency session called to address the Salt Lake
City bid crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The full session begins Wednesday with a scheduled vote of
confidence for IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch, who has become
a lightning rod for criticism directed at the committee over the
scandal. Members here are expressing little doubt that Samaranch
will have overwhelming support from the committee of about 100
members from around the world. Nevertheless, the fight over the
expulsions could get nasty with some IOC members expressing concern
that some high-profile members implicated in the scandal have been
issued only warnings by the special inquiry commission while other
members with lower profiles were recommended for expulsion. A
two-thirds vote is needed to expell the accused members.
</P>
<P>
   Six members face losing their positions, but two of the most
influential members _ Un-Yong Kim of South Korea and Phil Coles of
Australia _ were let off Friday with warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition to the list of IOC members recommended for
expulsion, Paul Wallwork of Samoa, told reporters in New Zealand on
Sunday that he questioned whether inquiry commission chaired by
Canadian IOC member Dick Pound had applied a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   Wallwork compared his situation to that of Coles, who has been
involved in Sydney's preparations for the 2000 Games. ``Of course,
he comes from a major country with a city organizing the Olympic
Games for next year,'' Wallwork said. ``How can you possibly remove
a person like that? To clear some people and penalise others, I
find that inexplicable in my view.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallwork was named in a Salt Lake City ethics report last month
that said his wife borrowed $30,000 from Salt Lake City bid chief
Tom Welch. The report said the money, withdrawn by Welch from his
children's trust fund, was repaid.
</P>
<P>
   Coles had been cited by Salt Lake City's independent ethics
panel for accepting about $60,000 in travel to the Super Bowl and
ski resorts. Coles denied he did anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Another IOC member facing expulsion, Jean-Claud Ganga of the
Congo, told a London newspaper that he will fight when the full
session votes. ``If I am punished then I am a scapegoat,'' Ganga
said. ``There's been such a hullabaloo that some heads have to
roll. The IOC members are saying to themselves: How are we going to
resolve this before the international press? It's a show trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim said Sunday that he had not yet had a chance to review the
commission's report so he declined to comment to it. ``I didn't
take money,'' Kim said. ``I didn't get any benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   He raised questions about the propriety of the IOC's
investigating the allegations itself rather than seeking an
indepedent investigation. Rather than receiving preferrential
treatment because of his position, Kim said he was scrutinized even
more closely. ``I believe that 120 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that the press and other IOC critics have
failed to adequately distinguish between innocent gift-giving in
friendship and more onerous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should separate outright corruption, bribes, cash payments
from human relations, humanitarian relations and business relations
or else we can't function,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim allegedly used his Olympic position to help land profitable
positions in telecommunications and music for his children,
according to the IOC's Jan. 24 report and findings released Feb. 9
by the Salt Lake panel.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the agenda this week at the unprecedented session will
be reforming the Olympic host selection procedure, establishing an
ethics commission comprising mainly IOC outsiders, and implementing
a mechanism for further sweeping IOC reforms. The IOC is expected
to call a special session in December to address the bidding
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes for the meeting are very high. In a letter to IOC
members sent last week, Samaranch described the session as pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must confess that I consider the coming extraordinary
session one of the most important in our history, and the most
important of my presidency,'' wrote Samaranch, who has been in
power since 1980. ''Our duty requires that we take concrete
decisions, in some cases painful ones, for the whole world will be
observing.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most interested observers of the events here will be
corporate sponsors, who spend tens of millions of dollars to
associate their products with the Olympic rings, which have been
tarnished by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Deutsch, spokesman for the Coca-Cola Co., the oldest and
most influential sponsor, said his company would be watching
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectation is that the IOC will recommend and vote
through significant reform regarding their membership and the host
city selection process,'' he said. ``If they do that, the IOC can
take a critical step toward correcting the past and protecting the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch called Coca-Cola Chairman Doug Ivester last week to
reassure him. ``They've committed to us they are going to take
significant action and we expect them to do that,'' Deutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-ADVANCE15-COX     03-14 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-ADVANCE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC meets this week with world watching
 &HT;    (Eds: Today means Monday.)
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
