Congo, told a London newspaper that he will fight when the full
session votes. ``If I am punished then I am a scapegoat,'' Ganga
said. ``There's been such a hullabaloo that some heads have to
roll. The IOC members are saying to themselves: How are we going to
resolve this before the international press? It's a show trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim said Sunday that he had not yet had a chance to review the
commission's report so he declined to comment to it. ``I didn't
take money,'' Kim said. ``I didn't get any benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   He raised questions about the propriety of the IOC's
investigating the allegations itself rather than seeking an
indepedent investigation. Rather than receiving preferrential
treatment because of his position, Kim said he was scrutinized even
more closely. ``I believe that 120 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that the press and other IOC critics have
failed to adequately distinguish between innocent gift-giving in
friendship and more onerous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should separate outright corruption, bribes, cash payments
from human relations, humanitarian relations and business relations
or else we can't function,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim allegedly used his Olympic position to help land profitable
positions in telecommunications and music for his children,
according to the IOC's Jan. 24 report and findings released Feb. 9
by the Salt Lake panel.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the agenda this week at the unprecedented session will
be reforming the Olympic host selection procedure, establishing an
ethics commission comprising mainly IOC outsiders, and implementing
a mechanism for further sweeping IOC reforms. The IOC is expected
to call a special session in December to address the bidding
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes for the meeting are very high. In a letter to IOC
members sent last week, Samaranch described the session as pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must confess that I consider the coming extraordinary
session one of the most important in our history, and the most
important of my presidency,'' wrote Samaranch, who has been in
power since 1980. ''Our duty requires that we take concrete
decisions, in some cases painful ones, for the whole world will be
observing.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most interested observers of the events here will be
corporate sponsors, who spend tens of millions of dollars to
associate their products with the Olympic rings, which have been
tarnished by the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Deutsch, spokesman for the Coca-Cola Co., the oldest and
most influential sponsor, said his company would be watching
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectation is that the IOC will recommend and vote
through significant reform regarding their membership and the host
city selection process,'' he said. ``If they do that, the IOC can
take a critical step toward correcting the past and protecting the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch called Coca-Cola Chairman Doug Ivester last week to
reassure him. ``They've committed to us they are going to take
significant action and we expect them to do that,'' Deutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
