<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-PAYNE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV REVIEW: Scheduling will hurt 'Payne,' remake of 'Fawlty
Towers'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Payne.'' 9:30 tonight (Monday) on CBS (94080).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   As part of the television industry's ongoing public service
campaign to make finding a show as difficult as possible, CBS wil
debut the new sitcom ``Payne'' at 9:30 tonight. On Wednesday it
moves to 8:30 p.m. for one airing. Then the following week it moves
back to 8 p.m. Wednesdays for the rest of its short run.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a royal pain.
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly who we're talking about _ Royal Payne, the
aptly, if obviously, named lead character played by John
Larroquette. Owner of a small inn, Payne is cheap, manipulative,
oily, greedy, bumbling and sarcastic. He is a lot like Basil
Fawlty, only not as funny.
</P>
<P>
   Fawlty, of course, was the John Cleese character in the '70s
British comedy ``Fawlty Towers,'' which will be re-run sporadically
but in perpetuity as long as there are public television stations
with time to fill. Larroquette and his co-producers know it takes
massive audacity to remake one of the funniest shows ever done, but
apparently they figure if they can even make it about 25 percent as
funny as ``Fawlty Towers,'' it will be better than most of the
sitcoms that make it to TV. And what do you know, they hit their
mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Americanized version feels both familiar to ``Fawlty'' fans,
and different. Payne has a bitter wife (JoBeth Williams, answering
``whatever happened to...'') to rail at; a dim bellboy of
indeterminate foreign origin to cuff around; and a pretty maid who
doesn't get much airtime.
</P>
<P>
   There's much here that's as well-worn as a doormat, but also
some very festive bits. In tonight's pilot, a premise that's older
than ``The Honeymooners'' (Payne forgets wedding anniversary,
scrambles and cuts corners with last-minute present, gets into even
deeper trouble) degenerates into a lively, frenetic farce. The next
couple of episodes never quite match that, but still have some good
lines, such as the elderly patient who doesn't have glaucoma yet,
but is taking medicial marijuana ``as a preventative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne'' is a legitimate remake of ``Fawlty:'' money changed
hands, Cleese was consulted, etc. But Larroquette, despite four
Emmys for his work on ``Night Court,'' is too bland. Cleese was so
awkward and oblivious to basic human decency that you didn't know
whether to hug him or wish him dead. Larroquette's Payne is just a
big ol' lug, a little nastier than most sitcom leads, but not
anyone to make you squirm. You just never really feel his Payne.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
