<SLUG> BC-FASHION15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leger, Valentino wrap up previews for fall/winter
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A month's worth of fall/winter fashion previews that
started in New York and moved to Europe came to a close over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Among the last designers showing their cold-weather collections
were two, Herve Leger and Valentino, who specialize in clothes for
the dressiest of occasions. Both made brief forays into the
sportswear and careerwear realms _ a lady needs something to wear
during the day, n'est ce pas? _ but the bulk of their collections
revolved around eveningwear themes.
</P>
<P>
   Leger's preview began with long black dresses with large,
chevron-shaped slashes that revealed cream, red or green
underskirts. From there, he moved to a revised take on
color-blocking: coats, dresses and suits in varying-sized panels of
red, black and white.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't long before Leger launched into his signature
look: form-fitting apparel made from strips of leather, wool crepe,
silk, jersey and organza. His most noteworthy pieces were short,
sleeveless gowns that looked as if they were made of spun sugar,
angel hair pasta, cotton candy and dental floss.
</P>
<P>
   In his preview, Valentino made bold statements in favor of
beading, embroidery, dainty lace and brocades. His designs drew
attention to the waistline, the back and the leg.
</P>
<P>
   The show began with clingy cashmere sweaters and snug, silk
``jeans'' with bold top-stitching. Valentino's satin jackets were
trim-fitting and cropped at the waist, and his cashmere overcoats
included beautiful brocade linings.
</P>
<P>
   The only segment of the show that seemed of improbable
marketability featured silky tap pants with lace edging worn over
leggings. Valentino made up for that by showing a range of silk,
satin and leather skirts that featured beaded or embroidered belts.
</P>
<P>
   Using shades of pale pink, gray, blue, tobacco brown and
``acid'' green, Valentino's eveningwear segment began with a
selection of long, loose pleated skirts paired with tight,
sleeveless tops and tunics.
</P>
<P>
   The Leger and Valentino shows made summary statements for the
monthlong series of fall/winter collections. For now, at least, the
age of minimalism is over. Decorative dressing represents fashion's
next wave.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
