<HEADER>
A9953 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAPERBACKS-MEDIA-2TAK     03-14 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPERBACKS-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHERS OF PAPERBACKS ARE FACING SLIDING SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when the lowly and cheap paperback tucked on a
drugstore rack was lavished with high praise, ranked in the
revolutionary stratosphere with the advent of the Pill, or at the
very least, air conditioning or color television.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers gleefully described the 1939 introduction of
paperbacks as a revolution. And students of the late 1950s and
early 1960s were labeled ``the paperback generation'' _ a baby boom
of masses raised on Dr. Spock's ``The Pocket Book of Baby and Child
Care'' and inspired by copies of ``Catcher in the Rye'' that seemed
engineered to fit in bluejeans pockets.
</P>
<P>
   But today there is less room in those pockets or, perhaps, some
top publishers speculate, the aging eyes of that generation are
growing a little dim for the printed type in the purse-sized,
mass-market paperbacks, which were once promoted as ``good reading
for the millions.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the number of mass-market paperbacks sold in the
United States has declined by almost 9 percent, falling to 484
million copies last year, about three times the percentage loss in
consumer books overall. And the immediate future offers little
comfort; the book industry's research arm, the Book Industry Study
Group, is projecting continued slight annual declines for the
paperback market over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   With the average price of a paperback climbing toward $7, the
$1.5 billion market for the portable books remains profitable, but
it has been losing an increasing share of the market to discounted
hardcovers, which chains and independent bookstores generally
prefer to stock along with quality trade paperbacks, which are
larger and more expensive than ordinary mass-market paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The paperback has also been buffeted by other forces _ the
consolidation of the wholesale jobbers who stocked mass-market
paperbacks in the United States' supermarkets and drugstores;
sagging public interest in such genres as westerns; the general
aging of the industry's biggest group of customers, and the
declining popularity of mall stores that attracted more impulse
buyers than superstores.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are enough speculative, unproved theories in the
publishing industry to pack a paperback chapter. Are people
devoting less time to casual recreational reading and more to books
offering professional enrichment? Are people simply reading less?
Or are they getting their reading fix from audio-book tapes or the
Internet?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a business that hit a wall; it's still a business,
but no one can figure out how to make it grow,'' said Jack Romanos,
the president of Simon &AMP; Schuster, which owns Pocket Books, the
paperback publishing house that started the business in 1939 with
the experimental publication of ``The Good Earth'' and ``Wuthering
Heights.'' ``Culturally, we should care, because I believe that the
paperback is the logical entry into the reading place.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the ubiquitous 4\-by-7-inch mass-market paperback
has slipped from 39 percent of book purchases in the United States
to 36 percent in 1997, according to the most recent report from the
Consumer Research Study on Book Purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hardcover sales, while generally sluggish, rose to 31
percent of the market from 28 percent. The same survey noted
declines in paperback sales in outlets ranging from supermarkets
and drugstores to warehouse clubs and discount stores.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with that climate, paperback publishers have taken a
variety of approaches, starting with the occupants of the top
executive suites.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last two months, Gina Centrello, the president of
Pocket Books, departed after 16 years with the company and
reappeared as the new head of a rival paperback publishing house,
Ballantine. Soon after, Pocket Books announced the hiring of its
new president and publisher, a top executive from Ballantine,
Judith Curr, who will be taking over a unit where mass-market
paperback revenues were down last year by more than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some paperback publishers have responded to reduced demand by
trimming the number of titles that they offer and shipping copies
more cautiously than in the halcyon days of paperback publishing,
when shipments of a book like Jacqueline Susann's ``Valley of the
Dolls'' could reach 15 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   With the lone exception of the best-selling author John Grisham,
marquee authors today are generally more likely to sell in the
range of 1 million to 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes some publishers wistful for the volume that was.
``I do think these changes have had an effect,'' said Esther
Margolis, the publisher of Newmarket Press and Ms. Susann's former
publicity representative, who believes that people were clearly
reading more then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paperbacks were available, instantly available. If the covers
were enticing, people who had never read books before read them.
They weren't intimidating. They were little books that had pretty
little covers and they were inexpensive and you could throw them
away. It demystified the book for a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Avon Books, a paperback publisher owned by Hearst Corp., is
shipping 25 percent fewer copies of paperbacks than it did five
years ago, while at the same time it has reduced the number of
titles it publishes by 10 percent to about 300 a year, Avon's
publisher, Lou Aronica, said.
</P>
<P>
   Other paperback publishers like Pocket Books and Warner Books
have also cut back on the paperback titles they offer. Some have
tinkered with price reductions without making much difference in
sales. And generally they can't reduce prices dramatically, because
of fixed costs for paper, shipping, author advances, and the
expense of unsold books returned by booksellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five years ago, we used to sell eight to 10 mass-market
paperbacks for every hardcover that we sold,'' said Laurence
Kirshbaum, the chairman of Time Warner Inc.'s trade publishing
group, which includes Warner Books. ``Now the ratio is a 2-to-1
relationship. So there's been a tremendous transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paperback market has settled in at a certain core, and it
doesn't seem to be growing,'' he continued. ``And what we've done
at Warner is refine our distribution and cut. Something has been
lost here in the sense that what used to be much more of a truly
mass-market phenomenon has become more specialized and to some
extent more elitist.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The contemporary history of the mass-market paperback in the
United States dates back to 1939, when Robert de Graff, an
ambitious publisher, introduced a line of plastic-laminated books
that sold for 25 cents each. Despite some debate over credit for
the idea, legend has it that de Graff settled on this price after
concluding as he tossed two bits into the toll booth at Jones Beach
State Park on Long Island, N.Y., that nobody ever misses a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, de Graff's company, Pocket Books, and its
kangaroo mascot, Gertrude, ushered in the paperback revolution,
creating an alternative mass distribution network.
</P>
<P>
   It moved beyond the elite carriage trade of existing bookstores,
turning to a sprawling network of magazine distributors who took
books to the world where Americans walked _ thousands of
newsstands, candy stores, cigar shops and food stores. But with
consolidation in the 1990s, these distributors have dwindled from a
high of about 700 companies to a handful, and the result is that
they are stocking fewer books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrific bargain that was available in 500,000
outlets instead of 5,000,'' said Thomas Bonn, the author of
``Undercover: An Illustrated History of American Mass Market.''
``You couple that with the return of World War II servicemen who
were reading armed-service paperback editions and the postwar
expansion of education, and you have the creation of a generation
of readers. The paperback successfully defended reading because it
was a format that could compete with television.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the top executives in major publishing companies count
themselves in the 1960s paperback generation that developed an
appetite for reading with paperback versions of ``Siddhartha,''
``To Kill a Mocking Bird'' or ``Slaughterhouse Five.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, they say, they speak with personal experience when they
wonder whether readers from the baby-boom generation are shifting
to more expensive hardcover formats simply because the larger type
is more comfortable for their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   So if readers are buying fewer paperbacks, where has their
attention been diverted? A prevalent theory is that they are
spending more time on competing diversions such as exploring the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Greco, an associate professor of business at Fordham
University who follows the publishing industry, said there were
indications that some readers might be finding more entertainment
on videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, in 1997, consumers spent more on home videos
than on books, a narrow gap projected to increase through 2001,
according to figures from the Statistical Abstract of the United
States. The same figures show that consumers have increased
spending for online access to the Internet, but those expenses are
still less than spending on home videos and books.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how people are voting with their dollars,'' Greco
said. ``In 1998, the average American spent $88.79 buying or
renting videos and spent $88.09 on books. That's less time and
fewer dollars being spent on reading. You can't rely on videos of
Air Force One to create an enlightened electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   But readers still spend enough on paperback books to convince
publishers that it remains a viable business. ``Like Broadway, it's
that fabulous invalid, and every day there are rumors of its
demise, but people keep showing up,'' said Irwyn Applebaum, the
publisher and president of Bantam Books, which has been publishing
paperbacks for more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the mass-market paperback business
has declined and will probably continue to decline, whether you
look at units or dollars or the number of titles that are produced.
But the mass market is still a thriving, multifaceted business. The
bright spot is that on any given day people are still buying
books.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one publisher has returned to the very roots of the
revolution to keep his sales growing. Walter Zacharius, the founder
and chairman of Kensington Books, the second-largest publisher of
romance novels, keeps searching for new sales outlets _ the
critical element that powered the growth of Pocket Books and the
paperback revolution.
</P>
<P>
   On Valentine's Day last year, his company tried pitching
romance-club memberships to a QVC cable television audience, an
effort that did not succeed despite the heart-tugging efforts of
one of his authors.
</P>
<P>
   At age 75, Zacharius has struck a deal to distribute a line of
black romance books through distributors of cosmetics aimed at
black women. He is also negotiating to stock his new line of Latino
romance novels in bodegas through Spanish-language newspaper
distributors in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read this all the time that it's tough to compete,''
Zacharius said. ``They're crazy! We're competing. We're growing.
We're more successful than last year. The truth is that this is
garbage. I really think that people in the mass-market field cannot
forget two words.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, savoring the words like a businessman's mantra in a
scene from ``The Graduate'': ``Mass market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
