A9963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAROLYNDAVIS-AD-COLUM     03-14 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAROLYNDAVIS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGINARY SPOKESWOMAN STEPS OUT FROM THE PAGES OF READER'S DIGEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As imaginary advertising characters go, Carolyn Davis
is no Betty Crocker. The prosaic Davis, who pitches products in the
pages of Reader's Digest magazine, is more akin to Carol Wright,
the fictitious queen of cents-off coupons, than to a widely
familiar, ever-popular creation like Crocker.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis is now starting to get around, too.
</P>
<P>
   Reader's Digest, which has long used the character in ads
carrying the typically cheery title ``Tips for Better Living,'' has
developed a program under which Davis is appearing for the first
time in ads in magazines from other publishers.
</P>
<P>
   The initial Davis foray outside Reader's Digest comes in ads
produced for laundry and cleaning products sold by the Clorox Co.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are running or will run in magazines like Bon Appetit,
owned by the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance Publications;
The Ladies' Home Journal, part of the Meredith Corp.; Metropolitan
Home, owned by the Hachette Filipacchi Magazines unit of Lagardere
Group; Parents, part of the Gruner &AMP; Jahr USA Publishing unit of
Bertelsmann AG, and Redbook, owned by the Hearst Magazines unit of
the Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The ads look almost exactly as they do in Reader's Digest. A
likeness of the make-believe Davis is posed next to short blocks of
ad text and photographs of the products being endorsed. There are
two differences: the ads are of course full-sized, not
digest-sized, and the Digest name and its Pegasus logo are added in
the top left corners.
</P>
<P>
   As with many journeys from home, the Davis trip has not been
entirely bump free. Another Hearst magazine, Good Housekeeping, is
bowing out of the program after running the ad once because,
executives there say, it violated that magazine's particularly
stringent advertising acceptability policies by not identifying
Davis as imaginary.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling Davis ad venture is emblematic of efforts by the
print media to exploit the positive perceptions of their core
brands among readers. Reader's Digest _ which began the Davis ads
about 25 years ago after using the character in subscriber mailings
since 1932 _ is hoping brand expansion will help revive its
flagging operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time thinking whether or not we wanted to do
this,'' said Gregory G. Coleman, president for U.S. magazine
publishing at the parent, the Reader's Digest Association.
</P>
<P>
   Research showed ``a tremendous amount of equity in Carolyn,''
said Coleman, who is based in New York, ``and there's a rub-off
effect to seeing that trusted friend in a different environment.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clorox suggested the idea, Reader's Digest worked out the
details. Clorox agreed to run the Davis ad, produced in-house, in
Reader's Digest as well as in the 12 other magazines and agreed to
pay a small, undisclosed fee for rights to use the Davis trademark.
</P>
<P>
   In the other magazines, the ad will appear inside four-page
inserts planned to run four times in 1999 at a total cost of about
$4 million; the first ad promotes Clorox 2 bleach, Tilex shower
cleaner, Soft Scrub cleanser and Pine-Sol spray cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ad format our brand people really liked that is
known and recognized,'' said Sandy Sullivan, a spokeswoman for
Clorox in Oakland, Calif. ``So they asked whether we could use it
in other publications. It was really pretty simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The other magazines did not balk at taking ads with another
publisher's trappings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clorox is a good customer of ours, and we thought it was
interesting to use the Reader's Digest brand equity,'' said Deborah
Barrow, publishing director for Meredith in New York, which will
run the Davis ads in Country Home, Midwest Living and Traditional
Home in addition to The Ladies' Home Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like this is completely unheard of,'' she added,
comparing it to carrying ``ads for Martha Stewart paint,'' which
could be construed as promoting Martha Stewart Living magazine. And
many ads that run outside Good Housekeeping serve as miniature
billboards for that magazine by including its seal of approval.
</P>
<P>
   But Good Housekeeping, which carried the Davis ad as part of a
Clorox insert in the February issue, will not run it again.
</P>
<P>
   That had ``nothing to do with the fact it's from Reader's
Digest,'' said Patricia Haegele, senior vice president and
publisher in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, she added, ``a fictitious person'' like Davis seemingly
endorsing products ``falls into the category of being confusing and
misleading to our reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Good Housekeeping would ``be happy to create something'' for
Clorox, Ms. Haegele said, ``with a real person from the Good
Housekeeping Institute'' offering ``handy, helpful hints.'' Her
reference was to the laboratory that bestows the seal, which tests
products advertised in her magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Reality in ads? What a concept.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
