<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-SCHIAVO-NYT &LR;      03-14 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SCHIAVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT OFFICIAL SAYS HER BAG CAUSED DELAYS AT
AIRPORT  
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ohio) (rk) 
 By   MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former Transportation Department official
acknowledged Sunday that she was the person who checked a suitcase
at the airport in Columbus, Ohio, on Friday that security officials
suspected contained a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Mary Schiavo, said that her aim was to help
a local television station prepare a story about security, not to
disrupt operations at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airport police evacuated the ``B'' concourse at Port
Columbus airport, ordering hundreds of travelers from the area, and
planes were pushed back from their gates. The bomb squad took the
bag to a pre-designated spot on the north runway and closed the
runway for five hours. The FBI and the Federal Aviation
Administration have joined the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schiavo is a former inspector general of the Transportation
Department, and before she left her job in 1996 she issued many
reports critical of the FAA, including several on security.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Sunday, Ms. Schiavo said that she had
been at the airport, which is near her home, with WCMH-TV, an NBC
affiliate in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me to go with them to tell them what I thought of
security,'' said Ms. Schiavo, who said she had done the same last
year with ``local print media.''
</P>
<P>
   Airport police and the FBI complained on Saturday that the
incident had disrupted the airport operations for hours, and said
they were investigating whether any laws were broken.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Sunday if airport officials were mad at her, Ms. Schiavo
said, ``they are, but they were mad at me before.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schiavo said she was trying to prove a point, that bags
checked by passengers are not routinely X-rayed before they are
loaded, and that they should be.
</P>
<P>
   She said airport officials had been tipped off by the television
crew that she was testing their safety arrangements, and had made
as big a fuss as possible over the checked bag.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Richard L. Morgan, the director of public safety at
the airport, said the bag had been pulled aside because airline
workers had become suspicious. ``I find it ironic that as the hours
go by, she comes up with more allegations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have probable cause that possible criminal
violations were involved here,'' he said, but added that the FBI
would decide whether to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Ms. Schiavo had some long-standing dispute with his
department, he said, ``My understanding is that she has a beef with
the FAA and airports in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington said the bag may have been pulled aside
because Ms. Schiavo did not board. She said Sunday she had a second
ticket to Washington on a different flight that day.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, America West workers carried the bag up to the
screening checkpoint usually used for carry-ons, and screeners
became alarmed about what they saw on X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schiavo stressed that it was not she who had taken the bag
into the concourse, and that ``it was certainly, certainly not my
intent'' to disrupt the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The bag had a running suit and shoes, a tape recorder, a can of
shaving cream, a can for racquetball balls, children's modeling
clay and wire for stereo speakers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The cans and the wire, she said, should have attracted the
attention of a security screener if the bag had been X-rayed; the
clay, she said, would not appear suspicious on X-ray but would show
that the bag could just as easily held explosives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
