<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERM-LIMIT-ENFORCER-A     03-14 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERM-LIMIT-ENFORCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING POLITICIANS TRUE TO THEIR INNER SELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ark., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a Libertarian with attitude, Paul Jacob is
simply not going to let House members forget their ballyhooed
term-limit promises of the Contract With America class of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your word, George,'' declares one of the needling ads
with which Jacob, national director of the U.S. Term Limits
Foundation, has flooded the district of Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., who is reconsidering his 1994 pledge to stay here no more
than three terms.
</P>
<P>
   He is thereby drawing furious flak from Jacob and the movement
that made Nethercutt its poster boy in the Republicans' victory
year when he defeated Speaker Tom Foley, attacking him as
incumbency personified. Nethercutt, under pressure from Republican
leaders concerned about their shrinking margin of majority power,
now is saying that six years is ``probably not enough'' to serve
his constituents well, and that he will be consulting them about
his original pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to be playing dodge-ball with his integrity is very
troubling,'' said Jacob, who in laboring among the legions of
special-interest movements here has a personal history of not
merely talking the talk of government reform. He is a Libertarian,
not a conservative Republican as many assume, and his fervor was
forged in what he terms ``re-education camp'' 20 years ago, when he
served five months in a federal prison for resisting, in the name
of principle, the government's attempt to create a roster of men
theoretically eligible for future military draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that at a very young age I had done something that
justified my existence,'' said Jacob, who grew up in a family of
eight in Little Rock, Ark., where ``only politics and religion were
discussed at the dinner table.'' His mother was a nurse, his father
a small-businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first political memory was when I was three, and my mom was
crying after dad lost a race for city council in 1964,'' Jacob
recalled. ``I remember someone telling her not to cry, he would
have another chance. And she replied, `I'm not crying about Jack' _
my father _ `I'm crying about Barry Goldwater.'''
</P>
<P>
   The father of two and a weekend basketball player, Jacob at
first seems an entirely gentle special pleader, well cut from the
institutional cloth of this vast government milltown. But he
flashes steely dedication in targeting Nethercutt. Jacob's cheeky
television ads lump the congressman with Presidents Nixon and
Clinton as perfidious incumbents. His billboard message to the
congressman in Seattle sarcastically blares ``Thanks for keeping
your word!''
</P>
<P>
   ``George Nethercutt will go down in history as the hero of the
movement if he keeps his word,'' Jacob said. ``If he doesn't keep
his word, then he goes down as the Benedict Arnold.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Jacob figures his movement keeps going, with
Nethercutt a handy attraction and a $20 million campaign planned
for next year. Most of it, he says, will be spent in enlisting and
praising new pledge-taking candidates, but enough of it, too, in
excoriating any balking incumbent. The campaign suffered a blow in
1995 when the Supreme Court struck down its busy round of citizen-
initiative drives designed to limit federal terms by way of
statehouses.
</P>
<P>
   This made the tactic of gathering _ and morally enforcing _
pledges from candidates the critical device, Jacob said. He insists
the movement is far from fading in tandem with the Contract With
America. He currently counts three-term pledges in hand from 45
House incumbents, including nine Democrats, and two-term pledges
from 14 senators, including one Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob is a 39-year-old dropout from Westminster College in
Fulton, Mo., who followed his parents' political passion beyond
Nixon-era Republicanism and volunteered to work for Libertarian
presidential candidacies. He loves issue-oriented politics, jotting
off a note to a newspaper the other day as a private citizen
devoutly opposed to the death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He became an initiative organizer on the issue of term limits,
targeting ``the incumbent party'' as the underlying problem of
politics. He finds most officeholders more devoted to extending
their careers than to pursuing controversial changes that put them
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the country is yearning for are people who will stand up
and say what they believe,'' Jacob declared. ``And, where they
think the majority of people aren't with them, will at least have
the guts and the integrity to come out and try and convince the
people otherwise.'' He himself shrugs at such a notion in an era
when politicians vett and tailor issues in focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   For all the attention Nethercutt is attracting, six of the other
nine incumbents whose pledges are falling due have clearly said
they will honor them, Jacob noted. ``It's about how you become
happy _ being true to yourself,'' declared the proud jailhouse
dissenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why when I hear someone who understands how powerful
incumbency is, like a George Nethercutt, say he's going to let
voters decide, I say no, he gave his word,'' Jacob continued,
firmly maintaining the term-limits needle. ``This isn't about the
voters; it's about him and his own inner self.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
