<SLUG> BC-AIR-FARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 AIRLINES RAISE TICKET PRICES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines, US Airways and Trans World Airlines raised
their ticket prices over the weekend, matching fare increases made
late last week by the nation's other major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the industry's second price increase this year and comes
as airlines try to raise revenue to meet Wall Street expectations
but also face a strong backlash from consumers and some
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines raised the fares for last-minute unrestricted
tickets favored by business travelers by 1 percent and for less
expensive advance-purchase tickets that are intended for
vacationers by 3 percent. The previous wave of increases, which
began in late January, raised business fares by 2 percent and
leisure fares by 4 percent. Before that, the industry had not
raised prices systemwide in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines file their prices several times a day to a
centralized computer system and are barred by law from alerting one
another to any changes beforehand. The industry is so
price-sensitive that an across-the-board fare increase will not
stick unless all the major carriers go along. Thus the latest
increase, which was initiated by United Airlines, a unit of the UAL
Corp., on Thursday, was not assured until the last three holdouts _
Northwest, US Airways and TWA _ also raised their prices.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said it matched the rise on Saturday, while a
spokeswoman for TWA said the airline raised its prices Sunday. US
Airways declined to comment but the other carriers said it, too,
matched the fare increase.
</P>
<P>
   Though systemwide fare increases have been scarce until
recently, the prices for unrestricted walk-up fares between major
cities have risen steadily during the last three years, while many
leisure fares have fallen. The high fares paid by business
travelers _ which rose as high as $2,000 for a round-trip coach
ticket coast to coast in 1998 _ have outraged many corporations.
Politicians have complained that the high cost of travel limits
economic growth in their regions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, overcrowded planes, cutbacks in amenities like
in-flight meals and a rising number of delays have increased
consumer frustration. Several lawmakers in Congress have proposed
legislation to promote more competition in the industry and to
improve airline accountability.
</P>
<P>
   After four consecutive years of record profits, the industry is
now facing pressure from Wall Street. Airline sales began declining
late last year and do not appear to be recovering despite the
country's continuing strong economic growth. In addition, many
carriers are expanding their fleets this year, leading some
analysts to think that fares will have to be cut to assure that the
added seats are filled.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Buttrick, an analyst at Paine Webber, said that each
successive increase helped the airlines less than the previous one
because they still must offer corporate discounts and other
incentives. ``It just means that the sales will be deeper,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
