LEGOLAND (Carlsbad, CA) Built of 20 million bricks in primary
colors, Legoland California is opening March 20 in Carlsbad, 30
miles north of San Diego. The theme park is only the third Legoland
in the world, and the first one in the United States. This will be
a look at what to expect, including the six themed areas, the
rides, whether you can see the creases where the Legos are joined,
as well as facts and figures, history and fun stuff. With info boxs
and Legoside. By SUE DOERFLER. Story will move in the `A' and L
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AIRPORTS (PHOENIX) As the Valley continues to grow, small airports
that were once in the middle of the desert are being surrounded by
housing. The crash of two small planes over Scottsdale raises new
questions about the safety of these airports, and the possible
dangers they pose to people on the ground. We evaluate the Valley's
small airports, getting historical data on the number of takeoffs
and landings at each field, as well as the number of registered
aircraft. To determine if these airports are safe, we look at NTSB
accident data and the FAA's Near Midair Collision database, as well
as talking to private pilots and city officials. To peg the effect
of sprawl, we look at population growth in Census tracts around the
airports. We also examine the state of general aviation in Arizona.
According to NTSB records, there have been 338 small plane
accidents statewide since 1994, including 59 fatals. By BILL
MULLER. Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEGOTIATE (Phoenix) When flight attendants union President Bill
McGlashen squares off in negotiations Wednesday against America
West Airlines management, he'll be fighting for more than a
suitable contract. His job is on the line. At the end of March,
members of the Association of Flight Attendants Council 66 will
choose between McGlashen and two challengers, Lisa Bunch and Tim
Brennan. With the strike deadline looming at the end of the day
Friday, McGlashen's ability to deliver a good contract or an
effective strike that wins concessions for the flight attendants
may be a key factor in whether he's re-elected.McGlashen's
counterpart during three days of ``supermediation'' will be Greg
Garger, America West's vice president of labor. Garger, who joined
America West two years ago, helped negotiate a contract with the
mechanics union that was ratified in October. He was joined by
management labor consultant Jerry Glass during those discussions,
and Glass will be at Garger's side later this week. By PETER
CORBETT. Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
