<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-MEETINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL OLYMPIC COMMITTEE IS RESOLVED TO REPAIR REPUTATION
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ In a palatial hotel lobby with crystal
chandeliers, members of the International Olympic Committee began
gathering Sunday with a sense of both resignation and defiance
about the future of the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be a stain,'' said one member who spoke on
the condition of anonymity. ``Twenty or 30 years from now, people
will say: `Remember the corruption? Remember the bribes? How do we
know you are not taking bribes now?'''
</P>
<P>
   As they acknowledge the need for inevitable reform, however, the
delegates also say that they will move at their own pace. A sort of
back-to-the-wall aggressiveness has emerged in recent days, as
evidenced by a backlash against American and Salt Lake City Olympic
officials. The delegates appear sensitive, perhaps even resentful,
of being sternly told to clean up their act by American sponsors,
Olympic officials, investigators and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to compete with the media's expectations or the
public's expectations,'' said Kevan Gosper, a member of the IOC's
executive board from Australia. ``We're out to recover our
reputation. We have not gone belly up.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the sponsors' wishes into account, he said, ``is a
different thing from being driven by the sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the week when the IOC will show how serious it is about
reform in the wake of the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. A mood of
lowered expectations already seems to have taken hold. While there
appears to be no chance of immediate sweeping reform, there exists
the possibility that things could devolve into chaos, as did a
doping summit last month.
</P>
<P>
   The key moment of this week's extraordinary session will come
Wednesday, when the delegates, more than 100 of them, will be asked
to ratify the expulsion of six fellow members. Such a vote has
never happened in a century of the modern Olympics. A two-thirds
majority of the assembly is necessary to oust a delegate. If any of
the six are not expelled, it would be viewed as a vote of
no-confidence for Juan Antonio Samaranch, the beleaguered IOC
president, and would undoubtedly further compromise the rattled
confidence of corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   A failure to ratify the expulsions could be ``seriously
damaging,'' said Richard W. Pound, the IOC member who headed the
investigation of Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members say they are concerned about a scorched-earth
attempt by accused members to save their jobs or take others down
with them. Jean-Claude Ganga, an influential member from Congo
Republic, has vowed to vigorously contest the attempt to oust him
for receiving more than $250,000 in cash payments, medical
treatment, travel expenses and other favors from Salt Lake's
excessive bid to win the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear we could be destroyed from the inside,'' one delegate
said.
</P>
<P>
   One executive of a corporate sponsor, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity, said: ``I see this as a real wild card. If this
implodes, we might be forced to do some things we don't want to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the agenda this week are changing the process of bidding
on the Olympics, creating an ethics committee, implementing a code
of conduct and forming a committee to study reforms such as
democratic elections and term limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unrealistic to think the IOC can make the problem
disappear in a week,'' said Ben Deutsch, a spokesman for Coca-Cola,
an Olympic sponsor for 71 years. ``This is an issue where we are
not going to be fully satisfied until it has been completely put to
rest, and that is going to take some time. What will be important
is their ability to embrace and enforce the reforms that come out
of the meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a halt in allowing delegates to visit bidding cities,
it remains unclear what reforms will be accomplished. It has not
been decided, Gosper said, whether the yet-unnamed reform committee
will be asked to consider specific proposals or to develop its own
ideas in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the IOC was roundly criticized in the United
States, and its appetite for reform was questioned, after it sought
to shift blame for the corrupted bidding environment of extravagant
gifts and lavish favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reject out of hand that we've encouraged the gift-giving
mentality,'' Gosper said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Some American officials have found such remarks disingenuous,
considering that a quarter of the IOC assembly has been implicated
in the Salt Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that the gifts weren't turned down,'' said Jeff
Benz, a San Francisco lawyer who was a member of a U.S. Olympic
Committee investigative panel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
