<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU ARE THERE: MEDIA CIRCUS MAXIMUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's March 15 _ ``The Ides of March are come.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Caesar's famous boast to the Soothsayer in William
Shakespeare's ``Julius Caesar.'' (``Ay, Caesar, but not gone,'' the
clever devil, who had warned Caesar to beware, shot back.)
</P>
<P>
   The ides are nothing more than the 15th day of March, May, July
and October, and the 13th day of other months. But March 15 marks
the date of one of history's most famous murders _ Caesar's, at the
hands of Brutus and his cohorts.
</P>
<P>
   How word was spread to the rest of the world back in 44 B.C.
isn't known. But if the murder took place today, it's easy to
imagine the media firestorm:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CNN: (Logo with bloody dagger and fallen garland; voice-over
read by James Earl Jones _ `` Rome in Crisis: The murder of
Caesar.'') ``Romans are in a state of shock today after the murder
of dictator for life Julius Caesar. Caesar, a military hero and
successful author, was stabbed to death at the Senate. We'll be
back with round-the-sundial coverage, including a panel of experts
debating Caesar's favor with the gods, after these messages. And
don't forget to tune in tonight for our four-hour special:
``Caesar: From veni, vidi, vici to a violent end.'' (Fade to
profile of slain leader, with ``Caesar, C-XLIV B.C.'' written in
black script; somber music plays underneath.)
</P>
<P>
   Rome Today &UR; : ``Dictator for life Julius Caesar was stabbed to
death at the Senate yesterday. A CNN-``Rome Today'' poll taken
minutes afterward finds that 3 percent of those asked think this is
a bad thing for Romans, 2 percent think it's a good thing, and the
other 95 percent are illiterate and didn't know who Caesar was.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Local TV news: ``. . . and more sunny weather is expected
tomorrow! In some sad news: Julius Caesar, dictator for life,
apparently has been murdered. News Chariot XII is at the Senate, so
we'll go live to reporter Cassius Dufus. . . . Cassius?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, Clarissa. Witnesses here say that Caesar has indeed
been murdered. As you can imagine, this has caused a traffic
nightmare around the Senate building, so if you're planning to pass
this way, you can save time by taking another route. Try the road
by the temple as an alternate. Back to you, Clarissa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good work, Cassius. Love the tunic. So remember, avoid the
Senate building, at least for the next few hours. And now, in more
weather . . .''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Local newspaper: ``G. Julius Caesar, Rome's dictator for life,
was murdered by conspirators at the Senate yesterday. In response,
Josephus Arpaio, Rome's self-proclaimed toughest constable, vowed
to form a `Posse Senatus' made up of retired soldiers, farmers and
vagrants to roam the Senate area on horseback armed with swords and
daggers to help prevent other assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   `` `This is not a publicity stunt,' Arpaio said at a hastily
called (by him) news conference. `Neither were the public
floggings, the pink togas for prisoners or the death-by-hungry-lion
punishment for rabble-rousers. Mark my words: In time, you'll
forget this Caesar fellow, but you'll remember me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Inside Edition &UR; : ``He's sexy, he's powerful. Is he in charge? In
the wake of Julius Caesar's tragic murder, Mark Antony's funeral
speech has his name on all Romans' lips. `Friends, Romans,
countrymen, lend me your ears'? Women all over Rome are saying,
`We'll lend you more than that, mister!' ``Inside Edition'' brings
you an exclusive profile of the heroic hunk. And coming up
tomorrow: `Cleopatra _ Why Won't the Rumors Die?' ''
</P>
<P>
   20/20 &UR; : ``Tonight, more from Barbarus Walters' exclusive
interview with Calpurnia, Caesar's widow. Up next:
</P>
<P>
   `` `All that badgering, all those omens, all those warnings _
just before your husband's death, you were a pain in the butt!'
</P>
<P>
   `` `You bet. You bet. But (close-up of her wiping away tear) he
was a really good kisser. I feel so cheap.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `If thou were a tree, what tree wouldst thou be?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Larrius Rex Live &UR; : ``Tonight we have a full slate of guests,
including Marcus Brutus, who will explain why he helped stab his
best friend to death, and Mark Antony, who, I understand, has a
different take on the murder. Assassination _ naked ambition or
good career move? We'll take your calls, so don't go away!'' &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
