<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-ARMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTICIPATING CONFLICT IN EURASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With ARMY-REFORM) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In its search to remain prepared in today's ever
unsettled, rapidly changing world, the Army has a notion at least
of the type of messy international mission its forces may well have
to face in the years ahead: protecting Caspian Sea oil.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's war-gamers, based at the Army's Training and Doctrine
Command at Fort Monroe, Va., have devised an elaborate geopolitical
``model'' of the Caspian Sea region that will serve as the
computerized basis for conducting exercises and training missions
well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with tradition and diplomatic niceties, the Army's
model includes only generic names for the countries involved, like
Blueland and Purpleland. But even a rudimentary familiarity with
geography makes it clear that the Army envisions conflicts
ensnarling a swath of Eurasia from Turkey to Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
   Army strategists who once conducted war games against the Soviet
Union will soon be waging their mock wars in former Soviet states
like Georgia, Armenia and Azerbiajan.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Michael Mehaffey, director of Battle Lab Integration,
Technology and Concepts at Fort Monroe, emphasized that the new
model was not meant to send signals about U.S. intentions in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that the region's characteristics posed a stew
of challenges for commanders considering how to fight future wars.
Among them: ethnic rivalries, austere terrain, a lack of major
seaports, regular and irregular forces and a credible threat of
chemical or biological weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
