<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-NASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASH TURNING AROUND A FRUSTRATING SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Privately, there were some rumblings among Mavericks
players when the team signed point guard Steve Nash to a six-year,
$33 million contract extension before he even bounced a basketball
in a regular-season game for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   And when Nash started this season in a shooting slump _ combined
with the superb up-tempo play of backup point guard Robert Pack _
the talks intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Nash said he heard none of the scuttlebutt. He was too busy
unpacking to see if he had left his jump shot in his suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people have been disappointed perhaps in my
play, but I've learned not to worry about what other people
think,'' Nash said. ``In time, I know the people here will
appreciate what I do, and I think that's the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the way we play, I may not be in the stat sheets every
night. As long as my teammates and the coaches know and appreciate
the effort and commitment that I give to the guys, I'm happy. I
don't need my name in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the only time Nash got his name in the paper was
because his jump shot was lost at sea and his quarterbacking skills
were all wet. But within the past week, that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games, Nash dispensed 11 assists against Orlando
and 10 assists against Vancouver. He's shooting for double-digit
assists for a third consecutive game when the Mavericks play the
Portland Trail Blazers at 7:30 tonight at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Nash's early-season shooting slump, the Mavericks'
coaching staff never soured on the 6-foot-3 playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``His performance on the floor has nothing to do with selfish
reasons or financial reasons,'' Mavericks assistant coach Donnie
Nelson said. ``The only thing he's concerned about is the good of
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to put his best foot forward; he wants to win, and he
wants to perform well in a team concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 22 games, a new contract, a broken nose and a viral
infection later, Nash has finally settled down and become the
player the Mavericks thought he was when they gave up their
first-round pick in this June's draft for his services.
</P>
<P>
   The third-year veteran is letting the game come to him instead
of pressing as he was during the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was going through the slump and the broken nose and
the viral infection that he had, it was really depressing to him
because he wanted to put on a much better show for the fans, for
management and for his teammates,'' Nelson said. ``The fact that
he's coming through this thing is no surprise to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting this before the slump, the nose and the
viral stuff. Plus, his teammates have been great. They've been real
patient with him because they know what kind of a guy he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure for Nash to perform well has intensified because
Pack will be sidelined for two to four weeks. A magnetic resonance
imaging exam yesterday revealed that Pack suffered a slightly torn
right hamstring in the first half of Saturday's 91-74 victory over
Vancouver. But Nash seems to thrive on pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what happens on offense, I don't care who scores,
I don't care who shoots, I don't care what we run, I don't care
what we do, and I don't care if we shoot 30 percent,'' Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only care what we can control every single night _ and
that's our defensive effort. If we do that, we're going to
definitely win some games that we've lost already this year.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Nash continues progressing the way he has lately, he'll
keep getting his name in the paper in a positive light.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
