<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE WOMEN GAIN CREDIT AS INVENTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the stacks at the Patent and Trademark Office archives,
researchers often have to turn sideways to pass one another in the
narrow walkways between towering shelves that hold paper copies of
every patent issued since the 1790s.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly six million patents on record, those copies
represent the work of millions of inventors. Yet for almost all the
first 200 years of patent history, fewer than 2 percent of those
inventors were women.
</P>
<P>
   The share has increased in the last 15 years _ but women
inventors have by no means caught up with male inventors. The
Patent and Trademark Office says that between its official opening
in 1790 and 1984, only 1.5 percent of the inventors who received
patents were women.
</P>
<P>
   From 1984 to 1996, that jumped to 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another way of considering the numbers is that 1,100 women
earned patents in 1977 from that year's total of 43,000. In 1996,
more than 6,000 women shared in 66,000 patents. In that interval,
the percentage rose from 2.6 percent to 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But even today, cursory scans of the roughly 3,000 patents
issued each week show that inventions tend to follow gender
stereotypes. Women are disproportionate winners of patents for
child care, household, clothing or personal-care inventions, while
the majority of inventors listed on scientific and engineering
patents are men.
</P>
<P>
   But that, too, is changing. Women inventors have traditionally
been scarce in the agency's category of chemical technology. But in
1996, 15.7 percent of those patents bore the names of women
inventors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is high,'' says Joanne Hayes-Rines, publisher of
Inventor's Digest. ``That's a lot of what accounts for the
increase. I think it's just the feminist movement from the 1960s
finally kicking in. I've seen this especially in the biotech area.
It's a new industry, and there's no old boys network. That goes
back to women in science, and the push from the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   Since March is both Women's History Month and National
Inventor's Month, this is as good a time as any to look at societal
changes since the 1960s that have made it easier and more practical
for women to patent their ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taken more seriously by banks when they need a loan,
more seriously by manufacturers when they want to get a product
made,'' Ms. Hayes-Rines said. ``A lot of those walls have come
down. Women inventors were butting their heads against those walls
40 years ago, and the gals from the 1960s made it possible to go
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the affiliation of female inventors is changing,
too. More are now winning patents the way men have for decades _ as
employees of large corporations or as part of scientific and
research teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the numbers back up the idea that women are all
independent inventors,'' Ms. Hayes-Rines said. ``The women working
at places like Dow Chemical represent the increase in the chemical
and engineering areas. The independent inventors are solving
family-related and household problems. I think it is half and
half.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, necessity is the mother of invention, not the father.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're at home, raising family, it's a problem-solving
environment,'' Ms. Hayes-Rines said. ``Women are constant problem
solvers, and that shows itself in these increased numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, women are responsible for inventions like the
automatic drip coffee maker, the dishwasher, disposable diapers,
frozen pizza dough, Scotchgard fabric protector, liquid paper,
windshield wipers and the Snugli baby carrier. But they also
devised a diphtheria vaccine, Common Business-Oriented Language, or
COBOL, and Kevlar, the bulletproof material used in vests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've met one woman who would say she was an
inventor from the time she was a little girl,'' Ms. Hayes-Rines
said. ``They're all people who solved a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiggle Those Toes in a Sandal Sock
</P>
<P>
   Warmer weather may not be too far off, and with it comes an
eternal fashion question for those whose summer wardrobes feature
sandals: socks or no socks?
</P>
<P>
   While no socks is the obvious answer for most people, some, like
Charles Corry, prefer them. Corry, who lives in Chicago, has
designed a pair of sandal socks that take account of the fashion
faux pas in wearing any. The patented socks are, in fact, a kind of
woven sandal themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The sock covers the sole of the wearer's foot, but not the top
and sides.
</P>
<P>
   It attaches to the foot with three bands _ one each that cross
the foot over the toes and over the arch of the foot, and a third
that extends upward from the heel of the sock to circle the ankle.
Thus, the sock protects the bottom of the foot but leaves the toes
and top of the foot suitably naked.
</P>
<P>
   Corry received patent number 5,867,838.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
