<SLUG> BC-GRITZ-COMMUNITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDAHO COMMUNITY LEAVES SOME RESIDENTS FEELIN THEY'VE BEEN HAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMIAH, Idaho _ The instant they heard Bo Gritz describe Almost
Heaven, it sounded like the answer to Ross and Patty Stirling's
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   A sanctuary sprawled across a 1,200-acre plateau above a rustic
Idaho town, where people could live like their forefathers, was
something the Stirlings could not pass up.
</P>
<P>
   So they sold their house and their shrimp business near
Galveston, Texas, and plunked down $15,000 for a piece of land 12
miles from Kamiah, a town of 1,200 people along the Clearwater
River in north-central Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   At first the Stirlings thought the world of Gritz, a Vietnam War
hero and now a spokesman for the Christian Patriot movement. The
development was shaping up to be exactly what they had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Now, struggling to get by and having lost faith in Gritz, about
the only thing they want is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't Almost Heaven,'' Patty Stirling said. ``I call it
Almost Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gritz has loyal supporters at Almost Heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bo is a wonderful person, and he's always welcome here,'' said
Barb Fuller, one of the original settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by Gritz in 1994, Almost Heaven was to be a Promised
Land for patriots, a place where people could live free from
government intervention. Come to Almost Heaven, Gritz said, and the
ex-Green Beret commander would protect them from the evils that
were bound to be brought on by Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   But now, parts of the community are in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 residents signed a letter to the county sheriff
dissociating themselves from Gritz, saying they were not interested
in ``cult lifestyles or behaviors.'' Others have scared townsfolk
by flying their flags upside down, showing up at public events with
weapons and declaring their ``sovereignty'' from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Almost Heaven's financial manager left in 1997. Other residents
would like to leave, too, but are having problems selling their
property because, they say, they cannot get clear titles to their
land.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gritz doesn't live at Almost Heaven anymore. He moved to
Nevada last year after his wife divorced him, but he continues to
promote the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely two sides to Bo Gritz,'' Patty Stirling
said. ``What he says and what he does are two different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told people, `Come live like the Amish. We'll find a way to
take care of you.' And here Claudia (Gritz's ex-wife) is with a
tanning bed in her house.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz's ex-wife could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the area surrounding the subdivisions are angry,
too, complaining that Gritz has brought blight to a
once-picturesque community settled by pacifist Quaker farmers in
the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really disgusting,'' said Audrey Spence, whose family
helped establish the area 104 years ago. ``Bo brought all this
here. Now he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're armed to the teeth. This is a powder keg just waiting
to blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz shrugs off the complaints, saying most people in his
communities are peaceful, happy folk. He noted that residents
included a Los Angeles doctor, a bank president and the mother of
former Olympic star Bruce Jenner.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz said he got the idea for a covenant community _ a
development in which residents must pledge to defend their
neighbors' constitutional rights _ when he began to worry about
Y2K. He began selling plots for around $5,000 an acre. He says
about 175 families live in the nine developments.
</P>
<P>
   While the views from Gritz's former $184,000 house and his
neighbor's half-million-dollar log cabin are picture-perfect, other
parts of the development aren't so pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Dilapidated trailer houses and school buses dot the landscape.
One man built a house out of dirt-filled car tires. Another lived
in a dwelling made of hay bales. The county appraiser's office
lists some property values at $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, government officials say, is that Idaho County has
virtually no zoning or building codes.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Gillespie, Almost Heaven's former financial manager,
accused Gritz of misleading his followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning he was a great man,'' said Gillespie, a
former Arizona state senator. ``But I found that after working with
him a while, he started to change. I think he became very greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz denies Gillespie's claims, saying his former financial
manager nearly bankrupted him _ something Gillespie denies. Gritz
said that the land debts have been paid and that all the deeds are
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally will never see a dime from Almost Heaven,'' Gritz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho County officials said that after Almost Heaven was born,
strange things started happening. For example, the district court
clerk's office was inundated with paperwork from people wanting to
declare their sovereignty or revoke their U.S. citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused a paper jam,'' said Court Clerk Rose Gehring.
</P>
<P>
   But the only illegal activity, said Sheriff Eugene Meinen, is
``sovereign citizens'' driving without licenses or license plates.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Phil McLain, pastor of the Woodland Friends Church that
sits in the midst of Almost Heaven, said about 20 residents
attended worship services.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern is that a lot of the people seem to be living
in fear _ fear of Y2K, of Armageddon, of the millennium,'' McLain
said. ``And fearful people sometimes do irrational things.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents carry guns, McLain said. One brought a weapon to
church.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said: ``This is a wonderful place to live. All these
people want to be good people. They just want to be left alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
