<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ST.LOUIS-FIRE-KAN &LR;      03-14 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. LOUIS NEIGHBORS HOPE FIRE SERVES AS WAKE-UP CALL 
</HEADLINE>
 LOUIS-FIRE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Ten-year-old Deandre Stevenson woke up Saturday
morning with his worst nightmare fresh in mind.
</P>
<P>
   People screaming; flames billowing; children dying.
</P>
<P>
   But this nightmare had been real.
</P>
<P>
   After school Friday, Deandre and several classmates walked by
firefighters battling an apartment fire in his north St. Louis
neighborhood. Six children died inside, including at least two of
his schoolmates from Clay Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   Even in an area where violence is not rare, the fire jarred many
children. Those still living are victims too, parents said.
</P>
<P>
   Deandre was so shaken he could not sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep seeing those kids' faces,'' he told his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities Saturday identified the victims as Danielle
Williams, 9; Howell Jason, 8; Jason Wordlaw, 6; Forise Nowden, 5;
Briana Sanford, 2; and Amber Polk, 8 months. All the children lived
in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   A woman believed to be the mother of two of the children
suffered a broken leg when she fell from a second-story window.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the fire was set, possibly by a man who had argued
with his girlfriend, who lived in the building. Nevelynn Stokes,
23, was charged Saturday with six counts of murder and one count of
arson.
</P>
<P>
   Now residents of the Hyde Park area of north St. Louis wonder
whether this tragedy will rally the neighborhood or further
desensitize children who have grown up around shootings and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something they're accustomed to, which is the sad
part,'' said Kathy Schwab, owner of Hyde Park Donuts, where
neighborhood children often stop after school. ``They have so much
negative that they're learning that there is no room for the
positive. I hope this is a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Litter blows on the sidewalks here. Some businesses are boarded
up or burned out _ a $1,000 reward has been offered for information
on recent arsons of vacant buildings. One longtime business owner
compared the desolate streets with Bosnia, even with the Gateway
Arch as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, drugs are not hard to find, and children walk to
school amid guns and fighting. Schwab's shop has been robbed
several times.
</P>
<P>
   The children might be the area's best asset, residents say.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Elementary's after-school program has been hailed for its
tutoring and extracurricular activities. The school works with
nearby Friedens Haus, a nonprofit center, to provide one-stop
social services for children and adults. School attendance has
skyrocketed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   While most residents do not consider Hyde Park a close-knit
neighborhood, they say the children are tight because many have
spent years together in class and at the after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   Pupils in the after-school program were returning from a field
trip to the YMCA when they came across the fire in the second-story
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   They were whisked back to school, but the damage had been done.
Many were crying. Some wondered whether any classmates were inside.
One staff member described the scene as mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   One pupil asked his classmates to just stop and pray.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, when he heard three had died, the child started
bawling. He burst out of the room, dashed up the stairs and out the
door. Staff members found him a block away, hysterical.
</P>
<P>
   The school district plans to bring counselors on Monday to talk
to pupils. Parents say they don't know what to tell their children.
Wanda Telford, Deandre's mother, had to ask her fiance, a minister,
to comfort her son early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to deal with this myself,'' Telford admitted.
``How is a child supposed to react? It's a lot to ask of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Ann Brandon, 8, tried to block it all out.
</P>
<P>
   When the television broadcast footage of the fire that killed
her school friend, she covered her eyes. Then she prayed for
Danielle, trying to comfort herself with the belief that her friend
is in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The two called each other almost daily, Carol Ann said, and
loved to play tag and jump rope on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss her,'' Carol Ann said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Ann's mother, Tammy Harmon, said: ``This hits so close to
home. You hope that it doesn't affect the children too much.''
</P>
<P>
   While Carol Ann tried to close her eyes, others did not want to
forget.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Becherer brought her son Saturday to lay two bouquets
of flowers at the fire scene. The pink, violet and yellow blossoms
contrasted sharply with the charred black steps leading to the
second-floor apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Becherer's son did not attend school with the children, but he
played with them in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Becherer, tears welling in her eyes, said the fire should
motivate parents to ensure that violence is not part of their
children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids need to know that they can be safe,'' she said. ``That's
the biggest contract we have as a society. When that is broken,
every parent and child suffers. We let our children down this
week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
