<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9985 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDNEY-KAN &LR;      03-14 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE-SAVING GIFT BONDS CASUAL FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALNUT, Iowa _ It's not often, Linda Krueger said, that you get
to fix something that's not fair.
</P>
<P>
   But there she sat one morning last fall listening in sad
disbelief to a colleague talk about Bernadine Hardisty, the cheery
junior high math teacher.
</P>
<P>
   A genetic disease was fast destroying Hardisty's kidneys. She
was performing dialysis on herself four times a day. She needed a
transplant. Soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, Bernie's done things right in her life,'' Krueger
said. ``She built a good marriage. She raised two good boys. She's
a nice person.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disease didn't seem fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Krueger has only one of her kidneys. Hardisty, grinning and
grateful, has the other.
</P>
<P>
   Across America physicians perform more than 230 kidney
transplants a week. The surgery is successful about nine times out
of 10. Usually the donor is dead _ maybe a teen-ager, killed in a
traffic accident, whose parents decided something good could come
out of something bad.
</P>
<P>
   Less often the kidney is taken from a live donor, someone
checked to make sure he or she understands the sacrifice and has a
body healthy enough to withstand the extraction of a vital organ.
</P>
<P>
   Typically in those cases, the donor is a family member. Fewer
than five times out of 100, it's not a sibling or a parent or a
spouse. Even in those cases, the National Kidney Foundation says,
the donor is usually a ``close friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Krueger barely knew Bernie Hardisty.
</P>
<P>
   They both taught at Walnut Community School, but Krueger had a
second-grade class, while Hardisty taught math and computer classes
for seventh- and eighth-graders. They lived in different towns,
socialized in different circles. A smile in the hallway, a shared
chuckle from time to time _ that was about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Krueger knew that someone she knew, or at least someone she
knew of, was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Hardisty had seen polycystic kidney disease do its damage
before. It took her father at age 49 _ he died on her sister's
birthday _ and also killed three of her aunts and her grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``I just knew I wasn't going to get it, because I
was a good girl. God wasn't going to let it happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then about four years ago she had trouble beating the flu. A few
visits to the doctor later, her diagnosis came: polycystic kidney
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Her kidneys were becoming less able to clean the toxins from her
blood and remove excess fluid from her body. Dialysis could help
for the time being. But not forever.
</P>
<P>
   By September 1998 she had been placed on a national waiting list
for a new kidney. Expect to wait two years, the doctors said. Wear
a beeper around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives, normally the choice for donations, posed a problem
because they were at risk for the same disease.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, word spread through the school in Walnut. Bernie
really looks bad. She needs a donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the waiting list was forever,'' Krueger recalled.
</P>
<P>
   And Krueger knew from giving blood over the years that she was
O-positive, meaning her organs were likely to be compatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it as an opportunity to step out of my comfort
zone...and help somebody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger had a loving husband, three great and mostly grown
children, a good job, a nice home. Maybe risking that, chancing
surgery she didn't need, might help her appreciate it all the more.
So she picked up the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie,'' Krueger said, ``I want you to have my kidney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure?'' Hardisty asked.
</P>
<P>
   She was sure.
</P>
<P>
   A television show the next night on a kidney transplant and a
minister's sermon the next Sunday on sacrifice seemed to bless the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Then began months of tests to confirm Hardisty was healthy
enough to receive a kidney, that Krueger had one to spare (some
people are born with a single kidney) and that the organ from one
could thrive in the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they'd call me with the results of a test,''
Krueger said, ``they'd ask, `Are you sure you want to go through
with this? We can make it look like you flunked one of the tests.'
'' She was always sure.
</P>
<P>
   As time passed the women came to know each other better. The
patter of jokes began. How would Krueger's kidney fare, she would
crack, without its regular dose of coffee?
</P>
<P>
   Finally in mid-February _ recipient and donor had hoped to get
this behind them months earlier _ they were in an Omaha, Neb.,
hospital room waiting on the surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger made a point to say something to Bill Hardisty, Bernie's
husband. ``If something goes wrong and I die,'' Krueger told him,
``tell Bernie I said it's not her fault.''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody died. Hardisty now has three kidneys, and Krueger has
one. Krueger holds her abdomen when she moves or when she laughs.
Hardisty swallows 26 pills a day, including some big ones that
``smell like a skunk'' but keep her body from rejecting its new
organ.
</P>
<P>
   Both are getting better by the day.
</P>
<P>
   One is grateful for a new appreciation for what she has. And
maybe it was going through surgery, or being part of extending
someone else's life, but Krueger said she also had a greater
appreciation for her own mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, I look at things a little differently,'' Krueger
said. ``I have come away enjoying every day more.''
</P>
<P>
   The other is simply grateful to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``How,'' Hardisty wonders, ``can I repay her?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
