<HEADER>
A9987 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-MEMORIAL-KAN &LR;      03-14 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-MEMORIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIAL TO HONOR DOG MANY BELIEVE WAS PSYCHIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Mo. _ At 77, Evelyn Counts describes herself as a pain
in the neck. ``People see me coming and skedaddle,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder. For the last three years Counts has been cajoling
people for money _ she's amassed more than $40,000 so far _ to
honor, of all things, a dog.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Jim the Wonder Dog, who 62 years ago this
Thursday, March 18, 1937, collapsed at the Lake of the Ozarks, died
a short time later at a Sedalia veterinary clinic and then was
buried before a crowd of hundreds at Marshall's Ridge Park
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Originally just outside the cemetery, the dog's grave now is
inside its boundaries because of expansion. Cemetery officials say
Jim's simple stone draws uncounted visitors, many of whom leave
flowers, coins and other mementos.
</P>
<P>
   Come 11 a.m. May 1, Jim's admirers and tourists will have
another sight to see with the opening of what Counts and others
here have been advocating _ ``The Jim the Wonder Dog Memorial
Garden'' _ just north of the courthouse square at 105-109 N.
Lafayette St. Several thousand people are expected to be at the
dedication.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will have a water garden, trees, shrubs, plaques
telling Jim's story, brick pathways and, at the entrance, a
life-size bronze statue of the Llewellyn setter named Jim who _
according to those who knew him _ was psychic.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a phenomenal bird dog _ 5,000 birds were shot over
him _ Jim did things that left people slack-jawed.
</P>
<P>
   Told to find a walnut tree, Jim would do just that, bypassing a
juniper or an oak. Given instructions in a foreign language, he'd
obey. Asked to find a car with a certain license plate on the
square, he'd trot off, a crowd following, and go unerringly to the
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Jim chose winners of the Kentucky Derby and the World Series and
the sex of unborn babies; picked unfamiliar people out of crowds;
and could decipher Morse code.
</P>
<P>
   As word of his accomplishments spread, things happened.
Paramount Pictures sent in a newsreel crew. Newspaper reporters
from all over the country flocked here to write feature stories.
Reader's Digest ran a piece on him. He was in ``Ripley's Believe It
or Not!''
</P>
<P>
   Jim appeared before the Missouri General Assembly. He traveled
as far as Wyoming to give demonstrations. A huge billboard 10 miles
south of here at the junction of U.S. 40 and U.S. 65 bore Jim's
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, in the 1930s, Jim probably was Missouri's best-known
resident. Folks in the Show-Me State knew Tom Pendergast, the
machine boss, or Lloyd Stark, the nursery man turned politician,
and even the new U.S. senator, that little fellow named Harry S.
Truman.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim was known all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the skeptics came, all trying to figure what sort of
magic Jim's master, Sam VanArsdale, was working on the dog, what
subtle cues he prompted the dog with, what sort of flim-flam was
being foisted on a gullible public.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto the veterinarians at the University of Missouri, the
visiting professors who poked and prodded, even the writers who
made the trek to the Hotel Ruff, which VanArsdale managed and where
he, his family and Jim lived.
</P>
<P>
   Most arrived convinced of a gigantic deception, conducted their
tests and then left muttering words and phrases like ``occult,''
``mysterious powers,'' ``enigma,'' and ``beyond understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   From all accounts Jim was the real McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   And so was VanArsdale, a religious man who feared gamblers might
kidnap Jim and refused vaudeville offers, and whose only profit
came from increased business in his hotel's dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jim died at age 12.
</P>
<P>
   And through the years, the memory of the black-and-white dog who
loved treats of cornbread and had deep, limpid eyes, somehow faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like World War II was a wall,'' Counts says. ``On one
side, we could believe in something like Jim. On the other side,
since the war and with all our gadgets, all our hurrying around, we
don't believe anymore. It's like he was a fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the kids still do. I can go out to a school, tell those
youngsters about Jim, and you can tell by their eyes they don't
doubt a word you say.''
</P>
<P>
   The resurrection of Jim started three years ago, when the state
assessed this area's tourism potential. Two things stood out, says
Walter Keith, a city official. One was the Nicholas-Beazley
Airplane Co., which in the early 1920s was the nation's largest
aviation school, and Jim the Wonder Dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had forgotten Jim,'' Keith says. ``Even here in Saline
County.''
</P>
<P>
   About then, in 1996, the stars seemed to align themselves. The
economy was good. Like a lot of small cities, Marshall was seeking
to develop a clean industry like tourism, and, most serendipitous
of all, there was an empty lot where the old Hotel Ruff had stood
until it was demolished more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting, Counts says. The old hotel was gone, but Jim's
garden would be where he lived all those years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Friends of Saline County committee formed a subcommittee
called the Friends of Jim, composed of Counts, Keith, Donna Huston
and Lee Bearden. The last three worked out the nitty-gritty of site
acquisition, utilities, landscaping and contracts.
</P>
<P>
   One contract was the commissioning of Andy Davis, a Marshall
native who now is a sculptor in Columbia, to do the statue.
</P>
<P>
   Counts got the task of raising the money to make it all happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I raised 99 percent of it,'' she says. ``It wasn't easy.
Right as I started, the YMCA was kicking off their $4 million
drive. And then here I'd come, asking for money. I'm sure some
people thought I was a nag.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with her personal appeals plus the sale of T-shirts,
sweatshirts and videotapes recounting Jim's life, Counts found
herself stuck at $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then she had a flash of intuition. She'd sell paving bricks for
the garden's courtyard, engraved with names or messages at $100 a
pop. ``One hundred bucks for a brick?'' people scoffed. No way.
</P>
<P>
   Counts sold 255 bricks, raising $25,500 and putting her over the
top. Representative of the messages on the bricks is this one:
</P>
<P>
   ``Saw Jim. It's All True.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the donations that affected Counts the most
came from children _ dimes, quarters, crumpled dollar bills. The
kids know, she says. After all these years, Jim is still real to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Counts still seeks donations for an endowment to support Jim's
garden in the years to come. Tax-deductible contributions can be
sent to the Marshall Chamber of Commerce, 214 N. Lafayette St.
Marshall, MO 65340.
</P>
<P>
   Could there be another Jim somewhere out there? After all, he
was just a dog, one of millions born every year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, Counts says. Especially if you could find some small
town where there's a dusty old hotel and unhurried people, their
supper finished, sit on a spacious porch amid the gloaming and
visit: about the weather, politics, their kids, or even dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Counts says, I don't know of anyplace like that
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
