<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH BOY, JUST WHAT BOXING DIDN'T NEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A 14-year-old boy who couldn't wait to see the
``big fight'' sat in rapture as Evandar Holyfield and Lennox Lewis
engaged in war.
</P>
<P>
   Someone uttered halfway through what became a pathetically
one-sided bout that ``this is boring.'' The boy, thrilled at the
mere magnitude of such a great event, would have none of it. ``No
way! This is great!'' he responded.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the judges' decision.
</P>
<P>
   The look of utter bewilderment on the boy's face and the words
that spilled from his mouth captured the moment perfectly: ``How
can they do this?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, how !ital!can!off! they do this?
</P>
<P>
   The Holyfield-Lewis fight on Saturday in New York was supposed
to be the best boxing has to offer. Instead, it was the worst.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 rounds, Lewis gave Holyfield the equivalent of a
back-alley whooping. Lewis, the WBC champion from England, rendered
a great but aging WBA and IBF champion helpless with shocking ease.
</P>
<P>
   It was very simple: Holyfield couldn't cope with Lewis' size,
his reach, his speed, his strength, his skills and any other facet
of the fight game that comes to mind. The fact Lewis was relatively
passive when he had Holyfield hurt and in the later rounds was
largely irrelevant: He won easily.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, computer statistics were indicative of a
rout: Lewis landed 348 punches, Holyfield a paltry 130.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the judges' decision was so disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   The first score to be announced was that of ``judge'' Eugenia
Williams of the United States: 115-113 for Holyfield. Jaws around
the world had to hit the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the score of South African judge Stanley Christoudoulou:
116-113 for Lewis. Whew. It appeared Lewis was going to get his
due.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, judge Larry O'Connell of England: 115-115. A draw.
There were two appropriate reactions, stunned silence or laughter.
The decision was that absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel ashamed tonight for the way we (Americans) treated
Lennox Lewis the way we did,'' said boxer Roy Jones Jr., a
television commentator for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``... Anytime Don King is involved, you can expect a draw to
come from somewhere. Ask Pernell Whitaker about the (similar) Julio
Cesar Chavez fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know something like that is in the air. That's the way it
goes. That's type of thing that makes people stray from boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication there is obvious: As Jones saw it, King, who
promoted the fight, played a role in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Did he pay off Williams and O'Connell? Did he pay off the
organizations that hired the judges? Or did he use his immense
influence in a less direct manner to gain the result he wanted, the
result that could translate into a rematch and a few more million
dollars in his pocket?
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing is certain at the moment: A 14-year-old can sense
that something was amiss.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and O'Connell ought to be ashamed of themselves. The
problem is they have no shame. Or integrity. Or pride.
</P>
<P>
   King? King was King, operating in his self interest at the
expense of everyone else with the possible exception of Holyfield,
an embarrassed champion left holding two championship belts that
have lost their meaning.
</P>
<P>
   It was as sad a night as boxing has ever experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight is what's really hurting boxing,'' said Emanuel
Steward, the respected trainer of Lewis. ``Every time we start to
move boxing forward and make a great fight of some type like this,
this type of (garbage) comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander won three rounds, four at most, and nevertheless it's
called a draw. This is what's killing boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   One must feel for Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   This was his moment, his rightful ascension to the pinnacle of
boxing and all that means in terms of glory and money. All the
years he tried to earn the respect of a chauvinistic American
boxing public, all the years so many top heavyweights avoided him
had finally paid off.
</P>
<P>
   And then his moment was gone, stolen from him by corrupt
officials overseeing a corrupt system.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crime, nothing less. Lewis must have cried in his
dressing room after the fight. And, certainly, many people around
the world felt like crying with him.
</P>
<P>
   One must also feel for boxing, the good elements that is, the
officials who are trying to clean up the sport and the countless
honest trainers and fighters who toil every day to realize their
own dreams.
</P>
<P>
   As Steward said, the sport seemed to have turned a corner in the
past year. Suddenly, promoters were making the kind of fights fans
wanted to see _ Oscar De La Hoya-Ike Quartey, Whitaker-Felix
Trinidad, Holyfield-Lewis, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson, who has been more bane than boon to the sport, was
twice humbled by Holyfield and ended up in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The aging King, the symbol of all that is wrong with boxing,
appeared to be fading ever-so-slowly from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   And then this.
</P>
<P>
   The powers that be in the sport had better wake up, they'd
better find a way to weed out the Kings and Williamses from the
sport before it loses any remaining credibility. And to the
legislators who are working to regulate boxing: hurry. There isn't
much time.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing probably has lost the 14-year-old boy as a fan. His
innocent faith was shattered. And millions of people around the
world must be feeling the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker-Savarese: Lou Savarese was down between 12 and 13
seconds when Lance ``Mount'' Whitaker decked him in the sixth round
of their March 6 bout in Atlantic City, N.J., which Savarese won by
decision.
</P>
<P>
   One apparent reason for the long count is disturbing: Referee
Steve Smoger was busy giving Savarese encouragement. He seemed to
say ``take your time'' and ``come on'' during the count.
</P>
<P>
   America Presents, Whitaker's promoter, has formally requested
that the new Jersey State Athletic Control Board review the
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   A rematch appears to be in order.
</P>
<P>
   WBO follies: It's time the WBO forces its featherweight champ,
Naseem Hamed, to fight No. 1 challenger Juan Manuel Marquez or
strip him of his title.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez, promoted by the Forum, has been the top challenger for
16 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight has to be done this year and soon,'' Marquez said.
``I don't think he is afraid but I don't know what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   What's going on is this: Hamed, who isn't as talented as many
people believe, is being protected by his handlers.
</P>
<P>
   A Forum spokesman said legal action will be considered if the
fight isn't made soon.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Erik Morales will defend his WBC super
bantamweight title against Wayne McCullough on the undercard of the
De La Hoya-Oba Carr fight on May 22 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Morales-McCullough fight is a mismatch. McCullough has
neither the skills nor speed to cope with this rising champion.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the card, Floyd Mayweather defends his WBC super
featherweight crown against Goyo Vargas....
</P>
<P>
   David Reid, who outpointed Laurent Boudouani to win the WBA
super welterweight championship on March 6, is scheduled to have
more surgery on his droopy left eye today....
</P>
<P>
   CBS Sportsline recently conducted a poll asking, ``Who is the
most promising heavyweight?''
</P>
<P>
   The results: Michael Grant, 34.4 percent of the votes; Andrew
Golota, 23.8; Chris Byrd, 15.7; Ike Ibeabuchi, 10.4; David Tua,
9.2; and Hasim Rahman, 6.4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
