<HEADLINE>
ONE FOR EVERY MAN, WOMAN, CHILD ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Stanford's Jason Collins's appearance on the cover
of Sports Illustrated in these parts _ sure that isn't Jarron? _ is
more fodder for those who believe in a cover jinx.
</P>
<P>
   How about the SI hijinx?
</P>
<P>
   This week's sign that the apocalypse is upon us would be that
new version of Sports Illustrated for Women exposing itself last
week on the news stands.
</P>
<P>
   So now we've got SI for Kids, for Women, for Men (the regular
one) _ the whole darn family is covered. Congrats to Time Inc. for
finding a way to bleed every last cent out of each imaginable
demographic.
</P>
<P>
   Or have they? We're waiting to see the ink dry on:
</P>
<P>
   SI for Retirees _ Each issue filled with long rambling letters
to the editor.
</P>
<P>
   SI for the Incarcerated _ A weekly diary from Mike Tyson and the
regular feature, ``Scarfaces in the Crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   SI for Panhandlers _ The column in the back: ``This is No Life
of Reilly.''
</P>
<P>
   SI for Grounds Keepers and Zamboni Drivers _ Morgana, who has
covered more sod than any rail-jumper in sports history, is the
cover girl for the annual jumpsuit edition, shot in George Toma's
backyard gazebo.
</P>
<P>
   SI for Michael Jordan _ Reissues of everything from the past 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   SI for Shut-ins _ Pages and pages of ``This week on TV'' and
Propecia ads. Kinda like what regular SI will soon be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Someone's already talking about a two-hour bio film on the life of
Joe DiMaggio and Marilyn Monroe now that apparently no one can
object. It's perfect movie fodder.
</P>
<P>
   To put things into perspective, the closest we can come in 1999
to a DiMaggio-Monroe marriage of sports and entertainment megastar
magnitude is....
</P>
<P>
   Well, the David Justice-Holly Berry marriage is dust. The Derek
Jeter-Mariah Carey tryst never got off the ground. So that leaves
us with....
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman and Carmen Electra?
</P>
<P>
   That's like comparing a champagne-and-caviar dinner party to a
Big Gulp and El Taco from 7-Eleven....
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky and Janet Jones?
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley and Tawny Kittain?
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Kathie Lee Gifford?
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad and Felisha Rashad?
</P>
<P>
   Norm Nixon and Debbie Allen?
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Peete and Holly Robinson?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Niedenfuer and one of those Landers sisters?
</P>
<P>
   We're pushing for Rick Fox making the hook-up with Vanessa
Williams. It's no wonder Fox doesn't complain about his playing
time....
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
So what did Cade McNown learn from this FBI point-shaving
investigation: a) Start watching ``The Sopranos'' on HBO more
closely, b) don't hang out with Paul Hornung and c) Do it again and
you could find the head of USC's Traveler next to you in bed....
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 ought to look next into UCLA's basketball team for
shaving. You know, whether the kids even use a razor and soap....
</P>
<P>
   Shake it off, Lennox. It's just Don King's way of saying,
``Welcome to America, now go home.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks' misplayed fly ball that cost the San Diego Padres
a spring-training game over the week is bound to inspire a Grammy
Award-winning song: ``One Step Back.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Comin' up this week: The NFL decides if L.A. deserves another
team and the IOC decides if Juan Antonio Samaranch deserves another
term. What are the odds of both those happening, Cade? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
