<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN BUFFETT ATTACKS MANIPULATION OF EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   In his annual report to shareholders, the investor Warren
Buffett makes an extraordinary attack on many of his fellow chief
executives, who he says have worked purposefully ``at manipulating
numbers and deceiving investors'' through accounting gimmicks and
misrepresentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many major corporations still play things straight, but a
significant and growing number of otherwise high-grade managers _
CEOs you would be happy to have as spouses for your children or as
trustees under your will _ have come to the view that it's OK to
manipulate earnings to satisfy what they believe are Wall Street's
desires,'' Buffett wrote in Berkshire Hathaway's 1998 report.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT PREPARES COUNTERATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, portrayed by the government as an entrenched
monopolist, will counterattack when its antitrust trial resumes
next month by presenting evidence that America Online plans to
become a head-on challenger, people close to the software giant
said.
</P>
<P>
   NANNY CONTROVERSY IS REVIVED
</P>
<P>
   CBS' ``60 Minutes'' has stirred new controversy in the so-called
nanny murder in Massachusetts, in which Louise Woodward, a young
British woman accused of killing an infant, was freed by a judge
after being convicted of second-degree murder. ``60 Minutes''
broadcast a report on the case that raised questions about whether
the prosecution had correctly identified the cause of death,
leading to a flood of coverage in Boston, some of it critical.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURE LOOKING DIM FOR PAPERBACKS
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the number of mass-market paperbacks sold in the
United States has declined by almost 9 percent, and the book
industry's research arm is projecting slight annual declines over
the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   WARNINGS ABOUT YEAR 2000 SCAMS
</P>
<P>
   While many consumers have worried that year 2000 computer
problems will cripple the banking system, bankers and
law-enforcement officials have been warning that the bigger
financial risks may come from scam artists and thieves playing on
such fears.
</P>
<P>
   EX-EXECUTIVE AT CENTER OF SCANDAL
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for B.J. Kingdon, the former Bankers Trust executive
identified as being at the center of a financial scandal, contends
that the bank is setting his client up as a scapegoat in order to
complete a merger.
</P>
<P>
   CASTING A LINE INTO CYBERSPACE
</P>
<P>
   It may lack the aroma and open-air experience of a traditional
fish market, but starting this week seafood lovers will be able to
bid on Alaskan king crab leg gift packages, four-course dinners for
two and live Maine lobsters on the auction site Ubid.com. Hoping to
do for Ubid what Beanie Babies did for Ebay.com, Stratis Morfogen,
who runs the Fultonstreet.com online seafood site, has signed a
deal to be the ``exclusive online fish store'' for Ubid.
</P>
<P>
   TALK RADIO IN POSTSCANDAL WORLD
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's travails proved both boon and bane to talk
radio over the last year, with listeners tuning out as the scandal
shifted from sex to constitutional questions. Radio hosts and
program directors say they are eager to move beyond the left-right
debates that characterized their shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
