<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-CINCINNATI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE UPSETS CINCINNATI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Jones 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Temple coach John Chaney is fond of talking about how
his team is criticized in Philadelphia for its ugly-looking,
trademark matchup zone.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it didn't play well for the Cincinnati audience yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Cincinnati never completely solved the Owls'
defense yesterday and Temple advanced to the Sweet 16 for the first
time since 1993 with a 64-54 East Region victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach always tells us your will is stronger than your skill,''
Owls' guard Rasheed Brokenborough said. ``They tried to beat us
with their athletic ability rather than their heads. We knew early
they were not attacking the zone like you're supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels good. A lot of people thought we going home. We
shocked a lot of people by going to the Sweet 16, but we're not
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple (23-10) jumped from a 6-6 tie to a 26-11 lead and led by
11 at the half. The Bearcats (27-6) closed to 35-29 seven minutes
into the second half. But Owls' guard Quincy Wadley _ who scored 14
off the bench _ nailed a three from the wing and Cincinnati never
again got as close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug ourselves a hole and had a hard time getting out,''
Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins said. ``Our whole deal coming in was
we had to do a better job on the glass and they beat us on the
offensive glass early.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we cut it to six, we had the ball but didn't score. Then
they hit a three, we gave up two offensive rebounds and they took
it back to 11. We were continually fighting out of a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamont Barnes and Pepe Sanchez each had 15 for Temple. Guard
Melvin Levett led the Bearcats with 16.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
