<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-EAST-DUKE-SW-MISSOURI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWEST MISSOURI DANCES INTO DATE WITH DUKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ To help dramatize its opening, CBS Sports
asked Kevin Ault to read from a book titled ``Cinderella'' as it
rolled tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was kind of strange, but after what's happened, I
guess it sort of fit,'' the Southwest Missouri State guard said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in school history, the Bears are in the Sweet
16 and Cinderella is required reading. For the second consecutive
game, 12th-seeded Southwest Missouri State (22-10) put the
defensive clamps on an opponent. Yesterday in the second round of
the East Regional, the Bears shackled Tennessee, 81-51.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team gave me 80 minutes of everything they had at the
defensive end and that was the difference,'' Southwest Missouri
State coach Steve Alford said of the Bears' effort in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-seeded Volunteers (21-9) shot 29.5 percent. Including
a first-round victory against Wisconsin on Friday, the Bears have
held opponents here to 28 percent shooting (30 of 108).
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well and when you shoot 29 percent, you're not
going to beat any good teams,'' Tennessee coach Jerry Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Moore scored 25 points to lead the Bears. The 6-foot-11
center also hit both of his 3-point attempts. His first gave
Southwest Missouri State an 11-7 lead at 14:09 of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee declined to double-team Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the first game all season I haven't been
doubled or tripled,'' said Moore, who was 8-of-14 from the field.
``I felt pretty good when I realized that they were going to guard
me with one man. My teammates got me the ball when I was open.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Southwest Missouri State advances to the Sweet 16 and faces
top-ranked, top-seeded, top-dog Duke in a semifinal game on Friday
in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream about games like that,'' Southwest Missouri State
point guard William Fontleroy said. ``You just go out and give your
best, and when it's over it's over.''
DUKE 97, TULSA 56
</P>
<P>
   With 10:26 remaining against Tulsa, Duke's Elton Brand stretched
his 6-8, 260-pound body flat out during a floor-burn-inducing dive
for a loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   Key play in a tight game? Yes and no. At the time, the Blue
Devils had a 77-38 lead. But Brand's hustle was far from
meaningless. No matter the score or the time, Duke just plays.
Hard.
</P>
<P>
   That effort translated into another name-the-score blowout here
yesterday in the second round of the East Regional. The top-seeded
Blue Devils (34-1) won their 29th consecutive game with a 97-56
domination of ninth-seeded Tulsa (23-10).
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great players and they've got a killer instinct,''
Tulsa coach Bill Self said. ``That appears to be a team on a
mission. They don't think like most humans. Most teams get a lead
that big, they let up a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, a 99-58 first-round winner against Florida A&AMP;M, became the
first team in NCAA Tournament history to record two 40-point
victories in a single tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Duke took a 9-2 lead, but Tulsa pulled to within 9-8 with a 6-0
run. That spurt was started by a Marcus Hill 3-pointer made
possible when the Golden Hurricane hustled for a loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the next timeout, \Rcoach Mike Krzyzewski\S reminded us
nobody got on the floor for that loose ball,'' said Duke guard
Trajan Langdon, who returned from a foot injury to score 12 points
in 26 minutes. ``We take pride in making those kind of plays.''
</P>
<P>
   That pride turned into a forget-about-it 30-5 run for a 39-13
lead 6:27 before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got to too many loose balls,'' said Tulsa forward Michael
Ruffin, who was shut out in 34 minutes of play. ``They competed a
lot harder than we did. When we got down, most teams let up, they
kept competing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa shot 33.9 percent for the game and was outrebounded 47-33.
Duke shot 48.7 percent and was 11-of-20 on 3-pointers, getting 3s
from six different players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look at the scoreboard,'' said Duke point guard
William Avery, who had a team-high 19. ``We play every possession
like the score is 0-0.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
