<HEADER>
A0047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOMBINGS-ART-N     03-14 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOMBINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A SERBIAN VILLAGE, RESIDENTS WAIT FOR PEACE OR BOMBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-TALKS) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOVO SELO, Yugoslavia _ On a tranquil Sunday morning, the
residents of this village were chatting in the sun outside their
local shop, or working among the chickens in the walled courtyards
of their houses.
</P>
<P>
   The peaceful scene belied the fear that lurks here, in one of
the few mixed villages left in Serbia's Kosovo province, a place
where Serbs and ethnic Albanians live side by side in apparent
harmony. They are surrounded by violence, and as the conflict
escalates around them, they are clinging desperately to the hope
that peace will reach them before war does.
</P>
<P>
   The previous day had been bad, said Ibrahim Maxhuni, 35, an
unemployed ethnic Albanian trader. Some of the villagers had been
in the nearby town of Mitrovica when a bomb exploded in the market
place. Not long before, two other bombs had exploded in another
local town, Podujevo. By Sunday, the toll was seven people killed
and 57 wounded in the three blasts.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the villagers had listened for hours as Serbian tanks
and artillery shelled the other side of their valley. All night,
they had watched the fires as neighboring villages burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it in the neighborhood and you wait for it in your own
home,'' said Rasim Maxhuni, a retired lawyer and another member of
the Maxhuni clan here. ``Everything is working up toward the
finale.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest violence erupted just as delegates from both sides
were leaving for Paris, where peace talks that stalled two weeks
ago resume on Monday. A political agreement seems within reach, but
the two sides are still far apart over carrying out the deal, with
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, Serbia's leader, still
refusing to contemplate the presence of a foreign peacekeeping
force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Novo Selo, Serbs and Albanians alike expressed hope that the
talks would bring peace, but said they could trust only in foreign
pressure on Serbia. ``If the West gets serious, they will sign,''
Rasim Maxhuni said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ibrahim Maxhuni said he expected the situation on the
ground in Kosovo to worsen. ``You could have a lot of bombings and
killings before the peace talks are over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Novo Selo has not been touched so far, probably because it is a
mixed village, and because there were no Kosovo Liberation Army
guerrillas in the village, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they worry. Serbian tanks and military units are positioned
only a mile away. Paramilitary groups and armed Serbian civilians
are active in the area, they said, and could come into the village
and attack Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to those in the village, but we are afraid of
groups from outside,'' said Sabri Maxhuni, the local shopkeeper. He
said no one went out after 5 in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turn off the lights in the evening,'' he said. ``We are
afraid someone might shoot from outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed Serbian policemen patrol the village twice a week, he
said, adding, ``We usually hide inside until they pass.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Serbs in the village the fears are different, but no
less real. There are 53 Serbian families here and some 300 ethnic
Albanian families, a mixture that is slightly less disproportionate
than the general breakdown in Kosovo, where Albanians outnumber
Serbs 9 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Mica Kostic, 62, has lived with her husband and sons in the
village for nearly 40 years, and her family traces its roots in
Kosovo back some 300 years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very hard,'' she said, wiping a roughened hand over
her lined face. ``But we trust in our future and in our neighbors.
Our neighbors are not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the villagers always have maintained good relations
with one another. Yet she more than anyone here has been touched by
the war. She was in the market in Mitrovica, selling vegetables,
when the bomb exploded on Saturday, she said. Her cousin was killed
last year by unknown people when he was driving across the
province, and another relative was shot dead recently in a mixed
village across the valley.
</P>
<P>
   That village, Bukos, is no longer mixed, because after the
killing, Serbian security forces moved in and caused the Albanian
villagers to flee. Mrs. Kostic refused to contemplate the same
happening in Novo Selo and said she would never think of leaving
the village or Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred percent, I will never go,'' she said. Yet the
Serbs in the village had evacuated all their children just days
before, as the conflict escalated in the neighborhood, she
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic should accept the peace proposal, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For everyone it would be better if he signs,'' she said. ``It
would bring back normal life. I think the Albanians think the same.
It would be good for the situation to calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Gesturing at the farmland behind her house, she said, ``It is
time to start working.''
</P>
<P>
   She longs for the return of her grandchildren. ``It is like the
house of the dead without them,'' she said. ``But it is good they
do not know fear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
