<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.Y.-BREAST-FED-DEATH     03-14 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-BREAST-FED-DEATH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RARE CASE, A BREAST-FEEDING MOTHER FACES TRIAL FOR INFANT'S
STARVATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Va., Ohio)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Tabitha Walrond, a 19-year-old welfare
recipient, gave birth to her first child on June 27, 1997, she did
what new mothers rich and poor are urged to do these days: she
breast-fed her baby. But on August 27th, seven weeks after leaving
the hospital, the son she had named Tyler Isaac Walrond died in her
arms of malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walrond goes on trial Tuesday in the Bronx, charged with
recklessly causing Tyler's death by failing to nourish him
adequately and by failing to obtain prompt medical attention when
his condition became dire.
</P>
<P>
   The case is unusual because while some nursing mothers have
problems producing enough breast milk, it is rare for a baby to die
as a result, and rarer still for the mother to then be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for women and the poor contend that Tyler's death was
not a crime, but a tragedy that reflects hidden perils of
breast-feeding and obstacles to health care for poor children.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors, urged in their efforts by Tyler's father, say
that Ms. Walrond was responsible for the baby's death because she
did not heed warnings and obvious signs that he was starving. The
most compelling evidence, they said, are photographs of the
emaciated infant taken eight days before his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is look at the pictures,'' said Steve Reed,
a spokesman for the Bronx District Attorney, Robert T. Johnson.
``Any reasonable person would look at this and say the baby looked
like something out of Biafra.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree on one point: Tyler's death should have been
prevented. But prosecutors focus on the last days of Tyler's life,
while Ms. Walrond's defenders say the circumstances that put him in
such jeopardy were shaped much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Tipograph, Ms. Walrond's lawyer, says that the young
mother nursed her son faithfully, not realizing that her supply of
breast milk was inadequate. Routine pediatric checkups would have
caught the problem, but records show that although Tyler was
entitled to such care under Medicaid, efforts to enroll him in that
health insurance program for the poor were rebuffed or delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Lactation experts say that photographs can be misleading,
because a nursing mother with insufficient breast milk typically
fails to recognize even drastic weight loss until it is pointed out
by a pediatrician with a baby scale because she sees the baby every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was unaware of it, Ms. Walrond was at great risk
for difficulties in breast-feeding. At age 15, she had breast
reduction surgery, which experts say greatly increases the chances
of insufficient breast milk. But her medical records indicate that
the surgery's significance went unrecognized during her prenatal
and postpartum care.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Tyler's father, Keenan Purcell, and his mother saw
the 7-week-old baby on a visit, the boy looked so skinny that they
urged Ms. Walrond and her mother to feed him formula, Purcell said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Walronds, confident of the superiority of breast milk
and bitterly estranged from the Purcell family, insisted that Tyler
was in good health, both sides agreed.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, on August 27, Ms. Walrond found her son
unresponsive in his bassinet. He died on the way to a hospital
emergency room, weighing about five pounds, almost three pounds
less than the day he was born at the Jack D. Weiler Hospital
division of Albert Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Because women have breast-fed their babies throughout history,
many people assume it comes naturally. In fact, problems arise in
some cases, but those in which a baby dies or is permanently
injured for lack of milk are extremely unusual, experts said, and
they are rarely, if ever, prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Zion Cox, the son of a nurse and a minister, died in Colorado in
1995. A baby in Cincinnati had a leg amputated because of blood
clots related to dehydration. A an infant in Norfolk, Va., suffered
permanent brain damage because of inadequate breast milk. None of
the parents faced charges.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Tatiana Cheeks, 21, of Brooklyn, who had been
breast-feeding her baby daughter, was accused of homicide after the
6-week-old died of malnutrition. Ms. Cheeks had brought her baby to
an outpatient clinic of New York Methodist Hospital for a checkup,
but was turned away for lack of Medicaid coverage or money to pay a
$25 fee.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn district attorney's office dropped the charges
after hearing from lactation experts. Later, the State Department
of Health faulted the hospital for its role.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Walrond case different, besides the photographs
and the additional weeks Tyler went without medical care, legal
experts suggested, are angry paternal relatives pushing for
punishment. ``As far as I'm concerned, she is a monster that I did
not protect my son from,'' Purcell said of Ms. Walrond, who faces
up to 15 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates contend that what sets the Walrond case apart from
those in other states is the mother's poverty and a reaction to
notorious cases of child abuse that has made New York too quick to
prosecute poor parents. Until Ms. Tipograph took over the defense,
they add, Ms. Walrond's legal representation, unlike Ms. Cheeks',
was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel strongly that in both cases the infants' deaths are
attributable to failures in health care provision for poor New
Yorkers, rather than criminal negligence on the part of their
mothers,'' Ronnie Eldridge, a city councilwoman from Manhattan,
wrote prosecutors last year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marianne Neifert, an authority on breast-milk insufficiency
syndrome and director of a lactation center in Denver, estimates
that the problem affects up to 5 percent of nursing mothers. At
first, starving babies may compensate, she said, using their own
fat and slowing their growth, but otherwise not acting sick. Then,
sometimes suddenly, she said, the baby rapidly declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen to anybody,'' said Dr. Neifert, who has agreed
to testify for the defense. ``To expect the mother to make these
self-assessments is completely unrealistic and unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By law, Tyler was entitled to automatic Medicaid coverage from
birth. In practice, experts in health care financing say, a city
caseworker had to approve and secure Tyler's enrollment in
Medicaid. This process became caught up in bureaucratic delays and
mistaken computer rejections, in part because Ms. Walrond, who was
finishing high school, was living with her mother, a former state
hospital aide, and was a dependent on her public assistance case.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ms. Walrond received her prenatal care through a
Medicaid managed care plan at the HIP (Health Insurance Plan of New
York) Medical Group in the Bronx, Tyler was supposed to be enrolled
there even before birth.
</P>
<P>
   The Walronds said that because the baby lacked a Medicaid
number, they were turned away when they tried to schedule his
checkup at HIP.
</P>
<P>
   The family's frustrated efforts to comply with the rules started
four months before Tyler's birth, they said, and involved separate
trips to at least three city offices, including one to Tremont
Multi-Service Center Number 41 six days before he died.
</P>
<P>
   According to a written account prepared by HIP last year in
response to a State Department of Health query, HIP asked the city
several times for the identification number needed to pre-enroll
Tyler as a HIP member, beginning five months before his birth. Each
time, the city's Medicaid computer system rejected the request,
classifying his eligibility as ``pending.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Creggett, director of public affairs at HIP's corporate
offices, said that company policy required care to be extended in
such cases and that HIP had no record of Ms. Walrond seeking an
appointment for her son.
</P>
<P>
   The Walronds' city caseworker would not discuss the case, but
the Walronds say she told them that Tyler's Medicaid coverage would
start after his Social Security card and birth certificate were
issued. When Purcell became alarmed at the baby's appearance, he
said, he called a different clinic and was told that it required
the same documents.
</P>
<P>
   Recent federal investigations and court rulings have found that
New York City welfare policies that are intended to push poor
mothers from public assistance to work and self-reliance have made
it harder for them to enroll their children in Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, Tyler was never seen by a pediatrician at
the HIP center, HIP's account acknowledged, not even after Ms.
Walrond proudly brought the baby to her own postpartum checkup, and
her doctor noticed that Tyler, then almost 5 weeks old, looked
underweight. That doctor, Ohmad Rotenberg, would not discuss the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her breast reduction surgery, Ms. Walrond suffered
complications in childbirth that experts said should have alerted
doctors to potential breast-feeding problems. Because of fetal
distress, Tyler was delivered by Caesarean section and Ms. Walrond
developed a fever and blood clots that kept her in the hospital for
12 days. In that time, she was allowed to nurse only for the first
three days and the last two, because she was being treated with
medication.
</P>
<P>
   Records from the hospital, a division of Montefiore Medical
Center, reflect confusion over whether the baby was going to be
breast- or formula-fed at home. Follow-up care is listed as HIP,
but with no appointment date.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Silverman, a spokeswoman for the hospital, said, ``We are
confident that all the medical and ancillary care were
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends that
breast-feeding newborns be checked after they have been home for 48
hours. But pediatricians still typically schedule a baby's first
checkup at 2 weeks of age, with a second checkup at 6 weeks for
immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walrond, now a college student, met Purcell when they were
children at the Love Gospel Assembly, where his mother taught
Sunday school and she and her own mother still attend services
twice a week. By Purcell's account, they broke up after she refused
to get an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when she was six months pregnant, he informed her in the
HIP waiting room that he had a new girlfriend who was also having
his baby. Distraught, Ms. Walrond asked her doctor for an abortion.
She quickly dropped the request, but it is part of her medical
record.
</P>
<P>
   After Tyler was born, Purcell went to court to secure visitation
rights, and would have sought custody of the child, he said, except
that he lacked the means to support him.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Tyler's parents are haunted by his death. Purcell said
he thinks of his dead baby when he looks at his other son, now 16
months old. In interviews, Ms. Walrond's tear-streaked face still
lights up when she recalls her 3 a.m. breast-feedings with Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he would hear my voice, you'd see his little face turning
in my direction, and his eyes would open wide and he'd stop
crying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Months after Tyler died, two different Medicaid cards and a HIP
membership in his name arrived in the mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
