<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIPLAGAT'S RUN AT RECORD IS ILL-TIMED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DALZIEL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everything was in place Sunday morning for Lornah
Kiplagat to begin her quest for a third straight L.A. Marathon
title.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Kenyan woke up at 5:30 a.m., had a bowl of
cereal and washed down a bagel with some tea. More importantly,
Kiplagat was physically ready to take on the 26.2-mile course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling absolutely OK,'' she said. ``I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Kiplagat, everything didn't turn out OK.
</P>
<P>
   Right before she hit the 10th mile, Kiplagat came to a complete
stop on Olympic Boulevard. She bent over and put her hands on her
knees. A few seconds later, she slowly started walking, but she
wasn't going forward. Instead she was making her way to the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplagat sat there on the curb, spitting up phlegm and refusing
water from various on-lookers.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after being taken to her downtown hotel, she would find
out she was coming down with bronchitis. Kiplagat's vision of
becoming the first three-time winner in the 14-year history of the
race vanished before her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started the race not feeling any problems,'' Kiplagat said.
``I had no problems with my legs. The first two or three miles I
felt good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed they (the leaders in the pack) were using was
perfect. I thought it would be a perfect time to run a good race,
and I'm absolutely sure I would break 2:30:00.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Kiplagat reached the fourth mile, the symptoms hit her,
and it was downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the fourth mile it was hard for me to breathe,'' she
said. ``I couldn't understand. Then at the sixth mile I was
coughing; then I started coughing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the seventh mile it was hard for me to breathe and I
continued to cough. I've seen it before and I didn't want to take a
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Kiplagat felt this way was in 1997 at the Chicago
Marathon. But in the Windy City, the flu-like symptoms didn't begin
until halfway through the race, but she finished.
</P>
<P>
   Barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was just my muscles getting tired,'' she
recalled. ``I finished, but I was in a daze when I went through the
finish line and then I collapsed and was unconscious for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sunday) I realized I saw the same thing happening and I
didn't want to take a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in front of the few dozen media members after the race,
Kiplagat kept a positive attitude about not finishing the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I be angry,'' she said about pulling out. ``This is
just beginning; I'm not even halfway in my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the human body and we have to accept what happens.
This is something that I didn't expect, so why should I be angry? I
have no problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Marathon president Bill Burke expects Kiplagat to be ready
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lornah has carved herself a very special place in this history
of the marathon,'' Burke said. ``Like she said, she's young, and I
expect her to be back here and win it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
