A0052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      03-14 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MEDIA FAULT `60 MINUTES' FOR NANNY REPORT  
 A WRITER WITH A PAST TURNS TO ADVERTISING  
 THE CELEBRITY AUTHOR WHO SAT AND WROTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The so-called Nanny murder stirred widespread debate in 1997,
especially after Louise Woodward, a young British woman accused of
killing an infant in her charge, was freed by a judge after being
convicted of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the controversy was back in full force, especially in
Boston, where the trial took place, after CBS' ``60 Minutes''
broadcast a two-segment report on the case that raised questions
about whether the prosecution had even identified the correct cause
of death.
</P>
<P>
   The ``60 Minutes'' report, presented by Mike Wallace, introduced
a medical expert, Dr. Floyd Gillis, chief of neuropathology at
Children's Hospital in Los Angeles, who declared that Matthew
Eappen, the 8-month-old victim, did not die of shaken-baby
syndrome, as had been asserted during the trial, but was strangled.
He also suggested that the baby showed signs of ``serial abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The report set off a flood of further coverage, some of it
critical, especially from The Boston Globe and The Boston Herald.
The news department of the CBS station in Boston, WBZ, held a
discussion with Wallace, which several people called combative, the
day after the report was broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Bogdanich, one of the producers of the report, said on
Friday that ``60 Minutes'' had anticipated some heated reaction
because ``we were saying everyone in the case was wrong and a lot
of people have their careers invested in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   A major criticism was that the report did not adequately
identify a doctor who supported Gillis' findings, Dr. Marvin
Nelson. He is chief of radiology at the same hospital and was a
paid consultant for the defense in the case. Wallace did in fact
report that Nelson had been in contact with the defense and had not
been called to testify. He said in subsequent interviews that the
report should have noted that the doctor had received $700 for his
consultation.
</P>
<P>
   Boston news reports also cited a letter sent to CBS by 77
doctors who called the strangulation theory ``preposterous'' and
urged the network to apologize to the infant's parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace said Friday that the program would include a
statement backing the report. And Bogdanich noted that the program
had not taken a position that Ms. Woodward was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward's lawyers said they intended to ``investigate the
evidence presented on `60 Minutes.''' How this might affect the
ultimate disposition of the case is unclear. Ms. Woodward, whom
Wallace interviewed for the report, is now studying law in England.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   A Writer With a Past Turns to Advertising
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Shalit, a former associate editor at The New Republic whose
quick rise to prominence as a political reporter was halted by
charges of plagiarism, has found a new calling: advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Ms. Shalit, 28, who left The New Republic at the
end of January, began her new job helping to develop ad-campaign
strategies at Mad Dogs and Englishmen, an advertising agency in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shalit said one of the main reasons she decided to change
careers was a realization that the charges of plagiarism leveled at
her in August 1994, and again in June 1995, ``would be a data point
about me as long as I stayed in journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Those accusations were based on a close resemblance between
several passages and sentences in articles she wrote and in
articles by other reporters about the same subjects. At the time,
Ms. Shalit said she had confused her typewritten notes with
articles downloaded from the Lexis-Nexis database.
</P>
<P>
   The New Republic printed apologies in both incidents and at the
end of 1995, after a critique she wrote about affirmative action at
The Washington Post and continued criticism over the incidents of
plagiarism, Ms. Shalit took a six-month leave of absence.
</P>
<P>
   When she returned in 1996, she moved away from the often
scathing critiques of Washington institutions and people that had
earned her a reputation as one journalism's rising stars and a
lucrative contract with GQ magazine. Instead, she began writing
cultural criticism, book reviews and trend pieces, and maintained
generally low visibility.
</P>
<P>
   But her case drew revived attention last spring when another New
Republic writer, Stephen Glass, was found to have fabricated large
parts of articles he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   So, Ms. Shalit said, she decided it was time to make a fresh
start in ``a field where I could use of all my talents and be
judged for who I am instead of on the basis of mistakes I made when
I was a dippy 23-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lane, the editor of The New Republic, refused to comment
on Ms. Shalit's departure. But Leon Wieseltier, the literary
editor, said she had left the magazine of her own accord and
expressed confidence that Ms. Shalit had put the incidents of
plagiarism behind her. ``If I thought that she hadn't paid her
dues, I would never have had her write for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG
</P>
<P>
   The Celebrity Author Who Sat and Wrote
</P>
<P>
   It's become common to assume that celebrity authors rarely write
more than the autograph in their books.
</P>
<P>
   So even a veteran publisher like Esther Margolis of Newmarket
Press paused when approached with a manuscript for her independent
publishing house from the actor Gene Hackman and his co-author, Dan
Lenihan, who had worked together in Santa Fe, N.M., for three years
on ``Black Star Rising,'' a novel about early 1800s pirates and
shipwrecks and the requisite wood-splintering storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this for real?'' Ms. Margolis recalled asking the author's
agent, Noah Lukeman. ``I'm a small publisher and I don't do much
fiction. And here was fiction that appeared to be very commercially
viable with a bona fide movie star as an author.''
</P>
<P>
   After a trip to Santa Fe in January to meet with the first-time
authors, Hackman, 69, and Lenihan, 53, an underwater archaeologist
with the National Park Service, Ms. Margolis said she was satisfied
that they truly had written the manuscript and were prepared to
submit to editing and rewriting.
</P>
<P>
   Hackman said that he and Lenihan divided up the writing into a
``labor of love,'' and that he worked from the beginning and his
co-author worked from the end.
</P>
<P>
   They chose a rather unconventional approach to publishing, he
said, because ``if we were going to do it, we were going to do it
in a way that we had some control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been involved in the last 40 years in film and theater,''
he continued, ``and I know what it's like to do something under
pressure that you consider to be artistic _ something of value as
opposed to something commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   And that unconventional attitude applies to ghosts of the
literary sort. ``I just couldn't do that,'' Hackman said. ``If you
go to a ghostwriter, how do you go out and publicize it? I just
couldn't. I don't need the money for one thing. You have to be
honest with yourself about what kind of achievements that you come
up with.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel is expected to be published later this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
