<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-LAFONTAINE-NY     03-14 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-LAFONTAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDE WHO RESIGNED TOSSES A BARB AT SCHROEDER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Oskar Lafontaine, who threw the German
government into turmoil on Thursday by quitting as both finance
minister and as chairman of the ruling political party, ended three
days of silence Sunday with a thinly veiled attack on Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for my resignation is the poor teamwork that we
provided in the last few months,'' he said Sunday outside his home
in Saarbruecken, near the French border. ``Teamwork requires that
you watch out for each other and that you stick together,
especially in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he barely mentioned Schroeder, Lafontaine confirmed that
his own brand of left-wing doctrine had become irreconcilable with
Schroeder's pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart isn't traded on the stock market yet, but it has a
home,'' Lafontaine said. ``And it beats to the left.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment was telling. Lafontaine had enraged industry leaders
and investors across Germany and even across much of Europe with
his plans to raise taxes on industry and his campaign to raise
German wage levels, which are already among the world's highest.
</P>
<P>
   After he resigned, the stock market soared more than 200 points
and Europe's new single currency, the euro, enjoyed its biggest
one-day jump against the dollar since its debut on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   As Schroeder struggled this weekend to pull together his new
government, that same split between left-wing traditionalists and
more pro-business modernizers was evident throughout the ruling
Social Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said the split is certain to be Schroeder's greatest
challenge in the months and years ahead. Sunday, the leftists were
clearly on the run and the pragmatists were on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine's two top deputies turned in their resignations. One
of them, Heiner Flassbeck, is an economist who provided Lafontaine
with arguments that the source of unemployment problems had nothing
to do with high wages and almost everything to do with hawkish
monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more pro-business Social Democrats began pushing for
new tax breaks for industry. Wolfgang Clement, premier of the state
of North Rhine-Westphalia, contended that corporate income taxes
ought to be dropped to as low as 28 percent from their current
level of about 50 percent. Bodo Hombach, Schroeder's chief of
staff, said the government would reduce corporate taxes in order to
contribute to ``an enduring relief, particularly to middle-sized
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressures are great. Schroeder campaigned for election on
his pledge to reduce the jobless rate, which has been above 10
percent for years _ a rate for which former Chancellor Helmut Kohl
also failed to reduce. Unemployment has increased slightly in
recent months and the economy has abruptly slowed down once again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the most active and powerful groups within the Social
Democratic Party, including the huge labor unions, are fighting to
prevent any change in the country's almost unparalleled system of
social benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of ``poor teamwork,'' Lafontaine alluded to
complaints from ``the team'' that he was pursuing anti-business
policies. That appeared to be a direct allusion to Schroeder's
angry complaints at a cabinet meeting last Wednesday as well as to
Schroeder's personal attempts to water down plans for increasing
business taxes and shutting down nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were able to cut taxes for small- and medium-sized
companies by five billion marks, the team was discussing whether we
were making policies aimed against industry,'' he said indignantly.
``Work that out for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the election campaign last summer and during their
first five months in power, Schroeder and Lafontaine had portrayed
themselves in countless rallies as a perfect team.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the two were political rivals who had formed a
marriage of convenience.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, relations with Lafontaine deteriorated so badly
that Schroeder was not even able to reach Lafontaine on the
telephone until after he resigned. After Lafontaine spoke Sunday, a
spokesman for Schroeder said only that the chancellor had ``taken
note.''
</P>
</TEXT>
