<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0060 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN     03-14 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA-KENTUCKY: THE NEW CHAPTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA vs. Kentucky. Can't beat that matchup of
traditional college basketball powers.
</P>
<P>
   Except this isn't the men. It's the women who meet tonight in an
NCAA Tournament second-round game at Pauley Pavilion, with the
winner advancing to next weekend's West Regional at the Sports
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup remains attractive, even if it involves two programs
succeeding in the large shadows of their male counterparts, who
have combined for 74 NCAA appearances and 18 national titles, more
than any other two schools.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3-seeded UCLA (24-7) has come further than No.6 Kentucky
(21-10). The Bruins won the Pacific-10 for the first time this
season and their first conference title of any kind in 20 years and
are making their second consecutive NCAA appearance.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, behind Maylana Martin's 18 points and LaCresha
Flannigan's 16 points, the Bruins beat Wisconsin-Green Bay 76-69.
</P>
<P>
   In Martin, the conference Player of the Year and third-team
All-American with an 18.5-point average, they have a legitimate
go-to player. In Janae Hubbard (12 points, 12 rebounds Saturday),
they have a legitimate post player. In Erica Gomez (15 points,
eight assists), they have a true point guard. And in Flannigan,
they have an exciting player who can score and get down the court.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, UCLA beat Kentucky this season 64-54 in the final of the
Rainbow Wahine Classic in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   But Kentucky has made tremendous strides in recent years. It won
20 games for the first time in nine years and is in the tournament
after a 17-year absence. A victory over UCLA will go a long way
toward earning the women more recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lineup has changed,'' Kentucky coach Bernadette Mattox
said. ``Our younger people have matured. Our older people have
matured even more. The play in the SEC has matured us. Because of
the toughness of our schedule (fifth strongest schedule
nationally), it forced us to mature.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the schedule and a ratings percentage index (RPI) of
18, Kentucky regularly has three players scoring in double figures:
forwards Laura Meadows and guards Erica Jackson and Tiffany Wait.
</P>
<P>
   Against Nebraska on Saturday, it had six. It doesn't matter what
defense is thrown at them _ trap, box-and-1, 1-2-2, 2-3, full-court
man _ they can score.
</P>
<P>
   ``(On Saturday) our defense was shaky in the second half,''
Gomez said. ``We have to play 40 minutes against Kentucky, and we
can't have those kind of lapses.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez referred to Wisconsin-Green Bay's 22-9 second-half run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get low and go for 40 minutes,'' UCLA coach Kathy
Olivier said. ``When we get up 18-20 points, we get soft. If we
take breathers, Kentucky will come up after you. We have to make
sure we rebound. Kentucky attacks the glass well, and their guards
penetrate, so we need to contain better from the zone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
