<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HOPE IS LOW AS TALKS RESTART ON KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 17th graf to change date of Solana meeting to SUNDAY.)  (Eds.: See also KOSOVO-BOMBINGS) 
(ms) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The second round of Kosovo peace talks was set for
a desultory start in Paris on Monday with few in the Clinton
administration predicting success.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the grand ceremony that opened the first round of
negotiations in the French town of Rambouillet, Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright had no plans to go to Paris, her aides said.
She invested substantial personal capital in the talks last month,
only to see them end in virtual collapse.
</P>
<P>
   And after watching its diplomatic offensive of the last 10 days,
involving Bob Dole and Richard C. Holbrooke, fade without result,
the Clinton administration was downplaying the final stage of the
talks. The negotiations are resuming as bloodshed continues and
even escalates in Kosovo, where marketplace bombs killed seven
people and wounded 58 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus in Washington is that there is little chance of
reaching an agreement,'' a senior official said. The Albanians'
refusal to sign the accord so far, the stubborn Serb refusal to
countenance foreign troops in Kosovo and the increasing violence
apparently have shifted the mood in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear what the administration's strategy was to
resolve the conflict if, as is currently expected, the talks end
after several days.
</P>
<P>
   The best that the administration hoped to extract from Paris was
a &QL; 
signature from the ethnic Albanians on the plan presented at
Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   The peace plan calls for a three-year interim period of autonomy
for Kosovo, for the withdrawal of Serbian forces and for the
disarming of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which has been fighting
for the independence of Kosovo, which is ruled by Serbia but
dominated by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But while the likelihood of an agreement from the ethnic
Albanian delegation appeared more likely than in the last two
weeks, it was still not certain they would sign on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to think they are going to sign,'' an adviser to the
ethnic Albanians said, choosing his words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   One promising point, diplomats said, was that Hashim Thaci, the
leader of the delegation and key member of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, arrived in Paris for the talks. He had eluded Western
officials in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of the peace plan by the ethnic Albanians is the
critical step before NATO can threaten a tough bombing campaign of
the Serbs if the Government of Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav
leader, does not also accept the proposal _ and the 26,000 allied
peacekeepers to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that after the Paris talks, they
expected the focus to move to Belgrade where Milosevic remains as
recalcitrant as ever.
</P>
<P>
   But the options for forcing a peace plan looked so grim that one
senior administration official suggested that it might take another
massacre in Kosovo to galvanize momentum for a meaningful threat of
NATO airstrikes against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may turn out that we may need another Srebrenica before we &QL; 
have a Dayton,'' said the official, reviewing the options on
condition of anonymity. ``But wasn't Racak sufficient?'' The
massacre at Srebrenica in 1995 of Bosnian Muslims by Serbian forces
led to NATO air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs which in turn
enabled Holbrooke to build on earlier groundwork and organize talks
at Dayton, Ohio, that ended the 1992-95 war.
</P>
<P>
   A massacre in the Kosovo village of Racak of more than 40 ethnic
Albanians by Serbian forces in January spurred the current efforts
of Ms. Albright to persuade NATO to authorize air strikes against
the Serbs if they reject a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   When the ethnic Albanians failed to agree to the peace plan, the
NATO threat against Milosevic was vitiated. As the president of
Yugoslavia, Milosevic is the leader of the two remaining Yugoslav
republics, Serbia and Montenegro. Kosovo is a southern province of
Serbia where ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general of NATO, Javier Solana, was in Washington
Sunday conferring with the administration's national security
adviser, Samuel R. Berger, and was expected to meet with Ms.
Albright Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Solana, authorized by NATO in late January to unleash air
strikes against Milosevic if he did not agree to a peace
settlement, is reported to be disturbed about the credibility of
NATO as the threats of air strikes have lost their punch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Holbrooke was sitting with Milosevic last week in
Belgrade telling him that if he did not agree to a peace settlement
NATO air strikes would result. Just at that time, American
diplomats who had been evacuated from Belgrade two weeks weeks
earlier because of the possibility of strikes were returning to
their posts.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were also perturbed about
events on the ground in Kosovo, where Serbian security police and
Yugoslav soldiers were on the march and where the increasingly
well-armed Kosovo Liberation Army were getting restless.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Milosevic appeared to be thumbing his nose once
again at the West with an extraordinarily long news broadcast on
Serbian state-controlled television.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than an hour of the program, which has been extended
frequently in recent days, was taken up with anti-NATO propaganda,
including such slogans as ``No NATO, we will fight NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of the hysteria, there were laudatory
interviews with five waiters who were brought from neighboring
Macedonia to Belgrade as heroes because they claimed they had
beaten up NATO soldiers who had become drunk in their bar in the
Macedonian capital, Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand NATO soldiers are in Macedonia ready for quick
deployment to Kosovo if a peace settlement is reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
