<SLUG> BC-NY-PARADE-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 ARRESTED AS GAYS ARE ORDERED OUT OF ST. PATRICK'S PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until the moment the whistle blew, Brendan Fay said
with tears rolling down his face, he held out hope that a showdown
would be averted, that his exclusion would not be made palpable.
</P>
<P>
   But when the first St. Patrick's Day Parade in the Bronx in 70
years got under way at noon Sunday in the Throgs Neck section, and
Fay's group of gay and lesbian Irish-Americans, the Lavender and
Green Alliance, stepped in to march, it became clear that no
welcome would be extended.
</P>
<P>
   Police stepped in, too _ acting, they said, on instructions from
the parade's organizers, the Throgs Neck Benevolent Association _
and told the group to step out of the parade line.
</P>
<P>
   Some did; Fay and five others, including City Councilwoman
Christine Quinn and state Sen. Thomas Duane, both openly gay
Democrats who represent parts of Manhattan, did not. All six were
arrested, charged with disorderly conduct, issued summonses and
released.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx parade thus followed the example of the annual St.
Patrick's Day Parade along Fifth Avenue in Manhattan, which has
prohibited gay organizations from marching under their own banners
since 1991. This year's Fifth Avenue parade is to be held on St.
Patrick's Day, Wednesday. The organizers of the Bronx parade
decided to march earlier to avoid a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Lavender and Green Alliance said they would not
have tried to march in the Bronx had they not been invited. But an
invitation from the parade's organizers was abruptly revoked on
Thursday, Fay said, after numerous church groups and the Ancient
Order of Hibernians of Bronx County said they would pull out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was heartbreaking, devastating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fay, the founder of the Lavender and Green Alliance, and other
advocates for gay issues said police officials told them that
Patrick Devine, the parade chairman who issued the original
invitation, had received death threats. A police spokesman said he
could not confirm that report.
</P>
<P>
   Fay sought support from numerous elected officials and religious
leaders. Some agreed with him: Bronx Borough President Fernando
Ferrer withdrew from the parade, as did the city's public advocate,
Mark Green, and the city's comptroller, Alan Hevesi. But when
parade organizers would not budge, the alliance decided to march
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Devine could not be reached for comment Sunday, but other
members of the Throgs Neck Benevolent Association tried to downplay
the controversy. Some insisted that the group had never been
invited at all. ``There was a miscommunication,'' said Karin
O'Connor, a member who was involved in the organizing.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Hibernians stayed away from the parade, but
representatives of the organization could not be reached for
comment Sunday. Many churches and Catholic school groups did
participate, as did the Emerald Societies of the Police and Fire
Departments, more than 30 other groups and a total of about 2,000
people, under the watchful eye of several hundred police officers.
Members of most of the groups said they supported the parade
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they wanted to march,'' it would be fine, Fran Mahoney, a
district leader for the local Democratic organization, the Chippewa
Democratic Club, said of the gay group. ``But not under a banner _
it's a Christian community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Connor shared her view. ``We're celebrating a Catholic
holy day,'' Ms. O'Connor said. ``We're marching for St. Patrick,
and people who march should be in line with what we're celebrating
_ Irish pride and Irish Catholic pride.'' An openly gay group, she
said, did not fit in at a Catholic celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The several thousand spectators, wearing green hats and scarves
and carnations, seemed more divided. Mary Ellen O'Brien, a Yonkers
resident, said the pressure to rescind the invitation was
disgraceful. ``Who would it have hurt to let them march, if it
makes them feel better about themselves?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   But Rocky Roff, a 48-year-old neighborhood resident, said he did
not think a parade was a place for a political statement. ``There
are other places to air your laundry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throgs Neck is a tightly knit neighborhood of mostly Irish and
Italian residents. At a morning Mass at St. Benedict's Church, more
than 1,000 residents heard the pastor praise the community because
it has changed so little over the decades. It is the kind of place,
residents said, where children grow up, marry and return to live.
</P>
<P>
   After the parade along East Tremont Avenue, many of the marchers
crowded into Charlie's Inn, where the beer and whiskey flowed like
the sentiment, and Irish waltzes sent elderly couples onto the
dance floor. March organizers said they were so pleased with the
march that they would have another one next year.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, a smaller crowd attended Ferrer's previously
scheduled celebration of Irish heritage and culture. There,
Lavender and Green members said they, too, would be at next year's
march _ with, they hoped, the approval of march organizers.
</P>
</TEXT>
