<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-OWNERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WORD YET ON NFL EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The NFL owners apparently do not have the hurry-up
offense in their playbook.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting for 90 minutes or so Sunday morning, the league's
expansion committee adjourned without taking any vote or making any
recommendation on a proposed 32nd team in either Houston or Los
Angeles. The committee will convene again today with the hope of
having something to present to the full ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, it's quite likely everyone will leave here only
slightly further along in the process.
</P>
<P>
   If Los Angeles, as anticipated, is named as the location for
team 32, it likely will be one of the more vague decisions in
sports history. No ownership group or stadium site will be
attached. Neither Michael Ovitz and Carson nor Ed Roski, Eli Broad
and the New Coliseum will be given the league's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there will be a list of conditions longer than the
Starr Report _ most of them having to do with money _ that Los
Angeles owners must meet within a league-set time frame. Think
Christmas. If the stipulations aren't met, the opportunity would
likely revert to ready-to-go Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing you can draw is that the most we'll get out of
this week is the selection of the city,'' NFL spokesman Joe Browne
said. ``I don't see, based on the discussion, that we'll (select) a
stadium or an owner. It's too big a piece to bite off in one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see the league going to one city or the other on an
if-see basis, but it's just speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Goodell, the league's vice president of development, said
there never was a mandate for the league to make a hard decision at
these meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of these meetings (is) to evaluate the proposals we
have and see if we have the best possible solution,'' he said.
``Whatever decision we make will dictate what else we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Los Angeles, the league seems less interested in
what else Ovitz and Roski/Broad have to say at this point as much
as whether there are any other potential bidders out there.
</P>
<P>
   Its list of prospective sites is currently limited to the
Coliseum and Carson, but only because they're closer to breaking
ground, especially the Coliseum. Goodell said the league would
consider another site if the facility could get off the mark
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   If Los Angeles gets the bid, the time frame to fill in the
blanks would be by the end of the year. In the case of Houston,
businessman Robert McNair's bid contains a clause for a new stadium
that must be exercised by Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been working on this for a couple of years, and he's in
it for as long as it takes,'' McNair spokesman Chip Nieves said.
``There's been a lot of speculation about where things are headed,
but (McNair) has been reassured by (the league) that he's not
wasting his time.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NFL attorney Frank Rothman said the Raiders' legal
claim on owning any rights to Los Angeles is not a factor in any
expansion decision. ``We don't think it's a threat in any way,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Browne also said owners received a letter Sunday from a group
interested in an expansion franchise in Anaheim, which the Rams
vacated after the 1994 season. ``But we're not looking at any other
site in Southern California than the two that have been
presented,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
