<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0084 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-14 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS TUTOR GEORGE W. BUSH ON DOMESTIC AND FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ind., Calif.)  (js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE with RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He is the early favorite for the Republican
presidential nomination, but even Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
concedes that his foreign policy experience goes no farther than
Mexico. Kosovo? Not even on the radar screen. And he has never had
to worry about the future of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing to fill in his blank slate on pressing issues of the day
before the campaign swings into full gear, Bush has embarked on a
cram course that could be titled ``What you need to know to run for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning a second term last November, Bush began summoning
dozens of the nation's brightest thinkers around a table in the
Governor's Mansion for sober-minded tutorials. Politicians in both
parties said they had never seen such a comprehensive and elaborate
undertaking, particularly this early in a campaign. There may never
have been a ``serious'' candidate who needed it more.
</P>
<P>
   The endeavor is intended to counter what are widely seen as
among Bush's biggest vulnerabilities: that he lacks experience
beyond Texas and that he has not articulated a grand view of what
he would do in the White House. It was no accident that in their
announcement speeches last week, Elizabeth Dole and former Gov.
Lamar Alexander of Tennessee emphasized their credentials on
national issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's visitors defended the governor as a quick study. ``Nobody
knows everything about what goes on in the world, so you've got to
find out,'' George Shultz, secretary of state under President
Ronald Reagan, said recently as he sat back in his rocking chair
with a State Department seal at his office at Stanford University,
where he is a fellow at the Hoover Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ability to draw big names _ all of whom, in the
beginning, paid their own way to Austin _ is not simply testament
to the governor's personal appeal or skills at outreach.
Self-interest is at play as well: Academics like to be asked for
advice, particularly by a politician who is leading in the polls
and who might someday be in a position to appoint them to
something. What for Bush is a tutorial might serve as an audition
for his tutors.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the prestige factor. ``They come back and say,
`Well, I was just down in Austin,''' said Martin Anderson, an
economist at Stanford University and an official in the Reagan
administration. Participants have been plucked from around the
country, but there is particularly heavy representation from the
Hoover Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Al Hubbard, an Indianapolis business executive who coordinated
the early meetings for Bush, said people were invited to Austin
``under the condition that they would be supportive of him'' and
all but one person accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The deep conversations about policy are all the more surprising
because _ fairly or unfairly _ Bush is known more for his hands-on
governing style than for his intellect. He has never been known for
savoring the minutiae of policy like President Clinton. ``Having
known George as a student, I'm shocked, and his professors would be
shocked,'' said Hubbard, a classmate of Bush at the Harvard
Business School. ``He wasn't a great student. But he's the most
conscientious politician I've ever worked with.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence B. Lindsey, a former member of the Federal Reserve
Board who was on Reagan's Council of Economic Advisers and is
Bush's chief outside economic adviser, described him as ``a very
good and patient student.''
</P>
<P>
   The sessions started informally after the election and they have
become more organized in the past few months. Besides Lindsey, who
invites economic experts to the meetings and structures the agenda,
Bush has named Mayor Stephen Goldsmith of Indianapolis to preside
over domestic policy, while Condoleezza Rice, the provost of
Stanford University, oversees foreign and military policy. Josh
Bolten, an international trade lawyer in the Bush administration,
recently signed on as overall policy coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings are often convened in a formal, deep blue dining
room in the Governor's Mansion, and sometimes in a smaller, sunny
conservatory. They usually include just over half a dozen experts
in a field and are scheduled for three hours, but often last
longer.
</P>
<P>
   To all but the most devout policy wonks, the conversations can
be eye glazing. According to an agenda of a health care briefing
that Goldsmith presided over on Feb. 18: Six minutes were allocated
for introductory remarks; 25 minutes for a discussion of the
financing system and the delivery systems, with such topics as
``trends in patient care: acute to chronic conditions; diffusion of
technology, rise of pharmaceutical therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a 30-minute discussion of philosophy, including ``What
level of care are we prepared to guarantee?'' Then a 50-minute
examination of the uninsured, followed by 50 minutes on the
``anxious insured.'' Goldsmith was to close with a 20-minute review
of matters for further discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Several participants said in interviews that the discussions
were framed less around how the governor should respond to a
particular question on the campaign trail and more around how he
would tackle the matter as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like a very interactive seminar than people sitting
around giving formal talks,'' Ms. Rice said. The governor, she
said, ``is not somebody who puts on airs or attempts to appear
imperial, so there's a kind of easiness about the conversation.
Sometimes you get a bunch of foreign policy experts together and
they talk on a plane where nobody asks the basic questions. He'll
drive you back to the basic question.''
</P>
<P>
   When the end of the Cold War came up, she said, Bush asked:
``What does America's role really mean to you? What did we mean
when we talk about the expansion of NATO? What is the military of
the future going to look like?''
</P>
<P>
   In conversations about economics, participants said, Bush always
returns to job creation. ``What can I do to make higher paying
jobs?'' said John B. Taylor, an economics professor at Stanford.
``That's a bottom line for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts said Bush appears confident and does not pretend to
know more than he does. Like Ronald Reagan, Anderson said, ``He has
no problem talking to people who were smarter and quicker. There
are other candidates who don't like to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   While they described Bush as smart and disciplined, many
participants said he obviously still had a lot to learn. ``He still
has some growing to do,'' said Michael Boskin, a Stanford
University economist and former chief economic adviser to President
Bush, who organized some of the early meetings. ``But he's become
the most impressive presidential or potential presidential
candidate that I've seen in decades.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to portray himself as more conservative than his father,
Bush has stayed clear, at least publicly, of many of the former
president's top advisers. Even after hours of meetings, several
participants who know his father were hard-pressed to distinguish
the philosophies of the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the governor was more conservative than his father,
Shultz replied, ``Out of the blue I would say that. But then if you
said `Why?' I wouldn't have a good answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The visits have ignited a firestorm of gossip in academic and
political circles about how people are angling for posts in a Bush
administration. But participants said the preening is kept to a
minimum, though experts sometimes compete over who brings the most
colorful graphics. ``You could think about the jobs available:
budget director or treasury secretary or national security adviser.
I haven't participated in lists of names of who would be good for
things,'' Taylor said. Referring to Bush, he added, ''I don't know
if he's done that. He's probably thought about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush's visitors do not dare speculate openly about their
futures, they clearly delight in the attention. When Ms. Rice, a
national security official in President Bush's administration, was
shown an editorial in the Stanford University student newspaper
with the headline ``Secretary of State?'' she gasped, ``My God!''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Ms. Rice, who is stepping down as provost,
retreated to a position of studied nonchalance. ``Certainly,
nobody's asked me to be secretary of state,'' she said. ``And I'm a
terrible long-term planner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
