<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTONCOLL-TENNESSEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE WOMEN NOW MUST COMPETE WITH THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After qualifying for the National Collegiate Athletic
Association women's basketball tournament for the first time,
eighth-seeded Boston College was riding an emotional high. And with
a 72-59 victory over ninth-seeded Ohio State on Saturday night at
the Thompson Bolling Arena in Knoxville, Tenn., before 11,190
screaming fans, the Eagles (22-7) gained the confidence necessary
to play a significant role in the outcome of the East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Except the Eagles now face the difficult task of continuing
their unexpected run Monday night by upsetting top-seeded
Tennessee, the three-time defending champion. The Lady Vols (29-2)
trounced their first-round opponent, Appalachian State, by 113-54
on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The winner advances to Greensboro, N.C., for next week's East
Regional semifinals and finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message all week was, `Don't be happy just to be here, come
to win,''' said Coach Cathy Inglese, who is in her sixth year at
the Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Brianne Stepherson, a guard who scored 11 points on 4-for-8
shooting against Ohio State, is taking a more conservative approach
to Boston College's biggest game of its program's 27-year
existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an incredible team and a great coach,'' Stepherson
said of Tennessee. ``They have 16 possible all-Americans on that
team. They basically have the type of status that we want, so we're
going to come out and play our hardest. And no matter what the
outcome of the game, hopefully we'll just come away with something
that we've learned and we'll get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Having held its opponents to 40 percent shooting this season,
Boston College will have to continue that performance in the second
round of the tournament. In addition, the Eagles must avoid being
pressured by Tennessee from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols opened up against Appalachian State with a 19-0
run and built a 53-19 lead at halftime. They forced the
Mountaineers to commit 33 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Against Ohio State, Boston College turned the ball over eight
times in the first eight minutes, prompting Inglese to call a
timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still very confident because there were some things that
we just were not executing,'' Inglese said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we'd be successful if we got the ball to Alissa and
really cut down their post play,'' she said of Alissa Murphy, who
is averaging 15.9 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese must also find a way to contain the Tennessee
all-American Chamique Holdsclaw, who became the NCAA tournament's
career-leading scorer with 405 points, surpassing the former Lady
Vol Bridgette Gordon, who had 388 points from 1986 to 1989.
Holdsclaw also surpassed Cheryl Miller as the tournament's career
leader in rebounds with 172.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's victory was not entirely a celebration for Tennessee.
The sophomore guard Semeka Randall injured an ankle while driving
to the basket in the second half. Her status for Monday night was
not known. ``She's got a pretty tough sprain there,'' Coach Pat
Summitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the season, Boston College has faced adversity of its
own, but has managed to persevere.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Bouchard, a starting guard who is Boston College's leading
scorer, sustained a season-ending knee injury in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Becky Gottstein sprained her ankle during the Big East
Conference tournament. She did not return to practice until
Thursday, but came off the bench Saturday night to register a
career-high 23 points on 10-of-14 shooting and get 12 rebounds
against Ohio State. Boston College is 7-2 when Gottstein has led or
tied for the team lead in scoring.
</P>
</TEXT>
