<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-TORRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE PLANS TO MEET WITH HIS YANKEES' PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Yankees Manager Joe Torre is expected to meet
with his players Monday, the first time he will speak to the team
collectively since he was found to have prostate cancer last week.
Others in the organization believe he will give the players the
details of his treatment, and an estimate of how long he will be
away from the team.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees officials have been protective of Torre's privacy, at
his request, and most of those who were asked about whether Torre
would appear at the park _ including the coach Don Zimmer and
General Manager Brian Cashman _ either declined to answer or
responded coyly. However, two members of the organization said
Torre wants to speak to the players, and a sign was posted on a
clubhouse wall noting boldly that players will be required to be
dressed in uniform and in the clubhouse at 2:15 p.m. Monday,
unusually early for a night game. Cashman said, ``If he is planning
on being there, he could always change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Zimmer, ``This is Joe's team and he's going to do what he
wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre has sought multiple opinions as he considers his treatment
options; he used George Steinbrenner's private jet to visit the
Washington University hospital in St. Louis on Friday for tests.
Others in the organization continue to say he is leaning toward
surgical removal of the cancer. If Torre has surgery, he will
probably be out for anywhere from three weeks to three months,
according to estimates of club officials and friends. If Torre made
a swift recovery, he would still miss the first week of the regular
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
