<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BRADLEY-COLUMN15-     03-14 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BRADLEY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kentucky shows why its champion
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ This isn't the best team. It wasn't the best team
a year ago. It is simply the hardest team to beat, a team that has
an otherworldly grasp on the concept of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not national champions for nothing,'' said Ryan
Robertson, the Kansas guard. The Jayhawks nearly ended the Kentucky
reign Sunday, leading by five with 89 seconds left. But then it
happened, same as it happened to Duke and Stanford and Utah last
March. The Wildcats tied it in regulation, won in overtime, marched
ever onward.
</P>
<P>
   ''A heartbreaking experience for us,'' said Roy Williams, the
Kansas coach. ''We were so, so close.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have been similarly close these past two seasons, but no
opponent has yet managed to finish off these Wildcats. A senior,
Scott Padgett was playing his 14th NCAA Tournament game Sunday.
Likewise a senior, Wayne Turner was playing his 19th.
Over141/2-minute span that carried deep into OT, the two scored all
30 of Kentucky's points. Said Padgett: ''We sort of willed
ourselves to this win.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first postseason meeting of these hallowed
programs, and for nearly 39 minutes Kansas was the more resourceful
team. Robertson and Jeff Boschee kept air-mailing treys, and there
were moments when it seemed that even the Wildcats believed this
day, at long last, would be someone else's. But only moments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Down five with a minute to play, a lot of teams would fold,''
Padgett said. ''But we've been there before.''
</P>
<P>
   Five points down, time flying. Turner drove, same as he'd driven
against Duke's Steve Wojciechowksi in epochal comeback a year ago.
Fouled, Turner made a pair. Kentucky chose not to foul, defended
expertly, forced Boschee to take an ungainly banker as the shot
clock ran down. Jamaal Magliore rebounded. Turner drove again --
''I was glad to see they weren't taking a three,'' Williams said --
and missed. Magliore won the scramble, shoveling the ball to
Padgett on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   It was Padgett's three that brought down Duke in St. Petersburg,
and here he was again. ''I was already thinking about the shot
before I got the ball,'' he said. Kenny Gregory ran at him. Padgett
pumped. Gregory flew past. Padgett took one dribble, stepped behind
the line, drained the trey.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen seconds remained, time enough for Kansas. Robertson
broached the lane and heard Gregory calling. Said Robertson: ''I
misread the play. I thought we'd have a layup. If I had it to do
again, I'd have taken the shot myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Magliore closed on Gregory, turning the presumed layup into a
contested 10-footer that flew 11 feet. Overtime. Forced to choose,
Kansas chose incorrectly. At such times, Kentucky seems never to
misread anything. Kentucky just knows.
</P>
<P>
   ''This tournament is hard,'' Williams said. ''If (Robertson)
could have made that play, a different decision, we'd be talking
about it years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked about luck, about the twists of fortune that keep
leaving Kansas a red-eyed March loser, the same twists that never
befall Kentucky. ''When you're sitting by yourself you call it bad
luck,'' Williams said. ''But I'm realistic enough to know that
Scott Padgett made a heck of a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
