</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon takes third Atlanta win
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The skies above Atlanta Motor Speedway eventually
opened up at about 6 p.m. Sunday, about the same time it seemed
NASCAR's spotlight would finally shine on someone other than Jeff
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With less than 30 laps remaining in the Cracker Barrel Old
Country Store 500, however, the clouds returned and so did Gordon's
reign on the Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the two-time defending points champion, led 56 of the
final 69 laps to win his second race in a row _ and third overall _
at AMS. His previous victories in Atlanta came in the Purolator 500
in March 1995 and November's NAPA 500, the 1998 season-finale.
</P>
<P>
   After rain delayed the race for one hour, 40 minutes, Gordon,
points leader Mike Skinner and pole-sitter Bobby Labonte dominated
the 43-car field on the 1.54-mile oval, combining to lead 291 of
325 laps.
</P>
<P>
   The final few laps were completed under lights, because rain
started to fall again at the Hampton facility. Two of the six
caution flags during the race were because of precipitation on the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the lights came on that thing was a rocket,'' Gordon said
of his No. 24 Chevrolet. ``We weren't the best car all day long,
but by the end _ when it counts _ we were. We just hope we can be
consistent, and right now having two wins is big. It'll carry some
momentum the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon pulled away from Labonte in the final 25 laps, beating
him to the finish line by 2.537 seconds. Mark Martin finished
third, while Jeff Burton and Dale Jarrett were fourth and fifth,
respectively. Skinner, who had engine problems late in the race,
dropped to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that (Gordon's) car just got better toward the end,''
Labonte said. ``He probably took care of it during the first part
of the race. He was steady. I saw him back there all day. It was
probably the best car when it counted.''
</P>
<P>
   After Gordon took the lead from Labonte on lap 257, he led until
the leaders made their final pit stop 41 laps later. But Labonte,
who entered the race having won three of the last five Cup events
at AMS, was faster off pit road, grabbing the lead from Gordon one
lap later. Labonte's lead grew to as much as 50 yards during the
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Labonte) got up there in front of me the last time after the
pit stop and I thought we were in big trouble,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   But Labonte says he immediately knew that his No. 18 Pontiac was
in trouble after taking only two new tires during the pit stop.
Gordon also took only two tires during refueling, but he says his
car was handling much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there at the end, it was just one of those deals where
our two tires didn't work out,'' Labonte said. ``I'm not very good
at that anyway. I can't ever make two tires work. I just didn't run
the right line for a few laps and Jeff made up a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also made up time when Labonte got slowed behind the
lapped No. 98 car of Rick Mast with only 22 laps remaining. When
Mast didn't move near the apron to allow Labonte to pass, Gordon
passed Labonte on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   After all of the lead-lap cars made their final pit stop by lap
311 -- Bill Elliott and Sterling Marlin were the last to stop after
running low on fuel -- Gordon had the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when you work real hard all day to get your
car right,'' Gordon said. ``When you do, you want to show everyone,
especially a car without a sponsor on it. (Mast) was running really
strong at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I feel bad for Bobby because he was cheated a little
bit. I wouldn't have closed on him if he hadn't been held up. In
fact, I couldn't have taken the lead. But lapped traffic is a part
of racing. I got held up a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been a few weeks since Gordon and his Rainbow Warriors
last saw victory lane. After winning the season-opening Daytona 500
on Feb. 14, Gordon finished 39th at Rockingham after the engine in
his car blew up. Last week at Las Vegas, he finished third behind
Burton and his brother, Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
