<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SWEET16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High seeds' path blocked to Sweet 16
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A classic between two of college basketball's heavyweights put
the perfect ending to the first week of the NCAA Tournament on
Sunday as Kentucky outlasted Kansas 92-88 in overtime in the second
round of the Midwest Regional in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (27-8), the defending national champions, advance
to this week's regional semifinals in St. Louis, where they meet
10th seed Miami of Ohio, which stunned second-seeded Utah 66-58.
</P>
<P>
   Even though all four top seeds advanced to Sweet 16, five
double-digit seeds _ Gonzaga, Southwest Missouri State, Purdue,
Miami of Ohio and Oklahoma _ beat the odds and will crash the
party.
</P>
<P>
   A quick look ahead:
</P>
<P>
   EAST: Duke's path was made considerably easier Sunday by two
upsets in Boston. Third seed Cincinnati, the only team to beat the
Blue Devils this season, was upset by sixth seed Temple 64-54. Then
second seed Miami of Florida was knocked off by 10th seed Purdue
73-63. The Blue Devils (34-1) will be the only ranked team in the
regional semifinals when they take on 12th seed Southwest Missouri
State Friday in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH: This was the only regional holding to form, with the top
four seeds advancing. No. 1 seed Auburn (29-3) won a tough game
with Oklahoma State on Saturday and will have its hands full with
Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd, the Ohio State backcourt, Thursday
in Knoxville. Maryland (28-5) vs. St. John's (27-8) could be one of
the tournament's best games.
</P>
<P>
   WEST: Tenth seed Gonzaga (27-6), which upset second seed
Stanford on Saturday, next meets Florida (22-8), which is in the
Sweet 16 for only the fourth time. But the team to beat in Phoenix
will still be top seed UConn (30-2), which is going for its first
Final Four. The Huskies must first beat surprising Iowa (20-9), on
an emotional high as it plays for coach Tom Davis, who is leaving
at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   MIDWEST: No. 13 seed Oklahoma (21-10), the last at-large team to
get a bid in the tournament, played its way into the Sweet 16 by
beating N.C. Charlotte 85-72 and will face top seed Michigan State
(28-5), which rallied to beat Mississippi 74-66.
</P>
</TEXT>
