<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BISHER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon gets a grip at AMS
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forty-three cars started the race and the survivors
were driving into the twilight in the 500-mile test of man and
engine, named for a chain of roadside food stops called Cracker
Barrel. There is some speculation that the Indian burial ground at
the north end of Atlanta Motor Speedway has cast a spell over this
stock car Taj Mahal. The November race, known as the NAPA, wasn't
finished until near midnight because of foul weather. The race last
March, known as the Primestar, was refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the gentlemen didn't start their engines until an
hour and a half after the time advertised. A pea soup fog shrouded
the place until after noon. Then the surface had to be dried. These
guys wouldn't put a tire on a racing surface where somebody had
spilled even a teacup of water.
</P>
<P>
   The sky scowled throughout the race, sometimes spitting a few
drops that sent the racers scurrying for the pits. In olden times,
this race probably never would have been finished, but the
entrepreneurial Bruton Smith had thought of everything. The maitre
d' of this shrine of speed installed a lighting system fit to read
by. Otherwise, this would have been a run against darkness as well
as cranky weather.
</P>
<P>
   When this place struggled into life about 40 years ago, it was
hampered by foul weather. Rain turned it into a mud bog. Races were
delayed, postponed or shortened. It was known then as Atlanta
International Raceway, AIR, which some translated to ``Atlanta
International Rainmaker.'' Almost as if by tradition, just as this
race ended and the winner (surprise!), Jeff Gordon, parked in the
winner's circle, a little benedictional shower sprinkled the area.
</P>
<P>
   It seems rather fitting that Jeff Gordon broke into NASCAR
racing in the race that Richard (The King) Petty drove his last, on
this same track, before reconfiguration, in 1992. He finished 31st.
In retrospect, though, it seems now like an unofficial succession
to the throne, for since that time Gordon has won 44 races, been
the Winston Cup champion three times, and married a beauty queen.
He's 27, looks 18, and has the trim frame of an athlete who should
be performing on the centre court at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   He came out of California, stopped over a few years at
Indianapolis, where he became introduced to serious racing, then,
lo and behold, went back and won the Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis
in 1994. Now his address is Mooresville, N.C., where he settled
among the top cats of stock car racing.
</P>
<P>
   Like golf needs Tiger Woods, like baseball needs Kerry Wood,
stock car racing warmly embraces the princely figure of Jeff
Gordon. The old guard is losing its grip, and while their lineage
is following them into the game, the weanling Earnhardts, Pettys,
et al. are not yet far enough from the crib to take up the slack.
Meantime, Dale Earnhardt, Bill Elliott and Darrell Waltrip, three
old standards, are having trouble finding their way to victory
lane.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt won just once last year. Elliott hasn't won in five
years. Waltrip hasn't won since 1992, and harsh as it may seem,
when he goes out now he has about as much chance as Arnold Palmer
has of winning a golf tournament. Earnhardt hit the wall on the
22nd lap Sunday, came back out 136 laps later, and it was sort of
sad to see his No. 3 limping around the oval at the end.
</P>
<P>
   This is Gordon's second winning trip in a row here,
contradicting his conclusion that he has ``not been my best here at
Atlanta.'' He had won the crown jewel, Daytona 500, conked out
early at Rockingham and rebounded with a third at Las Vegas. Still,
he wasn't, and still isn't, the points leader. A refugee from truck
racing, Mike Skinner, came into this race leading, and still does,
with a sixth-place finish. The 39th finish at Rockingham left
Gordon with a tough hill to climb, but he is accustomed to climbing
tough hills, though ``I never really thought of taking up racing as
a career.''
</P>
<P>
   He started slow Sunday, left the dueling to Bobby Labonte, who
has won three times on this track, and Skinner, the trucker. When
the lights came on, it was Gordon's time to shine. In the end, he
led 109 laps, especially No. 325. After which Gordon said, ``It has
been a stellar start to the season,'' and there's no questioning
that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
