<HEADLINE>
ANGELS MENDING FENCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The asymmetrical outfield fence dimensions at
Edison Field were meant to give the ballpark a look of its own and
a flavor of the old-time ballparks. But it also took a toll on the
number of home runs the Anaheim Angels hit last season.
</P>
<P>
   The dimensions in center and the power alley in left-center were
408 feet and 396, respectively. The result was the fewest number of
homers since 1994. Although the Angels used the extra room to hit a
club-record 314 doubles, a number of potential homers found an
outfielder's glove at the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   So the Angels announced Sunday they are moving the fence in to
400 in center and 387 in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``These alterations are something that was a topic of discussion
throughout last season,'' general manager Bill Bavasi said. ``When
the (Anaheim Stadium) renovation was taking place we discussed
leaving available the option of moving the fences forward in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason they didn't just build it that way originally was
because with newly built concourses, they were unsure how the air
currents would flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we built them in, it would be much more difficult to move
them back out,'' Bavasi said. ``Which was a concern not knowing how
the wind would affect fly balls. We didn't want a situation like
Baltimore (Camden Yards).''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: First baseman Mo Vaughn was scratched from
Sunday's game because of a tight right hamstring. Third baseman
Dave Hollins aggravated his left hamstring rounding second base in
the first inning and had to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   Some players have blamed the rash of sore hamstrings on the
infield dirt. ``I can't remember it being that soft,'' said
Hollins, who added his hamstring was ``just sore and he'd be OK in
a couple days.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley (muscle strain upper back/neck) will make his first
spring start Tuesday against the White Sox in Tempe. His catcher
will be Todd Greene (shoulder), making his first appearance behind
the plate this spring.
</P>
<P>
   On Dickson: Jason Dickson, competing for the fifth spot in the
starting rotation, gave up four runs (all earned) and seven hits in
two-plus innings in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little concerned,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``I've seen this guy pitch for two years. I know what he can do.
Today he got his pitches up, and he's down when he's on.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson said he simply ran out of gas in the third inning, when
he gave up three runs without recording an out. Omar Olivares, also
competing for the No. 5 spot, will pitch today at the Angels'
minor-league camp in Mesa. The rest of the team has the day off,
the only full day off all spring.
</P>
<P>
   Roster moves: The Angels are expected to option outfielder Norm
Hutchins to minor-league camp today. Hutchins, one of the best
Angels prospects, impressed Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played as good as anybody in this camp,'' Collins said.
``He's one of the most improved players on this team. He made
tremendous strides at both sides of the plate and in the outfield.
A couple years ago I saw him misjudge three balls in the outfield,
now he's making catches Jim Edmonds makes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels cut six others from their roster Sunday. Pitcher Reid
Cornelius was released, while pitchers Scott Brown, Kevin Lomon and
Paul Menhart, infielder Chuck Abbott and catcher Ben Molina were
returned to minor-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Second baseman Justin Baughman, recovering slowly from
multiple fractures in his left leg, said he'll decide by Wednesday
whether he'll have a second surgery.... The Angels are still
negotiating a multi-year contract with reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa
_ expected to be two years with an option for a third. Hasegawa
signed a one-year deal for $625,000 last week when the deadline
came for renewal of players with zero to three years of
major-league experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
