<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMATCH OF HOLYFIELD-LEWIS ORDERED BY SANCTIONING BODIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Originally slugged as BOX-HOLYFIELD-LENNOX) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The presidents of the three sanctioning bodies for
the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight unification bout
have ordered a rematch within six months. The bout Saturday night
at Madison Square Garden ended in a controversial draw, even though
it appeared that Lewis had clearly controlled the entire fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shame there was so much controversy attached to this
important fight,'' Bob Lee, president of the IBF, told The
Associated Press. ``But we did what we thought was the most
sensible thing by ordering a rematch in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee met with Gilberto Mendoza, president of the WBA, and Jose
Sulaiman of the WBC early Sunday morning, right after the fight,
and decided to order the rematch. Holyfield is the WBA and IBF
champion and Lewis holds the WBC title.
</P>
<P>
   What is not clear is whether a rematch can be scheduled,
considering the difficulty in working out the first bout. Both the
fighters and all the promoters involved are in favor of a rematch,
but that does not mean it will happen.
</P>
<P>
   There might not be enough money in the fight for both the boxers
_ Holyfield received $20 million for Saturday night's fight and
Lewis got $10 million. The rematch clause in Lewis' contract calls
for him to earn $15 million and Holyfield will probably ask for
more than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, Gov. George Pataki said he would ask the New
York State Athletic Commission to look into the controversial draw.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said that his administration has worked hard to bring
championship boxing back to Madison Square Garden, ``but it has to
be done in a way that upholds the integrity of the game and
people's confidence in the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Don King will have to get back the confidence and the
money from somewhere and it will be a tough sell, because it was
not a particularly tantalizing fight and the outcome appeared
tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the fans' reaction to King after the fight on
Saturday night, it will be an uphill struggle. As he was exiting
the main arena to attend the post-fight news conference, someone
from the stands yelled: ``Hey Don! Where are you taking the judges
on vacation?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a reference to the fact that in the past King has taken
the jury members of his federal court trials on vacation or made
them his guests at fights that he promotes.
</P>
<P>
   King said he expects to be made the villain in the controversy,
but he said he had no role in picking or assigning the judges. Each
of the sanctioning organizations selected a judge and the judges
had to be approved by both fighters' camps.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' trainer, Emanuel Steward, said he objected to the judges,
but he would not say which judge or why. Steward said, however,
that he only mentioned his objections within the camp. Frank
Maloney, Lewis' manager, said he didn't have a problem with the
judges when they were first selected.
</P>
<P>
   The fight left unresolved the question of who the next
undisputed heavyweight champion would be, and it put a greater
focus on the subjective nature of scoring by the ringside judges.
And with Lewis clearly controlling the fight from start to finish
and not getting a victory, the public will again call into question
the integrity of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hurts me that this happened in my sport,'' Steward
said. ``People spent millions of dollars on this fight. We owe it
to them to make sure things like this don't happen. I don't take
this lightly. This is a disgrace to boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stanley Christodolou of South Africa scored the fight,
116-113, for Lewis. Judge Eugenia Williams of New Jersey scored the
fight, &QC; 115-113, for Holyfield and judge Larry O'Connell of Britain
scored the fight 115-115. It was one of the most controversial
decisions in a big-time fight in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was interviewed by Fox Sports following the bout,
said she didn't have a problem with her scoring. She was the only
judge to give Holyfield the fifth round, a round in which Lewis
landed a big right hand on the top of Holyfield's head and pinned
him on the ropes with a barrage of unanswered punches for 45
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she based her final score on the number of punches
that Holyfield threw during the fight. According to Compubox punch
statistics, Holyfield landed only 130 of 385 punches, while Lewis
landed 348 of 613 punches. When informed that Holyfield threw fewer
punches than Lewis, Williams said she was merely doing her job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care what the public saw,'' Williams said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fight was broadcast live on TVKO pay-per-view to more than 1
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was in the minority in her view that Holyfield (36-3-1)
won the bout. Even Holyfield's trainer, Don Turner, thought the
fight was a draw. ``I had Evander losing five of the first seven
rounds, but I had him winning the rest of the fight,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, 36, wasn't sure whether it should have been a draw.
``I haven't seen the fight yet,'' he said. ``When I watch it, I'll
let you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said Holyfield did not fight the right fight to beat
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to fight more inside, but he could never get
inside,'' Turner said. ``He was never able to land more than one
punch at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox fights better tall than any fighter I've ever seen. He
leans back more away from punches. He fought a very different fight
than I expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield didn't look to be in good shape as he left the
post-fight news conference early Sunday morning. A doctor gave him
ice for various parts of his aching body and he remained standing
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Turner denied reports that Holyfield was treated early Sunday
morning for injured ribs, but he did confirm that Holyfield
suffered severe cramps in his legs during the bout beginning in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Strategically, Lewis, 33, fought a smart fight. He kept
Holyfield away with his jab and when Holyfield did manage to get
inside, Lewis tied him up so that he couldn't land any punches.
Holyfield also missed on several looping lefts and rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size and the style was too much for him,'' Steward said.
``Evander was missing punches by two feet. That's just Lennox's
size and style.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis (34-1-1) did what he needed to do to walk away with the
undisputed heavyweight title, but he left it in the judges' hands
by not knocking out Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's prediction of a third-round knockout never
materialized, even though he picked up the action more in that
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did predict I would knock him out in the third round,''
Holyfield said. ``I was wrong. Maybe in the next fight.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
