<SLUG> BC-TV-LARROQUETTE-435&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARROQUETTE'S `PAYNE' FOLLOWS A `FAWLTY' FORMULA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Larroquette's name in his new series is Royal Payne.
</P>
<P>
   And he is. The show is ``Payne'' (Monday night on CBS), and
Larroquette plays the ethically impaired proprietor of a seaside
inn.
</P>
<P>
   JoBeth Williams is his wife Constance _ close, I guess, to
constant pain. You almost expect them to have a kid named Stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chambermaid, Breeze (Julie Benz), and a much-abused
bellman, Mohammed (Rick Batalla) of indeterminate national origin.
</P>
<P>
   Does ``Payne'' sound familiar? Yes, it's yet another American
effort to duplicate the success of John Cleese's ``Fawlty Towers''
and its surprisingly sparse 12 episodes of British farce.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier try was ``Amanda's,'' which survived half a season
on ABC in 1983. Its star, Beatrice Arthur, found better lodgings
with ``The Golden Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The new show actually comes across more as a mean-spirited
``Newhart'' than as a ``Fawlty Towers'' clone. But it's not bad if
you have a high tolerance for broad physical humor _ and for
Larroquette.
</P>
<P>
   Whether as Dan Fielding on ``Night Court'' or Royal Payne here,
Larroquette is one of television's better comedy heels. The best,
maybe, since Gale Gordon blunderbussed his way through ``Our Miss
Brooks,'' ''The Lucy Show'' and ``Here's Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Gordon foils were mostly just over-starched shirts,
whereas Larroquette reaches his highest notes as a liar, a cheat
and a bully.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after forgetting his wedding anniversary, he tries to
placate Williams by giving her an antique diamond pin that's been
left behind accidentally by a guest. When the guest returns, things
become sticky.
</P>
<P>
   The stickiness includes much gesticulation, wringing of hands,
bounding here and there and _ an old comedy standby _ hiding an
intruder in the bedroom. Also, Larroquette clapping a palm over
Williams' breast. Whatever works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne'' would seem to be an adequate fit for CBS' midlife and
older audience. It's a handsome production with a strong comfort
factor, considering that the show is taking a fundamental risk.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is making Larroquette's character the center of the
show. Usually, we're supposed to like our lead characters and cluck
amusedly at the misdeeds of supporting scoundrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne'' returns on Wednesday at 8:30 p.m., and that will be
its usual spot. This Wednesday's episode is worth watching for a
piece of business Larroquette performs with a leaky pen. It's a
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ And then there's ``Rescue 77,'' barging into homes Monday on
the WB.
</P>
<P>
   The action series focuses on three paramedics (Christian Kane,
Victor Brown, Marjorie Monaghan) attached to a Los Angeles fire
station. Richard Roundtree plays the station house captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rescue 77'' is in the tradition of all sort of ``rescue''
shows, including ABC's ``240-Robert.'' I happen to remember that
one because it turned out that the helicopter was flown not by the
presumed pilot, Joanna Cassidy, but by a guy cleverly disguised as
a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the most important thing to know about ``Rescue 77'' is
that it's an Aaron Spelling show. That means the show is badly
written and populated with attractive young performers who can't
act a lick.
</P>
<P>
   Monaghan appears to be the worst actor on display here.
Good-looking blonde, mind you. But when she says, ``I'm sorry'' to
a dying woman, she makes it sound as if she's just knocked over a
salt shaker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
