<HEADLINE>
PRESERVING AMERICAN ART; THE PEACE CORPS; DANCES TO JAMES BALDWIN;
KOUSSEVITSKY LEGACY  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Artists like Josef Albers, Romare Bearden, Elizabeth
Catlett and Marsden Hartley are represented among the 150
paintings, sculptures and photographs that go on display on
Wednesday at the Studio Museum in Harlem in ``To Conserve a Legacy:
American Art From Historically Black Colleges and Universities.''
The exhibition is drawn from six of these institutions. It is
intended to focus attention on their collections and to increase
efforts to preserve these resources for the study of
African-American art and of 19th- and 20th-century American art in
general. The exhibition is to remain at the Studio Museum through
July 11 and then to tour seven cities. Information: (212) 864-4500.
</P>
<P>
   The Peace Corps
</P>
<P>
   A 47-minute oratorio, ``JFK: The Voice of Peace,'' celebrating
the establishment of the Peace Corps by executive order on March 1,
1961, will be given its world premiere by the Handel and Haydn
Society at Symphony Hall in Boston on Friday, with a repeat
performance on Sunday. The work, composed by Dan Welcher and
narrated by the Pulitzer Prize-winning biographer David McCullough,
was commissioned by New Heritage Music, a nonprofit foundation that
fosters new works commemorating people, places and ideas central to
American history. With Daniel Beckwith as conductor, McCullough
will speak the words of John F. Kennedy and choruses and a chamber
orchestra will present settings of some of the President's favorite
poetry, as well as poetry and letters from Peace Corps volunteers.
Information: (617) 262-1815.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz and James Baldwin
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Backed in one of four New York premieres by a live
jazz quartet with lead vocals by the jazz composer Philip Hamilton,
Danny Buraczeski's Jazzdance performs Tuesday through Sunday at the
Joyce Theater in Chelsea. Hamilton's score will accompany
``Ezekiel's Wheel,'' a suite of dances inspired by the writing of
James Baldwin. Information: (212) 242-0800.
</P>
<P>
   Koussevitsky's Legacy
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Serge Koussevitsky (1874-1951) directed the
Boston Symphony Orchestra, founded Tanglewood and became a patron
of new music, he was a double bassist. On Wednesday at Avery Fisher
Hall, Leon Botstein and the American Symphony Orchestra will
celebrate the Koussevitsky legacy with a rare performance of his
Double Bass Concerto (1905), performed by Gary Karr on the
composer's own double bass, plus three works commissioned by the
Koussevitsky Foundation. Information: (212) 721-6500.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
