<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TO ACQUIRE BANKBOSTON   IN $16 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fleet Financial Group Inc. sealed an agreement Sunday to acquire
BankBoston Corp., creating a powerful new financial institution out
of two bitter rivals and increasing the odds that Boston will be
home to a major bank into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The stock-for-stock deal, valued at $16 billion, stunned the
banking world by bringing together two strikingly different
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The combined entity, for now called Fleet Boston Corp., creates
the nation's eighth-largest bank, with $178 billion in assets, and
establishes a new, stronger player in national and international
banking.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly put together on the initiative of Fleet chief
executive Terrence Murray, the deal underscores the dominant
position of Fleet _ an aggressive company that has grown rapidly in
recent years _ over BankBoston, a patrician, 215-year-old
institution that has recently stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of New England's two largest banks, both
headquartered in Boston, may presage a new wave of consolidation
among the nation's top banks. Under such a winnowing, to be played
out in coming years, Fleet Boston Corp. could buy more financial
firms or itself be taken over, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Murray, 59, will be chairman and
chief executive of the new company for two years. During that
period, his counterpart at BankBoston, Charles K. ``Chad'' Gifford,
will serve in the No. 2 position as president and chief operating
officer. At the end of 2001, Murray will retire, staying on as
chairman, leaving Gifford, 56, to run the new company, according to
a joint statement issued by the institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A combined Fleet-BankBoston will have to sell off $13 billion in
deposits as well as an unspecified number of automated teller
machines to meet regulatory and antitrust requirements. Executives
at both banks said the new entity would also close a couple dozen
branches and lay off between 4,000 and 5,000 employees across New
England. The companies are expected to announce specific figures on
branch closings and layoffs Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks were keen to portray the combination as a merger of
equals. But Fleet has clearly acquired its smaller competitor.
Fleet is paying $53 per BankBoston share, an amount 13 percent
above the bank's closing price on Friday of $46 15/16 and 30
percent above its price one week ago Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks formally announced the deal Sunday after a report
first describing the acquisition appeared on Boston.com, The Boston
Globe's on-line service.
</P>
<P>
   For Murray, buying BankBoston is the crowning achievement in a
37-year career in which he turned a tiny unknown bank in Rhode
Island into a regional powerhouse and national contender. For
Gifford, whose bank is descended from the nation's oldest bank, the
deal comes amid disappointing earnings and investor worries about
BankBoston's troubled Latin American operations.
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street has been enthusiastic about Fleet's strong
growth and earnings in recent months, it has punished BankBoston by
pushing its stock price down and shrinking its market value. Such
pressure made BankBoston vulnerable to a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has been rife with rumors in recent months that a
regional, national, or overseas bank would try to acquire
BankBoston. One source close to the deal said Murray moved to
acquire his competitor before anyone else did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry drove the deal,'' the source said, adding that talks
between the two banks began approximately six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, with bank mergers in full force, Gifford and Murray
held talks about a possible combination. But the merger fell apart
when senior BankBoston executives objected that the companies were
too different. This time around, sources said, BankBoston's board
was more enthusiastic about a deal, mostly because of the company's
weakened financial position.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston Corp. will produce annual savings of $600 million a
year several years from now, Fleet chief financial officer Eugene
McQuade said in an interview Sunday, adding that the transaction is
expected to boost earnings next year.
</P>
<P>
   McQuade will be chief financial officer of the new entity, while
his counterpart at BankBoston, Susannah Swihart, has been asked to
step down and run a new $100 million charitable foundation that
Fleet Boston Corp. will establish.
</P>
<P>
   Henrique Meirelles, now BankBoston's president, will join Robert
Higgins, currently Fleet's president, in managing the combined
entity's core business lines.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, currently the nation's ninth-largest bank, is a
diversified financial services company, with credit card, mortgage,
discount stock brokerage, and asset management operations. It has
$104.5 billion in assets and a market capitalization of $25
billion. With 35,000 employees and 1,150 branches, nearly all of
its business is US-based.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, BankBoston is a smaller operation, with different
business lines. Most of its 427 branches are in Massachusetts, and
it derives around 20 percent of its revenues from Latin America,
where it has been active since 1917. BankBoston, currently the
nation's 15th-largest bank, also owns an investment bank, San
Francisco-based Robertson Stephens. With $73.5 billion in assets
and 25,000 employees, its market capitalization, at $13 billion, is
half Fleet's.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's earnings last year were $1.58 billion, compared with
$879.2 million for BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the two companies are reflected in the
styles of their leaders. Murray, who grew up in blue-collar
Woonsocket, R.I., is a tough executive constantly in search of a
deal. By contrast, Gifford, prominent in Boston social circles, has
been more risk averse, banking analysts have said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's acquisition of BankBoston _ formalized in New York on
Saturday afternoon _ is expected to close in the fourth quarter
after approval from regulators and the Justice Department. Under
the terms of the deal, BankBoston shareholders will receive 1.1844
shares of Fleet stock for each BankBoston share they own. Fleet
shareholders will own 62 percent of the new company, while
BankBoston shareholders will own 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal means that Fleet is paying 3.2 times BankBoston's book
value of $4.9 billion _ a ratio analysts described Sunday as
neither too high nor too low.
</P>
<P>
   With 20 million customers, a combined Fleet-BankBoston ``creates
an organization that becomes large enough to compete with any bank
in the country,'' industry analyst Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Anthony
Inc. said. Cassidy said that based on branch concentration for both
banks, he expected branch closings to in the Route 128 area and in
Hartford and Providence.
</P>
<P>
   The merger creates a much more diversified financial services
company that corresponds more to the model of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combined company will have a healthy mix of earnings
streams, with greater emphasis on higher growth businesses and less
reliance on core banking activities,'' Fleet's Murray said in a
statement Sunday. He said that no line of business would contribute
more than 20 percent of total earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal was also driven by both Gifford's and Murray's
desire to see Boston end up with at least one major bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a major city and don't have a bank, it's a negative
and a disadvantage in terms of prestige and allocation of resources
to area businesses,'' said one source close to the transaction.
``Neither Terry nor Chad wanted Boston to become like a lot of
major American cities that don't have a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   The name Fleet Boston Corp. is temporary, and will be scrapped
after the new company conducts a market survey. But the new entity
will retain the name BankBoston Corp. for its Latin American
operations. The company will scrap BankBoston's corporate logo _ an
eagle in flight _ and may get rid of Fleet's logo _ three sailboats
_ as well.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives said the merger became possible after Gifford
reevaluated the company's strategic position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry and Chad got to know each other a lot better in the past
year,'' Swihart said. ``Our industry is steadily evolving, and
recent mergers have shown that scale and size are important.''
</P>
<P>
   New York investment banks Goldman Sachs Inc. and Donaldson,
Lufkin and Jenrette were Fleet's advisers on the deal. BankBoston
used Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Murray has said that he wanted Fleet to grow to $150 billion to
$200 billion in assets. By acquiring BankBoston, he is now in the
middle of that range. The new company has a market capitalization
of $40 billion, ranking it seventh in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Both Boston banks have grown this decade through acquisitions of
smaller area banks and financial services firms. Most notably,
Fleet bought Shawmut National Corp. in 1995 after then Bank of
Boston failed to seal a deal. Gifford responded by acquiring
BayBanks Inc. in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   US banks have gone through a wave of mergers in recent years
that have created a new breed of megabank with $600 billion in
assets and market capitalizations of $300 billion. Those deals,
designed to cut costs and boost market share, have put pressure on
smaller banks to combine in order to compete and survive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gifford had said in recent months that he felt no
pressure to do a deal and preferred to remain independent. That
sentiment clearly changed in recent months, as BankBoston failed to
convince Wall Street that it could go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston Corp.'s board of directors will have 22 members,
including 12 from the current Fleet board and 10 from the current
BankBoston board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Blanton of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
