<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKERSTRUST-FRAUD-54     03-14 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKERSTRUST-FRAUD-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICIAL AT BANKERS TRUST CLAIMS FRAUD-CASE SETUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ B.J. Kingdon, a once high-powered executive at
Bankers Trust Corp., is being unfairly singled out as the
mastermind of a fraud at the bank by his former employer and the
federal government, his lawyer contends.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Stanley Arkin, said Bankers Trust withheld stock
options and other benefits from Kingdon, who has yet to be charged
with any crimes, to compel him to cooperate with the federal
investigation into corruption at the bank. Kingdon is now the chief
target of that investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Arkin said, Bankers Trust only pleaded guilty to
criminal fraud charges filed against it by the U.S. attorney's
office in Manhattan to complete its merger with Deutsche Bank AG of
Germany more rapidly. Had the merger not been in the works, Arkin
speculated, Bankers Trust would have more forcefully contested the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust declined to respond to Arkin's assertions.
</P>
<P>
   Former colleagues of Kingdon said he enjoyed the good life. They
said he owned at least two racehorses, one of which, Crafty Card,
made regular appearances at the Monmouth Race Track in New Jersey.
They also described Kingdon, a resident of Oceanport, N.J., as a
natty dresser who favored expensive clothing and made frequent
visits to a castle he owns in Ireland. The former colleagues, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had family members living
in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Kingdon sat on Bankers Trust's 12-member operating committee and
oversaw its custody, corporate trust and pension services
businesses before resigning in early 1997. Last week, Bankers Trust
pleaded guilty to federal criminal charges that senior officers and
employees in Kingdon's division had illegally diverted $19.1
million in unclaimed checks and other credits owed to customers to
the bank's own books to improve its financial performance from 1994
to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That admission would cast the company's viability into doubt
were it not in the midst of completing a merger with Deutsche Bank.
Many large bank customers are forbidden to do business with a
company that has admitted to a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust agreed to pay a $60 million fine to the federal
government and a separate fine of $3.5 million to New York state
authorities for the illegal scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Unclaimed bank funds fall under ``escheat laws'' that typically
require that such funds be turned over to the state. Instead,
Bankers Trust used the funds to pad its performance at a time when
the bank was mired in a scandal stemming from questionable sales
tactics involving complex financial products known as derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust recorded a $20 million charge against its earnings
in early 1997 to reconcile accounting differences the bank had
uncovered in Kingdon's division. Kingdon's unit accounted for about
$94 million of Bankers Trust's overall earnings of $612 million in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Arkin said his client did not have criminal intent in mind when
his division appropriated the unclaimed funds. He also said that
cases involving suspected improprieties related to unclaimed funds
are typically weak because the law applying to such cases is murky.
Arkin said his client would contest any criminal charges that might
be filed against him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bankers Trust gave Kingdon a gentle sendoff when his resignation
was announced in 1997. Frank Newman, the bank's chief executive,
said at the time that Kingdon was leaving to ``turn his focus
toward his personal life'' and spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Kingdon reported directly to the president of Bankers Trust,
Eugene Shanks, during years in which Bankers Trust illegally padded
its results with unclaimed funds. Former colleagues of Kingdon said
he insisted on reporting directly to Shanks. Shanks did not return
phone calls seeking comment, nor did Charles Sanford, who was the
bank's chief executive during that period.
</P>
</TEXT>
