<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/14/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- March 14, 1999 -- N.Y.-BREAST-FED-DEATH-2,
03-14 -- Tyler, who died at 2 months from malnutrition, was
entitled to Medicaid, but his mother, Tabitha Walrond, a
19-year-old welfare recipient, was unable to get it. Now, in an
unusual occurence, Ms. Walrond is set to go on trial in New York,
in a prosecution engouraged by Keenan Purcell, the baby's father.
Ms. Walrond is charged with recklessly causing Tyler's death by
failing to nourish him adequately and by failing to obtain prompt
medical attention when his condition became dire. (Michelle V.
Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- March 14, 1999 -- N.Y.-BREAST-FED-DEATH-1,
03-14 -- Tabitha Walrond, a 19-year-old welfare recipient,
breast-fed her son Tyler after leaving the hospital, but the baby
died at 2 months from starvation. In an unusual occurence, Ms.
Walrond is set to go on trial in New York, in a prosecution
engouraged by Keenan Purcell, the baby's father. Ms. Walrond is
charged with recklessly causing Tyler's death by failing to nourish
him adequately and by failing to obtain prompt medical attention
when his condition became dire. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 14, 1999 -- DOCTOROW-COLUMN, 03-14 --
Author E.L. Doctorow, who believes a case could be made that the
novel's steady retreat from realism is as much a result of film's
expansive record of the way the world looks as it is of the
increasing sophistications of literature itself. ``Still, after a
hundred years or so, it may be that movies can do nothing more for,
or to, literature than they already have done,'' says Doctorow.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) FORT IRWIN, Calif. -- March 14, 1999 -- ARMY-REFORM-3,
03-14 -- An Army soldier taking a break during war game exercises
at Fort Irwin in California. Many military experts and
reform-minded critics, some within the Army itself, say the service
has moved far too slowly to transform a force that, although
smaller, looks much as it did when the United States prepared to
slug it out with the Soviet Union on the plains of central Europe.
Facing that reality, the Army is now moving to change the way it
organizes its units and trains them to fight. (Ted Soqui/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) FORT IRWIN, Calif. -- March 14, 1999 -- ARMY-REFORM-2,
03-14 -- Army units at Fort Irwin in California during war game
exercises. A decade after the end of the Cold War and eight years
after the triumph of Desert Storm, the units that come to this
sprawling desert base take on an opposing force designed to look
like some Warsaw Pact behemoth. It is an enemy no one expects them
to face, in terrain no one expects them to encounter, with tactics
no one is certain will prevail in the future. Facing that reality,
the Army is now moving to change the way it organizes its units and
trains them to fight. (Ted Soqui/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) FORT IRWIN, Calif. -- March 14, 1999 -- ARMY-REFORM-1,
03-14 -- Army soldiers at Fort Irwin in California may be training
to fight the kind of war that some experts believe is no longer the
primary threat. A decade after the end of the Cold War and eight
years after the heady triumph of Desert Storm, the units that come
to this sprawling desert base take on an opposing force designed to
look like some Warsaw Pact behemoth. It is an enemy no one expects
them to face, in terrain no one expects them to encounter, with
tactics no one is certain will prevail in the future. (Ted
Soqui/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CLEVELAND, Ohio -- March 14, 1999 -- FROZEN-FISH-2, 03-14
-- The Blue pike, native only to Lake Erie, caught by Jim Anthony
of Conneaut, Ohio, in 1962. Anthony, a 63-year-old barber, is not
exactly sure why he kept the pike in his freezer for 37 years,
carefully rewrapping it every so often. He simply had a feeling
that someday somebody might be interested. Now, nearly four decades
later the pike has become the central clue in a compelling
scientific detective story for scientists at Case Western
University, hoping that it will lead to an extraordinary result:
the return of an extinct species. (Phil Long/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LAKE ERIE, Ohio -- March 14, 1999 -- FROZEN-FISH-1, 03-14
-- Jim Anthony of Conneaut, Ohio, was near this Lake Erie shoreline
when he caught the Blue pike, native only to Lake Erie, in 1962.
Anthony, a 63-year-old barber, is not exactly sure why he kept the
pike in his freezer for 37 years, carefully rewrapping it every so
often. He simply had a feeling that someday somebody might be
interested. Now, nearly four decades later the pike has become the
central clue in a compelling scientific detective story for
scientists hoping that it will lead to an extraordinary result: the
return of an extinct species. (Phil Long/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- March 14, 1999 -- TERM-LIMIT-ENFORCER,
03-14 -- Paul Jacob, a Libertarian with attitude, is simply not
going to let House members forget their ballyhooed term-limit
promises of the Contract With America class of 1994. Jacob's fervor
was forged in what he terms ``re-education camp'' 20 years ago,
when he served five months in prison for resisting, in the name of
principle, the government's attempt to create a roster of men
theoretically eligible for future military draft. ``I felt that at
a very young age I had done something that justified my
existence,'' he says. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 14, 1999 -- BETTY-THEATER-REVIEW-2,
03-14 -- Kristine Nielsen as the culturally attuned Mrs.
Siezmagraff in ``Betty's Summer Vacation,'' an angry new comedy by
Christopher Durang that suggests that Western civilization is
ending not with a bang but with a laugh track. Stated baldly, the
premise of ``Betty's Summer Vacation'' is sitcom simple: Take a
group of wildly incompatible people, mix them together into one
small house and watch the fur fly! (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 14, 1999 -- BETTY-THEATER-REVIEW-1,
03-14 -- Kellie Overbey, left, as Betty and Julie Lund as Trudy in
``Betty's Summer Vacation,'' an angry new comedy by Christopher
Durang that suggests that Western civilization is ending not with a
bang but with a laugh track. Stated baldly, the premise of
``Betty's Summer Vacation'' is sitcom simple: Take a group of
wildly incompatible people, mix them together into one small house
and watch the fur fly! (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 14, 1999 -- BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS, 03-14
-- WBC heavyweight champion Lennox Lewis, left, of Britain backing
WBA and IBF heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield into the ropes
Saturday night at Madison Square Garden. The long-awaited fight
between Holyfield and Lewis ended in a draw after 12 rounds on
Saturday despite a widespread belief from reporters and boxing fans
