<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKING-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      03-14 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKING-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVE WILL MAINTAIN A NEW ENGLAND INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This was as good as it was going to get.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that plenty of people are going to lose their
jobs in the combination of Fleet Financial Group Inc. and
BankBoston Corp. (not good), but at the same time Terry Murray and
Chad Gifford went a long way to ensuring that Boston doesn't become
just another branch-bank city for BankAmerica Corp. or First Union
Corp. And make no mistake: That mattered not a little but a lot to
Murray and Gifford, both New Englanders.
</P>
<P>
   When the winners and losers are totaled, Murray emerges not just
as a winner but as a visionary. Here's a guy who came from nowhere
running a tiny Rhode Island bank called Industrial National, and
now sits atop all of New England banking. He was right: Size does
matter.
</P>
<P>
   And Gifford? He's scheduled to run the combined bank two years
down the road. But then BankAmerica chief executive David Coulter
was going to run the combined NationsBank-BankAmerica. Today's he
gone. We'll see soon enough on Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of inside-baseball aside, the region emerges as a
clear winner because it does matter where the bank calls home. When
the job cuts come, would you rather be working in the Boston
headquarters or in Charlotte's Boston office? If you are raising
money for the Boston Symphony Orchestra or Children's Hospital, do
you want to be calling on the hometown chief executive or a
regional vice president?
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why BankAmerica chief executive Hugh McColl is
a hero in Charlotte for making his bank, and city, a winner. Murray
and Gifford, in putting aside their real differences, have given
Boston the same chance.
</P>
<P>
   The people who run BankAmerica, First Union, and Bank One Corp.
are not going to be happy about this neat Boston deal. BankBoston,
with its sagging stock price, was beginning to look like lunch for
some of these big national players, and who is to say Fleet was
untouchable, either?
</P>
<P>
   Now Murray &AMP; Co. are going to do all they can to keep the big
competitors out. To get this deal past the regulators _ and you can
be sure they have already gotten a wink and a nod there _
Fleet-BankBoston is expected to have to divest something like $13
billion of $110 billion in deposits, maybe $10 billion of that in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what the regulators require, there could either be
one big buyer or several small ones. Already there is talk about
establishing three separate banks _ one each in Massachusetts,
Connecticut, and Rhode Island _ and selling them to separate
bidders. The last thing Murray wants is for regulators to force him
to spin off enough branches and deposits that someone like First
Union could turn into a serious competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly in the space of a decade we're down to one New England
megabank and a bunch of midgets. Murray and others will tell you
quite rightly that there is no shortage of competition: How many of
us are walking around with Visa cards in our wallets from Citicorp?
The mortgage business is driven by brokers and their only loyalty
is to who has the best rate, not the address on the headquarter's
door.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end it would be better for everyone to have a
world-class competitor on the ground who could push back against
the new Fleet-BankBoston behemoth. Competition is good, and we just
eliminated one big competitor. Replacing it with another would be a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   It could, ironically, even be good for Fleet-BankBoston. These
are two very different banks, and the chance of internecine warfare
at the top is real. A tough competitor would focus its attention
where it belongs _ outward _ and not allow it the luxury of years
of battles on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   A final note: The Boston Connection may not have run its course.
Even after the merger, Fleet-BankBoston will have a market
capitalization of just $40 billion; BankAmerica's market cap is
$125 billion; Citigroup's is $149 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Citicorp and Travelers combined, insurance is the next
logical piece for Murray's puzzle. Wouldn't John Hancock or
Massachusetts Mutual fit just fine?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
