r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     03-14 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL TO L.A.'S SUITORS: SHOW US THE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Four NFL seasons have come and gone since the Rams and
Raiders left greater Los Angeles, long enough for its most fervent
NFL fans to have discovered a life.
</P>
<P>
   There's been no anguish, no rallies for a common cause. There
has been no sense of outrage like there was in Cleveland when Art
Modell abruptly moved the Browns to Baltimore. If we're losing
contact with any need for pro football, it is developing slower
than the Rams' old running game.
</P>
<P>
   The two men who are exceptions to this are here in Phoenix
seeking papal approval from the league to put an expansion team in
Los Angeles. For the last year or longer, Kings owner Ed Roski and
Hollywood shaman Michael Ovitz have put a spotlight on L.A.'s NFL
profile, such as it is, and talked the city up like no one in
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Without overstating the reach or motives of either, you have to
go back to the days of Walter O'Malley and Jack Kent Cooke, who
built facilities on their own dime, to find someone with this much
L.A. loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL's response to both men has been typically feckless.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of acknowledging all that Roski, a commercial real
estate baron, has done in the last five years -- breath life into a
new visage of the Coliseum, save the Kings from bankruptcy, build
the Staples Center, add a billionaire (Eli Broad) to his New
Coliseum team -- it is frowning at his debt.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of bonding with Ovitz, who the league encouraged to get
involved because of his showmanship and glitz, it looks down on his
fractured financing, conveniently forgetting that agents are always
doing things with other people's money.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reasserting itself boldly in a market which once
supported two teams, the league comes with its hand out again. The
league's answer to every financial question is always the same:
More. If Cleveland's franchise fee was $476 million and the
Redskins' sale with stadium was $800 million, then any fee for the
``vast potential'' of Los Angeles must be $650 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   For the opportunity to return to the NFL, the league is telling
its two L.A. suitors that it wants more money than George
Steinbrenner wanted to sell the Yankees, and that their current
resources apparently are not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   A less patient man would have told the NFL to punt months ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are far fewer opportunities in L.A. to turn a profit than
there are in the two most recent examples. Fan loyalty was never a
concern in Cleveland; the Browns may sell out their new stadium
into the third millenium. Economists who studied Al Lerner's
purchase estimate he will start showing a profit in year six or
seven, as long as the league's TV revenue doesn't go into freefall.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners of the Redskins inherit a virtually new stadium
with all of the perks, plus a waiting list for season tickets that
circles the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   There are no such guarantees here, where construction costs run
higher, where one of the first versions of the PSL bombed when the
Raiders were still in the Coliseum. Whoever gets a team here, be it
Ovitz, Roski or some other rich man, will have to overcome the
sizeable ill will left behind by Georgia Frontiere and Al Davis.
And lord knows what ticket prices and PSLs will be for any owner
needing to cover an obscene nut.
</P>
<P>
   The league says it wants to make sure any franchise here will
succeed. But if that's true, then why is the rumored franchise fee
running hotter than the Dow Jones? Why isn't the league putting its
own money into a stadium, an idea it once suggested but now appears
to have abandoned?
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't have to go far to find people critical of the way
the NFL operates.
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants owner Wellington Mara left a committee meeting
Sunday shaking his head over the league's franchise follies, the
vacating of L.A., Houston and Cleveland in a two-year span. ``I
never thought we'd ever leave Houston, much less Los Angeles,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked what that says about the league. ``That maybe we
need to look at our own values.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the exec with a team who remembers one rancorous
closed session meeting of owners a year or so ago. An owner needing
renovations to his stadium presented a plan which featured $80
million of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, it featured (ital) no (end ital) public money.
``(Commissioner Paul) Tagliabue got up and said `no, no, no, we
can't have any team doing anything with its own money,' '' the exec
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when Pat Bowlen (Denver), Mike Brown (Cincinnati) and
Dan Rooney (Pittsburgh) were all looking for public money to help
with new stadiums. (Tagliabue) said there can not be an attempt for
a privately funded stadium when so many teams are seeking public
money for new stadiums or renovations. He said `If one team does
it, the public will get angry and expect every team to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When you hear stories like that and follow the public money
trail everywhere else, one's pessimistic view becomes even more
entrenched. As naughty as the Raiders and Davis were here, he's no
more cunning and rapacious as the league. Less so, because there's
no pretense.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. may or may not get an expansion franchise this week. One
way or the other, the sense is that despite four years without a
team, L.A. is still getting sacked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
