<SLUG> BC-CAR-SKINNER-RULING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKINNER'S BGN WIN TAKEN AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Ga. _ Upon further review, Mike Skinner's first NASCAR
Busch Grand National Series victory did not happen at Atlanta Motor
Speedway on Saturday after all.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials discovered an unapproved cylinder head during
an inspection after the Yellow Freight 300 Saturday evening.
Race-winner Skinner, making his second BGN start for team owner
David Ridling, was relegated to the 43rd and last spot in the
revised standings, and will receive the prize money and points for
that position.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the race's title sponsor also is Skinner's primary
backer on the No. 19 Chevrolet Monte Carlo he is scheduled to drive
in a limited BGN schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Former World of Outlaws champion Dave Blaney, who finished 2.261
seconds behind Skinner, was declared the revised winner of his
first BGN race. Pole-sitter Blaney, driver of the No. 93 Amoco
Pontiac Grand Prix, made his 24th career Busch start Saturday on
the 1.54-mile quadoval.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations, said Skinner's
team was in violation of a rule stating that all cylinder heads
must be NASCAR-approved, and all modifications must be submitted to
the sanctioning body before any proposed modification is eligible
for approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head was an approved part,'' Triplett said yesterday
morning, ``but the modification was unapproved. Our question was
the shaping of the port \Ron the inside of the head\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the reaction of Skinner's team, Triplett said,
``Well, they didn't agree with us. We didn't expect that. But they
have a right to appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, whose top BGN finish remains a 24th-place effort, was
taken aback by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision scarred what I thought was a great day on the
track,'' said Skinner, who was competing in only his ninth BGN
race. ``I don't know about the motors. I don't build the motors.
It's a judgment call and NASCAR has to make it. All I do is drive,
but I don't agree with it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
