<HEADER>
A0128 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-KIRKORIAN-COLUMN-     03-14 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KIRKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT WAS A FARCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KIRKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early Sunday morning after another one of his shows
had been tainted by the scoring of unscrupulous judges, Don King
was being interviewed by a TV guy in the Madison Square Garden
press area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person has an inalienable right in America to make the
kind of decision his conscience sees fit to make,'' King was
intoning in his characteristic booming voice. ``You don't have to
like it, you don't have to agree with it. There are a lot of
unpopular decisions made every day in this great land of ours. What
about the Dred Scott decision? There are injustices perpetuated
every day in America. What makes our country so beautiful and so
utterly unique is that we accept these decisions peacefully and do
our best to rectify them.''
</P>
<P>
   Don King paused momentarily, and suddenly his faced gleamed with
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do it again,'' he said. ``Let's have a rematch. That's
the only way to settle this burning controversy. Let's have these
two great warriors fight it out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Please, Don, spare us the agony.
</P>
<P>
   One one-sided, even tedious Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield fight
is enough.
</P>
<P>
   The only faint resemblance this tame affair had with that
memorable Ali-Frazier I classic held 28 years earlier in the same
building was that it was fought inside the same 20 by 20 ring.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, forget about it!
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to see Lennox Lewis, younger, stronger, quicker,
fresher, busier, once again relentlessly hammer a once gallant
warrior whose best days are far behind him?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if these two men have a rematch---and let's all keep our
fingers crossed that they won't---the only chance the aging
Holyfield would have would be if King once again makes sure the
officials are solidly aligned in his corner as they were Saturday
night when they somehow wound up giving Holyfield a draw even
though he landed only 130 punches across the 12 rounds to the 348
he received from Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   And knowing Don King as we all know him, he would see to it the
deck once again would be stacked against Lewis, who should be
savoring today being the first undisputed heavyweight champion from
Great Britain in 102 years but, instead, is grieving over one of
the most corrupt decisions in the history of a sport brimming with
them.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what behind-the-scenes machinations Don King did to
pull off this latest farce to curse boxing, but one grudgingly has
to hand it to King for the sheer chutzpah of doing it on such a
high-profile stage in which millions watched around the world and
21,284 saw first hand in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There are compelling reasons for King's typical shenanighans.
</P>
<P>
   Pure and simple, if Lewis had been given a victory that he
deserved because he dominated Holyfield throughout the fight with a
left jab that seldom missed its mark, King would have lost his
eternal hold on the heavyweight title that dates from Muhammad Ali
to Mike Tyson with Larry Holmes and a bunch of faceless
champions---Oliver McCall, Tim Witherspoon, Greg Page, Pinklon
Thomas, etc.---in between.
</P>
<P>
   King holds title options on Holyfield, but none on Lewis, who
would have certainly gone his independent way and avoided King had
he emerged victorious.
</P>
<P>
   The only other heavyweights King has in his promotional stable
are Henry Akiwande and Johnny Ruiz, neither of whom are destined to
hold a heavyweight title of any legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the two that Evander Holyfield still has in his
possession, the ones belonging to the WBA and IBF, won't be
accepted by anyone who viewed Saturday night's hoax in which Lewis
convinced everyone he was better than Holyfield except for two of
the judges, Jean Williams and Larry O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea what strings Don King yanked to once again
tarnish a profession in which he has dredged millions, but I do
know that his newest rumored silent business partner, IBC president
Bob Lee, was responsible for assigning Williams to work this fight.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Williams who gave Holyfield a two point win
(115-113), even though she just might be the only person on the
face of this earth to see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Williams' judging was so inept that she actually had
Holyfield winning the fifth round, which is quite hard to figure
since that happened to be the round in which Lewis pounded
Holyfield with impunity, pinning him on one occasion against the
ropes and unleashing one punch after another against his anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   In my notebook, I scribbled, ``. . .Holyfield seems hurt, being
overwhelmed, big, big round for Lewis. . .''
</P>
<P>
   But not according to Williams, who just might have mistaken
Holyfield for Lewis, or might have fallen asleep, or might have
been transfixed by the countless celebrities in the crowd like
Jerry Seinfeld, Jack Nicholson, Keith Richards, Spike Lee, etc.
</P>
<P>
   I have no logical explanation for Williams' wayward view, but
I'm sure Don King does.
</P>
<P>
   The chap who somehow viewed the proceedings even at 115-115,
England's Larry O'Connell, was assigned by, of all people, Jose
Sulaiman, the WBC president and a long-time King stooge.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure that O'Connell today is the most unpopular
figure in England since Charles I, whose head was dislodged by his
disgruntled followers for perceived indiscretions. The Brits are
more humane these days---they don't even let their cops carry side
arms---or Mr. O'Connell would be in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   You also can be sure Bob Lee, Jose Sulaiman, Jean Williams and
Larry O'Connell will be on Don King's Christmas gift A list.
</P>
<P>
   And you can wager your favorite 8 by 10 glossy of Don King that
the WBA-assigned arbiter, Stanley Christodolou of South Africa
won't be receiving any holiday goodies from King, not after his
116-113 ruling for Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   You must understand that Don King never has had the political
muscle with the WBA that he's had with the WBC, where he has that
touchingly warm friendship with Jose Sulaiman.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this isn't the first scandalous decision to pollute
boxing, and you can be sure it won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Don King will see to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
