<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF NEW HAMPSHIRE FACES FINES IN EPA PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the first step of a crackdown on environmental
violations at colleges and universities across New England, federal
officials Monday will file a complaint against the University of
New Hampshire that could result in a fine of up to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, which alleges that UNH violated hazardous-waste
management laws, is the first of several planned actions in a
sweeping campaign by the US Environmental Protection Agency to
bring the region's institutions of higher education into compliance
with federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very ambitious and concentrated effort to improve
environmental performances on college campuses throughout New
England,'' said the EPA regional administrator, John DeVillars.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the EPA will mail letters to 258 college presidents
outlining the agency's strategy, which will include training
college officials on how to improve environmental management on
their campuses and conducting inspections this spring at schools
suspected of violations.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges are being targeted for the crackdown, according to
DeVillars, because they normally have laboratories, waste-treatment
facilities, and power plants that have the potential to cause
environmental damage if they are not properly managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found that some educational institutions don't take
their environmental obligations as seriously as they should,''
DeVillars stated in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   While EPA officials emphasize they are holding universities
accountable for environmental problems just as they would any large
corporation, the agency also says it will help schools comply with
the laws by conducting workshops and providing technical
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   On March 24, the EPA will sponsor its first workshop at Harvard
Medical School to address the environmental pressures that colleges
and universities face.
</P>
<P>
   The action against UNH stems from a 1997 inspection of its
Durham campus during which officials found 15 violations of federal
and state hazardous-waste laws at several laboratories and storage
facilities, according to DeVillars. For example, the school is
being cited for pouring mercury down a drain without ensuring the
waste was properly treated, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   A UNH official expressed disappointment that the agency would
file the complaint at a time when the school has improved its
environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that although there were some technical compliance
issues back in 1997, our program was fundamentally sound then and
is even better now,'' said Donald Sundberg, UNH vice president for
research and public service.
</P>
<P>
   Sundberg said in a statement that UNH officials plan to work
closely with the EPA to satisfy the agency's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint against UNH represents the third EPA inquiry of a
New England college in the past four years. In 1995, Yale
University paid $348,000 in fines and environmental investments in
the community after being cited for mishandling and improperly
labeling hazardous chemicals on its New Haven campus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Boston University was cited for violating regulations
on underground storage tanks and storm water. An investigation was
prompted when a tank near the BU Bridge leaked 1,000 gallons of oil
into the Charles River. The school agreed to pay $753,000 in fines
and in community projects. It was the nation's largest settlement
between an educational institution and the EPA, according to
DeVillars.
</P>
<P>
   BU has since reduced its oil inventory on campus by 40 percent
and its underground tanks by 20 percent, according to Kevin
Carlton, a BU spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   UNH officials have the choice of fighting the complaint through
a hearing process or seeking a settlement with the EPA, like Yale
and BU, according to Ken Moraff, chief of the EPA's regional
enforcement office.
</P>
<P>
   Moraff said additional complaints are expected against New
England colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are often finding is that some schools don't have a
good system in place to manage hazardous waste or systems to manage
underground oil storage,'' he said. ``That can be dangerous if you
don't store it properly, risking explosions or spills.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
