<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA INVESTS IN HOME-NETWORK STUDIES  
 FROM CELEBRITY DOCTOR, MEDICAL ADVICE ONLINE  
 TAKING THE FISH MARKET INTO CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Motorola Corp. plans to announce Monday that it will donate $5
million to create a new research center at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology Media Laboratory to explore ``think and
link'' technologies that connect everyday appliances.
</P>
<P>
   The research center, to be named the Motorola Digital DNA
Laboratory, will explore concepts that are still years away from
development into commercial products.
</P>
<P>
   One example, according to Hector Ruiz, president of Motorola's
Semiconductor Products division, is a wireless technique known
inside the company as Piano, which can transmit information at
speeds as high as 500 megabits a second over distances of about 10
feet.
</P>
<P>
   There is already a great deal of activity in the computer and
consumer electronics industry on setting standards for connecting
networks of consumer devices. These might include PCs, television
sets, cell phones, personal digital assistants, stereo gear and
various home appliances.
</P>
<P>
   But Ruiz said that it was important to look further into the
future, when such devices might be far smarter, with far more
information and instructions to exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Motorola Digital DNA Laboratory will be housed in 5,000
square feet within a new building that is scheduled for occupancy
in early 2003 and will be connected to the current MIT Media Lab.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Lab has an annual budget of $30 million. Most of the
financing comes from about 160 corporate sponsors, and the balance
from government agencies and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   From Celebrity Doctor, Medical Advice Online
</P>
<P>
   Consider it the ultimate play in celebrity marketing. A new Web
site bearing the name of Dr. C. Everett Koop, who as U.S. surgeon
general during the Reagan administration became America's doctor,
is about to join the ranks of Internet initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that drkoop.com, which offers free medical information,
has been up and running for only nine months and last year had
revenues of only $48,000. The association with the outspoken Koop
is what the venture's founders are clearly banking on. The company,
which calls its site ``Your Trusted Health Network,'' will go
public under the Nasdaq symbol KOOP.
</P>
<P>
   Koop founded the company in July 1997 with Don Hackett, a former
executive with Physicians Health Network. The initial investment
was less than $500,000. With its public offering, underwritten by
Bear Stearns &AMP; Co., drkoop.com hopes to raise $50 million, much of
it for an advertising blitz later this year.
</P>
<P>
   As for Koop, he will own 11 percent of the public company, and
he has a five-year deal to receive 2 percent of the company's
revenue. And given the country's apparently insatiable appetite for
free medical advice, that could amount to a tidy sum.
</P>
<P>
   So far at least, Koop's site shows every sign of being a
success. In its first month, it had 2 million visits; these days
2.6 million people visit drkoop.com in a typical month and 83,000
of them are registered as regular users.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers free medical information about diseases and
treatments, discussion groups on subjects like allergies, and
online support groups for recovering alcoholics and others. An
insurance section provides policy quotes and information on
flexible spending accounts.
</P>
<P>
   And as one would expect from a former surgeon general, there are
plenty of reminders that smoking can be hazardous to your health.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Taking the Fish Market Into Cyberspace
</P>
<P>
   As a third-generation ``fish guy'' in New York City, Stratis
Morfogen practically grew up at the Fulton Fish Market, watching
men dicker over seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Auctions of hard-to-get delicacies were long a staple of the
wholesale market. So when he heard about the growing popularity of
online auctions, Morfogen, who is now 31, realized that he could
fuse the tension of the professional fish auctions with the fun of
``playing along'' at home for the online audience.
</P>
<P>
   After he first saw the Internet a year ago, Morfogen decided to
build his own site, Fultonstreet.com. His father thought he was
crazy, Morfogen said, until 300 orders started coming in each day,
at an average of $90 apiece. This week, Morfogen, who has signed a
deal to be the ``exclusive online fish store'' for Ubid.com, will
start auctioning Alaskan king crab leg gift packages, four-course
dinners for two, and live Maine lobsters. Starting bid: $7.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
</TEXT>
