<SLUG> BC-CMGI-MUTFUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING SUCCESS BREEDS UNLIKELY TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CMGI-WETHERELL) 
(lb) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is CMGI an Internet company or a mutual fund?
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the question seems almost absurd. The company owns
roughly a dozen Internet start-ups, which offer specialized
marketing services to companies that want to do business over the
Internet. CMGI had revenues of $90 million in its last fiscal year,
ended July 31, and $76 million in the first six months of the
current year.
</P>
<P>
   But in a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission last
month, CMGI notified investors that because of its highly
successful investments in Lycos, Geocities and other
Internet-related companies, it meets the characteristics of a
mutual fund under the federal securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which steadfastly states that it does not want to
be a mutual fund, has until October to rectify the situation. If it
succeeds, CMGI's shareholders will be no worse for the experience,
although investors in the companies that CMGI owns could feel a
downdraft from CMGI's selling of those securities. And if CMGI
cannot revamp in time, its shareholders could get hit with huge tax
burdens.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal securities laws, any company that owns
investment securities with a value exceeding 40 percent of its
total assets, excluding cash and government securities, is an
``investment company,'' subject to regulation under the Investment
Company Act of 1940, which governs mutual funds, closed-end funds
and other investment pools.
</P>
<P>
   By investing in Internet start-ups through a series of
venture-capital pools, CMGI's investment assets have grown far more
quickly than its underlying direct-marketing business.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of January, CMGI owned $1.6 billion worth of stock in
publicly traded companies. Roughly 60 percent, or $957 million, of
that is in companies where CMGI owns less than 20 percent of the
shares. The remainder is in ``affiliates,'' those companies where
it owns more than 20 percent but less than half of the total
shares.
</P>
<P>
   All told, those investments account for a huge portion of CMGI's
assets. Just how much, the company will not say; it is scheduled to
release those details later this month. But it is likely that it
amounts to more than half of CMGI's total assets. At the end of the
company's first fiscal quarter, which ended Dec. 31, noninvestment
assets were worth about $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's board of directors instructed the company's management to
make sure it is not considered a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   By Oct. 31 of this year, when the one-year grace period allowed
under federal securities laws will expire, the company's management
must take one of two actions: First, CMGI could buy the rest of one
of the companies like Lycos, where it already owns a substantial
stake. That would change the status of that holding from an
investment to a continuing business operation.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, CMGI could sell enough of its investments so that
they account for less than 40 percent of assets. But Andrew
Hajducky III, CMGI's chief financial officer, says that is ``a last
resort,'' and will generate big tax liabilities for CMGI, since
most of the investments were made at far lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Selling is not a particularly attractive option. Besides the tax
implications, the company has been banking on those Internet
investments to provide its direct-marketing business with
information about people surfing the Web. By selling some of those
investments, ``anticipated synergies between our core businesses
and disposed assets may never arise,'' the company said in a recent
filing with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most young Internet companies, CMGI does not have losses
on its books to offset the capital gains it is reaping from its
investments. In the six months ended Jan. 31, the company earned
net profits of $52.6 million, or $1.04 a share; the company's gains
on its investments in the period totaled $134 million, or roughly
double its revenues from the marketing businesses it operates.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI could also avoid having to buy or sell more businesses by
reorganizing as an investment company. (Technically, CMGI would be
a closed-end fund rather than a mutual fund, because it has a
limited number of shares that trade on an exchange.) But that, a
highly unlikely move, would create some unpleasant results for
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   As a fund, CMGI would be forced to distribute to shareholders
all of the capital gains it reaps each year as it cashes in some of
its investments. Last year, the company reported $101 million in
such gains, and in the first six months of this fiscal year,
another $95 million. Together, those would have resulted in taxable
capital gains of nearly $4 a share for the company's stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   That tax burden would take a lot of the fun out of investing in
the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
