<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS GET HELP IN FIGHTING TERRORISM  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dissatisfied with the pace of efforts to prepare the nation for
a germ or chemical weapons attack, President Clinton has decided to
provide an additional $11 million to train firefighters and other
emergency service personnel.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Sunday that Clinton would provide the
money for this fiscal year, which began in October, by transferring
money between accounts in the Department of Health and Human
Services.
</P>
<P>
   The money will enable officials in 12 cities to begin creating,
training and equipping a system of Metropolitan Medical Emergency
Response Teams to act in case of a terrorist attack using
unconventional weapons. Among the cities scheduled to receive the
emergency assistance is Salt Lake City, site of the 2002 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to announce the initiative when he speaks
Monday in Washington at the 17th annual convention of the
International Association of Fire Fighters.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said he did not know which
agency would lose financing to provide more money for the local
medical teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
