<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-CHARLOTTE-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE ROLLS OVER TULSA; SOUTHWEST MISSOURI STATE NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Tulsa's players had talked about a monumental
upset, about how they matched up with the top-seeded Duke Blue
Devils, about how they knew they could play with them.
</P>
<P>
   But 40 minutes and a 41-point loss later, the Golden Hurricane
admitted it was foolish to think this Duke team could be beaten in
the NCAA tournament. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All those boasts did was prompt Duke to eviscerate the East
Regional's ninth-seeded team, 97-56, and advance to the round of 16
and a match with Steve Alford's long-shot Southwest Missouri State
Bears, who defeated higher-seeded Tennessee by 81-51 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Though each team earned its trip to the regional semifinals, at
Continental Arena in East Rutherford, N.J., in impressive fashion,
Alford was careful not to let any errant thoughts, no matter how
hopeful, antagonize the Blue Devils (34-1).
</P>
<P>
   His team is made up of real-life Hoosiers, much like himself,
plucked from the high schools of Indiana. The Bears (22-10) are
making their first trip to the NCAA tournament's round of 16, the
Blue Devils their 10th under coach Mike Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players know that they're going to be going against nine
high school all-Americans, and I'll be going against a Hall of Fame
coach,'' Alford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're outstanding, but we'll show up and compete.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a loose ball in the opening minutes of the game that set
off first Krzyzewski, and then the Blue Devils. Eric Coley of Tulsa
went to the floor and got it. Elton Brand, Shane Battier and the
rest of the Blue Devils did not, and they heard about it from their
coach in the ensuing timeout. Their lackadaisical effort had led to
a 3-point shot by Marcus Hill, six straight points and the Golden
Hurricane's brief flirtation with backing up its boast as it crept
within 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   In a diplomatic interpretation of Duke's animated huddle, guard
Trajan Langdon said, ``We didn't go down on the floor and get it,
and coach challenged us to get physical.''
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, how they responded. The Blue Devils scored the next 26
points in a seven-minute span that showcased the variety of ways
they can take a team apart.
</P>
<P>
   Battier, a 6-foot-8-inch defensive stopper, tipped in one basket
and then made two 3-pointers from the top of the key. Brand bulled
his way inside of 6-8 Michael Ruffin and 6-10 Brandon Kurtz _ the
brawny tandem that was supposed to shut down the inside _ for three
more scores and two trips to the free-throw line. Chris Carrawell,
William Avery and Langdon turned pressure defense into
scalpel-precise fast breaks.
</P>
<P>
   It was Carrawell who offered a warning for Southwest Missouri
State, or any mouthy, optimistic opponent in a future round.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at us before the game and say they can play with
us,'' Carrawell said of Tulsa's boasts. ``But it's another thing
when you step on the court with us and you look up at the
scoreboard and say, `Dang, we're already down 30 points.' It's
funny how that works.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Hurricane (23-10) never recovered from its
seven-minute hammering. By the end of the first half it was down by
30 points. Tulsa shot 33.9 percent, gave up 40 Blue Devil points in
the paint and, as guard Tony Heard breathlessly lamented afterward,
``They just kept coming at us with players off the bench _ good
players.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, six Blue Devils reached double figures. The team shot 55
percent from the 3-point arc and was led by 19 points from Avery,
17 from Brand and 12 from Langdon, who was playing in his first
tournament game since he sprained the fifth metatarsal in his left
foot last week.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not depth or balance or athleticism or skill that
Tulsa coach Bill Self wanted to talk about after declaring the Blue
Devils unbeatable. ``The best thing about them is their mind-set.
They have the killer instinct. It appears to me that they're on a
mission that they want to make history. They're almost not human.''
</P>
<P>
   No.12-seeded Southwest Missouri State upset No.4-seeded
Tennessee by doing what its coach did best during his all-America
and national championship career at Indiana: taking care of the
ball and filling the basket with deadly accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears shot 51.9 percent in a display that was so
otherworldly that the 6-11 center Danny Moore twice popped behind
the 3-point line and drained shots. ``I've been shooting out close
to that line before, but today I was feeling it and decided to step
back,'' said Moore, one of four Indiana natives in the starting
lineup. He finished with 25 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The more athletic Volunteers (21-9) could not rattle Southwest
Missouri State's backcourt of William Fontleroy and Kevin Ault, and
the Bears stretched a 10-point halftime lead to as many as 32 early
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Fontleroy handed out four assists and Ault five to go with 14
points. The two players helped the Bears turn the ball over only
six times in the game, once in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears earned their celebration at the final buzzer, but they
were aware of what awaited them this week in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In the loose, joking manner that he wore all weekend, Alford
offered one strategy to slow the Blue Devils' tournament run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get some friends in New Jersey to put up some road signs
that detour Duke before the game,'' he said. ``That way we can
start the game five-on-zero and get a head start. We'll need it,
the way they're putting away people so quickly.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
