<SLUG> BC-CANADA-LAW-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA PROCEEDS WITH LAW TO PROTECT MAGAZINE INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By KALYANI VITTALA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Canadian House of Commons is expected to pass
legislation on Monday that would protect its magazine industry from
American competition, a move that could lead Washington to
retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which is also subject to approval by the Canadian
Senate before it goes into effect, would essentially make it
illegal for advertisers to buy space in ``split run'' magazines,
which are Canadian versions of publications like Sports Illustrated
or People. Officials on each side of the border are tyring to
negotiate a compromise that would satisfy Canada's desire to
protect its cultural industries without violating the North
American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal become law, American officials have threatened
to retaliate by imposing tariffs on goods including steel, lumber,
plastics, pharmaceuticals, textiles and clothing. Canadian
supporters of the legislation have accused the United States of
bullying tactics and vowed to hold firm.
</P>
<P>
   But after meeting Friday with senior Canadian officials, the
deputy United States trade representative, Richard Fisher,
announced no immediate action would be taken if the bill was passed
in the House of Commons. Fisher said he was confident that suitable
amendments would be made to the bill before it was passed by the
Canadian Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Canadian officials are conceding little at this point
except the willingness to discuss the issue further. ``It's very
easy to talk about retaliation and threats of war,'' Sergio Marchi,
Canada's Trade Minister, said Friday in Ottawa. ``It takes more
courage to refrain from going down that slippery slope.''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier law, which prohibited split runs through a
complicated set of taxes, was struck down as an unfair trading
practice by the World Trade Organization in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's magazine industry is modest at best, since 80 percent
of the publications found on newsstands here are American. But it
does provide an outlet for Canadian viewpoints. The rationale
behind the new legislation is that split run magazines are produced
almost entirely in the United States with minimal Canadian content.
This puts them in a position to undercut advertising rates and
siphon off significant portions of this country's $600 million
(Canadian) industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Maclean's magazine lost only 10 percent of its ad
revenue it would just cease to be,'' said Francois de Gaspe
Beaubien, a spokesman for the Canadian Magazine Publishers
Association, referring to Canada's leading news magazine which has
a weekly circulation of about 500,000. ``That would be one more
Canadian voice that has been silenced.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
