<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0137 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PURDUE-MIAMI-HNS &LR;      03-14 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PURDUE-MIAMI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The pundits said they should not have even been invited
to the Tournament after closing the season with a sub-.500
conference record and five losses in their last six games.
</P>
<P>
   Even their coach was ``surprised'' his team was given a chance
at a second life that comes with an NCAA berth.
</P>
<P>
   With two upsets in the East Regional, the Purdue Boilermakers
made sure they took advantage of the second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Miami became the second victim Sunday, as Purdue had a 15-0 run
to end the first half and held off several mini-charges from the
No. 2-seeded Hurricanes on the way to a 73-63 win at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers, who are one of three No. 10 seeds still alive
in the Tournament, will take on Temple, a 64-54 winner over
Cincinnati, in the regional semifinal March 19 at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   If a week ago you had told the Boilermakers' Brian Cardinal that
he would be going to the Sweet 16, he would have been
flabbergasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd want to know where I was sitting in the stands, because I
didn't think we could get there (to play),'' he said. ``I knew all
year that we had a good team, it was just a matter of us playing
well and playing together, and getting things worked out where we
were a ballclub on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the problems were, Purdue (21-12) seems to have worked
them out. Coach Gene Keady said it took an ``attitude adjustment''
for his players to come together.
</P>
<P>
   They did not look that well adjusted against Texas in the first
round, but a win is a win. Two days later, they looked fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers' offense flowed smoothly, making assists on 18
of its 22 field goals as the team hit 58 percent of its shots (22
of 38).
</P>
<P>
   But it was Purdue's defense that was the difference, holding
Miami to its third-lowest scoring output of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Miami made just 32.9 percent from the floor (25 of 76), going a
porous 1-for-14 from behind the 3-point line. Senior center Mario
Bland was the lone Hurricane to hit from long range.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hurricanes' first-round win over Lafayette, guard Johnny
Hemsley scored 31 points and was 9-of-12 from 3-point range as
Miami tied a season high with 10 treys. Hemsley managed just 13
points and was 0-2 on treys Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes' poor shooting skewed the final statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Miami took 76 shots to Purdue's 38, grabbed 27 offensive
rebounds to the Boilermakers' three (45-29 overall) and forced 20
turnovers while committing 18.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive rebounding number was inflated by the high number
of missed shots, but unfortunately for the Hurricanes, the extra
boards just afforded them more opportunities to miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything away from Purdue, because they
had something to do with how we played, but when you miss 17
point-blank layups, you have to take some of the blame yourself,''
said Miami coach Leonard Hamilton, whose team finished with a 23-7
mark, setting a school record for wins.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those misses came during the drought to end the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   After Miami had trailed by seven points in the early going, Tim
James scored inside to tie the score at 17 with 7:23 to play before
halftime. The Hurricanes did not score again until after the break,
going nine consecutive trips without a basket.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Purdue got points from four players, including two
3-pointers from Cardinal, who led the team with 20 points. The last
trey for Cardinal, who went 4-for-5 on 3-pointers, was a 24-footer
just before the halftime buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   After halftime, Miami made several attempts to get back into the
game, its best coming midway through the second period when the
Hurricanes cut the lead to 43-38.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal again stepped to the forefront, draining a 3-pointer
from the top of the key and finishing off a fast break started by
Tony Mayfield's steal with a layup to start a 13-2 run to put the
game away.
</P>
</TEXT>
