<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-ISLANDERS     03-14 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WIN 3-2 OVER ISLANDERS IN OVERTIME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Adam Graves was dragging after 64 minutes of
up-and-down hockey when the puck found his stick. Desperate, like
his Rangers, he fired a long shot from just inside the Islanders'
blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Graves' shot, hard and accurate, deflected off the arm of
Islanders goalie Tommy Salo and entered the corner of the net to
give the Rangers a dramatic 3-2 victory with 55 seconds remaining
in overtime before a sold-out crowd today at Nassau Coliseum. The
victory improved the Rangers' record to 4-0 against the Islanders
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck had eyes, so to speak,'' said Graves, who has 33
goals, three of which have been overtime winners.
</P>
<P>
   Graves' goal prompted a celebration behind the Islanders' net,
the kind usually reserved for big playoff victories. This isn't the
post-season, of course, but for the Rangers these last 15
regular-season games will determine whether they will get the
chance to cheer anything in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playoff hockey; you can't afford to lose one,'' said
Graves, who is expected to sign a multiyear contract extension with
the Rangers this week. ``Each game is a huge one because of the
position we put ourselves in.''
</P>
<P>
   Salo, who made 18 saves, said of Graves' shot, ``It hit my
shoulder and went right through before I got my arm up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers moved within 2 points of the Boston Bruins for the
eighth and final playoff berth in the East. Now in 10th place, the
Rangers also trail the Florida Panthers by 1 point in the
three-team scramble for the final spot. The Bruins and the Panthers
have each played one game fewer than the Rangers, who are host to
the Washington Capitals on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was huge for us,'' said Rangers goalie Dan Cloutier,
who made 31 saves. ``This was crucial when you're fighting for a
playoff spot. Every shift of every game is important.''
</P>
<P>
   But for much of the game, the Rangers played down to the level
of the Islanders, who are the second-worst team in the National
Hockey League. The Rangers were outplayed badly in the second and
third periods, surrendering a two-goal lead in the process. During
a 20-minute-10-second stretch bridging the second and third
periods, the Rangers failed to register a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we were the better team today,'' said Trevor
Linden, the Islanders' captain. ``But the bottom line is we lost.
We've had a couple of overtime losses the last 10 days. You've got
to come away with a point.''
</P>
<P>
   After goals by Manny Malhotra and Kevin Stevens, the Islanders
stormed back on goals by Mariusz Czerkawski, late in the second
period, and Zigmund Palffy, who tied the score at 2-2 at 5:19 of
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra scored on the power play 3:37 into the game to put the
Rangers ahead by 1-0. Malhotra, an 18-year-old rookie, who has seen
his ice time increase significantly since the injury to Wayne
Gretzky, buried a rebound of Ulf Samuelsson's shot from the point.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders had many scoring opportunities in the opening
period, but could not finish them off. Joe Sacco was stopped twice
from point-blank range, and Palffy came so close, his arms went up
in celebration. But the Islanders did manage to kill off a
five-on-three advantage for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens scored the Rangers' second goal at 2:49 of the second
period, stretching his team's lead to 2-0. Like Malhotra, Stevens
tapped a rebound past Salo. Again, the Islanders' goalie was down
and out of position after stopping the Rangers' first shot.
</P>
<P>
   Czerkawski cut the Rangers' lead to 2-1 late in the second
period. He fired the puck over Cloutier's glove at 14:39 for his
14th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy scored the tying goal at 5:19 of the third period. He
fired a turnaround shot from the slot between Cloutier's pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a team that couldn't find a way to win a game last
year,'' Islanders Coach Bill Stewart said of the Rangers. ``But
this year they are finding a way.''
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Rich Pilon, the rugged Islanders defenseman, left the game
during the second period with back spasms. He is probable for
Monday's game at Buffalo. Pilon appeared in his 500th career game,
all with the Islanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
