</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS' KNOBLAUCH FINDS HIS NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Chuck Knoblauch's locker in the clubhouse is a
few feet from that of Derek Jeter, and the banter between the New
York Yankee infielders is as steady as the trains running to and
from Grand Central Terminal. Jeter likes to adjust his
pronunciation of Knoblauch's name _ ``Knob-a-lockah,'' Jeter will
say _ and they play catch together before each workout, their
friendship growing.
</P>
<P>
   It is far different from last spring, when Knoblauch first
joined the Yankees. He is approachable and friendly, but during the
1998 season he knew few of his teammates. Knoblauch often sat in
front of his locker, his seat turned inward, and ate his specially
prepared meals with few words for others. He was like the new kid
in school, sitting in the corner of the room, quiet and intent on
his work.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch is over this initial discomfort, which he believes
contributed to some of his struggles last season. ``It was almost
like going through my rookie year again,'' he said. ``But I'm glad
I went through it _ it's all a learning experience, and like with
everything, you've got to take the good with the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, 30, did many things well in 1998: As the leadoff
hitter, he was terrific at working the ball-strike count, fouling
off pitches and wearing down opposing starters; he averaged 4.09
pitches a plate appearance, fourth in the American League. With his
pesky approach, Knoblauch gave teammates opportunities to see what
the opposing pitcher was throwing well or poorly the first time
through the order. ``He really set the tone,'' Yankees pitcher
David Cone said. ``He probably didn't receive as much credit for
this as he should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch scored 117 runs, drove in 64 runs, and played
excellent defense in the final two months of the regular season. He
did not commit an error after Aug. 29, and only three in the second
half of the season, his range improving markedly.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the bench coach Don Zimmer acknowledged, Knoblauch was
not the same player who haunted the Yankees in the past. From 1994
to 1997 for the Minnesota Twins, Knoblauch batted .319; last year,
he hit .265, his average sliding under .250 in one stretch.
Knoblauch had a great spring last year, slashing line drives to the
opposite field, reaching base time after time. After the All-Star
Game break, however, Knoblauch fell into the habit of lifting fly
balls, rather than hitting ground balls and liners.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch had been an intimidating base runner for the Twins,
taking a huge lead, daring the pitcher to pick him off, and there
was the inherent threat of a stolen base once he reached first. He
seemed unusually passive on the bases last year, some on the team
convinced he had temporarily lost his fearlessness and was worried
about making mistakes. Knoblauch attempted to steal 43 times _ down
from 72 attempts the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in game two of the American League Championship Series,
Knoblauch stood and argued a call as the ball rolled behind him and
a Cleveland runner circled the bases with the tie-breaking run.
Afterward, Knoblauch was not fully aware of the reaction to his
blunder. But when he saw the replays later that night _ ``about
five times,'' he says now, chuckling _ he realized how bad the play
looked, and acknowledged the mistake the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The play itself, Cone said, was not as important as the
aftermath. ``He was a stand-up guy,'' Cone said. ``He stood up and
apologized, and that was extremely important. That next day, to me,
was when he turned the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   As Knoblauch recalled the play Sunday, Knoblauch compared
himself to a boxer stunned with a jab in the first round: The
circumstances forced him to concentrate the rest of the postseason.
He batted .286 in the final four games of the ALCS, and then .375
in the World Series against San Diego, his three-run home run in
Game 1 proving pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   Before manager Joe Torre left the team last week after learning
he had prostate cancer, he talked about how much more relaxed
Knoblauch was, how he had grown more comfortable with his
surroundings. On Sunday, Knoblauch played a joke on reliever Mike
Stanton. Everybody laughed, and Knoblauch stood in the middle of
the visitors' clubhouse here, doubled over, no longer the new kid
in school.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte, the left-handed pitcher who strained his elbow
last week, will play catch Monday, the first time he will test the
joint since he injured it ... Yankees officials are extremely
pleased with Hideki Irabu's effort to lose weight in the last two
weeks _ he has dropped 11 pounds, and he managed to keep up with
Roger Clemens in Saturday's workout ... Paul O'Neill continues to
feel poorly from the flu that is making its way through the ranks
of Yankees; Chili Davis and others have also picked up the bug ...
Bernie Williams, out of action in recent days because of a strained
muscle, is expected to return to the lineup this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0249 </DOCNO>
