<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST-BOSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE AND PURDUE SURGE TO UPSETS AND THE ROUND OF 16
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Duke's waltz through college basketball's big dance
seemingly became easier Sunday when Miami and Cincinnati, seeded
second and third, respectively, in the East Regional, were
eliminated at the Fleet Center.
</P>
<P>
   Tenth-seeded Purdue scored the final 15 points of the first half
to build a commanding lead over Miami and coasted to a 73-63 upset.
Miami, one of the powers of the Big East Conference, never led and
only briefly challenged Purdue's double-digit lead in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue will meet sixth-seeded Temple in the regional semifinals
on Friday night at East Rutherford, N.J. Temple defeated
Cincinnati, 64-54.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Miami won the first NCAA tournament game in its
history with a 21-point victory over Lafayette. Sunday, Miami's
play was listless and careless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one of those off nights at a time when the other team
was having a good night,'' Miami Coach Leonard Hamilton said. ``It
wasn't very good timing on our part.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's weekend sweep was somewhat stunning since the
Boilermakers had lost five of their last six Big Ten games heading
into the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people didn't even think we belonged in this
tournament,'' said Purdue forward Brian Cardinal, who had 20 points
and 6 rebounds. ``It's kind of fun to shock people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal acknowledged that a trip to the Round of 16 was even
beyond his expectations. Asked what he would have said a week ago
if someone had told him he was going to the regional semifinals,
Cardinal said, ``I'd have wanted to know where I was sitting in the
stands because that's the only way I would have thought I'd be
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim James, Miami's star forward, led his team with 19 points,
but James, who missed 14 of 21 shots, appeared hampered by the back
stiffness that nearly kept him out of Friday's victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say Tim's injury was a factor,'' Hamilton
said. ``But anyone who has seen him play in the past would have
noticed that his quickness and agility was not the same as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   But James was just one of several Miami players struggling in
the first half, when Miami made just 18.2 percent of its shots from
the floor, including 0 for 7 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening game, Cincinnati became the only team in the
history of the NCAA tournament to be seeded second or third in
three consecutive years and not advance to at least the regional
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati, the only team to defeat top-ranked Duke this season,
has fashioned a national reputation for athleticism, aggressiveness
and a snarling, dependable defense, but the Bearcats played timidly
Sunday. Temple's matchup zone defense dominated the game, forcing
Cincinnati into 16 turnovers and 34.7 percent field-goal shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of a showing for one of the glamour programs in the
nation, a program that won 27 games this season and has not won
fewer than 26 games in the last four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Temple has a rich basketball history, and though the Owls
had twice lost to Cincinnati in the NCAA tournament in the 1990s,
they were not intimidated Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't afraid of them; they were afraid of us,'' Temple
guard Rasheed Brokenborough said. ``You could see in the first
three minutes of the game, they were worried and confused by our
zone. They were trying to use their athleticism and they didn't use
their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple took a 6-0 lead, and when Cincinnati made up that
deficit, Temple then outscored Cincinnati, 23-5. Cincinnati went 8
minutes 31 seconds without a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't attack,'' Cincinnati Coach Bob Huggins said.
``We kind of stood around on the perimeter and missed a lot of
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins said he was not concerned his team would be considered
underachievers, despite the three successive NCAA losses in either
the first or second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read the papers or listen to talk shows and those are
the only people who would say something like that,'' Huggins said.
``I don't worry about that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For Temple, the key substitution was guard Quincy Wadley, who
had played sparingly in recent weeks because of a broken finger on
his nonshooting hand. He came off the bench to score 14 points,
hitting four 3-point shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIDWEST-MILWAUKEE     03-14 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-MILWAUKEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEAVES ROUSES MICHIGAN STATE IN TIME TO ADVANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ When it came time for Mateen Cleaves to wake up, and
wake his team up, he did so in the nick of time. For much of
Sunday's second-round game in the Midwest Regional, Cleaves, the
all-America guard for top-seeded Michigan State, played in
desultory fashion against ninth-seeded Mississippi. Cleaves had
been racking up nearly as many turnovers as points at the Bradley
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi led by 3 at the half, and Cleaves had 8 points and 5
turnovers. And with less than five minutes to play, Cleaves, a
6-foot-2-inch junior who is built as solid as a beer keg, was
embarrassed when the player he was guarding, 5-5 Jason Harrison,
drilled a 3-point shot at the shot-clock buzzer to break a tie.
</P>
<P>
   That shot apparently shook Cleaves from his slumber, and he went
on to propel Michigan State to a 74-66 victory.
</P>
<P>
   He came down and hit a 3-pointer in the face of Harrison to tie
the game. He then drove and scored against Harrison on the next
possession, hit Antonio Smith with a scoring pass under the basket,
then scored again on a steal and fullcourt layup. After that, he
rebounded a Mississippi miss and dished to Morris Peterson for
another score. Suddenly, the game had turned irrevocably around.
Michigan State led by 67-59 after an 11-0 run with just over a
minute to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that's my role,'' Cleaves said. ``The guys know
that down the stretch I can hit some big shots. We call that money
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves finished with a team-high 18 points, seven assists and
had just one turnover in the second half. Jason Smith and Marcus
Hicks, who formed a formidable front line for Ole Miss, scored 18
and 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the half, we knew we could match their talent,'' said
Antonio Smith, the Michigan State forward. ``We just had to match
their intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans now go to St. Louis where they meet Oklahoma, 85-72
upset winners Sunday over North Carolina-Charlotte, on Friday in
the Round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, for Michigan State, could not have been any more
satisfying than it was for the Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to the Sweet 16!'' shouted Oklahoma Coach Kelvin
Sampson. ``I think there's some irony in that statement. We just
play basketball. We run our stuff. We're not going to wow you. I'm
tired of saying our players don't get their due. But the Sweet 16
gives us our credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, presumably the last at-large team chosen in the
64-team tournament and seeded 13th, led NC-Charlotte, the
fifth-seeded team, throughout the game, and by 15 points at the
half. The 49ers cut their deficit to 7 points on a 3-point shot by
Kedric Smith with just over four minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Just under a minute later, Oklahoma's Eric Martin, who scored 18
points, committed his fifth and final foul.
</P>
<P>
   The NC-Charlotte rooters, dressed in the blue and white school
colors, were shouting and shaking their pompoms. But Eduardo
Najera, as he had all day, replied immediately. He got fouled on a
drive and sank both free throws to make it 72-63.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the bench I was a nervous wreck; I could hardly watch the
game,'' Martin said. ``We had a lead, but with the 3-point shot in
today's game, it's so easy to come back.'' But the Sooners didn't,
and NC-Charlotte was unable to get any closer than it had after
Smith's shot.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma's coach and players had expressed huge disappointment
that they were given such little recognition in the seeding after
their 20-10 regular season. But they came into this game on a high
note after having upset fourth-seeded Arizona, 61-60, in the first
round on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After Oklahoma had built a 21-6 lead with 13 minutes left in the
first half, it seemed that neither the Sooners nor NC-Charlotte had
the time or the inclination to score a field goal, until Martin
sank a three-pointer for the Sooners with 6:55 remaining. Oklahoma
had also developed its lead without any points from its leading
scorer, Najera, the 6-8 native of Chihuahua, Mexico. Najera had
disappointed his father, Servando, a former Mexican League
infielder, when he grew too tall to play third base, but he has
obviously done his family proud as a basketball player. Even when
not scoring, one hardly notices, since Najera is so helpful in
every other area of the game, from passing to rebounding to
skidding nose-first across the court for a loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   Najera finished with 20 points and 15 rebounds, high for his
team in both departments. The sophomore Sooners guard Alex
Spaulding also gave a lift at critical points, hitting a big
3-pointer, 7 of 12 free throws _ all in the second half _ and
scoring 12 points and compiling 8 assists. Galen Young, the swift,
strong forward for N.C.-Charlotte. led his team with 23 points, 13
rebounds and six assists. Kelvin Price, normally the starting
center for Charlotte, was suffering from the flu and played just 23
minutes and scored five points.
</P>
<P>
   This is Sampson's fifth season as the coach at Oklahoma. He has
taken his team to the tournament in each of them _ but it was not
until this year that he had finally won a game in it.
</P>
<P>
   He's got five days now to figure out how to beat Coach Tom Izzo
and his favored Michigan State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
