<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PITCHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' WILSON DOESN'T WANT TO START SEASON IN THE MINORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ On his final day with the Mets before the
regular season starts, Tom Seaver was asked Sunday which young
pitchers had impressed him most in his nearly two weeks around the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Isringhausen, Paul Wilson, Grant Roberts and Octavio
Dotel, replied Seaver, who is scheduled to leave for his Napa
Valley, Calif., home on Monday. ``They've all got good, live
arms,'' said Seaver, who served as a roving instructor here and who
will broadcast Mets games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Arms that should not be rushed, however, the Hall of Famer
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are still seeking to improve their starting pitching
via a trade. But there is also the chance that they could give up
on Hideo Nomo or Masato Yoshii before the season starts, which
would open a spot.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo has struggled with his control for nearly two years. Yoshii
was hit hard in his first two appearances of the spring before
throwing four scoreless innings against the Florida Marlins in
Viera, Fla., in a split-squad game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners have expressed interest in one of the two
Japanese pitchers, a baseball executive said Sunday. That might
provide an opening for Wilson, who has not allowed an earned run in
nine innings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   But not if Seaver is allowed anything to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happened,'' Seaver said, envisioning a scenario where
Wilson would begin the season with the Mets, ``that's when I would
raise my hand and say, `No! No!' I think that would be a mistake.
He needs innings pitched. Both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver was also referring to Isringhausen. But there is almost
no chance that the 26-year-old Isringhausen _ who missed all of
last year because of elbow surgery _ will begin the season with the
Mets. He has allowed two earned runs in four innings while striking
out seven this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been a bit more of a question mark since training
camp began. On Saturday in the Dominican Republic, however, after
Wilson had tossed four scoreless innings, Mets manager Bobby
Valentine was asked if Wilson's chances of making the team had
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Valentine said. ``He's doing a very good
job to get back here, but I haven't seen anything change. I believe
he is going to be a major league pitcher for a long time. But he
needs to put Class AAA behind him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver agrees. Wilson, however, does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that mean?'' Wilson, the first overall pick of the 1994
draft, said Sunday. ``I put Class AAA behind me three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Wilson underwent labrum surgery on his right
shoulder in November 1996. Since then the right-hander, who turns
26 two weeks from Sunday, has pitched just 822/3 innings, including
382/3 innings last year at the Triple A level.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this spring, Wilson said he knew that the Mets had six
pitchers with six guaranteed contracts (and none of them him) vying
for their starting staff, and that he was resigned to beginning the
season at Triple A Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``But maybe all along I never wanted to believe it,'' Wilson,
who came to camp bigger and stronger than ever, said Sunday. ``That
it still wasn't the end of the story. It was just a way to put it
out of my head while we're preparing for the season. But I'm
frustrated with the system. And I think I have a right to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wilson has said previously that he would take a
demotion, if and when it came, in stride, he cannot help being
impatient and feeling he belongs with the major league club now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was on a different team, would I be making the team?''
Wilson asked. ``It just comes down not to fighting for a job, but
to there not being jobs available.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the caution that his manager, General Manager Steve
Phillips and Seaver want? ``I'm tired of being cautious,'' Wilson
said. ``I just want to be a part of it so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are likely to make their first cuts of the spring on
Monday. Wilson will most likely be spared, but probably only until
a later date.
</P>
<P>
   And if that time comes this year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll gripe and moan for about a day,'' Wilson said. ``And then
I'll go down there and do my job.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
