<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE COURT AND DISABLED STUDENTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Iowa)   (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, March 15:
</P>
<P>
   In an important recent decision, the Supreme Court interpreted
federal law to require public schools to pay for special care for
students with disabilities as long as the services can be provided
by someone other than a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in the case of a bright quadriplegic boy in Iowa
who was dependent on a ventilator and could not attend school
without a trained aide to monitor his needs. The 7-to-2 decision
was based on the Individuals With Disabilities Education Act, which
guarantees a ``free appropriate public education'' to students with
disabilities, and requires districts to furnish special education
and ``related services.''
</P>
<P>
   From a legal and humane standpoint, it is the right outcome.
Children should not be isolated or their education limited because
of a disability. But the decision also raises serious concerns. As
a practical matter, the expansive ruling will impose new financial
burdens on local school districts already struggling with the
mounting costs of special-education mandates _ exacerbating a
longstanding problem Congress needs to address, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   Educating disabled youngsters is a national obligation. The
expense should be borne by the nation as a whole, not imposed
haphazardly on states or financially strapped districts that happen
to serve a large number of disabled students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
