<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NEWSWEEK-EVERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYA'S NEW CROWN IS KNOCKED ASKEW BY PHILIPPOUSSIS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIAN WELLS, Calif. _ It seemed like only yesterday that Carlos
Moya, the newest No. 1 in men's tennis, was brandishing a champagne
bottle in one hand and a crystal trophy in the other as he jumped
in a Jacuzzi to celebrate his installation as ``king of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, after dutifully picking up his racquet for his first
official assignment as the top-ranked player, Moya had his new
crown rudely knocked askew by Mark Philippoussis of Australia in
the final of the Newsweek Champions Cup. Moya, who is guaranteed a
two-week reign at the top, and Philippoussis, who will move to a
career-high 11th, dueled in the searing desert sun for nearly three
hours before Philippoussis won, 5-7, 6-4, 6-4, 4-6, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have played the best match that I ever played
against him, but I still didn't beat him,'' said Moya, whose 0-3
record against Philippoussis includes a contentious semifinal loss
at the 1998 United States Open. ``I'm very confident, and maybe I
think now that I can beat anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Moya, who picked up his first Grand Slam title
at last year's French Open, became the first Spanish man to earn
the top ranking by prevailing over Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil in
their semifinal on Saturday. Dealing with the heavy artillery of
the unseeded Philippoussis was too taxing, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be No. 1 and then win the title on top of that, it would
have been the perfect beginning,'' said Moya, who was seeded fourth
here. ``But today he's better than me, so that's it. He has a great
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Living up to his reputation as a purveyor of ballistic serves,
Philippoussis had three aces in the final game of the match. His
impudent parting shot at Moya was a 129-mile-an-hour ace, his 23rd
of the confrontation. The 22-year-old Philippoussis, who was a
distant runner-up to his countryman Patrick Rafter last year in the
United States Open final, described himself as a slow bloomer after
earning his seventh career title and his first in one of the ATP
Tour's showcase events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big kid, a slow maturer,'' he said. ``I just had a lot
of other things on my mind. I love having fun.'' Philippoussis was
pondering premature retirement last spring until, coaxed to test
his serve-and-volley prowess at Wimbledon by his fellow Australians
John Newcombe and Pat Cash, he reached the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Now coached by Gavin Hopper, a fitness fanatic, and Cash, the
1987 Wimbledon champion, Philippoussis has declared himself mature
enough to take on, outwork and possibly even outlast the likes of
Moya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working hard the last few months, concentrating on
the court, just been fighting and enjoying the challenge, I'd have
to say,'' said Philippoussis, whose 14-2 start this season is the
best of his career. ``I think what's improved for me is just my
self-belief. In the past I would have broken down if it went to
five, sort of not gave it to him, but just mentally lost it in the
fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was Moya, already annoyed with himself for missing a
break point opportunity that would have put him ahead by 5-3 in the
third set, who felt his resolve cave in after Philippoussis broke
him in the third game of the fifth set. A weary, frazzled and
unconvincing passing shot that buried itself in the net allowed
Philippoussis a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he broke me at the beginning of the fifth set, I was
fighting like crazy, running to get to every ball,'' Moya said.
``And then stupid things, he broke me, and it makes me feel like
I'm there for nothing.'' Moya lost his serve again to trail by 5-2
when he barreled an easy forehand out of bounds at break point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I was a little bit tired, maybe mentally,'' Moya said.
He admitted that he had expended ample mental energy last week when
he discovered that he was in the hunt for Pete Sampras' No. 1 spot,
despite a horrible beginning to the season that included a
first-round loss at the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   When this event began, Moya was part of a four-man posse that
included his fellow Spaniard Alex Corretja, the Australian Open
champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov and Rafter, a two-time United States
Open champion. Once Sampras, who was eight weeks short of tying
Ivan Lendl's record 270 weeks at the top, took an opening-round
tumble against Felix Mantilla, all four of them had a chance of
toppling him.
</P>
<P>
   Moya now faces a similar scenario at the Lipton Championships,
which begin Thursday at Key Biscayne, Fla. Sampras, Corretja,
Kafelnikov and Rafter will have an opportunity to make Moya's reign
a brief one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being top 10 means you have to win every match,'' Moya said.
``Now I have to win even more matches than before.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
