<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 WAS EARLY CASUALTY OF MARCH MADNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Air! Give Pacific-10 commish Tom Hansen some air!
</P>
<P>
   Four teams, five games, and they're ... gone! The last time the
league didn't place a team in the Sweet 16 (1987), Walt Hazzard was
coaching UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected it, but perhaps we should have. After a
sparkling four-year tournament run that included two national
titles and 11 Sweet 16 appearances, the Pac-10 was due for some
early exits.
</P>
<P>
   If you're searching for an explanation, a trend, a theory _
don't. There isn't one. That's the beauty of March Madness, where
the only constant is chaos. Here's a quick look at the Pac-10
collapses:
</P>
<P>
   _Despite the discrepancy in seed, No.2 Stanford's loss to
Gonzaga was a mild upset at best. Stanford was injury-riddled and
exhausted; Gonzaga was skilled, experienced and beautifully
coached.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs beat Washington and lost close games at Kansas,
Purdue, Detroit and Texas Christian. They were playing a few hours
from home, in Seattle, and their seed (10) wasn't commensurate with
their credentials.
</P>
<P>
   _Washington's loss to Miami-Ohio was easy to predict. The
Huskies played poorly in the stretch, losing twice in Los Angeles,
and never seemed comfortable away from Edmundson Pavilion. They had
no chance against Wally Szczerbiak. Give up 43 points to one
player, and you deserve to lose.
</P>
<P>
   _Arizona's exit is not as easily explained, except the Wildcats
hadn't had a first-round loss in four years, so Lute Olson was due.
They also faced one of the nation's most underachieving teams,
Oklahoma, whose seed masked its talent.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been a battle of the present and future Arizona
coaches. Wildcats athletic director Jim Livengood hired Kelvin
Sampson at Washington State and could do it again in Tucson when
Olson retires. If Sampson does replace Olson, the league's coaches
will rejoice. Arizona could do a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   _For the third time in four years, UCLA drew a first-round foe
that loved to play slow _ first Princeton, then Miami, then
Detroit. Perhaps the selection committee is sending the Bruins a
message: Learn to play a complete game, or depart early. If not for
the UCLA women's team, which beat Wisconsin-Green Bay on Saturday,
it might have been the worst sporting week in school history.
</P>
<P>
   First weekend fodder: Sweet 16 seeds, by region: East _ 1, 6,
10, 12; Midwest _ 1, 3, 10, 13; West _ 1, 5, 6, 10; South _ 1, 2,
3, 4.
</P>
<P>
   Florida guard Eddie Shannon has a prosthetic eye, but he saw the
floor well enough to compile seven assists and five steals in the
second-round victory over Weber State. Shannon was an easy pick for
U.S. Basketball Writers' Most Courageous Player Award.
</P>
<P>
   Word is Gonzaga coach Dan Monson considers Washington State a
dead-end position; he won't replace departed coach Kevin Eastman.
Smart move. Monson has most of his best players back next year and
should be in line for a better job.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for former Arizona State interim coach Don Newman to get
the Wazu gig. He was an assistant there under Kelvin Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: Kentucky-Kansas was the best game so far, but
Kentucky-Duke in the Final Four will be the game of the tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2256EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0147 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEMPLE-CINCY-HNS &LR;      03-14 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-CINCY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It took less than 20 seconds for the player to get
slammed to the floor from a collision away from the ball. To no
one's surprise, he was a Temple Owl.
</P>
<P>
   But to nearly everyone's surprise, the final thud heard at the
FleetCenter came at the expense of the Cincinnati Bearcats, who had
the door to the Sweet 16 slammed in their faces _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Temple, which scored the first six points and went on a 15-2 run
shortly thereafter to take control, never trailed in walking past
third-seeded Cincinnati 64-54 Sunday in an East Regional game.
</P>
<P>
   Temple (23-10) will face Purdue in a regional semifinal March 19
at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati and Kentucky are the only schools that have been
seeded in the top three of the Tournament in each of the past three
years. But the Wildcats, who moved into the Sweet 16 with a victory
against Kansas on Sunday, have advanced to two consecutive
championship games, while the Bearcats have now lost three
consecutive second-round contests.
</P>
<P>
   Temple has been to 10 consecutive NCAA tournaments, but this is
the first time the Owls have advanced past the second round in six
seasons. The meeting was the third between the teams in the last
five tournaments, with Cincinnati prevailing in the first two (1995
and '96).
</P>
<P>
   It was apparent from the start that Temple, a No. 6 seed, was
not bothered by its Tournament record vs. the Bearcats or its
underdog status.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls employed coach John Chaney's famed matchup zone to
perfection, forcing Cincinnati to play from the outside in, but the
outside shots weren't falling and the Bearcats never came up with
another plan of attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach always told us that your will is stronger than your
skill, and they tried to beat us athletically,'' Temple guard
Rasheed Brokenborough said. ``They didn't try to use their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew from the first play they were going to have problems
with our zone. They were really hesitant out there, and they really
weren't attacking the zone like you're supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats elected to fire away from behind the 3-point arc,
taking almost half their shots in the first period from long range
and hitting just 2-of-9. For the game, Cincinnati was 6-for-22.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have anybody that when you leave him open outside he
can make the shot,'' Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins said. ``If we
don't make shots, we have a tough time beating people.''
</P>
<P>
   With the missed shots (Cincinnati went 17-of-49 for 34.7 percent
from the field), the Bearcats rarely got their press set up and
ended the game with just one point coming via a fast break. The
Bearcats' bench also was soundly whipped, getting outscored 20-1.
Cincinnati's reserves average 23.9 points a game, 32 percent of the
team's offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats also pointed to their rebounding as a problem in
the loss. Though Temple grabbed only one more rebound and was
outrebounded by three on the offensive end, the battle on the
boards appeared to be one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats managed to pull within seven points with less than
50 seconds remaining in the game, but they did not have any
timeouts left and the Owls made enough free throws in the final
minute to hang on.
</P>
<P>
   Lamont Barnes led Temple with 15 points and point guard Pepe
Sanchez matched Quincy Wadley with 14.
</P>
<P>
   Post Kenyon Martin led Cincinnati with 16 points. Melvin Levett
had 14 points and Steve Logan 13, but the Bearcats' backcourt
starters combined to hit just eight of 27 shots from the field,
including six of 20 3-pointers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
