<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGOLAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUN BUILDS AS LEGOLAND CALIFORNIA PREPARES TO OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUE DOERFLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ It's an Oz-like fantasy world where yellow
bricks _ and red, green and blue ones, too _ predominate. Lego
bricks, that is. Millions of them.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland California opens Saturday, March20, 30 miles north of
San Diego. It's the third Legoland in the world, the first in the
United States. Spread across 128 acres, it's bigger than Disneyland
and just as colorful, in a primary tone sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   Lego designers from Billund, Denmark, where the toy was invented
by Ole Kirk Christiansen in 1932, pieced together the park, using
the actual plastic blocks that are sold in Lego kits in 138
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Christiansen, who first made them in wood before turning to
plastic in 1947, called them Lego, which is a contraction of the
Danish words ``leg godt,'' meaning ``play well.'' And, in Latin,
Lego means ``I put together'' or ``I assemble.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other theme parks that have their share of adult thrill
rides, the $130 million Legoland California is designed for the
younger set, those ages 2 to 12, the ages of most Lego users.
</P>
<P>
   For the $32 adult and $25 child admission price, visitors are
treated to a few rides, some that even all ages will like, but the
main attractions are the 5,000 phenomenal Lego models scattered
throughout the park.
</P>
<P>
   It took 2 million Lego bricks and months to create the 9-foot
tall, 34-foot-long red dinosaur near the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Einstein's brain power takes on new proportions in the
Imagination Zone area: 1.2 million gray bricks were used in the
15{-foot-tall representation of his head that fronts one of the
buildings. The 19-foot-tall black and gray animated tyrannosaurus
rex towering nearby required 1 million bricks.
</P>
<P>
   And even though it's called Miniland, this area, a one-twentieth
scale re-creation of the Manhattan skyline, Washington, D.C., San
Francisco, New Orleans and a New England harbor, is made of 20
million bricks. The Empire State Building alone is 200,000 bricks.
The U.S. Capitol required 380,792.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who remembers building horses, bridges and skyscrapers
with Legos as a child could spend hours looking at these creations.
</P>
<P>
   There are gray Lego brick elephants that spray water through
their trunks. Well-fed-looking zebras with black and white zigzags.
Red flamingos. Yes, red. Pink isn't in the Lego brick color
palette.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials could take out most of the rides and add more
models, and most Legomaniacs wouldn't even notice. Visitors still
would be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The model possibilities are endless.
</P>
<P>
   There are 102,981,500 ways to combine six 8-stud bricks of the
same color. Three 8-stud bricks can be combined in 1,060 ways.
</P>
<P>
   But the Southern California location means fitting in with the
surroundings, thus, there are a few rides, mainly slow-moving ones,
such as a boat ride and a safari-car ride. The roller coaster on
Castle Hill, while faster than other rides at the park, still is no
match for those at Six Flags or even a state fair.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Montgomery, vice president of park operations, is quick to
point out that Legoland California's atmosphere is different than
that of amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about racing up to the next ride,'' he said. ``Our
appeal is very different. The scale and magnitude of Disneyland is
what you're impressed with. What is impressive about us is more
subtle. It's a series of little surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the model of a dog and a fire hydrant. Or the Mount
Rushmore model, where two Lego guys are using a Lego Q-tip to clean
one of George Washington's ears. Or the moving marching band that
parades in front of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its more relaxed feel, Legoland shouldn't have trouble
attracting visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Name recognition alone is a draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're a very strong brand and because we're a park
that has quite a narrow, specific focus, people will travel a lot
farther to come here than to a thrill ride park,'' Montgomery said.
There are many amusement parks, but only one Legoland in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all children have heard of or played with Legos, he said.
The United States ranks second in sales volume for the company,
topped by Germany, where children receive an average of six to
seven kits a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each hour, 2 million Lego bricks are manufactured at factories
in Denmark and the United States. Through 1998, 189 billion Lego
pieces had been molded.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it does with its toys, Lego is promoting family
interaction throughout the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we have has some form of interaction and
decision-making,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   On one ride, called Sky Cycle, kids and their parents have to
work together to pedal a colorful, zany-looking car around an
elevated track. At the Kid Power Tower, they sit in outward-facing
seats and pull on a rope to propel themselves up 30 feet to the top
for a view of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   In the Imagination Zone, kids _ and their parents _ can build
race cars out of Legos, then compete with each other on a downhill
track. At the Driving School ride in the Fun Town area, young kids
drive electric Lego-looking cars around a streetscape, stopping at
signals and yielding to others.
</P>
<P>
   But what about older children and teens who won't be content to
putter along in cars that don't even bump into each other?
</P>
<P>
   Will older teens be bored? Possibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are flatly not looking to attract and don't expect we'll
see many teenagers at the park,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   But some teens will enjoy bringing younger siblings to the park.
And they are certain to enjoy the restaurants, food booths and the
Lego factory tour that shows how the bricks are made and packaged.
They may even pull out their old Lego sets when they return home
and get creative.
</P>
<P>
   And parents and grandparents? They'll be watching or interacting
with the younger set, when they're not marveling at all the amazing
Lego models. &QL; 
Sue Doerfler can be reached at 444-8236 or at
sue.doerfler(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
