<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT &LR;      03-14 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I recently returned from a ``Theater at Sea'' cruise on the
Stella Solaris, which took us from Rio de Janeiro up the Amazon to
Manaus. Every night, those of us who were on board as stars of
Broadway, opera and cabaret performed for the passengers. My New
York colleagues were Patricia Neal, Julie Wilson, Brian Bedford,
Lee Roy Reams, Anna Bergman, Patrice Munsel and Margaret Whiting,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   On boarding the ship, we were asked to fill out a brief form.
After duly writing in my name, address and passport number, I
decided to respond whimsically to the final question, ``How do you
want to be called?'' by filling in the blank with ``hey you''
contracting it, for more whimsy, to ``heyou.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess I shouldn't have been surprised when the passenger guest
list was slipped under our door. There I was, listed as ``Heyou
Alexander.'' It gave us all a good laugh. _ JANE ALEXANDER
</P>
<P>
   MARCH
</P>
<P>
   Lion or lamb?
</P>
<P>
   Science or scam?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it really a matter of luck
</P>
<P>
   Whether or no
</P>
<P>
   The weather is so?
</P>
<P>
   'Cause March came in like a duck.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT H. NUTT
</P>
<P>
   The voice came from behind as Alison Schiff walked in Central
Park. ``Drop it,'' it said. Ms. Schiff turned to see a woman
scolding a dog on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a doughnut,'' the voice continued. ``And you just got
your figure back.''
</P>
<P>
   Scene: The warehouse sale at Barneys.
</P>
<P>
   Participants: Baile Jaffe and a sales clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jaffe: ``Would you help me find ties to match this suit for
my husband?''
</P>
<P>
   Sales clerk: ``Sure, what does your husband do? Is he a
banker?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jaffe: ``No, he's a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales clerk: ``What kind of doctor?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jaffe: ``Psychiatrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales clerk: ``Does he work in a hospital or an outpatient
clinic?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jaffe: ``Outpatient clinic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales clerk: ``Does he work with mainly depressed or manics? It
makes a difference, you know. A bright color would cheer up a
depressed person and a subdued tie would calm a manic person.''
</P>
<P>
   A professor of French history boarded a city bus on a bright but
showery day. Windows were open, so some of the seats had little
pools of water. The professor selected a dry seat, sat down, and
absent-mindedly took out a tissue and began to wipe up the moisture
on the seat beside her. The silence on the bus was broken by a
woman opposite the professor, who leaned forward and said, ``Do you
have any days free?''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Herrig was shopping at a specialty food store on
Lexington Avenue in the 80s. Waiting at the cash register, he was
startled when the man in front of him turned and pointed to a
basket of produce. ``That's the kind that usually get slapped,'' he
said sotto voce.
</P>
<P>
   Another weirdo, Herrig thought. Then he noticed the sign above
the basket _ ``Fresh Dates.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion Tuttle's 7-year-old niece, Stacey Day, had just received
a present and called her grandmother to share the news. ``It's the
greatest game, Grandma,'' she said. ``It's called Chinese checkers
and you don't even have to turn on the computer to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSY B's
</P>
<P>
   Alphabetically speaking, the B is abuzz,
</P>
<P>
   Doing what no other consonant does.
</P>
<P>
   Alone, it's a vitamin, blood type or grade;
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, the bolivar paid,
</P>
<P>
   A symbol for boron, a bishop in chess,
</P>
<P>
   A note, often flat, under musical stress,
</P>
<P>
   A BB's a gunshot, and travelers know
</P>
<P>
   A quaint B &AMP; B is the ``inn'' way to go!
</P>
<P>
   There are B-to-B ads in mellifluous tones
</P>
<P>
   Of Bell Atlantic's own James Earl Jones,
</P>
<P>
   But the twin B's have gained a new connotation
</P>
<P>
   As the B-line for '99's hot destination:
</P>
<P>
   The B &AMP; B we are packing for now _
</P>
<P>
   Is Spain's Barcelona _ and Bilbao!
</P>
<P>
   _ JOAN SOCOLOF
</P>
<P>
   David Creed, strolling on Columbus Avenue, took it in stride
when a well-dressed man walked up to him and asked, ``How are you
on Cole Porter lyrics?'' and almost immediately went on to ask,
``What comes after this: `A cigarette that bears a lipstick's
traces/An airline ticket to romantic places?''' Creed offered,
``Oh, how the ghost of you clings/These foolish things remind me of
you.'' The man thanked him and went off.
</P>
<P>
   Creed returned home, looked up the lyrics of ``These Foolish
Things'' and discovered that he was only partly correct. It should
have been ``And still my heart has wings/These foolish things
remind me of you.'' Nonetheless, he was still one-up on his
questioner. The song was not written by Cole Porter but by Eric
Maschwitz, Harry Link and Jack Strachey.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Nancy Y. Arndt loves New York: Shopping at
Bergdorf Goodman, she asked for directions to the Chanel
department. ``Take a left at the third chandelier,'' she was told.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Brand and her husband were having lunch at a neighborhood
restaurant in the East 70s and discussing what to do after they had
finished. The waitress, overhearing the conversation, said, ``You
should go to the Frick; it's really wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   When she left the table, Mrs. Brand and her husband wondered,
``Does she think we're tourists?'' And when the waitress returned,
Mrs. Brand asked her just that question. ``Oh, no,'' the waitress
answered. ``You're wearing too much black to be from out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   One thing I remember well from my youth is the family radio. The
evening shows were always so entertaining _ Fibber McGee and Molly,
Amos and Andy, the Shadow and many more.
</P>
<P>
   Time passed and World War II started. I joined the Army and was
stationed all over the world. We were lucky to have time to write
home or be fortunate enough to have a radio and tune in to the news
and music of the Armed Forces radio. Even Tokyo Rose and Axis Sally
supplied us with music.
</P>
<P>
   All the great music provided by Crosby, Perry Como, Sinatra,
Ella Fitzgerald, Doris Day, Benny Goodman and the big bands gave us
memories that will last forever. And with the music of Berlin,
Gershwin and Cole Porter, we made sure we were never without the
wonderful radio.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the war was over and I treasured the great American
classics each time I found them on my radio stations. Last year
there was only one such station left _ WQEW (1560 AM) _ and in
December that station changed its format.
</P>
<P>
   So it was over: The music I loved is gone, my romance with radio
is finally finished.
</P>
<P>
   _ FRANCIS DAHMS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990314.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0263 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORTS-AZR &LR;      03-14 1660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX-AREA SKIES ARE JAMMED, AIR PORTS SPUR FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ To the layman, the Phoenix area's flyway chart _ a sky
map for pilots _ is a confusing quilt of circles and arrows, dotted
lines and cryptic symbols.
</P>
<P>
   But a warning, found on the inside flap, is plain enough: The
skies may be friendly, but they sure are crowded.
</P>
<P>
   According to state records, more and more planes are flying out
of the Phoenix area's general aviation airports, which are on a
collision course with urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Around the airports, sagebrush and sidewinders have given way to
tile roofs and swing sets. Census figures show the population is
growing steadily, right along with the air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   With more planes flying over more houses, neighborhood activists
say it's only a matter of time before tragedy strikes, and a plane
crashes in a neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only thing that hasn't happened,'' said Don
Hopkins, a Scottsdale resident who has battled the city over
airport noise. ``There have been crashes, but they haven't been
severe enough yet for elected officials to understand there is a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, two planes collided near Scottsdale Municipal
Airport, killing two men and peppering an apartment complex and a
golf course with debris.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a plane in a mock dogfight failed to pull out of a
dive and crashed in the desert northwest of Phoenix, killing two.
At least one witnesses observed the crash from the parking lot of
an outlet mall.
</P>
<P>
   In February, high winds dragged a hot-air balloon across
rooftops in Peoria, seriously injuring a passenger and damaging two
homes. Since October, four F-16s flying out of Luke Air Force Base
have crashed near the increasingly populated area, prompting the
base commander to briefly ground his 212 fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials note that crashes are fairly rare, and say
safety really doesn't really drive the encroachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying is dangerous,'' said Deer Valley Municipal Airport
Manager Walt Fix, ``because you have to drive to the airport to get
to your airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   The key issue, they say, is aircraft noise, which spawns
hundreds of complaints from residents whose homes are beneath the
flight path.
</P>
<P>
   Airport executives take those complaints seriously, mostly
because they can be fatal to small airports. According to a
national aviation group, some 50 to 70 small airports close each
year, and encroachment is the No. 1 reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airports that take the approach `We were here first' are
playing a very short-term game,'' said Scottsdale airport Manager
John Kinney, ``and they'll lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials employ multiple tactics to deal with
encroachment: meeting with residents, encouraging low-density
development and sometimes buying land to block new neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   There are also laws that require builders to tell prospective
home buyers about airports, though they don't always work. People
continue to buy homes near airports, some knowingly, some not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a gal on the phone a few months ago, and she literally
was crying because she realized she was too close to the airport
after she built a custom home,'' said Mark Meyers, manager of
Falcon Field in Mesa. ``She didn't realize we were here, and she's
three-quarters of a mile away from the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   As sprawl continues in once-remote areas of Maricopa County,
skirmishes have flared up between homeowners and airports:
</P>
<P>
   In Gilbert, residents are suing U.S. Homes, alleging that the
developer did not disclose the impact of Williams Gateway Airport.
Traffic has steadily increased at the airport, which has been
touted as a future alternative to Sky Harbor for cargo and
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   In Chandler, the city will ask voters to approve a controversial
plan to lengthen the runway at the city airport. Residents who
oppose the plan say the city's ultimate goal is to attract larger
corporate jets.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, airport officials abandoned plans for a second
runway, mostly because of noise concerns. The city recently bought
200 acres just south of the airport to stop a development that
would have put 600 homes a stone's throw from the runway. Airports
officials have also restricted training flights at night.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesa, city officials ended a bitter fight by buying about 134
acres that buffered the residents of Red Mountain Ranch from TRW
Inc., a helicopter plant and nearby Falcon Field.
</P>
<P>
   As those fights play themselves out, the number of people living
near Phoenix-area airports continues to grow, according to census
figures.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at Falcon Field, air traffic has increased 50
percent since 1988. Between 1990 and 1995, the population around
the airport rose 98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic at Glendale Municipal Airport has risen 24 percent since
1998. Meanwhile, the population near the airport grew by 142
percent from 1990 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the smaller airports has siphoned small air
traffic away from Sky Harbor, leaving more room for larger planes.
General aviation at Sky Harbor dropped 33 percent between 1988 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Johnston, a Sky Harbor spokeswoman and pilot, said small
airports are just ``easier and quicker'' for general aviation
pilots to use.
</P>
<P>
   The airports haven't always been in competition with
neighborhoods. When they were first built, they were in the middle
of nowhere. The military, which used them for training, competed
with creosote bushes and the occasional coyote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the evolution of an airport, it starts in an
isolated area,'' Kinney said. ``Development takes place, in part
because of the airport, in part because of businesses located near
the airport, and it has that ripple effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being surrounded by neighborhoods, airports seem
determined to expand their operations.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale and Deer Valley, there are plans to extend or
improve runways, add hangars and attract more businesses. In the
East Phoenix area, both Chandler Municipal and Williams Gateway are
gearing up to grow.
</P>
<P>
   All the airports are big economic engines for the Valley of the
Sun, as the Phoenixarea is known. A recent study by Arizona State
University found that the Scottsdale airport generates about $119.6
million while Williams Gateway adds $113 million.
</P>
<P>
   With the helicopter plant (recently sold by Boeing to MD
Helicopters), Falcon Field generates about $866 million, while Sky
Harbor has an economic impact of $16 billion per year.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Torres, one of the Gilbert residents who is suing over
Williams Gateway, said he knows why the city wants to expand the
airport and lure cargo and passenger business from Sky Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the money,'' he said. ``They think that this is the
cash cow that's going to save their city bankrolls, that it will
bring in hotels, industry, and high-tech businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's going to turn it off . . . that's the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, Kinney said officials have worked hard to
encourage low density development, such as golf courses and
industrial parks, around the airport. The city also employs a
full-time noise abatement officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Residents) see we don't have horns and a tail and we will
work with them,'' Kinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Resident Hopkins writes off such statements as PR.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are employees of the city of Scottsdale, and it's
their business to keep that airport open and operating and making
money,'' Hopkins said. ``And the bottom of their list is noise
abatement and safety issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chandler, George Tandy Cook III says the city airport was
nothing more than a small strip when he moved into his log home in
1986. City officials told him it was going to stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was only one runway, and they didn't have any tower at
all,'' Cook said. ``They didn't have a fence around it. We used to
ride horses on the runway, and sit out there for hours waiting for
a plane to land.''
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. Today, there's a heliport about 100 yards
from Cook's home, though the city has promised to move it.
</P>
<P>
   The little airstrip has grown up into a thriving airport with
nearly 200,000 takeoffs and landings each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they don't want jets, they just want a bigger
runway,'' Cook said. ``We know that's a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Fix, Deer Valley's manager, says growth is inevitable around
airports, no matter how hard government officials try to manage it.
Even in the once-isolated area around Deer Valley, neighborhoods
are springing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously can't stretch our arms out beyond our land use
boundaries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While builders are required to disclose the airport's location
to home buyers, the airport still gets plenty of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become more and more of an issue over the last four and
half years,'' Fix said. ``As the residential areas grow near the
airport like they have, we get more complaint calls . . . and calls
from prospective home buyers wanting to to know more about the
airport before they purchase a home.''
</P>
<P>
   Deer Valley continues to expand. The airport plans to spend $15
million to build new hangars, remodel the terminal and reconstruct
the south runway.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing compared with business owners, who are preparing
for the arrival of the Outer Loop, which will slice through the
area in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been incredible,'' Fix said. ``Even right across the
street on Deer Valley Road, we have businesses going in, in all the
infill lots across the street, from 19th Avenue to Seventh
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinney, the Scottsdale airport manager, says Barry Goldwater
summed it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You can take an airport and build it in the absolute
middle of the Sahara Desert, and within five years, you'll be
completely surrounded by homes. I guarantee it.' '' &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at 444-8178 or at bill.muller(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
