<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NY     03-14 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' COACH PREPARED TO BE HELD ACCOUNTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The teaser worked. Jeff Van Gundy stayed tuned when
he heard his name mentioned just before a commercial during an NBC
broadcast Sunday. About 60 seconds later, NBC reported that Van
Gundy could be fired if the New York Knicks did not beat the
Charlotte Hornets Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did beat Charlotte. They wavered at times, but
unearthed an intense 11-2 fourth-quarter run to close out a 94-86
victory by leaning on an active Chris Dudley (13 rebounds) and some
pivotal jumpers from Latrell Sprewell, who scored 16 points. Allan
Houston added 20 points and Larry Johnson scored 19 to counter 23
points from the Hornets' newest arrival, Eddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, Van Gundy was reportedly on the verge of losing
his job, the way he was early in his first season, in his second
season and last year. A glib Van Gundy shrugged off the report
after he arrived at Madison Square Garden before Sunday night's
game, and the team president, Ernie Grunfeld, called it ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Van Gundy did not take comfort in the pregame
reassurances he received from management. It was hard to take
comfort in anything, with the Knicks having fallen to 11-9
following a horrendous, uninspired performance in a 76-63 loss to
the Chicago Bulls on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, until they fire you, they are never going to
say, `Hey, I'm thinking I'm going to fire you, but let's give it a
couple of games, and we'll see,''' Van Gundy said before the game.
``I'd say, `Hey, if we play like we did in Chicago, someone's got
to pay.' If we play like that consistently? It's my responsibility
to get the team to play with pride. I have no problem with being
held accountable for that. That's your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Van Gundy's job is to move his team to perform. And that
did not happen in Chicago. The Knicks showed no desire or pride as
they set franchise lows for points in a half (22) and field goals
in a game (19). They also tied a team mark with just five points in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of that performance, one official from the
Eastern Conference said Van Gundy's job was considered shaky but
added that Grunfeld's position was also in question. People within
the Knicks' organization have indicated that the relationship
between Grunfeld and Dave Checketts, the president of Madison
Square Garden, has cooled. Grunfeld, who has spent $64 million to
assemble the current roster, is also being held responsible for the
Knicks' underwhelming start this season.
</P>
<P>
   There have been injuries _ including ones to Sprewell and
Patrick Ewing _ but several other teams are struggling with health
problems and managing. So far, the moves the Knicks have made to
compensate for injuries and personnel changes have not consistently
worked out well. Marcus Camby, who arrived in a trade for Charles
Oakley, has not been the answer against physical teams. The passion
Oakley brought to the team has not been supplied by Kurt Thomas.
And Dennis Scott, who was signed to replace the shooting off the
bench once provided by the jettisoned John Starks, was waived
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy did not use the off-season moves as a cover. He
took responsibility for the problems that have haunted his team,
like poor rebounding, poor free-throw shooting and a lack of effort
on the road. Entering Sunday night's game, the inconsistencies had
meant just three victories in the Knicks' last nine games and a
five-game losing streak on the road. The atrocious loss to Chicago
only punctuated the obvious issues the Knicks face. So it did not
surprise Van Gundy to hear a report that his job was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wondered why it's taken so long,'' Van Gundy said. ``It
would be different if I didn't know what I was getting into. I knew
what I was getting into when I took the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny is intense in New York. Each loss leads to
questions about what is wrong with a team that started the night
fourth in the Atlantic Division. Some wonder if Van Gundy's
methods, and his pessimistic take on his team's play, have worn
thin on his players. At times, they appear to be tuning Van Gundy
out.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy disagreed, saying: ``I think that's a fiction type
thing. I don't think it happens as often as the media thinks. It's
not that simplistic. It's like 24 hours earlier they were listening
when we played Washington and then they stopped the next night in
Chicago. I don't know the answer, but I tell you the one way to
find out is what goes on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The core of the Knicks _ players like Johnson, Ewing and Houston
_ has been supportive of Van Gundy. After hearing the NBC report,
Houston said: ``I don't think there is a better-prepared coach than
Jeff. We have to look at ourselves after Chicago. Was that a
reflection on Jeff? I don't think it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has his stars' support. But he could not just dismiss
a television report that caught his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching,'' Van Gundy said. ``Then they said, `We'll
discuss Jeff Van Gundy when we return,' so I kept the TV on to find
out what was happening to me. Gee, I thought, maybe they'll say I
got a raise. You never know. You wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if we keep playing like we did against Chicago, my job
will be in jeopardy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
