<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-RENAULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN IN TALKS WITH RENAULT ABOUT STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Negotiations concerning the sale of a stake in Nissan
Motor Co., Japan's second-largest car maker, continued this past
weekend in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshikazu Hanawa, Nissan's president, and four other Nissan
executives flew to France on Saturday, people at the company said.
</P>
<P>
   In France, they were planning to meet with senior executives of
Renault SA, the French car maker that Nissan turned to after
Daimler-Chrysler AG broke off talks about taking a stake on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   NHK, the Japanese broadcasting company, reported Sunday night
that Hanawa had returned to Tokyo, apparently after discussions
with Louis Schweitzer, the head of Renault.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has decided it wants a deal by the end of the fiscal year
on March 31, though there is no obvious reason for the deadline.
Traditionally, Japanese companies prefer to settle all pending
matters and start the new fiscal year with a clean slate.
</P>
<P>
   Renault is expected to have a board meeting on Tuesday, after
which it may announce a deal, Nissan officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are expecting Nissan and Renault to reach some sort of
deal, largely because the French government, Renault's largest
shareholder, seems to favor it. The Nihon Keizai Shimbun financial
newspaper reported that officials from Japan's Ministry of Trade
and Industry were also talking with the French government to
support Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer said on Wednesday at the Geneva Auto Show that many
hurdles to a deal would be tough to overcome, like cultural
differences and development of a realistic plan for turning around
Nissan's operations and cutting its debt, which exceeds $21
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little overlap in the companies' operations, and,
unlike DaimlerChrysler, Renault has need of a big partner.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, as emissions regulations grow tougher in Europe,
Renault is interested in technology Nissan has developed for
producing more environmentally friendly cars. Renault also has its
eye on Nissan's two small-car plants in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A 33.4 percent stake in Nissan, the minimum needed for a board
veto under Japanese law, would cost more than 500 billion yen, or
$4.2 billion, based on Nissan's current share price. That price
would stretch Renault, which would have $2.1 billion in cash after
paying down its existing debt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
