<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEGOTIATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST FLIGHT ATTENDANTS' UNION CHIEF IN TALKS, THEN IN
ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When flight attendants union President Bill McGlashen
squares off in negotiations Wednesday against America West Airlines
management, he'll be fighting for more than a suitable contract.
</P>
<P>
   His job is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of March, members of the Association of Flight
Attendants Council 66 will choose between McGlashen and two
challengers, Lisa Bunch and Tim Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   With the strike deadline looming at the end of the day Friday,
McGlashen's ability to deliver a good contract or an effective
strike that wins concessions for the 2,400 flight attendants may be
a key factor in whether he's re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen's counterpart during three days of ``supermediation''
will be Greg Garger, America West's vice president of labor.
</P>
<P>
   Garger, who joined America West two years ago, helped negotiate
a contract with the mechanics union that was ratified in October.
He was joined by management labor consultant Jerry Glass during
those discussions, and Glass will be at Garger's side later this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Glass has his own consulting firm, J. Glass and Associates, in
Washington, D.C. He was America West's lead negotiator on the
pilots union contract and has represented other carriers, including
Mesa Air Group and Atlantic Coast Airlines, as well as trucking
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Garger, who shuns the spotlight that comes with a high-profile
labor dispute, said he's focused on reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Tempe-based America West, Garger spent 14 years
practicing employment and labor law with Winston and Strawn, a
Chicago firm. A Cornell University graduate, Garger represented
Caterpillar Inc. in a contentious labor battle with the United Auto
Workers that resulted in the longest strike in the heavy-equipment
company's history.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1995, the UAW ended a 17-month walkout with nothing
gained for more than 8,700 strikers.
</P>
<P>
   While Garger prefers a low profile, McGlashen seems comfortable
when the TV lights go on for live shots during union rallies and
news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   After joining America West as a flight attendant in 1989, he
became involved in organizing the flight attendants in 1994 and
became president of Council 66 last June.
</P>
<P>
   For McGlashen, it was a return to the political arena that he
first entered in 1997 when he immersed himself in Republican
campaigns in his home state of Texas. At age 21, he became the
central Texas youth coordinator for the Ronald Reagan presidential
campaign in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In his Tempe union office, McGlashen has a picture of himself
with President Reagan, who is disdained in union circles for
busting the air traffic controllers union.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen is quick to point out that it was an illegal strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't changed my stripes,'' he said, adding that he has
had disagreements with Reagan's politics over the years.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen also points out that it's not inconsistent to be a
Republican and a union leader. About 40 percent of union members
are Republicans, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his relatives are retired UAW members.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen was born near Flint, Mich., and raised in the Houston
area. He graduated from Houston Baptist College with a history
degree and worked in corporate communications for a Houston
hospital for about 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen then took a radio job in Albuquerque with KIVA-AM/FM
as a producer and salesman.
</P>
<P>
   His timing in joining America West didn't work out so well.
Within two years, the company filed for bankruptcy. McGlashen had
to take a 10 percent pay cut and his 60 shares of company stock
became worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's union president, McGlashen said he is used to the
ebb and flow of the job, which is similar to what he experienced in
political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Once he leaves office, McGlashen is eager to return to flying a
``normal schedule'' as a flight attendant and returning to work
part time at the Poisoned Pen, a Scottsdale mystery bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he has an interest in running for the state
Legislature from Tempe's District 27. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
