<SLUG> BC-DRAGON-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAGON SYSTEMS DELAYS INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock-market debut of Dragon Systems, a voice-recognition
software company in Newton, Mass., has been postponed until at
least next month, following Dragon's report of unexpectedly anemic
sales revenue in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon's Naturally Speaking software products have made the
small company the retail leader in its niche, against hefty
competition from IBM and weaker rivals including Lernout &AMP; Hauspie.
The company had expected to sell a minority stake to the public
this week.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, potential investors had been relying on
financial statements for the first nine months of 1998, though
Dragon warned that the fourth quarter was its most important
selling season. When the full year's numbers were tallied, in
amended financial statements filed recently with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, they showed less than exciting results.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon's sales revenue inched up only slightly in the fourth
quarter, to $21.8 million from $20.7 million in the third quarter.
By contrast, revenue in the fourth quarter of 1997 was more than
twice that reported in the third quarter of that year.
</P>
<P>
   And net income in the fourth quarter last year dipped to $1.6
million from $7.6 million in the third. Though the company posted
losses in all four quarters of 1997, its loss in the fourth quarter
of that year was considerably smaller than in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon's revenue for 1998 totaled $71.4 million, more than twice
its 1997 revenue of $26.8 million. And after several years of red
ink, Dragon posted profits in 1998 of $10.3 million, compared with
a loss of $5.3 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But when surprises like this crop up, underwriters typically
seek more time to explain them to potential institutional
investors, people familiar with the company's plans said. A
spokeswoman for Dragon refused to comment on the reasons for the
disappointing quarter, citing SEC restrictions on a company's
comments about a pending stock offering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
