u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC &LR; - &UR; BKN-NETS-HEAT-840&AMP;A     03-14 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCK TICKS FOR CALIPARI AS NETS FALL TO HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 BC - BKN-NETS-HEAT-840&AMP;ADD-NYT  (rk) 
 By   CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Rarely has a game between the best and the worst of the
Eastern Conference encompassed as much drama as Sunday's game
between the Miami Heat and the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   While the game evolved into the rout the team's records
forecast, the atmosphere remained as tense as a courtroom awaiting
a jury's verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the intensity was generated by the intrigue surrounding
John Calipari, the third-year Nets coach whose job is in jeopardy
because of the team's poor performance. So strange were the events
encircling the crestfallen coach that they overshadowed the Nets
debut of Stephon Marbury, whose acquisition on Thursday led NBC to
change its plans and give the game national rather than regional
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing sentiment heading into Sunday's game was that a
strong performance might delay Calipari's firing, while a poor one
could cement his demise.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets players, who have read the newspapers, heard the rumors
and privately fingered Calipari as a large reason for their 3-17
record, knew what was at stake going in. In response, they played
softly and inconsistently and were routed, 102-76, at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   After the game it appeared that Calipari was on the verge of
being fired. While the assistant coaches, the players and the rest
of the staff headed to the airport on the team bus, Calipari left
with Lewis Katz, the team's principal owner, in a private car.
</P>
<P>
   The two went to dinner, where a Nets official said they
discussed the team's problems and possible solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari, who has two years and $6 million remaining on his
contract, might be given the option of stepping down as coach but
remaining with the organization in some other capacity or accepting
a buyout and leaving the Nets altogether, according to a person
close to the team who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari, who carried a travel bag with him when he got into the
car with Katz, did not fly to Toronto with the team for Tuesday's
game against the Raptors. He might fly to Canada on Monday,
however, and the Nets expect to make an announcement concerning
Calipari's future Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   If playing to save Calipari's job was not enough inspiration for
the Nets Sunday, the debut of Marbury (21 points and five assists)
might have sparked them. But the excitement of adding him to the
lineup wore off quickly and the Nets stumbled to their seventh
straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   This one was the worst of the season, though, as they fell
behind by as many as 28 points and allowed Miami, whose 16-5 record
is the best in the East, to reach 100 points for only the third
time this year.
</P>
<P>
   As his team crumbled before his eyes, Calipari paced the
sideline, weakly yelling out instructions and wearing a morose
look. Katz had refused to give his coach a vote of confidence two
days earlier and with him now observing Sunday's action from a
courtside seat, grimacing after every Nets' miscue, Calipari seemed
like a dead man walking.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, a huge basketball fan who is ecstatic about having the
opportunity to run his own team, admitted that it was hard watching
the Nets get pummeled. That he had invested more than $120 million
into contract extensions for Marbury and Kerry Kittles within the
past three days certainly did not soften the blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to watch because of the way you feel about the
players, the coaches, Cal,'' Katz said. ``This is a terrible
feeling to watch. You could see him on the sideline. It's a
dreadful human emotion to watch a guy give his heart and soul and
the players, and you never feel like you're in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari, who has repeatedly denied the obvious in stating that
he is not worried about his job, said after the game that he was
not bothered by Katz's refusal to publicly support him. ``I hate
votes of confidence,'' said Calipari. ``A vote of confidence is
ugly. It's like kissing your sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Finn Wentworth, Katz's co-chairman of the ownership group,
Michael Rowe, the Nets' president, and John Nash, the general
manager, were also present, sitting a few rows behind the Nets'
bench and seemingly analyzing Calipari's every move. It appeared as
if the beleaguered coach, who only a few months ago was being
hailed as the franchise's great fix-it man, was being zeroed in on.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, the four Nets' officials met in a room near the
Nets' locker room, presumably to discuss Calipari's future. In the
third quarter, Don Casey, the Nets' assistant who would likely take
over on an interim basis if Calipari is fired, left the bench and
headed toward the area in which the power meeting was taking place.
And after the game, Wentworth met with Calipari for nearly 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just talking about our situation and what's the
solution,'' Calipari said. ``He just wanted to know where we're
going. How we get this thing changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expected to be the Nets' coach Tuesday against
Toronto, Calipari said, ``There was nothing said in that meeting
that led me to believe anything different.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many of the Nets players believe that Calipari is on his way
out, and while no one is fighting to keep him aboard, they denied
conspiring to get him removed. Van Horn, who recorded 15 points and
12 rebounds Sunday, was upset about published reports that the team
held a players-only meeting that ended with a 12-1 vote against
Calipari remaining as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't discussed it at all as a team,'' Van Horn said.
``Some of the stuff that's being written is just so ridiculous. One
guy wrote a whole article on how we had a team meeting that never
existed. We never had a team meeting and voted Cal out of here.
That never took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams, who over the years has been one of Calipari's
greatest and most consistent critics, seems to feel sorry for his
coach. ``I'm not in the business one way or the other of making a
man lose his livelihood, so anything I say right now that's
negative against John Calipari would be adding fuel to the fire,''
he said. ``John is in this hole with us all. I'm playing hurt
because I'm not going to leave this hole. We're all in this hole
together, not just one person. This whole team, including Cal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
