<HEADER>
A0290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BUDGET-565&AMP;ADD-NYT     03-14 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY FACES A NEW REALITY: A LATE BUDGET MEANS LATE PAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ One of the most emotionally charged questions
before the state Legislature these days has nothing to do with
welfare, taxes, crime or any other major policy matter. It centers
on a far more personal concern: whether lawmakers will be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Under a law enacted late last year, the state must withhold pay
for all 211 members of the Legislature if they fail to approve a
new state budget by April 1, the start of the new fiscal year. The
paychecks of each member will be held in escrow for as long as it
takes both houses of the Legislature to approve a new budget and
send it to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The law, the only one of its kind in the nation, was adopted at
the insistence of Gov. George Pataki, who has presided over the
latest budgets in state history, much to his chagrin _ since he
pledged to deliver timely budgets. In return for approving the
bill, Pataki agreed to give lawmakers a coveted pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   To many lawmakers, the trade seemed like a good idea at the
time, given that they had not had a salary increase in a decade.
But now, with the April 1 deadline approaching and budget
negotiations deadlocked, the policy has stirred protest and concern
in the Legislature, particularly among members who voted against
it.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, many are bracing for the worst, prepared to take loans
or dip into savings to meet mortgage payments, rents and other
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are genuinely concerned about their family finances,''
said Richard Gottfried, a Democratic assemblyman from Manhattan who
voted against the measure. ``For many members, this is their sole
income.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the practical concerns, many people inside and outside
the Legislature complain that the new law is akin to extortion,
maintaining that it could seriously impair the Legislature's
ability to do its job impartially.
</P>
<P>
   What of lawmakers who oppose the budget? Should they feel forced
to approve it because their livelihoods hang in the balance, the
critics ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this law is allowed to stand,'' said Alexander Grannis, a
Democratic assemblyman from Manhattan who voted against the
measure, ``people will never be able to know for sure whether their
legislator signed off on a budget because it was the right budget
or because they were worried about getting paid and taking care of
their families. This law is bad government, and it is bad policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The irritation is not limited to Democrats. Sen. James Lack, a
Republican from Long Island, suggested that the public was
inconsistent by clamoring for on-time budgets while demanding that
lawmakers fight to keep funds for particular projects in the
budget. He said the no-pay policy was making the job of legislating
all the more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think legislators should be put in the position of
making those decisions with that sword of Damocles over their
heads,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others say they doubt that the policy would force lawmakers
to compromise their principles. Rather, they say, the policy should
help prevent negotiations from becoming stalled for weeks, perhaps
months, by partisan posturing, as they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that we can't agree to in April that we have
to wait until August to do,'' said Nicholas Spano, a Republican
from Westchester County who voted for the new law. ``The bottom
line is that we have a job to do, and that job is to pass a
budget.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Late budgets have not always been the rule in Albany. Gov.
Nelson Rockefeller, a Republican, had the cooperation of
Republican-dominated Legislatures for most of his 14 years in
office, insuring that most of his budgets were adopted on time.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed in 1974, when a Democrat, Hugh Carey, was
elected governor and the Democrats took control of the Assembly.
Democrats have held the Assembly ever since, while the Senate has
remained in the hands of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That political divide has made it almost impossible for a budget
to be adopted by the April 1 deadline. Since 1975, Carey's first
year in office, the budget has been late 20 times: six times under
Carey, 10 times under Mario Cuomo, a Democrat, and four times under
Pataki, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation has been particularly embarrassing for Pataki,
because he vowed to put an end to Albany's record of tardy budgets
when he took office. In 1995, in his first year in office, Pataki
tried to withhold the pay of state legislators and their aides
until the budget was passed. But his efforts were successfully
challenged in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, he has the law on his side. And that has spurred
protests from lawmakers who accuse Pataki of having displayed
arrogance and contempt for the Legislature's authority when in
December he linked their raises to the no-pay policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has a personal contempt for the Legislature, and
he is entitled to that,'' said Richard Brodsky, a Democratic
assemblyman from Westchester. ``But it is regrettable when he
attempts to undermine the constitutional role of the Legislature.
It is un-American to attempt to influence people on issues
affecting the public by putting at risk their personal
well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that, it is strange to hear that Brodsky voted for the
measure. How does he explain that? ``I'm prepared to forgo my pay
if I can't in good conscience vote for the budget,'' he said. ``I
am not going to expend any political capital fighting the governor
on that issue. I have bigger fish to fry in the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of Brodsky's colleagues were far more cynical. One
lawmaker, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said that he and
other members voted for the measure, figuring that they would
challenge its constitutionality in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe this law will stand up in court,'' the member
said. ``But I'm not going to vote against it at the same time I'm
voting to give myself a raise. That may sound cynical. But it's a
matter of political survival.''
</P>
</TEXT>
