<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, RACE IS A STROLL(ER) IN THE PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ John Ramseyer knows he could have shaved almost an
hour off his time in the L.A. Marathon, if not for that extra 100
pounds in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Ramseyer, of La Canada, was just one of a record 20,630
(unofficial) to run in Sunday's 14th L.A. Marathon at his own pace.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than compete against time, the 40-year old prefers to
share it with his two children, who accompany their father in a
double-stroller designed for such an occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Ramseyer, who says he used to run the event in less than three
hours, has pushed Cole, 4, in his stroller at the past four L.A.
Marathons. For the past two, they've been joined by sister Lauren,
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of fun,'' Ramseyer said of his eldest. ``They
usually take a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ramseyer, running his 12th marathon, comes prepared for
nearly everything. Attached to the back of the aerodynamic stroller
_ fitted with one large, spoked wheel in front and two in back _ is
a compartment which houses the essentials: water, food, toys,
chocolate milk and ``a cell phone, in case we need mom,'' Ramseyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Atmosphere: The main reason spectators Jim and Chris Roberts of
Orange County came to the L.A. Marathon was to root for their
daughter, Heather.
</P>
<P>
   For Jim and Chris, the icing was the marathon's festive climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only time you get to walk around downtown L.A.
without any traffic,'' Jim Roberts said. ``It's a big street scene,
it's meeting people, watching all the fun costumes.''
</P>
<P>
   Costumes were many in number, with one runner donning a gold
cape and clown mask. Others simply painted their hair loud colors,
while still another juggled five balls during the race.
</P>
<P>
   And, in true L.A. fashion, there was no shortage of runners
talking on their cellular phones during the event.
</P>
<P>
   I will survive: For Frank Vasquez, 63, Sunday's race marked his
51st marathon. He has competed in all but one L.A. Marathon,
missing it in 1996 through no fault of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got run over by a car while training two weeks before (the
marathon),'' said Vasquez, of City of Commerce. ``It was very
disappointing; I go to them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspiring: There was the man who had a roller skate on his only
leg while pushing himself along with crutches and the blind man
being walked by two volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   While the elite marathoners attracted the crowds, those who
overcame obstacles drew the spectators' attention and admiration.
One elite runner, Kenya's Christopher Cheboiboch, did both.
</P>
<P>
   Stricken with malaria only 10 days prior to Sunday, Cheboiboch
led throughout much of the race but was overtaken by fellow
countryman Simon Bor, who shattered the course record en route to
victory. Cheboiboch finished third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the diet to eat, I feel restless; I couldn't go
through training as usual,'' Cheboiboch said. ``As you know, when
you don't eat anything, you lose a lot of weight. My body is so
weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Said L.A. Marathon president William Burke of Cheboiboch's
performance: ``I had malaria when I was working in Africa ... it
hits you like a baseball bat. It was a heroic, heroic effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Local talent: Runners from the San Fernando, Santa Clarita and
Antelope valleys fared well, with Glendale's Jose Luis Arriaga
(2:25.35) finishing in 17th place. Also from Glendale, Alvaro
Morales (2:29.26) took 21st place.
</P>
<P>
   Canyon Country's Brian Spangenberg (2:34.43) and Chuck Teixeira
(2:41.21) finished 32nd and 56th; Sylmar's Roberto Leonardo
(2:35.28), Martin Garcia (2:38.10) and Jose Luis Acuchi (2:38.20)
took 36th, 44th and 45th, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Ruiz (2:39.57), of Van Nuys, finished 49th and Palmdale's
Gustavo Mercado (2:45.21) came in 66th.
</P>
<P>
   Among the women, La Canada's Marie Romero (2:59.54) finished in
13th place.
</P>
</TEXT>
