<SLUG> BC-NY-HOTEL-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN ECONOMIST KILLED IN WALDORF-ASTORIA ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The man killed Saturday at the Waldorf-Astoria was
identified Sunday as a well-to-do Brazilian economist who ran
agricultural projects in the Amazon rain forest, owned a popular
antiques store and traveled the world several times a year, the
police and his relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim was Joao Saboia, 56, a resident of Belem, a city on
the northern coast of Brazil. His throat was slashed and his face
was badly cut and bruised, the police said. They refused to provide
details about Saboia or the circumstances of his death, but in a
telephone interview from Belem, his nephew, Carlos Saboia, 32, said
the police told relatives that about $50,000 was missing from the
hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He traveled all over the world, at least five times a year,''
Carlos Saboia said. ``But he really loved New York. That makes this
even more sad, because it happened in his favorite city.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not unusual for Saboia to travel with a lot of cash, his
nephew said. He said his uncle had stopped in New York on his way
to Atlantic City, where he was well known as a high-stakes gambler
and was often invited as a special guest by casino managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police told us that whoever did this had a fight with my
uncle and then took everything,'' Carlos Saboia said. ``They said
that they did not know who did it, but that it could have been
someone who works at the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Joao Saboia was single and had no children, relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   His eldest brother died of cancer two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to recuperate from my father's death, and now
this,'' Carlos Saboia said. ``We are just in total shock. Everyone
loved my uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives described Joao Saboia as a ``very influential
economist,'' and they said that he and his staff advised
corporations interested in establishing farming or industrial
projects in the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Saboia said the police told the family that they
discovered Saboia's body about 5:30 p.m. Saturday after travel
companions reported that they had not seen him for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   When officers went to his room, a ``Do Not Disturb'' sign was
hanging on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives also were told that this was the second attack within
a year at the Waldorf-Astoria, visited by the world's most
prominent dignitaries and long a symbol of New York's opulence.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, a 37-year-old guest was injured in a stabbing by a
homeless youth he had invited to his room.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said they had no suspects in Saboia's killing
and had made no arrests. An operator at the Waldorf-Astoria said
the manager would not speak about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Saboia's relatives are scheduled to arrive in New York Tuesday _
to discuss the slaying with the police and hotel officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know what happened,'' Carlos Saboia said.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the hotel expressed shock about the killing in their
midst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about walking last night to make a show,'' said
Sue Schmitt, of New Albany, Ind., who spent Saturday evening at
``The Phantom of the Opera.'' ``But I guess I was really safer on
the streets than I was in the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting next to Mrs. Schmitt was her daughter Julia. They had
come to New York to celebrate Julia's 13th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really scary,'' Julia said, referring to the killing. ``I
had nightmares all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Sipping beer and Jack Daniels in the lobby bar Sunday, Kathy and
Bob Foster of Dallas seemed to shrug off the incident after hearing
about it from a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend not to worry about things,'' said Foster, 77, decked
out in a pinstripe suit with a striped tie and matching
handkerchief. ``When you're old, most people are really nice to
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
