<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-NORLEANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY WILL GET A CHANCE TO SEE WALLY'S WORLD  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Wally Szczerbiak sat on a table in Miami of Ohio's
locker room when it was over, his right knee wrapped in ice as he
leaned against a wall. The 43-point man of Friday had a sweet
encore Sunday, and he clearly wants more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, when I'm healthy, I feel like there's not too many
people can stop me,'' Szczerbiak said after the 10th-seeded
Redhawks' 66-58 victory over second-seeded Utah in a Midwest
Regional second-round game at the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I'm in my game and our team's playing our game,''
said the 6-foot-8-inch, 243-pound senior forward, ``then we're a
team to contend with.''
</P>
<P>
   The player they call Wally's World again made the NCAA
tournament his personal stage. ``I just let the game come to me,''
the Long Island native said after a distinctive show of versatility
_ 24 points, seven rebounds, five assists, two blocked shots and a
pair of steals.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Szczerbiak took 33 of his team's 55 shots in Friday's
victory over Washington, Sunday he rationed himself to 11 of 46.
Instead of a shot machine, he became the base from which other
noteworthy things came from.
</P>
<P>
   The focus Utah placed on him helped forward John Estick free up
inside for 18 points and Jason Stewart free up outside to hit four
crucial 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   And then when the Redhawks needed Szczerbiak the most, he
responded with 16 second-half points, as Miami overcame a
three-point halftime deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like in some respects I played better today than I did
the other day,'' said Szczerbiak, who is from Cold Spring Harbor,
N.Y. ``I was forced to work harder to make some things happen. I
wasn't used to being so open the other night. This is a little more
like the games I've been going through during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time for the Redhawks (24-7) among the
tournament's final 16 teams. They play Kentucky, a tense 92-88
overtime winner over Kansas in Sunday's second game, in St. Louis
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Utah (28-5), which had a 23-game winning streak snapped, looked
strong inside in jumping to a 24-13 lead 13 minutes 31 seconds into
the game despite a swollen left hand that hampered its all-America
guard Andre Miller (20 points). The Redhawks called a timeout and
there wasn't much positive going on in the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had any confidence,'' Szczerbiak said. ``We needed
someone to pull us out of the dumps and get us going again.''
</P>
<P>
   That someone happened to be Stewart, a substitute swingman who
is the classic example of the guy who never saw a shot he didn't
like. He came in and made the first trio of 3-pointers he
attempted. Suddenly Miami was back in it.
</P>
<P>
   So now the Redhawks will try to buck the tradition and talent of
Kentucky (27-8).
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats needed sterling performances from their three
seniors _ Scott Padgett, 29 points; Wayne Turner, 19, and Heshimu
Evans, 14 _ to advance.
</P>
<P>
   They were down by five with just 1:08 left in regulation. Then
Turner made a pair of free throws and Padgett hit a 3-pointer with
19 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The defending national champions asserted themselves in
overtime, led by Padgett's seven points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we sort of willed ourselves to this win,'' Padgett
said. ``We weren't ready to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who set an NCAA record Sunday by playing in his 149th
career game, is trying to become the first non-Duke player to
compete in his fourth Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   This game pitted the collegiate game's two winningest programs
of the 1990'. The difference was that Kentucky has won two national
titles during that span to Kansas' zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the pride and satisfaction that you competed, and the
kids gave it everything they had,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams said.
``But it all hurts the same in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the Redhawks hope the fun is just starting. ``We're
trying on the glass slipper,'' Szczerbiak said smilingly of his
team's Cinderella tag. ``I'll say this: When you can beat a team
like Utah, obviously you've got to be a good team. We're going to
see how far we can take this.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
