<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-RUTGERS-ARIZONA-N     03-14 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-ARIZONA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS RUNS PAST ARIZONA AND INTO THE ROUND OF 16 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ The seedings, the national rankings and a
little insight said Rutgers should have beaten Arizona Sunday night
in the second round of the NCAA women's tournament. But this
easily? By a runaway score of 90-47?
</P>
<P>
   The game was not yet 12 minutes old and third-seeded Rutgers had
a 29-7 lead. Sixth-seeded Arizona tried to be fast, but Rutgers was
faster, quicker and sharper. By halftime, the score was 41-22, and
early in the second half it reached 56-24.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Sutton-Brown, Rutgers' 6-foot-4-inch sophomore center from
Canada, took quick command of both backboards. Shawnetta Stewart
was deadly from long range, and in a 69-second span in the first
half she hit two 3-pointers and a 14-foot jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers had been concerned about injuries to its three starting
guards, but the three _ Stewart (jammed finger), Tomora Young
(swollen disk) and Tasha Pointer (bruised calf) _ showed no signs
of infirmity.
</P>
<P>
   Pointer led Rutgers (28-5) with 18 points, seven assists, six
rebounds and four steals. Young and Stewart had 16 points each, and
Sutton-Brown had 13 points and nine rebounds. Angela Lackey, with
12 points, was Arizona's only player to score in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   The noisy crowd at Rutgers's Louis Brown Athletic Center watched
the Scarlet Knights reach the round of 16 for the second
consecutive year. Last year, Rutgers was eliminated by Tennessee,
the eventual national champion, after winning its first two games.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, in the Midwest Regional in Normal, Ill., Rutgers
will face the winner of Monday night's game between second-seeded
Texas Tech (29-3) and 10th-seeded North Carolina State (17-11).
</P>
<P>
   The other regional semifinal will match fourth-seeded North
Carolina (28-7) against the winner of Monday night's game between
top-seeded Purdue (29-1), the nation's No.1 team, and ninth-seeded
Kansas &QC; (23-9). Saturday's winners will meet the next Monday, with
the regional champion advancing to the Final Four on March 26 and
28 in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
