<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PURDUE-MIAMI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-SEEDED MIAMI OUSTED BY PURDUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Purdue's unlikely venture into the NCAA Tournament
continued yesterday with a surprising 73-63 victory over Miami,
which was seeded second in the East Region.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers (21-12) ended the Hurricanes' most successful
season and landed a berth in the East Regional semifinals against
Temple on Friday in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's victory gave the Tournament's 10th seeds a 7-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had better teams rated higher that this,'' Purdue coach
Gene Keady said. ``But to come back \Rfrom a 7-9 Big 10 season\S
and play like this the last two games _ I couldn't be prouder.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was marked with statistical anomalies. For instance,
Miami got 27 offensive rebounds, but made 25 of 76 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if went to the offensive boards we could create
problems for them,'' Hurricanes coach Leonard Hamilton said. ``But
to my surprise, we had 13 offensive rebounds in the first half and
still shot 18 percent. I've never seen 20 offensive rebounds we
couldn't put back in the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything away from Purdue. But when you
miss 17 point-blank layups, you've got to take some of the blame
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue shut down Miami's Johnny Hemsley, who nailed 9-of-12
3-pointers and scored 31 in a first-round victory over Lafayette.
He only got off two 3-pointers against the Boilers and missed both.
He finished with 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make sure I was there every time he caught the
ball and make it tough for him to get looks and maybe rush some
shots,'' Boilers guard Alan Eldridge said. ``I'll end up getting a
lot of credit, but the team did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Mario Bland hit Miami's only 3-pointer of the game in 14
attempts _ with 1:37 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue closed the first half with a 15-0 run, then outscored
Miami 13-2 when the Hurricanes got to five in the second half.
Brian Cardinal led a balanced attack with 20 points. Purdue scored
its last 19 points from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilers shot 57.9 percent, second-only to a 58.6 night in an
overtime victory over Indiana a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great win,'' Keady said. ``We did a lot of good
things _ defense, hitting free throws and we had a couple of spurts
each half. The nine straight shutouts the last of the \Rfirst\S
half probably won the game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami (23-7) set a school record for victories and won its
first-ever NCAA Tournament game, beating Lafayette in the first
round.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
