r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UTAH-MIAMI-OHIO-T     03-14 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UTAH-MIAMI-OHIO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI, OHIO, WINS FIRST TRIP TO REGIONALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Prior to his team's engagement with Miami of Ohio
in the second round of Midwest Region play, Utah's Rick Majerus
cautioned against keying too much on Wally Szczerbiak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the danger of winning the Szczerbiak battle and
losing the war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Utah lost both yesterday, as Szczerbiak scored 24 points,
leading the Red Hawks (24-7) to a 66-58 victory and the first Sweet
16 berth in the school's history.
</P>
<P>
   Majerus, watching the Utes (28-5) lose a 23-game winning streak
and a shot at trying to repeat last year's Final Four run, was
philosophical at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intended this to be a rebuilding year and never figured on
us being a No. 2 seed in this tournament,'' he said. ``It's been a
year that I will remember fondly, and the loss is not as
devastating as losing to Kentucky \Rin the NCAA championship game\S
last year. Miami just played harder and with more purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Charlie Coles, who at this time last year was in a
hospital recovering from a heart attack, said he came in ``feeling
that this would be the biggest challenge I've ever been a part
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak, who buried Washington with a 43-point binge in the
first round, finished this one with 24 points, seven rebounds, five
assists, two blocks and two steals.
</P>
<P>
   While the game ended with Miami's elated fans raising the
familiar chant, ``Wal-lee! Wal-lee!'' this was no one-man job, and
Coles found a helping hand on the bench to help with the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   With the Utes holding an 11-point lead in the first half and
seemingly rolling toward a decisive win, Miami sub Jason Stewart
was inserted into the game. He promptly banged in three consecutive
three-point shots, and Utah was swept away with the turning tide.
Miami also got 18 points from John Estick, who successfully battled
Utah's taller forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them before the game that we needed someone to step up
and do something,'' Coles said. ``You know how coaches are _ I was
bluffing and reaching. But Stewart came in and showed us we could
play with these guys, and we were OK after that.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the second half, the Miami lead stood at 11
points, and when the Utes attempted a final charge, Szczerbiak
answered by scoring eight points in the final three minutes to put
them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always there when you need him,'' Coles said. ``He always
knows where to strike, and when.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
