</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KENTUCKY-KANSAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAYHAWKS FALL SHORT IN OT VS. KENTUCKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Perhaps the most unfortunate aspect of a whirring
little battle between Kansas and Kentucky yesterday was that it
arrived too early.
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of game the NCAA Tournament orchestration crew
hopes to present to the world in two weeks _ for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (27-8) won it in overtime, 92-88, and Wildcats coach
Tubby Smith called it ``the kind of game everybody likes to come
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Nary a soul among the 15,804 Superdome patrons is likely to
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks (23-10), battered mercilessly by Kentucky in
December, played brilliantly during regulation and battled in
overtime after two starters fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary on these heart-wrenching occasions, Kansas coach
Roy Williams was in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fantastic college basketball game,'' he said. ``A
great experience for them, a heartbreaker for us. Once again, we
came so close to getting something we really wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, in fact, was 18 seconds away from a stunning upset when
Kentucky's Scott Padgett fired in a 3-point shot to tie it at 79-79
in regulation. Kansas' Kenny Gregory missed an off-balance shot at
the buzzer, and the game went to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Kansas had lost its starting forwards, Nick
Bradford and T.J. Pugh, both of whom fouled out. But the Jayhawks
got 49 points _ including 10 3-pointers _ from guards Ryan
Robertson and Jeff Boschee.
</P>
<P>
   Boschee tied the game at 84 with a 3-pointer with 2:14 remaining
in the overtime period, but it was the Jayhawks' last gasp. A
putback by Jamaal Magloire and four free throws by Padgett opened a
six-point gap with 45 seconds left. From there, the Wildcats were
on their way to the Midwest Regional later this week in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Padgett finished the game with 29 points and 10 rebounds, while
Robertson _ playing his final game at Kansas _ had a career-high 31
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' Robertson said. ``But I was proud of the
way we played this game, after losing to them so badly before.
After Padgett hit that shot to tie, we brought it down and I had
good penetration for a shot, but Kenny yelled for the ball so I
dished to him. I thought he had an open layup, but I misread the
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams called Padgett's shot, with Kansas leading, 79-76,
``the key play, and a smart move on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   The play began with Wayne Turner (19 points) missing a shot off
a drive. Magloire rebounded and passed to Padgett, standing inside
the three-point arc at the top of the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about the shot when I caught the ball,'' he
said, ``but somebody \RGregory\S came flying at me. I gave him a
head fake, then stepped back outside the arc, because we needed a
three. Luckily, it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Williams lavishly praised his team, in spite of a
sometimes disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had 11 years of great teams at Kansas,'' Williams said.
``But I am prouder of this team than any I have ever coached. They
have come back from so much adversity, including bad play and bad
coaching in some cases, and I was especially proud of them today.''
\Ntagtop:Whit Canning, (817) 390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-14-99 2350EST &QL; 
