<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKIN-COLUMN-MUCKLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MUCKLER HAS RANGERS MAJORING IN POSITIVES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ After the mob of happy Rangers congratulated
Adam Graves for his overtime game-winner Sunday, they skated in a
loose procession to the opposite corner of the rink in Nassau
Coliseum. There, in front of the open exit, stood coach John
Muckler, like the doorman at the China Club, his big grin bright
enough to be seen from the top row.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler greeted his Blue Shirts with handshakes and pats on the
back after their 3-2 victory over the Islanders left them two
points behind the Boston Bruins, who hold the eighth and final
playoff berth in the Eastern Conference. With 15 games left, the
Rangers might not make the playoffs and, even if they do, they
probably won't win even one round of the four-round tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But their persistence over the last few weeks, and their recent
8-3-1 record despite significant injuries, illustrates the
effectiveness of this experienced coach, who is molding a positive
attitude on a rebuilding team.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Rangers were outplayed but managed to win.
Muckler seems to press the right buttons with his players, old and
young alike. He has avoided the finger-pointing and scapegoating
that soured the mood in recent seasons under coach Colin Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Kevin Stevens is playing his best in five seasons, and
rookie Manny Malhotra is taking regular shifts and sparking his
teammates with skill and effort. Both scored early Sunday on power
plays as the Rangers played for the fifth time in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   When the Islanders tied the game in the third period, they might
have sagged and lost. Without Wayne Gretzky, Todd Harvey and Jeff
Beukeboom, with so many games in so few nights, the excuses were
there. But the Rangers found a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as excited as anybody else,'' captain Brian Leetch said
of Muckler. ``He highlights the positives. The assistant coaches
and everybody never make it into a feel-sorry-for-ourselves type of
thing. Today, he was very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have been negative. In the previous game, Muckler
watched his team squander a lead and lose an important game in the
final three minutes, 5-4 to Boston. But Muckler seemed to shrug it
off, noting that his players tried hard, that young players will
make mistakes, and that the Rangers simply gave up the last goal in
a high-scoring affair.
</P>
<P>
   At age 64, he is the second-oldest coach in the business, behind
only Detroit's Scotty Bowman, who is 65. Although a close friend
and Buffalo neighbor of Bowman's, Muckler operates somewhat
differently. Mike Knuble, who played for Bowman as a Red Wing until
this season, said, ``I can compare and contrast the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is much more approachable,'' Knuble said, comparing Muckler
with Bowman. ``He's positive 95 percent of the time. He has an
open-door policy. Some coaches say it's open door, but you won't go
in and ask anything. Muckler doesn't play mind games, sticking
people on the fourth line and trying to get a rise out of them.
He's done a great job of keeping our ship together. This team could
have gone in the tank in February.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler expresses faith in his players in different ways with
different people. With Stevens, he warned him on the first day of
camp to get involved in checking and defensive play. At first, he
kept Stevens off the power play. Now, Stevens' good games outnumber
his bad games, and he is back on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muck's been a big part of what I've done,'' Stevens said. ``We
communicate. He tells me when things are bad. He tells me when
things are good. Some coaches back off and don't say much. He's not
afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gretzky out since Feb. 22, Muckler has found more minutes
at center for Malhotra, Marc Savard and, especially, Petr Nedved,
who played more than 32 Sunday. Nedved credits conversations with
Muckler for direction.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous time with the Rangers, in 1995, Nedved read
scathing criticisms in the newspapers. Muckler keeps critiques
private. ``He motivates guys,'' Nedved said. ``In one-on-one
meetings, maybe what he has to say is not pretty, but he gets the
point across much clearer.''
</P>
<P>
   If and when Gretzky returns this season, Muckler will have a
delicate chore. He must provide the Great One with enough minutes
to satisfy his professional pride without hurting the other three
centers. No problem, Muckler said. ``Gretz will be a very important
part of this hockey club,'' Muckler said. ``We don't have enough
game-breakers, and Gretz is a game-breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, to distinguish his style from previous
regimes, Muckler ran long, hard practices. He has eased off now.
Another major change came on road trips.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of commuting home after night games, Muckler keeps his
players on the road, sometimes for a day or two, so that they
socialize and grow as a group. After defeats, Muckler tends to
scowl and growl at reporters, assuming every question about
strategy or personnel is a second-guess. After victories, he is
more willing to share his philosophies and emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun,'' he said. ``We're back on track. We're
playing well and we're working. It's thrilling. It's fun. I've
really been enjoying this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
