<SLUG> BC-NY-SOUTHWEST-AIR-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANDED SOUTHWEST FLIGHTS BRING MIXED REACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLIP, N.Y. _ Bumped off an overbooked flight home hours
earlier, Jim Mihnovich stood at the end of a long line at Long
Island MacArthur Airport on Sunday morning a grateful man. Grateful
mostly for Southwest Airlines, which started operations at
MacArthur on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was awesome,'' he said, pocketing one of the carrier's
distinctive blue plastic boarding passes for a 12:10 p.m. flight to
Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others in Islip who do not share Mihnovich's
enthusiasm. While many frequent flyers said they hoped the arrival
of Southwest would force other large airlines to cut prices to the
Long Island airport, people who live near the airport complained
about the prospect of more jet engines roaring overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the airline will offer 12 nonstops a day from
MacArthur to Baltimore, Chicago, Nashville and Tampa, Fla. If that
modest beginning stimulates enough interest, the airline may add
more flights later.
</P>
<P>
   That concerns residents like Ronald Falcone, who said he is
already weary of hearing planes flying over his four-bedroom home
in Holbrook, a hamlet bordering the airport's property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I use the airport; nobody wants to see it closed,''
said Falcone, 43, a manager for an insurance company. ``We want to
see it prosper. But you could do it with a little bit of class and
consideration for the residents. What's this house going to be
worth in 10 years if this airport takes off?''
</P>
<P>
   If Sunday's large and enthusiastic crop of first-day passengers
was any indication, Southwest may increase the airport's popularity
in much less than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Mihnovich's story. With no chance of getting on an
overbooked American Airlines flight at La Guardia Airport on Sunday
morning, he summoned his father from Brooklyn for a car ride out to
Islip, about 40 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in the car, got on my cell phone, called Southwest and
bought a ticket for $130 _ and that was at the last minute,'' said
Mihnovich, 35, an executive for a Nashville home health-care
company. Less than one hour later, he had his boarding pass.
``That's pretty amazing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline is almost guaranteed to enhance the image of the
no-frills airport, a decaying one-story structure with two
linoleum-tiled concourses and 1970s Muzak piped over the
public-address system.
</P>
<P>
   Marian Wise, a 56-year-old lawyer who was also waiting for a
Southwest flight to Nashville, said the airline's new service would
put an end to eight-hour plane-to-train-to-automobile odysseys to
visit friends in Islip. ``It's inexpensive, it's efficient, they
get you where you need to be when you need to be there,'' she said.
``And I love the peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Islip officials said they expect Southwest to generate hundreds
of thousands of dollars in revenue for the town each year. The
town's supervisor, Peter McGowan, said he hoped that the eight
other airlines that serve the airport would cut fares to match
those of Southwest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The traveling public will certainly gain from the spirit of
competition that Southwest will create,'' McGowan said in a
telephone interview. ``It will certainly help the economy of Islip
and all of Long Island. It brings Islip MacArthur Airport into the
next millennium, and it helps to bring Long Island into the next
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   But some residents in two adjacent communities believe
Southwest's arrival at MacArthur, which serves more than a million
passengers a year, may be a harbinger of more noise and traffic
congestion. Falcone and other residents have formed the Committee
for the Enforcement of MacArthur Airport Control, which is seeking
to force Islip to cap the number of daily flights to and from
MacArthur and to prohibit late-night flights.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan said the airport's jet traffic complies with federal
noise regulations and will remain within such boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Southwest will be able to draw New York City-based
passengers away from Kennedy International and La Guardia airports
remains to be seen. Though the airline is offering rock-bottom
one-way prices _ $39 to Baltimore, $79 to Chicago or Nashville, and
$89 to Tampa _ MacArthur Airport, on the South Shore of Long
Island, is a good hour's drive from Manhattan even when there is no
traffic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
