<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Neb., Wash., Calif., Ore., Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MacManus Consolidates P&AMP;G's Account
</P>
<P>
   MacManus Group in New York is consolidating its large Procter &AMP;
Gamble Co. accounts by shifting brands from its smaller agency,
N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners, to its larger one, D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP;
Bowles Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation, which had been expected, involves brands with
estimated billings of $100 million out of Ayer's estimated total of
$585 million: Folgers and Millstone coffees, Puffs tissues and
Hawaiian Punch and Sunny Delight juice drinks.
</P>
<P>
   They will be added to the Procter brands handled by DMB&AMP;B, which
include Crest toothpaste, Scope mouthwash and Pampers diapers. The
50 to 60 Ayer employees working on the Procter accounts out of the
total of about 400 will join DMB&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come as Procter has been paring its agency roster,
consolidating accounts at its biggest shops for greater
efficiencies. The company supports the decision, said Denis
Beausejour, vice president for global marketing at Procter in
Cincinnati, in part because DMB&AMP;B will be ``providing additional
resources and support'' for the brands.
</P>
<P>
   MacManus is also taking advantage of the looser conflict policy
recently adopted by P&AMP;G, which now frees Ayer to pursue accounts
from other marketers. And MacManus has plans to enhance the image
of Ayer as a more creative agency; eliminating a packaged-goods
marketer from the client roster may help Ayer in recruiting
creative talent.
</P>
<P>
   Two Marketers Select New Agencies
</P>
<P>
   Two advertisers have named agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon McElligott and its Duffy Design and Interactive unit,
both in Minneapolis, have been selected by IBP Inc. in Dakota City,
Neb., the giant meat packer, to handle a new national assignment,
the introduction of a line of brand-name fresh and prepared beef
and pork products. Billings have not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a two-month review involving four
agencies. The others, according to Adweek, were: DDB Needham
Chicago, part of the DDB Needham Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group;
Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding in Chicago, a unit of True North
Communications, and TBWA/Chiat/Day in Playa del Rey, Calif., part
of the TBWA Worldwide unit of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   And Onhealth Network Co. in Seattle named three agencies to
handle its general advertising, interactive advertising and public
relations accounts, with combined billings estimated at $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco office of TBWA/Chiat/Day was named as the
first agency to handle general advertising. Thinking Media in New
York was named to handle interactive advertising, which had been
handled by Quantum Leap Communications in Chicago, part of Leap
Group. And the New York and San Francisco offices of
Fleishman-Hillard, part of Omnicom, will handle public relations.
</P>
<P>
   New-Media Shops Share Honors
</P>
<P>
   Three agencies shared top honors for new-media advertising,
winning the most awards, at a ceremony in New York sponsored by the
One Club for Art and Copy.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies, which won three awards apiece at the One Show
Interactive, are CKS Partners in New York, a unit of U S Web/CKS
Group; Ogilvy Interactive Worldwide in New York, part of the Ogilvy
&AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group PLC, and Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in
Portland, Ore. Nicholson New York won Best of Show for a
self-promotional campaign featuring an online game called ``Snow
Craft.''
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com, Waltham, Mass., to Arnold Communications, Boston,
a unit of Snyder Communications, as the first agency to handle the
account of the Internet-based educational toy retailer. Billings
were estimated at $10 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
