<SLUG> BC-NJ-SUSPECT-SHOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED KILLER SHOT TO DEATH BY POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A man in Chatham, N.J., who the authorities said had killed his
estranged wife and their 8-year-old son was shot dead by a police
officer Saturday night after he refused to drop a large kitchen
knife, the police said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After the officer shot the man, Thomas Spranger, 49, the police
found the bodies of Spranger's estranged wife, Karen Knispel, 44,
and their son, Kevin Spranger, in Ms. Knispel's home on Longhill
Road in Chatham Township, about 10 miles west of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-year-old son, Trevor Spranger, was found alive but
seriously injured from numerous knife wounds. He was listed in
critical but stable condition at Morristown Memorial Hospital, said
Christopher Linne, a spokesman for the Morris County prosecutor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Spranger and Ms. Knispel, who had separated in January, had no
police record of domestic violence, Linne said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Ms. Knispel, a veterinary assistant and daughter of
Theodore Knispel, a former Chatham police chief, became worried
when they could not reach her by telephone to confirm a planned
Saturday evening outing, Linne said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Ms. Knispel had told a friend during a telephone
conversation at 9:45 a.m. that she was concerned about Spranger.
</P>
<P>
   When the friend, whom the prosecutor's office did not identify,
tried to call back later in the day, the line was continually busy,
Linne said. The friend became so concerned that she drove to Ms.
Knispel's house about 6:20 p.m. and saw Spranger's car in the
driveway, according to Linne. She called the police at 6:33 p.m.,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   When two Chatham police officers, Sgt. George Petersen and
Officer Michael Giannone, arrived at the home and began to search
the back yard, Linne said, Spranger leaped from the bushes wielding
a knife and was ordered by Petersen to drop it.
</P>
<P>
   Spranger did not say anything, according to Linne, who declined
to describe Spranger's demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Spranger continued to advance with the knife, Linne said.
Petersen fired two rounds from his .45-caliber semiautomatic
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen and Giannone then entered the house and found Kevin
Spranger dead in the living room and Ms. Knispel dead in the
basement, Linne said.
</P>
</TEXT>
